<HEADLINE>
SWIMMING FEDERATION LIFTS BAN, HAL FREE TO COMPETE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC  
 c.1998 The Arizona Rpublic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Olympic gold medalist Gary Hall Jr. will be able to
compete again after FINA, the international swimming federation,
ended his provisional probation Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Arizona Republic'' was unable to reach Hall, but his
prepared statement said, ``I am pleased that the situation with
FINA has been resolved. It allows me to concentrate properly on
what I believe I do best _ competitive swimming.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, 25, was placed on provisional probation after he tested
positive for marijuana on a May 15 drug test. He has said he is
innocent of violating FINA regulations and had asked FINA to give
him a hearing before its doping panel.
</P>
<P>
   But the waiving of the suspension comes too late for him to
participate in the National Championships, which end today in
Clovis, Calif. The championships are considered a steppingstone to
the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The Phoenix Swim Club athlete won four medals in the 1996
Atlanta games and is considered the best sprinter in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   He tested positive for marijuana at the Atlanta games, but there
was a legal question as to whether a violation was committed, since
FINA only banned marijuana use around that time period. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
