<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-MAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGH TAKES LEAD AT PGA CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Traditionally, the PGA Championship is the weak
sister of the four majors. At the U.S. and British opens, par is a
good score, as it was this year. The Masters champ usually finishes
somewhere in the 8- to 10-under range, like the 9-under that won it
earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA? In the last five years, the average winning score has
been 12.5 under. Not good, considering the majors like to pride
themselves for their tenacity. Hey, these are not supposed to be
one of those ``let's take it deep'' PGA Tour shows.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there were reservations about little-known Sahalee
Country Club, primarily because the only research in the past had
been on woodpeckers and termites and their impact on club's tall
timbers. This was Sahalee's debut into tournament golf, and
organizers were not sure if the world's best players were facing a
hurricane or a light breeze from this course that lies near the
Pugent Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, Sahalee is a fairly stern gale. At least that's what
the results indicate after Vijay Singh emerged Friday as the leader
at the midpoint. His 4-under 66 was good enough for a 1-shot
advantage over Colin Montgomerie, Steve Stricker and Scott Gump.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the same score that Tiger Woods had recorded the day
before, and Woods and Singh both had to shoot course records to get
there.
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions (the guys who missed the cut), the
tightness of these tree-lined fairways has virtually taken the
driver out of most players' hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even hitting irons off the tee, it's not a gimme that you're
going to put it on the fairways,'' said Singh, who birdied three of
the first four holes, and five of the first nine, before Sahalee
snapped back.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to hit really good shots on the correct side of the
fairway to score. Nothing's stopping you from hitting driver, but
the problem is keeping it on the short stuff (grass). The fairways
are so fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods agreed, and even issued a warning for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``The course is really drying out, like a British Open. The
greens and fairways are brown in spots, and if they don't put any
water on them, it's going to be really hard to shoot a low number
the next two days,'' said Woods, who never got it going on his way
to a 72 that pushed him back to 2 under.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, the bombastic Scot, had his own prediction after a
67.
</P>
<P>
   ``The championship will be determined on Sunday at the 18th.
There's no question about that,'' said inpregnable ``Monty,'' who
would have shared the lead with Singh if not for a bogey at that
475-yard, uphill par 4. ``You could almost call the course a par 71
because of that hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker had the lead late in the day at 5 under until a 5-iron
into the water at the 17th resulted in a double-bogey 5. He ended
up with a 68, long after the TV cameras had shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Sahalee's fear factor seemed to be escalating among everyone
except Gump, who has a little bit of Forrest in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the course, and I don't feel any pressure,'' reported
the laidback pro from Florida, who has one top-10 finish this
season. ``Trying to make the cut, that's pressure. But playing well
in the PGA, that's fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Five players were at 2 under, including defending champ Davis
Love, who shot an erratic 68. Also at that number was Scottsdale's
Andrew Magee, whose 68 was much more even-keeled behind three
birdies and a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Two other Phoenix-area pros were 4 shots off the pace. Phil
Mickelson rallied on the back nine with three birdies for his
second straight 70. And Billy Mayfair, last week's winner of the
Buick Open, turned around a 73 in the opening round with a 67, the
second-best score of the day.
</P>
<P>
   The cut came at 5 over. One of those who did not advance was
Stuart Appleby, who was playing for the first time since his wife,
Renay, was killed in a freak accident in London three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not glad it's over,'' said Appleby, who was 10 over after
a 73. ``But again, I'm not expecting great things.''
</P>
<P>
   Those will have to come from others on a course that grows
quicker by the minute. Perhaps someone like Mark O'Meara, who is
attempting to become the first player to win three major
championships since Ben Hogan in 1953. The Masters and British Open
champ is 1 under after a 70.
</P>
<P>
   Now that would be truly a great thing. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
