<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOLS-CHANCELLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SCHOOLS CHANCELLOR LIKELY TO GET $50,000 RAISE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew would be paid more than
any other top school administrator in the country _ as well as
President Clinton _ under a new contract the Board of Education is
likely to approve on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed contract, which would be retroactive to July 1,
raises Crew's salary 25.6 percent, to $245,000 a year from
$195,000. Crew already earns more than Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
($165,000) and Gov. George Pataki ($130,000), and his new salary
would surpass Clinton's base salary of $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   The contract would also extend Crew's tenure. The old contract
was scheduled to expire next July 1. Under the new contract, Crew
would have to stay until June 30, 2000, with the option of two
one-year extensions.
</P>
<P>
   Board officials said the raise was needed to remain competitive
with other urban school districts and to bring stability to a
position that has seen 11 occupants in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The salary of the schools chancellor, who oversees a system with
1.1 million students, 63,500 teachers and a $9-billion budget, has
remained the same since 1990. In addition to his salary, Crew lives
in a Brooklyn Heights brownstone owned by the board and, when on
school business, has the use of a car and driver.
</P>
<P>
   William C. Thompson Jr., the board president, said he and the
chancellor had discussed the terms of the contract in recent
months. He said Crew, who was appointed in October 1995, was not
job hunting but wanted greater compensation for what he considered
an increasingly difficult job. Aides to Thompson said the board
president had secured the votes to approve the contract.
</P>
<P>
   If Crew stayed for the new contract's minimum of two years, his
six-year tenure would make him the longest-serving New York schools
chief in 40 years. Thompson said that Crew intended to stay for the
contract's full four years.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the chancellor said he would leave a few months
before the next mayoral election, in November 2001. Giuliani, with
whom Crew has a close relationship, is barred from seeking a third
term and the chancellor has said he does not want to work with
another mayor. The two one-year options were included to allow the
chancellor the flexibility to change his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Crew was unavailable for comment Friday, said a spokesman, J.D.
La Rock. Colleen Roche, a spokesman for Giuliani, said the mayor
would not comment on Crew's contract.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said a national survey conducted by the board showed
that Crew earned more than any other chief school administrator
aside from Robert C. Cuevas, the superintendent of the Miami-Dade
County Public Schools, whose salary was $199,800. The school system
in Miami, with an enrollment of 331,000 and a $3-billion budget, is
the nation's fourth largest _ trailing those in New York, which has
the largest, Los Angeles, and Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   While the average salary for a superintendent, according to the
American Association of School Administrators, is $94,000, Thompson
said many smaller urban districts pay their chief executives
salaries that approach Crew's. Seattle, for example, pays its
superintendent $186,000 to oversee a system with 44,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is the result of Rudy being happy with the job he
is doing and helping to change the school system, and this board
being very happy with him,'' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson cited the rise in reading and math test scores on city
exams, which he said was a better gauge of students' performance
than recent state exams that showed a downturn, as well as Crew's
success in winning broader powers from Albany to hire and fire
local district superintendents.
</P>
<P>
   The contract extension, he said, would allow Crew to follow
through on a number of changes he has begun, including ending the
automatic promotion of schoolchildren to the next grade if they
have not demonstrated competency in basic skills.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Levy, executive vice president of the principals' union,
the Council of Supervisors and Administrators, called the timing of
the raise insensitive because the union and the board have failed
to agree on a contract during the last two years. But Ms. Levy said
she did not take issue with the new salary, which is about three
times the amount a high school principal makes a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly, if they want stability and continuity in the system
and they are pleased with his job, he ought to be compensated and
validated by giving him a contract,'' Ms. Levy said. ``But it is
unfortunate they have not expressed the same feeling toward school
leaders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
