<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUE SORROW NOT FROM LOUSY ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Redmond, Wash - Golfers mourn missed putts. Double bogeys are
heart-wrenching tragedies.
</P>
<P>
   Then Stuart Appleby looked at us with those haunted blue eyes.
Steeling himself, summoning his courage, he gazed around the room
and politely invited our questions. Though he dreaded it, he needed
to do it. It was time. Go ahead, he urged, breaking the silence.
``Don't be shy.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the usual press tent interview in which a player is
quizzed about his putting problems or an errant tee shot.
</P>
<P>
   Three days ago, Appleby spoke publicly for the first time about
a real tragedy. His sorrow and tears reminded us what we forget.
Sports aren't life and death. Golf? It's a ``game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bravely, as best he could, the 27-year-old Australian put words
to his deepest feelings. He spoke of Renay. He talked openly about
the task of learning to accept the reality that he will spend the
rest of his life without her.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, Appleby's wife was struck by a taxi as she
unloaded luggage outside a London train station. She died before
her husband's eyes. Married two years, the couple was going to
Paris for a second honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral in Australia. Flowers. The notes of condolences are a
blur. Emotionally numb, Appleby was unprepared to play golf when he
showed up this week for the PGA Championship. He hadn't hit a ball
since Renay's death July 23.
</P>
<P>
   Appleby played because tournament golf is what he does for a
living. He needed to resume his life, even if his heart wasn't in
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just needed to get out again,'' he said. Also, part of him
wanted to reassure those who care about him most, to tell them by
taking the first step that he will be OK.
</P>
<P>
   It never was Appleby's intention for this to be a public
spectacle. TV cameras trailed him around the course. In the
gallery, where his wife would have been following on every hole, he
felt the sympathetic stares.
</P>
<P>
   ``So much attention,'' he said, ``for reasons I really didn't
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Golf is a mental game. Appleby couldn't give it his undivided
attention, nor did he expect to. His mind wandered as he trudged
around the course, a solitary figure, head bowed. After he shot 77
in the first round, Appleby's caddie said what was painfully
obvious: ``Stuart wasn't really himself.''
</P>
<P>
   As a golfer, he is a robot right now, although Friday he felt
himself smile. Appleby rolled in a 40-footer for birdie at No. 17.
Then, on the final hole, a monster par 4, he stood over his ball
below the green, about 60 feet from the cup. The gallery hushed
itself as the bearded golfer drew back his wedge and struck his
third shot.
</P>
<P>
   The ball hopped onto the putting surface and began rolling
directly toward the flagstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let it happen,'' a man standing next to me whispered.
</P>
<P>
   The ball kept rolling, rolling, closer now . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Let it happen. . . . Let it HAPPEN!''
</P>
<P>
   And it did.
</P>
<P>
   I saw a golf ball ``wished'' into the hole. Surprised, Appleby
broke into a smile and raised his arms in thanks, thanks for a
birdie, and for the warm outpouring of support.
</P>
<P>
   Healing?
</P>
<P>
   His fingers touched the silver necklace he wore, the one made of
small squares that spell out his wife's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose you could call this week a step in the healing
process,'' Appleby said, a note of caution in his voice.
</P>
<P>
   He is playing golf again. There's a tournament next week, and
another the week after before he makes the trip he dreads, back to
Orlando. For the first time since burying his wife, he will unlock
the front door and step into an empty house, their dream house _
her ``pride and joy'' _ and listen to awful sounds of silence. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
