<SLUG> BC-FBO-RATTLERS-PREDATORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATTLERS SET TO DUEL PREDATORS  
 ARENABOWL, NATIONAL EXPOSURE AWAIT WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Here they meet again, the Rattlers and the Orlando
Predators, this time with the most historic ArenaBowl date in the
league's 12-year history at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Loser goes home. Winner gets to play Aug. 23 in the first
nationally network-televised Arena football game at Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   You think none of these guys wants a piece of that exposure?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be enormous,'' Rattlers quarterback Sherdrick Bonner
said. ``This is probably the biggest game in the franchise right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's 5 p.m. semifinal at America West Arena is even bigger
than last year's championship, when the Rattlers ripped the Iowa
Barnstormers at home. Bigger than '94, when the Rattlers captured
their first ArenaBowl with the greatest upset in league history,
36-31, over a seemingly invincible Orlando team at ``The Jungle'' _
the name the Predators like to call their home arena.
</P>
<P>
   These guys just can't seem to get away from each other. Two
years ago, the Rattlers beat Orlando again in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Don't think the Predators have forgotten for a second their past
two playoffs losses to Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always been a Rattler fan, but even though I'm a Rattler
fan, I want to beat them that much more,'' Scottsdale resident and
Predators Chairman Will Meris said. ``I think we're still looking
for redemption after being the big favorite in '94.''
</P>
<P>
   Orlando never has won the big trophy, something the Rattlers
have earned twice and something the Predators' archrival, the Tampa
Bay Storm, has done four times.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Gruden, a new, young coach who quarterbacked the Storm to
those four championships, brought in 13 rookies and injected a
championship energy in the Predators, who possess the league's
second-best defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week was probably the best game we played all year,''
Gruden said of his team's 58-43 victory over the Nashville Kats.
The Rattlers couldn't stop the Kats until the last series the week
before, when the Rattlers won, 59-54.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to whether we can turn it up and keep the level
of intensity.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rattlers haven't forgotten June 20, when they lost to
Orlando, 42-40, at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It was their last loss at home, and Calvin Schexnayder turned in
his worst game, gaining only 77 receiving yards. He was a
non-factor against a secondary led by Kenny McEntyre, Damon Mason
and Chris Barbers.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Danny White is sickened even when he watches tape of that
game. He sees receiver Randy Gatewood was ejected just before
halftime for brushing an official. He sees lineman Tony Henderson
knocked unconscious on the same play. He sees how the offense
continually broke down because of missed blocking assignments and
dropped passes, and he sees how a fumbled kickoff resulted in an
Orlando score.
</P>
<P>
   The highest-scoring offense at the time was shut out in the
first quarter, something that had not happened before to the
Rattlers, even during their expansion year in '92, when the
Predators whipped them, 71-21. That score remains a team record for
the largest margin of defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But White said losing at home doesn't add incentive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the fact that they beat us,'' he said. ``We have a chance
to go one up on them. We have a chance to turn the tables.''
</P>
<P>
   Count on Gatewood, who caught the winning touchdown pass in
overtime against Tampa Bay in last year's semifinals, to stay away
from the officials.
</P>
<P>
   Bonner just wants to finish. He became a spectator at last
year's ArenaBowl after suffering a broken leg in the fourth quarter
of the semifinal game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, we can't shoot ourselves,'' Gatewood said.
``The last time we played Orlando, that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Meris, who had some Orlando players over Friday night to watch
Tampa Bay beat New Jersey, 49-23, in a semifinal, said the
Predators' goals are to beat Arizona and ``to sack Bonner.'' Bonner
has gone 34 straight games without a sack. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
