<HEADLINE>
NO SHORTAGE OF RECEIVERS  
 EXPERIENCED WIDEOUTS GIVE ASU SOME DEPTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BECKY GRUHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAYSON, Ariz. _ Tariq McDonald doesn't need preseason magazines
to tell him where Arizona State's receiving corps ranks in college
football. He thinks the answer is, well, rather obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the best corps in the nation,'' the sophomore
receiver said. ``I feel that real deep in my heart. I think we have
the most talent and most experience coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   While McDonald's assesment may be hard to prove, a quick glance
at the Sun Devils' roster does give the bold statement some
validity.
</P>
<P>
   All-American candidate Lenzie Jackson and senior Kenny Mitchell,
the top receivers a year ago, are two of seven true receivers who
return after seeing considerable action last fall. In fact, ASU
didn't lose a player at the position from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of veteran players who know the game,'' Jackson
said. ``We have a lot of versatility. We have the deep threat, the
possession receivers and the little quick guys who can get the
first downs.''
</P>
<P>
   But greeting all those familiar faces at Camp Tontozona hasn't
convinced Sun Devils Coach Bruce Snyder that he has enough depth at
receiver. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe I see it different than some people,'' Snyder
said. ``I think our front-line players are very talented, but we
have some questions still to answer beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   One lingering question will be whether senior wideout Ricky
Boyer will see action this season. Boyer did not make the trip to
Camp Tontozona because of academic difficulties, but receivers
coach Robin Pflugrad doesn't want to rule out Boyer's return this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ricky is working on some situations that he has to improve
upon academically,'' Pflugrad said. ``He's working on it
day-to-day. It's really going to depend on how well he accomplishes
some of the tasks he has to get done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really out of my hands. I don't know if he'll play.''
</P>
<P>
   Boyer, nicknamed ``The Rocket'' because of his speed, caught 21
passes last season, averaged 13.6 yards a reception and scored four
touchdowns. He also rushed for 85 yards on seven carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm praying for him; we need him out here,'' Jackson said.
``He came in with me and Kenny (Mitchell), and I want to leave with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if Boyer doesn't return, Pflugrad is left with six
receivers who played in 1997. For Pflugrad it creates a nice
scenario, but still far from ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we know we have enough people that we'll get better
and be capable of making big plays,'' he said, ``and hopefully that
will be able to take a little bit of the pressure off Jackson. But
as a coach you can never have enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute you're satisfied as a coach, you should really
probably retire and go fly-fishing or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson has already locked up one of the starting positions. The
6-foot senior was quarterback Ryan Kealy's favorite target last
year, leading the receivers with 53 completions for 733 yards and
five touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Pflugrad has yet to determine who will start opposite Jackson.
Mitchell, McDonald, sophomore Brian Forth and senior Creig Spann
are all likely candidates. However, McDonald appears to have a
slight edge in the battle.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1 sophomore has been running routes with Kealy at the
helm ever since high school when the two teamed up to lead St.
Mary's to the 1995 Class 5A state championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That gives me an advantage, but Ryan's such a good quarterback
he works well with all the receivers,'' McDonald said. ``If I go
out there and compete and maintain what I did in spring ball, I
think the starting job is mine to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   That prediction may be a bit easier to prove. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
