<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEES FERRY LIMITS ESTAB LISHED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a series of public meetings, the Arizona Game and Fish
Department has decided how it wants to manage the trout fishery at
Lees Ferry on the Colorado River.
</P>
<P>
   Lees Ferry, a 15-mile stretch below Lake Powell, is considered
one of the best tail water (below a dam) trout fisheries in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would establish a 16-inch maximum limit for trout,
meaning no fish more than 16 inches long could be kept. There would
be a daily bag limit of two trout and a possession limit of four.
</P>
<P>
   The department said the recommendation is based on fish
populations, law enforcement needs, public input and the ability of
the department to evaluate the fishery.
</P>
<P>
   The five public meetings seeking input on management changes
were not heavily attended, but Joe Janisch, head of fisheries for
the department, said comments at those meetings were consistent
with the comments from thousands of anglers interviewed during
creel surveys at the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different groups have different likes and dislikes,'' he said.
``The comments we heard at the public meetings reaffirm what we've
already heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the people have done is give us a vision of a quality
fishery and how to attack it.''
</P>
<P>
   Janisch said the department believes the new regulations will
meet most angler needs and all of the following biological
objectives:
</P>
<P>
   Maintain an average catch rate of not less than 0.6 fish an
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Maintain fish in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   Allow the fish to reach 16 inches in length or larger by their
third year.
</P>
<P>
   Sustain the fishery through natural reproduction, stocking only
when poor reproduction years threaten biological objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Monitor the populations of both native fish and rainbow trout.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of trout &QL; 
Montana usually is considered a model for trout management by trout
enthusiasts.
</P>
<P>
   Following are four tips that the state's wildlife management
agency provides to help ensure a healthy trout population:
</P>
<P>
   Don't disturb spawning trout. Be careful not to disturb fish
nests (redds). Fish carefully during spawning season so spawning
fish are not disturbed.
</P>
<P>
   At Lees Ferry in Arizona, fishing the redds is the primary way
of catching trout. If disturbing redds hinders natural
reproduction, there are serious problems at Lees Ferry.
</P>
<P>
   Use particular caution when fishing warmer waters. Trout become
stressed when water temperatures exceed 62 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Lees Ferry, it would be difficult to find trout
waters in Arizona that didn't exceed 62 degrees in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   If you practice catch-and-release fishing, improve your
techniques to reduce stress on fish. Use hook-removal tools and
soft, wet gloves, or at least wet your hands if you must handle a
trout.
</P>
<P>
   Limit your catch, whether you practice catch-and-release
techniques or not. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
