<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRL-BOAT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOAT BACK 7 WEEKS AFTER CRASH  
 HAS FALLEN TO 12TH PLACE BUT SEES SHOT AT IRL TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's back to the future for Billy Boat, thankful his broken left
leg and pelvis have healed sufficiently to allow a return to the
driver's seat.
</P>
<P>
   Still, seven weeks off has felt like seven years, Boat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why I was adamant about coming back so quickly,'' said
Boat, whose two-race absence will end Sunday in the Radisson 200 at
Pikes Peak International Raceway. ``The longer you're out, the
longer it takes to get your rhythm back.''
</P>
<P>
   Boat suffered the injury June 28 in an Indy Racing League event
at New Hampshire International Speedway, when a car driven by Raul
Boesel pierced Boat's car and struck his left leg.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went right through the side of the car, and the nose hit me
in the thigh,'' said Boat, who lives in Glendale. ``I'm not going
to sit here and tell you that I can't still see that nose sticking
into the car, but it's something you put out of your mind because
you have to go out and do your job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been racing all my life and I've had injuries before.
It's just a situation where you get right back on the horse and go
do it again. I've got no trepidation at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Boat made his return July 28-29, when he tested at
Atlanta Motor Speedway. Boat recorded a top speed of 220.95 mph
during the test, then two weeks ago, tested again at Texas Motor
Speedway, where he topped out at a similar speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, my leg was a little weak and it took some effort to
work the clutch,'' said Boat, whose leg was repaired with an
L-shaped plate and several screws. ``But it was a lot better at
Texas. I didn't experience any pain at all. Actually, it felt
better on the racetrack than it did sitting still.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Ray substituted for Boat while he was away, recording
finishes of 15th at Dover Downs (Del.) International Raceway and
17th at Charlotte Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Ray take over was disconcerting, Boat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like somebody taking your girlfriend to the prom,''
Boat said. ``You know you should be there, but you can't.
</P>
<P>
   The worst part is we have such a great race team and a great
chance to win every time we go out there. You hate to have those
opportunities slip by.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Boat won't attempt to ease back into the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that I've had a couple of chances to test, I feel very
comfortable in the car,'' said Boat, who has slipped from fourth to
12th in the IRL drivers standings and trails series leader Scott
Sharp by nearly 100 points (214-122).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect to have any type of (learning) curve coming
back at all. I think I'll be right back up to speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel like we've got a chance to win the championship,
and with only four races left, that's not enough time to ease back
into it. We'll be jumping in with both feet.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
