<SLUG> BC-CAR-TRANSAM-NEVILLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONANS CONSIDERED RISING TRANS-AM STARS  
 ROOKIES WINLESS BUT 3RD, 7TH IN DRIVER STANDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should they choose to stay put, Phoenix-area drivers Chris
Neville and Ross Thompson have been endorsed as potential Sports
Car Club of America Trans-Am stars.
</P>
<P>
   Who says?
</P>
<P>
   Bill Saunders, one of the circuit's top drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ``will'' be stars if they decide to stay in Trans-Am,''
said Saunders, who trails only teammate Paul Gentilozzi in the
driver standings with three races remaining this season. ``They're
terrific young men. A lot of times, new drivers come in and have
attitudes that are difficult to deal with. These two guys are the
exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've adapted to Trans-Am, and it's not that easy to adapt
to these cars.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Neville has adapted slightly quicker than
Thompson, who has fallen down the driving ladder after mixing it up
with the leaders through much of the first half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Poor finishes due to mechanical failures or rotten luck have
dropped Thompson, who attended Corona del Sol High School, to
seventh in the overall driver standings and third in the rookie
points chase.
</P>
<P>
   Neville, who lives in Scottsdale, has a large lead in the rookie
standings and is in third place overall, only two points behind
Saunders, who trails Gentilozzi by 70 points.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Neville nor Thompson has won, hardly a sin for the two
rookies. Gentilozzi (seven) and Saunders (two) have combined to win
nine of 10 races. Lou Gigliotti has the other victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a chance to catch (Saunders), but (Gentilozzi) is
running away with it,'' Neville said. ``That team has spent a lot
of money testing their cars, and like any professional sport, the
more money you spend, the better team you're going to be. Our
budget is probably 40 percent of their budget, which I would guess
is around $800,000 to $1 million per car.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not unhappy with our season. I never guessed we'd be
this successful. My goal was to be Rookie of the Year, but I didn't
realize I'd be third in points. It's been a pleasant surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Neville, 26, and Thompson, 24, met while working at the Bob
Bondurant School of High Performance Driving, where they are
instructors when not racing.
</P>
<P>
   They share a similar goal, which, at present, is to remain in
Trans-Am. Down the road, however, Neville is eyeing a possible
NASCAR Winston Cup career, and Thompson hopes a NASCAR Craftsman
Truck Series ride or one on the Championship Auto Racing Teams
circuit is awaiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't start racing until I got out of high school,''
Thompson said. ``I played mostly football and ran on the track
team. But I was always a racing fan. I used to ride a dirt bike all
the time. I thought one day I'd be the next Jeremy McGrath.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I took a course at the Bondurant school when I graduated
from Corona, and I really got the bug.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson spent a couple of seasons driving in a minor series,
then was forced to the sidelines when something happened that
plagues many racers. He ran out of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't race for two years,'' Thompson lamented.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson returned last season, driving a Camaro in a national
sedan series on the SCCA club level. In doing so, Thompson
impressed car owner Mike Lewis, who hired the Scottsdale driver to
drive a Ford Mustang Cobra this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, it was going well,'' Thompson said. ``Then we had
a string of five races that I wouldn't wish upon anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Neville, who moved to the Valley three years ago from Chicago,
didn't begin racing full time until he completed college at
Indiana-Purdue with a degree in communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents always wanted me to go to college, and I mostly did
it for them,'' Neville said. ``But I'm glad I did. College helped
me figure out how to put proposals together to find money from
potential sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realized the best way to try and make it was to be an
instructor, and that's when I sent Bondurant a resume. I had done
some racing before that, and one of the guys I raced against was
Bill Cooper, who was Bondurant's chief instructor. That helped me
get my foot in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Neville spent several seasons in the SCCA World Challenge
circuit before he and car owner Jim Derhaag, a retired driver,
struck a deal this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim's got the second most starts ever in Trans-Am, and he was
looking to get back into the sport as a car owner,'' said Neville,
driver of the ARCO Chevy Camaro. ``I came up with a little bit of
sponsorship money and we got going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm trying to put together a program for another
year in Trans-Am. But I only want to do it if I can be a major
contender, which means more budget and test time. This year, I
don't consider myself a contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that doesn't happen, I want to do as many stock car races
as possible. I have to look down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been contacted by some other (Trans-Am) teams, but
whatever I do, I need to stay with Ford because I've got close
allies with them,'' Thompson said. ``If things don't work out, I
wouldn't mind trying the (NASCAR) trucks or CART. I just need to
keep racing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
