<SLUG> BC-CAR-ARMIJO-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNGER EARNHARDT GETS ROLLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watch out, Jeff Gordon. Your future nemesis and budding rival
may be right around the next bend.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Earnhardt, but not that Earnhardt. Not the
seven-time NASCAR Winston Cup champion Earnhardt, the one with 71
career victories and enough trophies to fill a shopping mall.
</P>
<P>
   Uh-uh.
</P>
<P>
   This Earnhardt is only 23 years old, has blondish hair and
doesn't yet know how to say no to questions or autograph requests.
</P>
<P>
   Meet Dale Earnhardt Jr., the nicest, humblest stock-car driver
this side of a parish priest.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Earnhardt jumped from nowhere into the NASCAR Busch
Series this season, and 21 races later, is in an excellent position
to capture the driving title as a rookie. Entering Sunday's race at
Michigan Speedway, Earnhardt has a series-high five wins (no one
else has more than two) and leads the standings by 48 points over
runner-up Matt Kenseth.
</P>
<P>
   Such early success might turn some sports celebrities into
instant Albert Belle-types. Not Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt doesn't appear to have an ornery bone or an arrogant
thought in his body, which he still drags to the race shop most
every day.
</P>
<P>
   And while so many trips into victory lane have produced numerous
sponsorship and other demands for his time, Earnhardt still hasn't
lost sight of what winning means most.
</P>
<P>
   And it has little, if nothing, to do with seeing his name in
headlines and on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't know that (my racing) is all for my
daddy,'' Earnhardt said. ``When I win races, it puts a smile on his
face. I don't care much about anything else as far as the bonuses
that come along with winning . . . the money, the exposure, the
fame or whatnot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all just to make him happy. It's what it's all about to
me. He's my daddy and I love him to death. And I want to do it for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Daddy should be proud.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the younger Earnhardt envisioned such a fast start to
his Busch career. But he refuses to believe he is ready to take the
next step, which would the NASCAR Winston Cup circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's humility is surpassed only by his obvious talents,
which haven't gone unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup car owner Bud Moore was around when NASCAR first
began 50 years ago, and many of his former drivers would fill a
who's who list of some of the sport's biggest names: drivers such
as Bobby Allison, David Pearson, Cale Yarborough, Buddy Baker, Joe
Weatherly and, uh, Dale Earnhardt Sr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to tell you, he's very stout,'' Moore said. ``He's
an up-and-coming driver, just like his daddy. He's determined to
make races, and he's got the ability to win races. I see no end to
him winning races.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. plans to honor his current contract, which
includes another season of Busch racing in 1999. Then, Earnhardt,
who drives his father's Busch car, is expected to move upward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm definitely still a rookie,'' Earnhardt said. ``I have a
lot of polishing and molding to do on some of my skills. I have to
learn to be a lot more patient.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's learning curve also entails gaining experience off
the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea we were going to do this well,'' he said. ``But
we came out of the box running good and we've become a hot topic.
We've had to become somebody right away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never met with sponsors before. I'd done some autograph
sessions, but nothing with like 3,000 race fans standing in line.
I've just always been a T-shirt-and-jeans guy. But I don't think
that's what cuts it anymore. I've got to clean up my act a little
bit, start shaving every day, things like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big change, and I've had to learn a lot of things.
It's been overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   But it hasn't derailed Earnhardt, who has been compared to
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flattered to even be mentioned in the same sentence with
the man,'' Earnhardt said. ``He's doing an excellent job. But I'm
not one to boast about it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for one day possibly challenging Gordon for NASCAR
superiority, Earnhardt welcomes the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might eat my words, but I think I'm ready for something like
that,'' Earnhardt said. ``I'd like to get in the mix with him and
just be competitive. Jeff Gordon is one of the best, if not ``the''
best, out there right now. If I can be competitive, I'd be
happy.'' &QL; 
Mark Armijo can be reached at 602-444-8323 or at
mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
