r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PAYBACK-AZR &LR;      08-15 1642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAYBACK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELDERLY WOMEN TURN TABLES ON TORMENTORS, RESEARCH INDICATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 70-something woman had survived a long marriage of abuse.
She had been thrown through a storm door, suffering severe cuts.
She had been tossed into a wall, dislocating her shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Year after year, the attacks had come.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was her turn. Her husband was in the next room, elderly,
helpless, pleading for his dinner.
</P>
<P>
   But she wasn't going to feed him _ at least for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should he eat a decent meal when for 30 years I suffered
through every supper we ever had?'' she told a family friend as the
food grew cold.
</P>
<P>
   A longtime abuser was getting his payback, thought the younger
woman, now an Arizona elder-issues professional _ probably every
moment, every day, for as long as he would last.
</P>
<P>
   Tragic as they may be, such situations may be far more
widespread than previously thought, according to researchers
looking more carefully into the elder years of abusive marriages.
</P>
<P>
   As couples live longer, with women staying healthier than their
men, experts say instances of extended payback may be steadily
increasing.
</P>
<P>
   The state identified women as the perpetrators in 65 of 168
cases of elder spousal abuse from July 1996 through July 1997,
according to Adult Protective Service records.
</P>
<P>
   As with most of the cases involving elder men, abuse usually
took the form of neglect, although sometimes it was physical
violence.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows for sure how much elder abuse exists. Only a small
fraction of elder-abuse cases are officially reported. Cases where
the man is being abused are thought to be reported even less often.
</P>
<P>
   The woman who witnessed the above scene didn't report the
incident and apologized for the actions of the older woman: ``This
was not a mean, vindictive woman, but a beaten-down person,'' she
explained, remembering her own years of pain as the victim of an
abusive husband.
</P>
<P>
   University of Arizona researcher Elaine Rousseau believes
payback situations aren't isolated. For years, Rousseau, an expert
on domestic abuse, has heard stories about long-abused wives who
turned the tables in old age. She is doing research to learn more
about what goes on behind the closed doors of older couples with
abuse histories.
</P>
<P>
   Elders generally don't talk about the subject, and their kids
and contemporaries often look the other way. Older men won't easily
admit being physically outmatched by a woman. Most physicians,
according to caseworkers, make excuses for not seeing the obvious,
and many are not prepared to speak candidly to victims and offer
program advice.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic abuse started coming into the public spotlight in the
1960s when people who are now in their 70s and 80s were
middle-aged. If they were in abusive situations, they kept it to
themselves and usually stayed married _ the ``shut up and put up''
generation. Only a small percentage of people over 65 are divorced.
</P>
<P>
   After telling her nurse practitioner students at the University
of Phoenix how to assess older women for signs of abuse, Jody
Pelusi asked them whether they should do the same for men.
</P>
<P>
   The room went quiet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think it occurs?'' Pelusi asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Men wouldn't admit it if they were abused anyway,'' a student
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we should ignore it?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   In her job as a nurse practitioner and cancer-outreach
coordinator for Maryvale Medical Center, she has seen an increasing
number of abused older men. Sometimes the abuse comes at the hands
of their grown children. When the abuser is the wife, it is more
likely to be emotional abuse or neglect, she observed.
</P>
<P>
   One case involved a prominent older couple in a rural Arizona
community. The husband had been a longtime drinker and the wife a
full-time homemaker.
</P>
<P>
   The wife continually complained that, from the early days of
their marriage, he verbally abused her. When he came down with a
chronic disabling condition, she grew more resentful because she
was housebound. She would neglect his needs, such as making him
wait a long time before helping him to the bathroom. She needed
outside help, but in a small community that was impossible:
``Everyone would know.'' OVERWHELMED SPOUSES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes abuse isn't ``payback'' but the result of a health
condition beyond the ability of a spouse to handle.
</P>
<P>
   A person with some forms of dementia can become violent, or the
abuser may not understand the changes in their spouse _ and lash
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be very combative,'' said Scott Gardner, executive
director of the Phoenix Alzheimer's Association. ``There is a
tremendous risk for elderly abuse in early Alzheimer's.''
</P>
<P>
   During the two years Olle Steinwall's 71-year-old wife,
Constance, has been diagnosed with Alzheimer's, he has handled her
care on his own, managing to withstand the verbal abuse and
incontinence. Only recently, when she started striking him, did
Steinwall move his wife to a care facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife only weighs 125 pounds and is 5-foot-7,'' said
Steinwall, 72. ``You wouldn't think anyone who looks the way she
does has any strength, but she does.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of their 43 years of marriage the childless couple were
very close, Steinwall said. Only when Constance became physically
abusive did he seek out professionals at the Alzheimer's
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not that I can't defend myself; I don't believe in
manhandling a woman,'' he said. ``I can't handle her anymore
without something happening to me or something happening to her.'' &QL; 
TWO-WAY ABUSE &QL; 
Some abusive elder households are two-way battles, with husband and
wife taking turns as abusers and victims.
</P>
<P>
   Most elder couples stay together, fighting to the end. One Adult
Protective Services case file includes an extended battle of
neglect and abuse where the untended husband lost a leg from
diabetes and suffered from heart disease. The wife, an alcoholic
and longtime victim of his physical abuse, joined him in horrific
verbal battles.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she wanted him out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was ugly _ an ugly situation all around,'' Rousseau said.
</P>
<P>
   When the husband was put on a tranquilizer, however, the wife
decided to let him continue living at home.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of a year's cases from Adult Protective Services
that Rousseau is studying to see if patterns emerge.
</P>
<P>
   Another report describes a husband admitted to a hospital for
pneumonia who reported that his wife had physically abused him and
had for quite some time. He was unwilling to leave her, and did
return home. He said she had health problems and needed him. The
caseworker disagreed with his decision but had no power to stop
him, so long as he was legally competent.
</P>
<P>
   Most elderly abuse victims fear a nursing home or the street
more than they fear the conditions at home, according to case
workers.
</P>
<P>
   Some abuse has gone on for so long that the elders have adjusted
over the years _ they may not realize they are being abused,
according to Rosalie Wolf, of Worcester, Mass., president and
founder of the National Committee for the Prevention of Elder
Abuse.
</P>
<P>
   They may be suffering from paralyzing depression, guilt, fear,
shame, alienation, feelings of helplessness, and even
post-traumatic stress syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if they do report it, where would they go?'' Wolf asked. &QL; 
CAUSE A GRAY AREA &QL; 
Alice Ghareib, domestic-violence specialist with the Maricopa
County Area Agency on Aging, believes that neglect is a dangerously
gray area and that each situation needs careful analysis: ``Is it
caregiver stress or is it really domestic violence? Is the
perpetrator's motive power and control over a partner?'' she asks.
</P>
<P>
   Rousseau agrees, but believes that abuse is abuse, whatever the
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Rousseau said older caregivers are allowed far more excuses than
younger people in justifying violence or negligence, she added.
</P>
<P>
   She and Rosalie Wolf say treatments that work for younger people
are not necessarily useful for elders. A support group for elderly
men in California was a flop. Many elderly people don't want to
move into shelters.
</P>
<P>
   If the chance of payback is there, it is even more important to
help older women who have been or are being abused.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Area Agency on Aging in Phoenix provides several resources
for elder victims of domestic abuse. Support groups for women over
50 have formed. Groups meet Tuesdays in the Sun City area and
Mondays in Mesa. About 60 women have gone through the groups. Many
of them have stayed in abusive relationships, but obtained new
coping skills and emotional support. In an emergency-housing
program that began a year ago, victims can stay up to two weeks in
any of 21 adult care and adult foster homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could do more outreach for men,'' Ghareib said. ``My
director said that if we could get just two men to come forward and
say they need help, I could start working on a program for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Elder men are a tough case.
</P>
<P>
   ``While more men may be abused, we still have a long way to go
to prove that is so,'' said Sue Beastall, a family therapist who
leads the local support groups for women. She points out that new
family-violence textbooks still report that 80 to 85 percent of
victims of abuse are women.
</P>
<P>
   What can be done if the traditional approaches to domestic abuse
don't quite work for elders?
</P>
<P>
   Wolf says counseling is helpful, especially if a person doesn't
want to leave the home. Reducing isolation is key: having someone
visit the home on a regular basis or taking advantage of adult
day-care programs can take some of the pressure out of a bad
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Rousseau's study on abused elderly couples is expected to be
completed next spring. &QL; 
 &UR; Maureen West can be reached at 444-8167 or maureen.west &LR; pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
