<HEADLINE>
APACHES TO DEFY DEMAND FOR PRAYER PERMITS ON MT. GRAHAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The University of Arizona is requiring Native Americans to
obtain prayer permits before they cross the top of Mount Graham
near the university's $200 million telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   The university established the permits in an effort to
accommodate traditional-spiritual San Carlos Apaches and other
native peoples who hold sacred the high peaks of the Pinaleno
Mountains, 120 miles southeast of Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Native American representatives say the permits are an attack on
their religious freedom, and they say they will not seek the
permits today when more than 80 Indians from across Arizona ascend
the 10,700-foot mountain, the nation's southernmost alpine forest
ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   Wendsler Noise, a San Carlos Apache, is organizing a 100-mile
run from his home on the reservation to near the top of the
mountain. Near the summit, Noise will lead 15 traditional-spiritual
Apaches to protest the university's telescopes, which they contend
interfere with their spiritual rites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I should have a permit. We are the original
inhabitants of this land. We are not going to vandalize their
telescopes. They know that for all these (hundreds) of years, the
Apaches have gone there to pray. I can't see why we need permits
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Noise was arrested last year for trespassing when he ventured
near the telescopes while he was praying for his 10-year-old
daughter's impending passage into womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   Noise, a former tribal council member who repeatedly voted to
oppose the telescopes, was acquitted in Graham County Superior
Court. After his acquittal, he said he hoped that the UA would
liberalize its visitation policies.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the university came up with the prayer-permit policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some confusion about how you acquire permission to
come into the area,'' said Michael Cusanovich, UA vice president
for research and graduate studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a policy to make it clear to the public _ or in this
case, Indian people _ that if they want to come in, we encourage
that, but that we would make permits available to them,''
Cusanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not meant to be restrictive. It's meant to be
inclusive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the university never made a public announcement of the
prayer-permit policy, and few knew of its existence until last
month, when environmentalists obtained a copy of the policy through
a federal freedom of information request.
</P>
<P>
   The policy requires that permission be requested in writing, at
least two business days before a visit, and include a description
of where on the mountain the prayers will take place.
</P>
<P>
   The persons requesting the permit and all members of their party
must be enrolled members of a federally recognized tribe. In
addition, they must receive permission from the U.S. Forest Service
to enter the 1,600-acre refugium of the endangered Mount Graham red
squirrel.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Silver, conservation coordinator for the Southwest Center
for Biological Diversity, said the university's prayer policy is
not only offensive to Native Americans but shuts out everyone else
from visiting the high peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Silver contends that the telescope project would never have been
built if Congress had not passed specific exemptions to the
Endangered Species Act and other environmental laws in 1988 and _
when the project ran afoul of the laws again _ in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In an Oct. 7 letter to the Forest Service, the university said,
``The intent of this policy is to ensure that opportunities for
access remain for those Native Americans whose religious beliefs
call for worship on our site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Second, given the level of construction activity on the Large
Binocular Telescope site, we believe that a written policy is
essential to protect the safety of those visiting the . . . site as
well as to provide for security,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Cusanovich said the site has been plagued by ``monkeywrenching''
in the past, including nails scattered on roads, sugar poured in
gas tanks, locks glued shut and drain pipes stuffed to cause roads
to wash out.
</P>
<P>
   While no one has been caught, Cusanovich blames
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what these guys do for a living, as far as I can
tell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Two smaller telescopes were dedicated on Mount Graham in 1993.
By the end of this year, the containment building for the Large
Binocular Telescope will be completed.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, electrical and other interior construction
and telescope mounts will be done. By the summer of 2000,
astronomers may be ready to install the first of two
33-foot-diameter mirrors, making it one of the world's largest and
most powerful optical astronomy instruments. &QL; 
 &UR; Steve Yozwiak can be reached at 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
