<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS FALL FROM AL WEST LEAD WITH 6-4 LOSS TO YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Right-hander Aaron Sele considered his pitching
performance worthy of victory.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the glove, Sele said, that failed him during the
Rangers' 6-4 loss to the New York Yankees last night at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' three-run seventh inning began with a ground ball
through the middle of the infield that resulted in the first of
five base hits and the Rangers' third consecutive loss.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the Rangers will begin play today staring at a half-game
deficit in the American League West after the Anaheim Angels' 7-5
victory against the Blue Jays last night in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The three-run inning gave the Yankees what proved to be an
insurmountable five-run advantage. The Rangers, though, put a scare
into baseball's best with a late-innings rally that forced Yankees
manager Joe Torre to summon closer Mariano Rivera from the bullpen
in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a case where I felt I threw the ball well enough to win a
game we needed to win,'' Sele said. ``If I field that ground ball,
we win the ballgame, 4-3. That's the way I look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, who improved to 60 games over .500 for the first
time since their 1939 ballclub finished the season with a 106-45
record, removed most of the doubt of this outcome with their
seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Sele (13-10) fooled left fielder Chad Curtis with a changeup,
yet Curtis' big swing fooled the pitcher. Sele expected the ball to
be hit harder, and the ground ball went through the infield for a
one-out single.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was supposed to be there and it wasn't,'' Sele said. ``You
watch the ball go by and you have no idea how you missed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sele answered the base hit with a strikeout of third baseman
Scott Brosius, but catcher Joe Girardi responded with the first of
three consecutive hits against the AL All-Star.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Chuck Knoblauch drove the first run home by
fighting off a 1-2 fastball in on his fists and dumping a bloop
single into shallow center field. The next two runs scored on a
two-strike single from shortstop Derek Jeter, and that ended Sele's
evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Aaron threw the ball extremely well,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``I thought he pitched a lot like Rick
Helling did (Thursday) night. He kept us in the ballgame for 62/3
innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the Yankees did most of their damage when Sele pitched
ahead in the count. Sele surrendered solo home runs to center
fielder Bernie Williams and Knoblauch on counts of 1-2 and 0-1,
respectively. The two run-scoring hits in the seventh inning were
on two-strike pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're playing the best team in baseball,'' said Sele, who
surrendered six runs on eight hits. ``They're not just going to
give in with two strikes and let you have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees left-hander Andy Pettitte, who surrendered a
fifth-inning solo home run to third baseman Todd Zeile, departed in
the eighth inning after consecutive singles by shortstop Royce
Clayton and second baseman Mark McLemore.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored twice with a sacrifice fly from center
fielder Tom Goodwin and a run-scoring single by first baseman Will
Clark off right-hander Ramiro Mendoza. The latter forced Rivera
into the game, who induced an inning-ending ground ball from
catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Mike Simms crushed a ninth-inning slider from
Rivera to pull the Rangers within two runs, but the Yankees' closer
induced a game-ending, double-play ground ball from second baseman
Mark McLemore for his 32nd save.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps two seventh-inning singles _ neither hit well _ by
Curtis and Knoblauch separated the Rangers from their fifth loss in
six games this season to the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to take anything away from them,'' Oates said.
``Look at the eighth inning: They smoked three balls and got
nothing out of it. They're doing what it takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers and Sele did not.
</P>
</TEXT>
