<HEADLINE>
SUTTON SEES NUMBER RETIRED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Don Sutton, the winningest pitcher in Dodgers
history who was inducted in baseball's Hall of Fame on July 26, had
his No.20 retired by the club during pregame ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, who recorded 233 of his 324 career victories with the
Los Angeles Dodgers, became the 10th player to have his number
retired by the club. He also had his likeness unveiled on the
outfield wall near the right-field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the appearance of Dodgers greats Pee Wee Reese and
Sandy Koufax and his first big-league pitching coach, Red Adams,
that forced Sutton to fight back tears during his acceptance
speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected to win 300 and I hoped to make the Hall of Fame,
but I never planned for this,'' said Sutton, now an Atlanta Braves
broadcaster. ``I never really thought about having my number up
there. Those guys are legends in Dodger history. It's a very
emotional night, and it's going to take a while to recover from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton pitched with the Dodgers from 1966-80 and returned
briefly in 1988. He also pitched with Houston, Milwaukee, Oakland
and the Angels. Last Monday marked the 10th anniversary of the last
day of his 23-year career. He was released by the Dodgers to make
room for a promising right-hander, Ramon Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield out, Mondesi in: Gary Sheffield, who ended an 0-for-18
slump Thursday night, was sidelined Friday with a sprained right
thumb. Sheffield injured his thumb sliding into third base on a
stolen base in the third inning. Last season, Sheffield was placed
on the 15-day disabled list with an injury to his left thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi returned to the lineup Friday after fouling a pitch off
his left ankle Thursday night. Mondesi was removed from the final
game of the Florida series in the fifth inning and taken to
Centinela Hospital Medical Center for precautionary x-rays, which
were negative.
</P>
<P>
   Batting practice was canceled Friday because of the Sutton
retirement ceremony, so Sheffield and Mondesi did not arrive at
Dodger Stadium until 5:30 p.m. ``We didn't know until then who
could play and who couldn't,'' manager Glenn Hoffman said. ``I made
out four different lineups today.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick hits: Carl Pease, mayor of Vero Beach, Fla., the Dodgers'
spring training site for the past 50 years, was a guest of former
club president Peter O'Malley at Friday's game. There is fear in
Vero Beach that, with the new ownership, the Dodgers will move
their training camp to Arizona, closer to their fan base.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0017 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5310 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-15 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THIRD STRAIGHT GAME, M'S BLOWN OUT IN BIG INNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM STREET  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Another disastrous inning Friday night kept the
Mariners' once-promising road trip spinning out of control.
</P>
<P>
   Six runs in an inning one night. Seven the next day. And then
nine.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we give 'em up, we really give 'em up, don't we?''
manager Lou Piniella said after the Chicago White Sox turned a
pitching duel between starters Ken Cloude and Mike Sirotko into a
14-2 rout before 22,713 fans at Comiskey Park.
</P>
<P>
   Only the inning changed.
</P>
<P>
   After being hammered in the seventh inning twice in Toronto, the
Mariners were bludgeoned by a nine-run sixth inning Friday _ the
most runs they have allowed in an inning this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three bad innings in three different games,'' said Piniella.
</P>
<P>
   The M's started this nine-game road trip with four straight wins
in Detroit. They have lost the past three and trail first-place
Anaheim by 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a time for scoreboard watching. Unless you are Jerry
Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We watch the scoreboard,'' the White Sox manager said. ``Not
in the sense that we can catch anyone. We watch to see how many
runs we score.''
</P>
<P>
   A whole bunch Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Sox designated hitter Frank Thomas singled and doubled, hit his
20th home run and drove in three runs. Albert Belle hit the 300th
and 301st doubles of his career and drove in four runs. And Robin
Ventura capped the 16-hit barrage off the suddenly
once-again-hittable Mariner pitching staff with a solo homer.
</P>
<P>
   Although Ken Griffey Jr. emerged from an August slump with three
hits, a misplay by fellow All-Star Alex Rodriguez provided an
opening in the sixth inning that the entire White Sox lineup
charged through.
</P>
<P>
   Cloude, trailing 2-1 when the sixth began, seemingly had kept
the inning in relative check before the onslaught. The right-hander
had surrendered two runs and there were runners on first and third
when Magglio Ordonez hit a grounder to Rodriguez's left.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mariner shortstop got to the ball, which routinely would
have been an inning-ending double play, it skidded off his glove
for an error, and Cloude never recorded another out.
</P>
<P>
   Mariner reliever Bob Wells fared even worse, allowing three hits
and four runs, including Thomas' towering homer to left-center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have ended the inning,'' Cloude said of the grounder
by Ordonez, ``but the ball hit the lip (of the grass) and stayed
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloude tried not to get too down after his eighth loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to tip your cap to the hitters,'' he said.
``They put the ball in play, and it just goes to show what can
happen. The key is keeping the little guys off base and limiting
the damage Thomas and Belle can do to you.''
</P>
<P>
   And he didn't keep the little guys off base.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Durham, the leadoff batter, went 4-for-5. Mike Caruso, the
No. 2 hitter, reached base four times and scored four runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some good pitches, but some bad ones, too,'' Cloude
said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of the bad ones occurred in the decisive sixth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken was sailing along pretty well,'' Piniella said. ``When
he's had difficulty this year, he's not been able to work himself
out of the middle part of the ballgame. Same thing (Friday).''
</P>
<P>
   Sirotka, who improved to 12-10 with his fourth win in his past
five decisions, mastered the Mariners by mostly staying on the
outside part of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albert's on fire, and we're much better defensively,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kid threw strikes and got ahead of the hitters,'' Piniella
said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey's second hit of the game helped produce Seattle's first
run. The Mariner center fielder stole second, his 16th theft of the
season, and scored on Edgar Martinez's single. That pulled the M's
even at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Junior swung the bat much better, and that's good to see,''
said Piniella of Griffey, who had been 8-for-41 this month. ``Now,
we have to get David (Segui) going.''
</P>
<P>
   Segui, one of the American League's batting average leaders
before injuring his right knee in a freak accident in Detroit, is
1-for-11 since returning to the lineup after missing four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days off haven't helped him,'' Piniella said. ``He lost
his rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Same goes for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the off-days (Monday and Thursday) helped us,''
the manager added. ``Let's see if we can get get into a rhythm and
start playing better.''
</P>
<P>
   And most of all, stop surrendering big innings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
