<HEADLINE>
SEAHAWKS SEEK QUICK STOP, TEAM LEADER IN NO. 1 DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, B.C. _ Michael Sinclair was not smiling, and that is
unusual.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear the Pro Bowl defensive end has ample reason to
beam. After all, the subject on the eve of Saturday night's
American Bowl game against the San Francisco 49ers was how well the
Seahawks' No. 1 defensive unit has played in the team's first two
preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   In 13 series against the Dallas Cowboys and Indianapolis Colts,
Sinclair and his fellow Seahaw starters have forced six
three-and-outs, come up with two turnovers and squelched another
drive by batting down a pass as time expired in the first half.
They have allowed two touchdowns and a field goal, but each was the
result of, or set up by, a mental mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers like that will allow a defense to rank among the NFL's
top 10, as the Seahawks did last year. Efforts like that also will
allow the Seahawks to win a lot of games, which they haven't done
since going 10-6 in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   But something is missing, and it's not just Sinclair's trademark
Chesire-cat grin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, you can say we've played pretty well, but we've got to
kill that first series,'' Sinclair said. ``We can't let it be a
wake-up call and then go three-and-out maybe six or seven times.''
</P>
<P>
   In the opener at Dallas two weeks ago, the Seahawks allowed the
Cowboys to move to the 40-yard line before forcing a punt. Worse
yet _ much worse _ cornerback Shawn Springs blew a coverage in last
week's game against Indianapolis that resulted in a 48-yard TD pass
on the Colts' opening possession.
</P>
<P>
   ``That first drive, we have to stop that like right now,''
Sinclair said. ``That sets the tempo for the game. So stopping that
first drive has to become our signature.''
</P>
<P>
   For whatever reason, that has been as difficult to do as trying
to decipher why the Seahawk defense has yet to become as dominant
on the field as it appears on paper.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Allen has an idea, and who knows the Seahawks' defense
any better? With the possible exception of John Elway, no player
has been as productive over the years against the Seahawks as
Allen. He hurt them running, receiving and even passing in 16
seasons with the Los Angeles Raiders and Kansas City Chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, they've been sort of an enigma,'' Allen, now a CBS
studio analyst for NFL games, said Friday. ``At least of late,
they've always had excellent talent, but it just hasn't come
together completely for this team like a lot of people envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder why some teams have so much success against them. I
was always sort of perplexed by that,'' he said. ``Maybe it's a
lack of leadership. Not from the coaches, but the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen wasn't trying to be critical, just analytical.
</P>
<P>
   When Allen broke into the league in 1982, Kenny Easley was just
hitting his stride while hitting anything and everything in his
stride as Seattle's strong safety. Easley was driven and the
driving force behind a defense that did more with less than the
Seahawks have now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always sort of puzzled me why, as talented as they are,
they have not come together,'' Allen said. ``I don't mean to slight
anybody, but who's the leader of this defense?''
</P>
<P>
   To prove his point, Allen quizzed a couple of players as they
left the field at B.C. Place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose team is this?'' he asked Pro Bowl free safety Darryl
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren Moon's, I guess,'' was Williams' less-than-convincing
answer. Besides, Moon plays offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose team is this?'' Allen then asked linebacker Chad Brown,
the team's leading tackler last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we're still waiting to determine,'' Brown
replied.
</P>
<P>
   Allen didn't have to offer an I-told-you-so. The sly smile on
his face showed he had proved his point.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's up to one of the Seahawk defenders to prove him wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
