<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TWINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX CELEBRATE AFTER BASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Red Sox and Twins returned to bountiful Friday night,
turning Updike's lyric little bandbox in the Back Bay into the big
league version of a roadside batting cage.
</P>
<P>
   Drop a dollar's worth of quarters into the machine, cock bat,
swing for downtown, and keep swinging until someone turns out the
lights.
</P>
<P>
   When the quarters finally ran out at Fenway Park, it was the Sox
who were left standing, their bats red hot in a wild 13-12 triumph
that was decided on Donnie Sadler's two-run single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest-working guy out there,'' said Sox manager Jimy
Williams, who had seen his club outlast the Twins, 8-7, the
previous night, ``was the guy changing the numbers on the
scoreboard.''
</P>
<P>
   If it gets any busier when the clubs meet tonight at the Fens,
Vanna White will have to be summoned to work the big board.
</P>
<P>
   Sadler, who went 3 for 4 with three RBIs, drove home Troy
O'Leary and Jason Varitek to give the Sox a 13-11 lead in the
seventh, and they hung on for their 71st win of the season. The
wild 'n' crazy Sox moved 23 games over .500.
</P>
<P>
   A sellout crowd of 32,888 (No. 25 this season) saw hometown
starter Tim Wakefield fall into a 6-0 deficit in the third, a lead
that was erased in the bottom of the inning when the Sox sent 10
hitters to the plate and scored a half-dozen runs on six hits,
capped by Mike Stanley's two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of 3 hours 28 minutes, the Sox lost leads of 8-6
and 9-8. They moved in front, 11-9, in the bottom of the fifth on
Damon Buford's two-run triple, but the Twins tied it again, 11-11,
in the seventh on a two-run double by Paul Molitor. For yet another
night in the Fens, the ups and downs resembled the recent whipsaw
moves of the Dow Jones Industrial Average.
</P>
<P>
   Get the idea out there in Red Sox Nation? If the Townies do make
it to the national stage in October, the viewing audience will be
warned not to watch the broadcast without donning catcher's mask
and chest protector.
</P>
<P>
   The top of the ninth, left in the hands of Sox reliever Tom
Gordon, mimicked much of the night. Pat Meares led off with a walk,
moved to second on Molitor's one-out single to right, and took
third when Matt Lawton drew a pass on four pitches. Marty Cordova
chopped a grounder to first, easily scooped by Mo Vaughn for a soft
toss to Gordon covering the bag. But Gordon missed the touch with
his right foot, Cordova was safe, and Meares skipped home with the
12th Minnesota run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost it _ I thought it was a popup,'' said Gordon, who hung
on for his 31st consecutive save, the longest current streak in the
bigs, and 34th of the season. ``That's why I reacted late and
missed the bag. Well, I might have just touched it with the side of
my foot, but if I did, there was no way to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   It took Gordon two grounders, and perhaps the tiniest skip of a
heartbeat, to end it. First, Todd Walker hit a grounder to third
that John Valentin scooped and fired home in time to erase Molitor.
Bases still loaded. Ron Coomer, who hours before socked a homer off
the gargantuan Coke bottles, then drilled one to third. Valentin
made a quick scoop of the shot _ a sure two-run single if it got
through _ and ended the evening by stepping on third base for the
force on Cordova.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what he gets paid for; he should make those,'' kidded
Gordon. ``Really, that was a beautiful play. He hit that pretty
hard. I left it out over the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   In two nights, the clubs have combined for 38 runs. They
combined for 32 hits Friday night, with every starter on each side
contributing at least one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was still early in the game,'' said Stanley, thinking back
to when the Sox were looking at the 6-0 deficit. ``It was one of
those things where we said, `OK, just start pecking away.' And it
gave us a chance to be in the ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Game time Sunday: 5 p.m. Bring lots of quarters and an extra
eraser if you plan to keep score.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
