</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DIAMONDBACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT DIAMONDBACKS, 3-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Last season, Rick Reed, a baseball journeyman,
surprised everyone by winning 13 games for the Mets. Friday night
he went one better, winning his 14th game of this season, and he
demonstrated again that he has turned into one of the National
League's best pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   In pitching seven strong innings in a 3-2 victory over the
Arizona Diamondbacks, Reed allowed just eight hits to move to 14-7
this season, his 12th and best as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not his best performance,'' Mets Manager Bobby
Valentine said. ``I thought he got away with a lot of pitches up
tonight. But it was good enough. I'm not complaining.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed (14-7) needed a little help from Dennis Cook, who pitched a
scoreless eighth, and Turk Wendell, who closed out the ninth for
his first save of the season, to surpass his season high.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell walked the first two batters he faced in the ninth, but
the next two batters _ pinch-hitters Andy Stankiewicz and Hanley
Frias _ hit grounders to short, one that Rey Ordonez was not able
to turn into a double play, another that he was.
</P>
<P>
   And, with their victory over the expansion Diamondbacks, the
Mets (65-54) were able to keep pace with the Chicago Cubs in the
National League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Mets' 17th in their last 25 games, as they
pulled a season-high 11 games over .500 for the fifth time this
year. Because Chicago won in Houston Friday evening, the Mets still
trail the Cubs by one-half game in the post-season chase.
</P>
<P>
   Reed, a first-time All-Star selection this season, struck out
five and did not walk a batter to lower his walk per nine inning
average to 1.2, tying him with Atlanta's Greg Maddux for the
stingiest ratio in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   A career 22-24 pitcher coming into this season, Reed's best
season was 1997, when he went 13-9 with a 2.89 earned run average
for the Mets. Reed, starting his 24th game of the year Friday
night, was coming off one of the worst performances of his career.
</P>
<P>
   One week earlier in Denver, Reed had allowed 12 hits and 7 runs
_ both tying his career highs _ in an 8-7 victory over the Colorado
Rockies. Reed nearly squandered a 7-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Friday evening, in the Mets' first game at Bank One Ballpark,
Reed fell behind early. He allowed a one-out single in the second
to Karim Garcia, who took third on a long Jay Bell fly to left and
then scored on a Tony Batista single for a 1-0 Arizona lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored in the top of the fourth off the Arizona
right-hander Amaury Telemaco. John Olerud, the league's batting
leader when the day began, opened the inning by lining a single to
center for his second hit of the game. One out later, Brian McRae
drove a full-count offering over the fence in left-center field.
The home run was McRae's 18th of the season, a career high, putting
the Mets ahead by 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   The lead did not last the inning, however. Garcia belted a
one-out home run into the pool area beyond the fence in
right-center field to tie the score at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets rallied again in the fifth, as Ordonez singled to
left-center to open the inning. Reed sacrificed Ordonez to second,
and Ordonez moved to third on a Telemaco wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Telemaco went to 2-2 on Tony Phillips before Phillips grounded a
run-scoring single just wide of Travis Lee at first base for a 3-2
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then the managing began. After Todd Hundley struck out for the
second time in three at-bats to end the Mets' sixth, Valentine
switched Phillips from right to left, moved Lenny Harris from third
to right and inserted Edgardo Alfonzo into the game at third.
</P>
<P>
   The moves saved the Mets a run in the bottom of the seventh.
With Reed still clinging to the one-run lead, Batista singled to
left with one out. Damian Miller followed with a single to right.
As Harris charged the ball, Batista decided to test the new right
fielder's arm.
</P>
<P>
   Harris delivered a perfect one-hop throw to Alfonzo at third to
nail Batista for the second out, as Miller took second on the
throw. But Reed was not out of danger. The 32-year-old right-hander
hit pinch-hitter David Dellucci with a pitch to put runners on
first and second. But after the former Yankee Andy Fox nearly hit a
first-pitch, three-run home run that went just foul down the right
field line, Fox popped up to second to leave Reed two innings away
from his 14th victory with a lead the bullpen was called on to
protect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
