<HEADLINE>
RENEGADES, WINGS GAIN WLEAGUE FINAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUPEN FOFARIA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRAMINGHAM _ It's too bad the Boston Renegades weren't playing
pinball Friday night. Given all the shots that went off players'
bodies and the four that hit the top bar of the goal box, they
could have had the game easily in hand before the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, they were playing soccer in the W-League semifinals at
Bowditch Field, and bouncing balls were worth nothing. So the hosts
had to start using their heads _ literally.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Connors scored twice in the second half and Boston
defeated the New Jersey Stallions, 2-0, before a crowd of 1,361.
That sends the Renegades into Sunday's final against the undefeated
Raleigh Wings, who beat the Maryland Pride, 5-0, in the first
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we played well, especially in the second half, you
know, once everybody got over the nerves in the first half and
settled down and started playing,'' said team captain Amy
Heseltine. ``And what Rick (Copland, the coach) told us before the
game was get the ball to flanks and serve it far post or back post,
and that's how we won the game.''
</P>
<P>
   After a sluggish first half, the Renegades got going seven
minutes into the second as Laura Collins orchestrated a brilliant
drive down the left side. She crossed over the box and lobbed a
quick pass to Connors, who hadn't practiced with the team for a
week because of a hip flexor that she was still treating during
halftime. Connors headed the ball over a charging Amy Pseja in the
Stallion goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the back post wide open,'' said Connors, who was lifted
with 30 minutes left so she could rest her hip. ``None of the
defenders saw me running behind there, and Laura played a perfect
ball right to my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven minutes later, with the crowd still buzzing, Connors saw
the ball pop out near the goal and secured it about 8 yards from
Pseja. With a defender approaching on her right, she cocked her
left foot and blasted one, top shelf.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was easy,'' she said. ``I saw the far post open, so I
fired it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stallions didn't have such an easy time. Not only did they
face a solid performance by Renegade keeper Jen Mead, but they
plain ran out of gas trying to keep up with Connors and find
quality shots. Mead came up with two saves, both with a charging
Stallion inside the box.
</P>
<P>
   The Wings, unbeaten in 15 games this season, are the heavy
favorites to claim the title.
</P>
<P>
   But Renegade players and coaches said they aren't worried or
intimidated by Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be fun,'' said Connors, flashing a smile.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 0117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5317 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS &LR;      08-15 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Astros
</P>
<P>
   Winning streak &QL; 
ends at 7 games
</P>
<P>
   Cubs pitcher's single costs Reynolds
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Strategically, Astros manager Larry Dierker thought it was the
right move to make:
</P>
<P>
   Take a chance and pitch to No. 8 hitter Jeff Blauser, who was
batting .450 lifetime against Astros starter Shane Reynolds and had
homered an inning earlier?
</P>
<P>
   Or order an intentional walk with first and third base occupied,
load the bases and gamble with light-hitting pitcher Mark Clark?
</P>
<P>
   One decision. One wrong decision, it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Clark hit a two-run single off Reynolds with two out in the
sixth inning that broke open a two-run game as the Chicago Cubs
snapped the Astros' seven-game winning streak with a 6-4 victory
before a crowd of 45,040 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly the most unorthodox thing I've ever done
since I've had this job,'' said Dierker, whose club lost for only
the fourth time in its last 18 games. ``I think in almost every
situation it's a bad strategy to walk somebody and force a runner
into scoring position. That's not something I would believe that I
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet I thought we had a pretty good chance to have it work. It
was a very strange situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Blauser, who sent a 2-1 fastball from Reynolds over the
left-field fence in the fifth inning, had not been intentionally
walked in 330 at-bats this season. Clark was 1-for-45 (.022) before
his bloop single to center capped the Cubs' four-run sixth and put
the Astros in a 5-1 hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy is 1-for-45 and the other guy (Blauser) up there is
a nemesis for your pitcher, it seemed like the one time you might
do it,'' said Dierker, who this season has called for only 17
intentional walks, tied for second-fewest in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the Cubs' four-run sixth, the Astros toyed with a
possible 39th come-from-behind victory.
</P>
<P>
   Moises Alou hit his 33rd home run _ a two-run shot off Clark and
one of three Astros homers. Alou's blast made it 6-4 in the eighth,
and the Astros had runners at first and second in the ninth before
Cubs closer Rod Beck slammed the door for his 35th save.
</P>
<P>
   Sammy Sosa, second in the home-run chase behind St. Louis' Mark
McGwire, was kept in the ballpark to remain at 46 homers. He found
other ways to beat the Astros, going 3-for-5 with an RBI and
scoring twice.
</P>
<P>
   After dropping Milwaukee out of the NL Central chase with a
four-game sweep, the Astros were looking to deal a similar blow to
the Cubs. It appeared that might happen when Reynolds (14-8) got
eight strikeouts and allowed only one run through five innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was downhill from there.
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Morandini led off the sixth with a single, and Sosa
doubled to right-center to drive in the go-ahead run. Mark Grace
singled, and two batters later Jose Hernandez hit a run-scoring
single. Then came the intentional pass to Blauser and Clark's
two-run bloop into center.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Reynolds) looked like he was in total command of the game
when all of a sudden it's really sort of mysterious how fast it can
leave you,'' Dierker said. ``He just couldn't recover.''
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds ended with nine strikeouts in 5 innings but came up
short for the second time against the Cubs. He had 10 strikeouts in
a 2-0 loss May 6, when the Astros struck out 20 times and managed
just one infield single against Kerry Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a couple of pitches in that inning I missed my
spots and got hurt,'' said Reynolds, who had won eight of his
previous 10 decisions. ``That was pretty much the game. If you miss
some pitches against these guys, it will cost you the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Cubs manager Jim Riggleman defended Dierker's decision to walk
Blauser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a pretty good move,'' Riggleman said. ``He
knew Blauser is starting to come up (offensively) a little bit. It
took a lot of guts to make a move like that, but I thought it was
the right move.''
</P>
<P>
   Chicago added another run in the seventh on an RBI single by
Grace off reliever Trever Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Clark (7-11) allowed four runs (three home runs) and struck out
eight in 7 innings. He is 4-1 with a 3.15 ERA lifetime against the
Astros.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Berry gave the Astros a 1-0 lead in the third with his
third home run on the Astros' current homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell added a solo shot in the fifth, and Alou's two-run
blast pulled the Astros within two. Alou, who has homered in five
of the last eight games, is tied for fifth on the Astros'
single-season home-run list with 33.
</P>
<P>
   None of that power mattered Friday, though, when the game came
down to one decision and least likely of hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Was it the biggest hit of Clark's career?
</P>
<P>
   `` Yeah, I guess,'' Clark said after a long pause. ``Let's just
say I picked a real good time to get my second hit of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   And for Dierker to guess wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
