</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VAUGHN-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN WON'T BAR DUQUETTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn and Dan Duquette engaged in what appeared to be a
congenial conversation following Red Sox batting practice Friday
night at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Definition of congenial: The first baseman did not wrap the
general manager in a headlock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got no reason to have Dan Duquette in a headlock,'' said
Vaughn moments after the talk with his boss came to an uneventful
and peaceful conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   And, contrary to a report on Channel 4 Thursday night, Vaughn
said he remained open to having Duquette stay a part of the
negotiations _ provided they resume _ aimed at getting the All-Star
slugger signed to a long-term Boston deal.
</P>
<P>
   Channel 4's Bob Lobel, speaking last night from his car phone,
said his report Thursday made it clear, based on a conversation
with Vaughn, that the first baseman feels Duquette will be out of
the negotiating loop if a deal is struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's being fair to Mo, to put it that way,'' said Lobel.
``What he said was, `If it's going to get done, then John
Harrington's going to be the one to do it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the implication to Lobel was that Vaughn wouldn't be
run out of town by anyone less than Harrington, the club's chief
executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know about the report,'' said Vaughn. ``Anybody can be
involved, you know. It doesn't matter to me. (Duquette is) going to
be the general manager and he's going to do what he's got to do.
It's not about who's involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said he would not respond to the Channel 4 story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't comment on gossip presented last night,'' he said.
The GM went on to note, ``If you remember, I signed Mo to his last
contract and I made the (recent) offers in good faith for him to
stay in Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Vaughn, the conversation with Duquette last night
pertained to a photograph, the nature of which he didn't discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn sounded as if he has taken an all-business approach to
his stalled negotiations, which haven't resumed since he turned
down Boston's four-year offer worth $37 million last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say, `I can't talk to you,''' said Vaughn.
``Business is business.''
</P>
<P>
   Negotiating, said Vaughn, is not about personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing else to talk about,'' he said. ``It's like a
fax machine. Stick the numbers in and that's it. It doesn't matter
what desk it comes from ... Dan Duquette ... John Harrington ... it
doesn't matter. All the personal feelings are gone. Personal
feelings have nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if a deal with the Sox could get done, Vaughn said,
``There's always time. There's always time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
