<HEADER>
A5323 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-HNS &LR;      08-15 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Singh feasts on baked 
Sahalee, copies record
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
REDMOND, Wash. _ Sahalee Country Club put its toughest face forward
Friday at the 1998 PGA Championship, and while the names at the top
of the leader board changed, the leading number did not.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh was the man holding the top score of 4-under-par 136
following the first two rounds. Singh's 66 matched the course
record set by Tiger Woods on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Colin Montgomerie (67), Steve Stricker (68) and Scott Gump (69)
were one shot back at 137, followed by a group of five golfers at
2-under 138 that included Woods (72), Houston's Steve Elkington
(69), defending champion Davis Love III (68), Brad Faxon (68) and
Andrew Magee (68).
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-five players survived the cut at Sahalee, which was set
at 5-over-par 145. Among those heading home for the weekend were
Justin Leonard (147), Lee Westwood (150) and U.S. Open champion Lee
Janzen (148).
</P>
<P>
   There has been no rain in the Seattle area for days, and the
Sahalee tract reflected that Friday. The fairways were hard and
quick, and by the end of the second round, the baked greens were
fast and finicky.
</P>
<P>
   ``The greens got Sunday-afternoon-major hard,'' Faxon said.
``They got very crusty and dry. In the fairways, the ball was
rolling and rolling. So if you didn't hit it in the fairway, you
had a hard time making par. If you didn't hit it toward the middle
of the green, you were in trouble. It was what it's supposed to be
for a PGA.''
</P>
<P>
   And about two to three shots tougher than it was Thursday, by
Mark O'Meara's standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fairways were much firmer, much, much faster,'' said
O'Meara, who is still in the running for his third major victory of
the year. ``You could throw it in there at the greens the first
day. Today, I hit a nice little 7-iron into the last hole that hit
10 feet short of pin-high and went 25 feet past the hole. The golf
course is firming up, and the scores are going to reflect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh got a break because he had an early tee time, when the
course was at its easiest, and he took advantage of his
opportunities. Singh came out on fire, with five front-nine
birdies. He missed makable par putts twice on the back side but
hung on to match the course record with his 66.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the key was the start of my round,'' Singh said.
``That gave me confidence. And I'm hitting the ball really good,
too. I hit a lot more greens today than I did yesterday, and
obviously I putted a lot better. You've got to putt well on greens
like this. In the morning, the greens were a little bit softer and
you could actually hold the balls on the greens. But it's getting
hard and fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone who finished under par Friday was more than pleased,
including Woods, who had his share of problems but was willing to
take his 72 and move on. Woods had trouble off the tee for much of
the day and had to rely on his iron play to keep him in the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those rounds where I didn't hit the ball
particularly well,'' he said. ``I didn't give myself a lot of
chances for birdie. But I hung in there, and my short game was
great today. A lot of good saves. I'm not happy with the way I hit
the ball. But I'm pleased and ecstatic with the way I scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Love, who is trying to defend his PGA Championship title, also
left Sahalee on Friday evening a happy man. Love had one of the
latest tee times of those on the leader board, so his 68 was
especially satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only two strokes' difference from yesterday, but it's a
world of difference in the way I played,'' Love said.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker was the one player late in the day who had a good
opportunity to take the lead from Singh. Stricker got his momentum
going on the back side, making birdie on four of the first seven
holes on the back nine and taking sole possession of the lead on
No. 16 at 5 under par. But the advantage was short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   On the par-3 17th, Stricker put his tee shot into the water and
ended up making double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   ``My caddie and I couldn't really pinpoint the wind direction,
and it was swirling all day long,'' Stricker said. ``But I went
with a 5-iron and I tried to hit it fairly hard, and I didn't catch
it solid at all, and as soon as I hit it, I had a pretty good idea
it was going to come up short into the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions at Sahalee aren't likely to get easier for the final
two rounds. It is supposed to get cooler, but there is no rain in
the forecast, and unless the PGA dumped lot of water on the
fairways and greens overnight, hard and fast would be the rule, not
the exception.
</P>
<P>
   That was welcome news to all those players within striking
distance of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only two back, and that's perfect,'' Woods said. ``That's
where I really need to be. If they don't put a lot of water on the
course, it's still going to be very firm and very fast. It's going
to be very difficult to shoot a low number.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 0131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
