<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5324 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COL-HNS &LR;      08-15 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   Great expectations &QL; 
fuel second guesses
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IT was that time of the evening when during most Astros seasons _
say, 1962 through 1996, minus a couple of banner-hanging years _
much of the crowd would have turned its back on the game and headed
for the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Down two runs. Nothing going right. The bottom three in the
lineup due up.
</P>
<P>
   But these are Larry Dierker's magnificent Astros. These are the
guys who have come from behind 38 times this season and have looked
as if they could take out the '27 Yankees. Or, better yet, the '98
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   When Sean Berry, Tony Eusebio and pinch hitter Dave Clark
reached for the lumber going into the bottom of the ninth, you got
the feeling the Astros again would find a way. There would be a
final-inning home run, a bases-loaded double, to send it to extra
innings _ anything to give us something to marvel about Monday at
the office.
</P>
<P>
   You weren't the only one who thought it. The 45,040 fans at the
Astrodome believed, standing and cheering as if this was the day
everyone would go home with a Beanie Baby.
</P>
<P>
   Astros do all the right things
</P>
<P>
   Dierker thought it, anxiously shuffling around the dugout during
the final at-bat, wondering which of his players would be a hero
this time around. Cubs manager Jim Riggleman thought it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't help but notice that they have won a lot that way
all year,'' Riggleman said. ``It almost had an atmosphere of `We'll
come back and win this.'''
</P>
<P>
   But alas, the Astros didn't. The Cubs made all the plays,
including the unlikely ones, in a 6-4 win that reminded everyone
that no matter how many giveaways are scheduled for this weekend _
mouse pads, umbrellas, Beanie Babies _ every night remains Pennant
Night until the Astros can put away Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're eight games up _ we're going to have to beat the Cubs a
few times,'' Dierker said, explaining the NL Central race that
could become just that by the end of this three-game set if the
Cubs stay hot. ``We probably don't have to beat them as often as
they have to beat us, but we do have to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros will. This team is better than Chicago in every way,
if not better than all of the National League. They are Dierker's
magnificent Astros.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday night's loss shed light on an interesting twist to
the Astros now that they are a team that most everyone believes
could reach the World Series. It showed whenever there is a loss,
no longer is the water-cooler conversation going to be about the
hitter or pitcher the Astros need to acquire, or the tough upcoming
schedule, or the injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Talk is going to be about Dierker. A year ago, Dierker
honeymooned with Astros fans all the way to the division crown.
Hawaiian shirts were all the rage. He handled players and pitchers
masterfully. Nothing was Dierk's fault because, after all, he was
Dierk. The beloved Wrangler.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker under scrutiny
</P>
<P>
   But after a decision Friday night that Dierker himself called
``against the grain of my usual philosophy,'' Dierker realizes the
only thing worse than being the skipper of a bad team is being the
skipper of a great team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's under the microscope,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the glass Friday was Dierker's decision to walk Chicago's
Jeff Blauser, the No. 8 hitter, and pitch to pitcher Mark Clark,
who was a dismal 1-for-45 going into the crucial sixth-inning
at-bat. The move loaded the bases and, worse, according to the
big-league manager's manual, put another man in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, of course, cracked his bat but broke almost all Astros
hopes with a two-run single that made it 5-1. Fans shook their
heads over Dierker's decision. Then after the comeback fell short,
they called the postgame shows from cellular phones and _ could
this have happened a year ago? _ griped about the manager's call.
Dierker all but called the shows, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was certainly the most unorthodox thing I've done since
I've had this job,'' Dierker said of walking Blauser, who was a
mere 2-for-18 in his past five games. ``I thought it had a chance
to work. It didn't. That was two runs.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the ballgame. And that was Dierker's welcome to life as
the skipper of a team with great expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have pitched to him in almost every situation,''
Dierker said. ``I wouldn't believe it myself that I would have done
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did, and it told us how much things have changed for
Dierker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind (the second-guessing),'' he said. ``It's one of
those things that happen when things are going great and people are
watching you. It's what makes baseball great. Because you play
every day, there's something to talk about every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Astros fans will talk. Probably, it will be the usual
discussion about how far this team can go. But if things go bad,
then talk will be about the manager.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 0144EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
