<HEADLINE>
MONTGOMERIE BURNS U.S. SPECTATORS WITH HOT GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ For a place more whitebread than downtown
Norman Rockwell, Sahalee had an unusual PGA Championship
leaderboard Friday _ an older, wealthier version of ``We Are the
World,'' heavy on the khaki.
</P>
<P>
   One guy's from Fiji, of East Indian heritage. Another guy is
half-Thai. There's somebody from Australia, and one from Scotland.
For awhile, there was a gent, Carlos Franco, doing well from the
noted golfing hotbed of Paraguay, which produces international
sports figures as often as the Amish turn out porn stars.
</P>
<P>
   To complete this mystery box of golfing chocolates, there's even
a Gump.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the guy from Purgatory, Colin Montgomerie, who came
farther and felt better than any of his fellow heavy-mileage
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Vijay Singh, Tiger Woods, Steve Elkington and Scott
(Don't Call Me Forrest) Gump had reasons to delight in an afternoon
of sun and birds. But Montgomerie, the Scotsman who has been in the
oral crosshairs of American galleries, not only had a hot day, he
felt warm.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he was decidedly cool to discuss it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to ask you this ...'' began the inquisitor after a
round of 3-under 67 left Montgomerie one stroke off Singh's lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't then,'' Monty retorted. ``Just don't ask it. If you hate
to ask it, don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The scribe persisted: Any personal troubles on the course,
Monty?
</P>
<P>
   ``None at all,'' he said, momentarily relenting. ``The crowds
here have been super, and I've enjoyed myself playing, as I always
do in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the fact that Montgomerie is not prone to diplomacy, it
wasn't likely that he was giving the obligatory air kiss to his
Redmond hosts. But a second source is always helpful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been terrific,'' said Eimear Montgomerie, who accompanied
her husband around the course. ``The crowds have been very
supportive and polite. It's been very pleasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a completely different kettle of fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago at the U.S. Open in San Francisco, the fish was a
bit stinky. Hecklers were sufficiently annoying that police had to
accompany Montgomerie from mid-second round on. There were similar
troubles at the Open the previous year at Congressional near
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   After that tourney, in which he finished second, Montgomerie
found a quiet place away from fans and most media and cried _ a far
cry from the aristocratic arrogance that he sometimes conveys.
</P>
<P>
   Some Yank fans couldn't forgive him for his role in twice
whipping the U.S. Ryder Cup team, as well as his typically blunt
remarks about the American team. Up until this week, the verbal
sniping persisted.
</P>
<P>
   It would be swell to assume that folks here are merely more
polite. However, given the amount of airheaded applause given to
poor shotmaking by Fred Couples, Tom Watson, John Daly and others,
golf naivet &UR; ufacute &LR; e cannot be discounted. Not to mention the fact
that a lot of people just don't care about an issue that's
important only to those who tend to subscribe to the Golf Channel
and eat with Titlest-brand flatware.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the cause, the result was earnest credit for good golf,
which Montgomerie supplied. Phil Mickelson, the only American in
Monty's threesome, drew the bigger hand from the galleries, and
South African Ernie Els was cheered. But aside from one numbskull
who imitated a whining baby as Montgomerie moved up the 12th
fairway, the Seattle fish kettle was all bouillabaisse .
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, the leading money winner on the European PGA Tour
the last five years, was more pleased with the turn in his putting
fortunes than his Q-ratings. After another debacle in last month's
British Open _ he again missed the cut in his native land, for the
fifth time in the last seven Opens _ Montgomerie was sufficiently
dismayed with his greenswork to arrange a private tutorial Sunday
with renowned short-game guru Dave Pelz.
</P>
<P>
   They cleared some time at Seattle Golf Club and worked from
about 8 a.m. to 4:30 p.m., according to assistant pro Brent Webber.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him in the afternoon on the practice green, he was
hitting quite a few putts and not making many,'' Webber said.
``Obviously, something finally worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly on holes 14, 15 and 16, which would have been three
straight birdies except for a narrow miss from 20 feet on 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave oozes confidence and can only make you more confident,''
Montgomerie said. ``I've become more confident on the greens. The
greens (at Seattle Golf Club) were very similar to here, so it was
a great education.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wouldn't be the full Monty without a critical
assessment of something. He saved it for the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 18th is not a favorite of all the players,'' he said. ``I
think I speak on behalf of them all in saying that the 18th is
designed as a par-5, and I believe is a good one. Because the tee's
been moved forward 30 or 40 yards (for a par-4), the tee shot is
the problem. It's almost too tight to land it in (the fairway).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit two drives straight up the middle. And they've both
run into the rough on the right. Because of the 18th and the 6th,
you could almost call the course a par 71.''
</P>
<P>
   The man always has a shot, whether by lip or chip. Perhaps now,
he will no longer have to play it from his American bunker.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
