<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-DAYTWO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIGER TAKES TUMBLE AS SINGH SINGES SAHALEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Just when everyone thought they had Sahalee
Country Club all figured out, the Tiger Woods Open became the Equal
Opportunity Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   A faster, drier Redmond course Friday sent Woods tumbling out of
the lead and elevated four impoverished players past him as the
80th PGA Championship reached its halfway point.
</P>
<P>
   Vijay Singh, frequently a contender but never a winner in the
PGA's showcase event, broke from the pack to take a one-stroke lead
over Colin Montgomerie, Scott Gump and Steve Stricker _ all players
seeking their first victory in a golf major. Singh shot a
course-record-tying 66, matching Woods' first-day effort, and leads
with a 4-under-par 136 total.
</P>
<P>
   Woods was two strokes back, tied with five players, and grateful
to be so close. After suggesting that Sahalee wouldn't be able to
muzzle golf's greatest players and then shooting a course record,
he struggled.
</P>
<P>
   One birdie. He had seven the first day, throwing darts. Nothing
would stick Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He swore loudly while three-putting the fourth hole. He slammed
his club after launching a tee shot into a bunker on the 12th.
Finishing at 2-over-par 72, Woods was much more contrite regarding
Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't put a whole lot of water on this golf course,
it's going to be very difficult to shoot a low number,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A call for wet stuff in the Pacific Northwest is almost
ludicrous. Woods, however, won't get any help from Mother Nature,
and might be better served paying off the greenskeepers. Cooler
temperatures but no rain have been forecast for the final two
rounds Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Seventy-four players won't be around to check the moisture
levels. They missed the cut. The field, not the course, was watered
down considerably Friday. Ben Crenshaw, John Daly, David Duval, Jim
Furyk, Lee Janzen, Tom Kite, Justin Leonard, Jose-Maria Olazabal,
Jesper Parnevik, Payne Stewart, Tom Watson and Lee Westwood all
left early. As did all 25 club pros.
</P>
<P>
   Mark O'Meara is still around. The British Open and Masters
champion sits three shots off the lead as he attempts to match the
late Ben Hogan as the only player to win three majors in one
season. O'Meara shot even-par 70 in his second trip around Sahalee,
providing heroics. He chipped one in from 50 yards for a birdie on
the par-4 sixth hole, and eagled the par-5 11th with a 25-foot putt
from the fringe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pleased and proud of the fact that after two rounds, I've
played as well as I have and at least given myself a chance going
into the weekend,'' O'Meara said.
</P>
<P>
   Singh, a 35-year-old Fijian who has five PGA Tour victories and
18 more worldwide, moved in front of the field by birdieing five of
the first nine holes in the morning and playing carefully when the
course firmed up on his back nine. He used his driver just once, on
the 15th hole.
</P>
<P>
   A methodical player known for his intense practice habits, Singh
has finished fourth, fifth and 13th in the previous PGA
Championships. His final round has been the problem _ it hasn't
been enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try not to have a different mindset, but obviously the
pressure is going to make you do that,'' Singh said. ``I've played
a lot of weekends going into the lead or close to the lead. But
this is something different. ... I'm just going to go out there and
try to make it feel like a normal tournament as much as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, Singh left for an hour of work on the driving range.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, a Scotsman unpopular with American galleries, shot
67 to give himself hope. He hasn't won a major, finishing as a U.S.
Open runner-up twice and second in the 1995 PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come very close a number of times, more than most,''
Montgomerie said. ``Obviously, there's a reason why I've come over
here, and I haven't come over here to actually finish second. I've
got a good position now.''
</P>
<P>
   Stricker's situation could have been so much better. He was
5-under-par when he teed off with a 5-iron on the par-3 17th hole.
The ball sailed over five ducks floating in the greenside lake, but
didn't reach the green, 215 yards away. Wind was a factor. He took
a double-bogey 5 after getting wet, and fell from his temporary
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no clue where the wind was coming from,'' said
Stricker's caddy, Jimmy Walker. ``I probably had him so confused.
There was a lot of uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Gump provided more confusion Friday by putting his name high on
the leaderboard. People aren't used to seeing it. A former Nike
Tour player, he has struggled to keep his card, let alone win his
first PGA Tour event. He led briefly, reaching 5-under-par through
14 holes before consecutive bogeys bumped him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I haven't been in this position too many times, so
I'm having fun,'' Gump said.
</P>
<P>
   The Equal Opportunity Invitational demands nothing less.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
