<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-COUPLES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREDDIE GETTING READY FOR SERIOUS COUPLEHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ After barely making the cut Friday, Fred
Couples began thinking ahead to preparations for his next major _
his marriage to Thais Bren.
</P>
<P>
   Couples announced that he and Bren would wed Sept. 12 at a
location he wouldn't reveal yet. The wedding plans seemed to take
the sting out of a disappointing 5-over par 145 that nearly kept
him out of the final two days of the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it takes any practice to get ready for that,''
Couples said about the pending marriage ceremony. ``I know my golf
game has suffered, and maybe that will be a fun day. She's a great
lady, and I can't wait for that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the ceremony would be open to Seattle fans, Couples
chuckled: ``If they can find where this wedding is. It's going to
be very, very small, but we're going to have a reception up here
later on.''
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Couples, who is divorced from his first wife,
said he plans to return to live in the Seattle area once the rigors
of traveling the professional golf tour subside. He now lives in
the more centrally located Plano, Texas. As soon as he finished his
round Friday, Couples headed out to look at property on Camano
Island, where his good friend John Bracken of Greater Seattle Golf
Events lives.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't wait to see if he made the cut, thinking he probably
wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had that planned whether I shot 55 or 85 (Friday),'' Couples
said. ``I plan to live up there. It's not too far from Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Couples has been spending most of his time off the tour
living with Bren in Los Angeles. Bren last year underwent treatment
for breast cancer at the same time Couples' father was being
treated for the leukemia that took his life last Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Couples' mind was on things besides his golf score
Friday. Instead of talking about how he plans to get back into
contention, he sounded like someone ready to move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started Thursday, I was just a little bit off, and I
wish I'd had a couple more practice rounds to get ready,'' he said.
``I just wasn't good enough for four hours, and that's why I'm
shooting the way I've been shooting. And now I look forward to
Sept. 12.''
</P>
<P>
   His performance to date is not much different from his
experiences at the U.S. Open and the British Open, the only two
tournaments he has played in the past month before the PGA
Championship. At the U.S. Open, he finished 17-over and tied for
53rd. At the British Open, he finished 19-over and tied for 66th.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his erratic play, Couples is trying to have fun in his
hometown, staying in a home on the course and reveling in the
Seattle fans who lined the ropes rooting for their hometown hero.
On the 13th tee, he was greeted by a sign that read: ``Freddie for
President.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For me it is a once-in-a-lifetime deal, and I really have a
good time playing out there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Couples only wished his fans could have done a little more to
help him out on the course Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the rough a lot and felt I could have used them to
kick it out a few times,'' he joked.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he plays poorly over the weekend, Couples still is
singing the praises of Seattle and Sahalee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seattle has put on a great show,'' Couples said. ``I'm always
proud of Seattle. I get a kick when I'm out on the tour hearing
everything about (former coach) George Karl and the Sonics, and
talking with some of my friends about Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex
Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me growing up here, I'm never around, so to come back has
been a real treat.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
