<SLUG> BC-GOLF-PGA-GUMP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUMP? HE'S TIED FOR SECOND, YOU KNOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ With all of its cedars and firs, Sahalee
already had a forest. Now it has a Gump.
</P>
<P>
   Second-round PGA Championship leader Vijay Singh is recognized
worldwide as a man with impeccable credentials, winner of 23
professional tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Gump is recognized by his wife Christine. You could slide
his resume under the door. He has two Nike Tour wins.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Gump shot a 69 and is tied for second with Colin
Montgomerie and Steve Stricker.
</P>
<P>
   In seven years of grinding, Gump has never won on the PGA Tour,
let alone a major. This is his first of the year and his first PGA
since 1992 when he finished in a tie for 79th.
</P>
<P>
   If Gump has any connection with the fans at Sahalee, it is
because of his last name. He's the box-of-chocolates guy, and
Friday his life was good.
</P>
<P>
   As the Tiger throng watched another golfer elsewhere, two dozen
fans watched Gump's threesome at the fifth hole. The little
leaderboard that travels along with each group incorrectly showed
playing partner Ronald McDougal at 2-under and Gump at 6-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which one's Gump?'' asked a spectator from the bleacher seats
at the 18th green as Gump's threesome walked up the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows,'' came the reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the one with the white shirt in the trap,'' said another
fan, finally figuring it out.
</P>
<P>
   When Jim Britt of Redmond saw Gump's name on the leaderboard, he
thought it was a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they did that to lighten up the folks around the
green. I have never heard of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gump climbed into the trap and awkwardly addressed his ball,
beached on a sidehill lie. He took a swipe at it, lofting the ball
gently toward the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get in there, Forrest,'' urged John Wirth of Juanita.
</P>
<P>
   Gump's ball nearly followed the order, hitting the flagstick and
ricocheting 5 feet left of the hole. He sank the par putt and
headed to the TBS tower for a rare national TV interview.
</P>
<P>
   Gump is 32 years old, long and lanky at 6-foot-2 and 185 pounds.
He is a straight hitter who has used his driver only once in two
days here. Friday, Gump went from missing cuts to making putts,
draining a 12-foot par-saving, momentum-building putt at No. 1. At
No. 6, he buried a 60-footer for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, after he birdied the 14th hole from 12 feet, the
man on the television said: ``Scott Gump is the new leader at
5-under par.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he bogeyed 16 and 17 coming in, acceptable mistakes,
Gump thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take it,'' he said. ``I haven't been in this position too
many times, so I'm having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   This is who will be chasing the more prominent names this
weekend: a player who has finished second twice on tour, shot 62 in
the second round at Hartford and won nearly $300,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   He seems nice enough. A Golf World columnist used Gump as an
example of what's wrong with the PGA Tour, allowing non-winners to
remain exempt as long as they finish in the top 125 on the money
list. He was 109th last year.
</P>
<P>
   Restraining the temptation to fire off an oh-yeah rebuttal, Gump
merely said: ``Obviously, my record is not that good, but I'm
trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Breston of North Vancouver captured him perfectly: ``I would
call Scott Gump a journeyman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
