<SLUG> BC-ABUSIVE-JUDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PANEL URGES REMOVAL OF A TOWN JUSTICE IN NEW YORK STATE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A state judicial review panel has decided that a town
justice from Rockland County should be removed from the bench for a
series of remarks he made that made light of victims of domestic
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Ralph T. Romano, an elected justice of the Haverstraw
Town Court for the last 20 years, compromised his office with the
use of profane language, ill-placed humor on the bench and acerbic
behavior toward detectives between 1993 and 1997, the New York
state Commission on Judicial Conduct said in a report issued on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Romano, a part-time lawyer, ``exhibited intemperate and biased
behavior, disregard of the law and an egregious assertion of
influence for private gain,'' the commission concluded.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission seemed most concerned with his attitude
toward victims of domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1997 case, a man was accused of violating an order of
protection by beating his wife with a telephone. ``What's wrong
with this?'' the judge asked during the arraignment in the case,
according to the commission. ``You need to keep these women in line
now and again.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge also said that he was reluctant to issue orders of
protection or put abusive husbands out of the house unless the
victims could show extraordinary proof, such as a ``turban of
bandages,'' the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   Romano's lawyer said he would appeal the decision to the state
court of appeals. If the court agrees with the panel's
determination, Romano will be banned from holding judicial office
in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
