<HEADER>
A5334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-INTERSTATE-TOLLS     08-15 0482
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-INTERSTATE-TOLLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: TOLL PHOBIA AND AMERICA'S INTERSTATES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, Aug. 15:
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas Highway Commission's interest in imposing tolls on
a stretch of one of its Interstates has trucking organizations
talking like latter-day participants in the Boston Tea Party. Last
week, the truckers decried using anything beyond existing fuel
taxes to maintain the Interstates, and deplored the federal program
that will authorize toll experiments in three states. Farther west,
the San Diego region is acquiring more transponders to expand the
use of variable tolls that motorists with no passengers pay to use
I-15's high-occupancy-vehicle express lanes. Both toll experiments
will test the proposition that critical stretches of the nation's
Interstate system have more in common with telephone or cable lines
than they do with parks.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas' interest in the federal experiment is based on the
premise that many of America's Interstates cannot be maintained by
gas taxes alone, even with the generous financing provided under
the latest federal highway bill. This pilot program will allow
Washington to determine whether giving states the power to charge
tolls on their Interstates is a reasonable way to generate funds
for repair and rehabilitation. Under Washington's $198-billion
Transportation Equity Act, a state must demonstrate that it is
strapped before it is allowed to impose tolls.
</P>
<P>
   The law also authorizes 15 variable-pricing experiments that use
tolls to reduce congestion and manage traffic conditions, with an
option to apply the revenues to mass transit. Many of these give
those driving alone the right to use HOV lanes if they pay a toll
that is higher during peak periods and lower in off-peak periods.
This process will make it possible to learn what kinds of variable
tolls can help end parking-lot conditions at rush hour and to what
degree they discriminate against those who cannot afford the price
of a shorter commute.
</P>
<P>
   Except in a few states, placing the words ``toll'' and
``Interstate'' in the same sentence has been anathema in America.
Both Franklin Roosevelt and Dwight Eisenhower, the father of the
Interstate highway system, saw toll financing as a good way to
build the system. Eisenhower abandoned his preference for tolls
only after his advisers ruled, perhaps correctly at the time, that
tolls would not work except in the East's densely populated
precincts.
</P>
<P>
   America has changed a lot since then. Many of the nation's
largest metropolises need a variety of ways to reduce congestion.
Transponders and other technologies have eliminated the need for
toll plazas and even for slowing down to pay a toll. Both
developments suggest that what appealed to FDR and Eisenhower just
may have legs after all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
