currency and safeguard the economy. Stocks stage their biggest
rally in six months, with the Hang Seng Index jumping 8.3 percent.
The rally capped a week in which the index swung more than 700
points, or 11 percent. Few investors think that the volatility is
over. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   ECON-ASSESS (Undated) _ With Russia facing financial turmoil,
Asia sinking deeper into depression and President Clinton in a
political crisis, the blindingly bright economic picture of the
past couple of years suddenly looks murkier. What makes things a
bit scary is that the economy has now shifted into much slower
gear. And slowdowns _ which make it harder for businesses and
consumers to shrug off random blows _ have a way of turning into
recessions. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   WALL-STREET-NORTH (New York) _ Morgan Stanley Dean Witter has
signed an agreement to move into a new 1 million-square-foot office
tower on Seventh Avenue between 49th and 50th Streets, according to
real estate executives. If completed, the deal would represent the
latest in a series of expansion moves by the city's big investment
houses, whose growth has helped fuel New York City's economic
resurgence in the last few years. It also would add another piece
to a building boom in the Times Square area driven largely by media
and financial companies. By Charles V. Bagli.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-WINERIES (Palisade, Colo.) _ Commercial vineyards and
wineries are proliferating throughout the United States, including
in some unexpected, out-of-the-way places. By William R. Long.
