<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 11:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5387 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARKANSAS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-15 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARKANSAS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT CALLED ARKANSAS FOR NOTHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By PETER APPLEBOME   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   All of Washington rolled its eyes last week when first lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton came up with a novel explanation for her
husband's continuing travails.
</P>
<P>
   Having previously cited a ``vast right-wing conspiracy,'' she
told a reporter from The Arkansas Democrat-Gazette that the soggy
mass of scandal surrounding President Clinton was due to an
anti-Arkansas bias. ``They wouldn't be doing this if we were from
some other state,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   With her Yale and Wellesley degrees, and her suburban Chicago
pedigree, Mrs. Clinton is oddly cast as a plain-folks defender of
Ozark pride. And it takes some doing to ascribe anti-Arkansas bias
to the Whitewater Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr, a Texan who
spent his first two years of college at Harding University in
Searcy, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a real context for Mrs. Clinton's remarks that
goes beyond Arkansas to one of the more pervasive, if
little-discussed, maladies of American life: rube-aphobia.
</P>
<P>
   The term, which was first bandied about in Texas in the 1980s,
does not refer to fear of bumpkins and hicks, but the opposite: the
fear that unless you have the approval of the media powers and
taste makers in Washington, New York and to a lesser extent Los
Angeles, you're treated like a bumpkin or a hick.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton and her husband, of course, are anything but rubes.
But if there's an underlying thought in her plaint, it's the
persistent divide between the masters of the universe in America's
three power and media centers and the rest of the country, with
Arkansas as subterranean rock bottom on the food chain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know exactly what she meant; she made a statement of fact
that the rest of us are defined by Washington and New York,'' said
Nathalie Dupree, an Atlantan who is the author of 10 books on
cooking and entertaining. Ms. Dupree says she is often amused at
the degree to which her professional certification depends on
someone in New York taking notice. ``It's like the way New York and
Washington seem to think this whole Clinton business is critical,
and we think it's a waste of time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If any place can engender a sense of being permanently dissed,
it's Arkansas. Even Mississippi, the nation's poorest state, at
least gets stereotyped in terms of both Faulknerian complexity and
abject redneckery.
</P>
<P>
   But dating from a 19th-century best-selling travelogue
derisively titled ``On a Slow Train Through Arkansas'' to H.L.
Mencken's ridicule of ``the miasmic jungles of Arkansas'' to Li'l
Abner and Dogpatch, perhaps no state has had such consistently
dismal public relations.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Lyons, an Arkansas journalist originally from New Jersey (a
state with image problems of its own), said Mrs. Clinton's
statement to The Democrat-Gazette, like her allegations of a ``vast
right-wing conspiracy,'' was a clumsy attempt at making a valid
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to talk for 15 minutes, you can say something
sensible,'' he said. ``If it's one line, you sound silly.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said Mrs. Clinton was onto something if she was saying
that ignorance of the state, its players and political culture
colored much of the coverage of the all-but-forgotten original
Whitewater scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Jubilation T. Cornpone and Li'l Abner,'' Lyons said.
``Reporters expected a morally deranged world where the governor
makes love to his first cousin and then appoints the idiot spawn
securities commissioner while the hogs scratch their backs on the
front porch.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, just because the rube-aphobic world view has some basis
in reality does not necessarily mean Mrs. Clinton's explanation for
her husband's problems is anything other than defensive pique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hard pressed to buy the idea that Judge Starr is spending
$40 million of the taxpayers' money because he wants to take a
stick and poke it at the good people of Arkansas,'' said Richard
Bearden, executive director of the Arkansas Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   And even many Arkansans have to wonder if the appearance of an
insular political culture and the seamy circus of the past few
years, from Gennifer Flowers to Paula Jones to Monica Lewinsky, is
providing enough gross-out fodder to update old stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   Confirmed rube-aphobics might say the fact that even a powerful,
Yale-educated first lady feels so aggrieved is evidence of how
pervasive the malady is. But, then again, maybe it just says
something about how tough it is to be from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the old gag that in the old days when you crossed the
Mississippi there was a sign that said `Texas left and Kansas
right,''' said John Shelton Reed, a University of North Carolina
sociologist. ``Those who couldn't read stayed in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard that from someone from Arkansas. They have a nice
sense of humor if you don't provoke them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
