<P>
   BOMB-TANZANIA (Dar es Salaam, Tanzania) _ Investigators here
have found parts of a vehicle that they believe probably carried
the bomb that exploded at the U.S. Embassy here, American officials
said Saturday. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-SUSPECTS (Washington) _ Developments in the search for
suspects in the bombing of the American embassies in Nairobi and
Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-STERILIZE (Beijing) _ In an unusual move, the 2,000
scientists gathered here last week for the 18th International
Congress of Genetics took time out from discussions of cloning and
cancer genes to confront a controversial Chinese law, one that many
experts believe permits doctors to forcibly sterilize people with
serious genetic defects. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-EVACUATE (Kinshasa, Congo) _ The United States, Britain,
France and other Western nations began a hurried final evacuation
of their nationals from Kinshasa on Saturday amid signs that
African-led negotiations to prevent a rebel assault on the capital
would fail. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS (Pristina, Yugoslavia) _ With the outside world
doing little to stop government forces driving tens of thousands of
Kosovo Albanians from home and shelling, looting and burning their
villages, heavily armed Serbian police backed by Yugoslav Army
soldiers are increasing their terror against civilians. By Mike
O'Connor.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CRISIS (Moscow) _ ``In Russia,'' sighed a young man at a
bank, ``things are explained to people less, that's why they fear
things more.'' By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   SWISSBANKS-SETTLE (Geneva) _ The front page of a leading Swiss
newspaper on Friday capsulized the country's ambivalent response to
the accord last week aimed at settling Holocaust-era claims. The
words and imagery highlighted the mix of relief and victimization
that the Swiss feel over the announcement between Jewish
organizations, American politicians and Switzerland. By Elizabeth
Olson.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE-DAM-DISPUTE (Ralco, Chile) _ The Chilean government and
Endesa, a Spanish-owned electric utility, want to build a $500
million dam project on the Bio-Bio river intended to provide more
than 10 percent of Chile's electricity by 2002. But a dozen Indian
families have refused to leave their lands, which would be flooded
by the dam. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-VOGEL (Berlin) _ For 25 years during the Cold War,
Wolfgang Vogel swapped spies and traded political prisoners from a
law office in East Berlin. But his world turned upside down after
the Berlin wall fell in 1989. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL: &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WEB-USER-DATABASE _ Some of the largest commercial sites on the
World Wide Web have agreed to feed information about their
customers' reading, shopping and entertainment habits into a system
developed by a Massachusetts company that is already tracking the
moves of more than 30 million Internet users, recording where they
go and what they read, often without the users' knowledge. By Saul
Hansell.
</P>
<P>
   SANFRAN-HOMELESS (San Francisco) _ To many people who live here
and to the millions who visit each year, San Francisco is a jewel
of American cities for its beauty, culture and quirkiness. For
entirely different reasons, a rising number of homeless people also
find it ideal. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   FARMER-HAY-DONOR (Harvard, Ill.) _ When a fellow farmer gets
into straits, Keith Kingsley knows, good neighbors come to the
rescue with muscle, machinery or feed. It should not matter whether
the family in peril lives down the road or 1,000 miles away, in the
Chickasaw Nation in Oklahoma. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   INDIANS-GANGVIOLENCE (Window Rock, Ariz.) _ In response to the
surge in violent crime on reservations, President Clinton proposed
increasing the 1999 law-enforcement budget for the Bureau of Indian
Affairs by $25 million, to $100 million. That total was reduced
significantly in recent House and Senate votes, and by time the
appropriation bill emerges from a conference committee the increase
could be below $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-VOLCANO-TOWN (Mammoth Lakes, Calif.) _ Postcard views of
snow-covered peaks, sparkling lakes and emerald pine forests
surround this resort town 7,800 feet up in the Eastern Sierra. But
to the dismay of residents, when the nation's attention is drawn to
their town next to the Mammoth Mountain ski resort, it most often
focuses on what is going on underground. The town of about 5,000
people sits in the Long Valley Caldera, a 20-mile-long volcanic
basin.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-BARR (Washington) _ Joel Barr, an electronics engineer
linked to Julius and Ethel Rosenberg who defected to the Soviet
bloc in 1950 and became a leading force in the Kremlin's computer
industry, died in a Moscow hospital on Aug. 1. He was 82 and had
lived in St. Petersburg for many years. By Irvin Molotsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON: &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-POLITICS (Washington) _ As President Clinton prepares
for his risk-fraught testimony before a grand jury on Monday, both
political parties _ and especially the Democrats _ are warily
looking for signs of how Kenneth Starr's endgame will change the
dynamics of an otherwise placid election year. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KENDALL (Washington) _ President Clinton's private
lawyer, David Kendall, has practically moved into the White House,
prepping his client in sessions at all hours in the days before
Clinton tells a grand jury about his relationship with Monica
Lewinsky. As chief architect of Clinton's legal strategy, it is
Kendall who will be at the president's side as he testifies on
Monday. And like his client, Kendall has his reputation on the
line. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DEPOSE _ Veteran prosecutors of perjury cases and legal
scholars are torn over whether President Clinton risks more by
continuing to say he did not have sexual relations with Monica
Lewinsky, or by acknowledging a certain kind of sexual contact and
trying to reconcile it with his earlier testimony in the Paula
Jones lawsuit. By Nina Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   CEMETERY-DEBATE (Washington) _ Space is becoming so scarce at
Arlington National Cemetery that the announcement that three of the
Americans killed in the bomb blast at the U.S. Embassy in Nairobi,
Kenya, would be buried there has helped reopen some old wounds. By
Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
