<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWISSBANKS-SETTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWISS EXPRESS RELIEF, MIXED WITH RESENTMENT, OVER HOLOCAUST
SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ELIZABETH OLSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The front page of a leading Swiss newspaper on Friday
capsulized the country's ambivalent response to the accord this
week aimed at settling Holocaust-era claims.
</P>
<P>
   A political cartoon showed a reproduction of a Swiss bank
payment slip that listed $1.25 billion to be paid to ``The World
Jewish Congress, New York.'' The square for writing in payment
details said, ``Ah, yes: pardon from Jewish people.''
</P>
<P>
   An adjacent editorial in the newspaper, Le Temps, bore the
headline ``Bargaining and Politics.'' The French word
``marchandage'' in the headline can also carry the connotation of
haggling.
</P>
<P>
   The words and imagery highlighted the mix of relief and
victimization that the Swiss feel over Wednesday's announcement of
a settlement after more than two years of testy relations between
Jewish organizations, American politicians and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement _ signed by Switzerland's two largest banks, the
Union Bank of Switzerland AG and the Credit Suisse Group _ appears
to stave off serious damage to Switzerland's important banking
sector, which has been accused of profiting from dealings with the
Nazis and from the bank accounts of Jews killed in the Holocaust.
Their refusal to settle had prompted widespread threats of boycotts
of Swiss banks. Insurance companies, which face separate lawsuits,
were not covered by the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But many Swiss feel it is too late to undo the damage that the
dispute has done to the country's image, its integrity and its
heroic view of its wartime history. In news media commentary around
the country, the word ``blackmail'' often cropped up, even in
articles favoring the accord.
</P>
<P>
   A national opinion poll taken immediately after the agreement
was announced found support from a slender plurality. Of the 611
people surveyed, 42 percent approved the plan while 38 percent
registered disapproval. Twenty percent said they had no opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have the feeling that it was not the search for
truth, but more a search for money,'' said Pascal Couchepin, the
Minister for the Economy. ``We were not accustomed to this kind of
exploration of our history.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the question of exactly who will pay the $1.25 billion
to Holocaust survivors seemed to ignite real worry. Many Swiss,
particularly those who lived through World War II, view any use of
taxpayer money for this purpose as an unacceptable admission of
wartime wrongdoing. This belief is combined with the fact that
Switzerland is now climbing out of its most serious recession in
decades, and has budget problems.
</P>
<P>
   Couchepin said that ``there is no reason for the Swiss
government to pay anything.'' He said that a report from a
government commission on Switzerland's dealings with the Nazis
``showed we did what was possible in the hard times of the war.''
</P>
<P>
   The Swiss National Bank, which has been singled out as a major
buyer of looted gold from Nazi Germany, was not part of the accord
and has not yet taken a position. Its spokesman, Werner Abegg, said
that the bank's governing body would have to review the accord.
</P>
<P>
   The bank already has given some $67 million to a fund set up by
Swiss banks and businesses to aid impoverished survivors of the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting the simmering resentment here, even enthusiasts of
the settlement peppered their remarks with comments about the
accord's amount, and the tactics used to get it.
</P>
<P>
   Lily Nabholz, a member of Parliament, said the amount was
``quite surprising because it is hard for the average person to
understand how the small amounts uncovered in the dormant accounts
suddenly turned into $1.25 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of explaining to do,'' she said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But many people have also expressed relief that the dispute
appears to be winding down. Ms. Nabholz said that ``the situation
created a lot of frustrations and anger'' and that ``now we need
time to put soul-searching on the agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the financial side settled, perhaps we can look to the
past with more serenity,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf Bloch, president of the Federation of Swiss Jewish
Communities, echoed the sentiment. ``I hope we can stop speaking of
money, and speak only now of the moral side,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
