<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRODIGAL-POOCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRODIGAL POOCH POPS UP AFTER 14 MONTHS ON THE LAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ So, where you been the last year and two months,
Bijou?
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas? Down south? Hop a freight train up the coast? Been
hanging out with some pals at the dog track? Where?
</P>
<P>
   It's a shame you can't talk, kid, because Hollywood would be
lining up for your story. The movie boys love long shots that hit,
and you just hit one of the longest. Trust me, kid, you could be
bigger than Beethoven or Air Bud.
</P>
<P>
   I talked to people who know. They say this is one for the books.
</P>
<P>
   A mutt from suburban Van Nuys with wanderlust busts out through
a kitchen window screen and hits the road in early June 1997, while
her owner is teaching night school.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher, Eva Zaleska, and her good friend Irene MacLean
spend the next four months haunting animal shelters, veterinary
offices, pet-supply stores, anywhere and everywhere people
congregate with dogs.
</P>
<P>
   They cruise the streets of the suburban San Fernando Valley and
stretch out their search all the way up to Ventura, in the next
county. They take out ads in all the papers and even hire people to
go door to door around your Van Nuys neighborhood, hoping somebody
took you in and failed to notice you had dog tags and a collar with
Eva's phone number on it around your neck.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing. Zip. Nil. Oh, somebody did call once and said they
thought they saw you hanging out around a suburban Sherman Oaks
neighborhood, but it wasn't you. It was some other wag with
wanderlust.
</P>
<P>
   After six months or so, Eva and Irene figured the game was over.
In their hearts, they say, they never gave up. But, they'd talked
to enough people hanging around animal shelters and vet clinics to
know if you hadn't shown up by now, kid, you were probably gone
forever.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing left was to hope that wherever you went and
whoever you were with, they were giving you a good home and that
you were finally over the wanderlust that sent you packing in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   Then, bingo, the phone rings a couple of weeks ago in Eva's
home. It's a woman living down south in suburban Inglewood. A
scrawny-looking dog had just wandered into her back yard, and it
was upsetting her cats. Could Eva please come and get the intruder?
</P>
<P>
   ``Is her name Bijou?'' Eva asks, standing there frozen at the
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it says on her collar with your telephone
number,'' the woman says. ``Bijou.''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen months after you hit the road, kid, you surfaced 40
miles south with your tags and ID still hanging around your neck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know these women, but I'd certainly like to go to Las
Vegas with them,'' says Gary Hack, who runs the organization
Petfinders.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one for the books _ unbelievable,'' he says. ``The
rule of thumb is if a dog isn't found in the first three or four
weeks, it's really tough to find them. After six weeks, almost
impossible. Fourteen months, forget it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Animal Regulation people dealing with lost
pets I talked to said they've had dogs show up six months after
being reported missing, but 14 months? Not that anyone could
remember.
</P>
<P>
   The thing that has everybody scratching their heads, Bijou, is
where you been? If somebody took you in, they would have dumped
your old tags. If you've been wandering around the streets, how you
been surviving?
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't know, but she was pretty scrawny and raggedy
when we got her back,'' says Irene, who's been taking care of you,
Bijou, while Eva finishes up a long-planned vacation to Brazil
she's on this month.
</P>
<P>
   Irene says you've been eating pretty well since you got home,
kid, and that you're acting like you were never gone _ kicking back
on the couch and catching some Z's.
</P>
<P>
   And she's pretty sure you're over that wanderlust you had back
in '97 because she left the kitchen window open the other day, and
you only yawned and went back to sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome home, pal. Ain't no place like home, is there?
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
