<SLUG> BC-TRANSIT-CEO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSS LIFTS MTA BIT BY BIT AFTER ONE YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Nearly a year ago, when the MTA board put
corporate turnaround specialist Julian Burke in the driver's seat,
the multibillion-dollar transit agency was careening down a very
steep hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Metropolitan Transportation Authority had been accumulating
so much debt for costly subway and light-rail projects that, if it
continued down the same track, it was going to run out of money.
The agency's reserve of credibility with state and federal
officials who control transit dollars was running on empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was going into a tailspin, it seems to me,'' said Burke,
who became the MTA's interim chief executive officer on Aug. 22,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   As his one-year anniversary approaches, Burke and others say the
MTA, with his guidance, is putting the brakes on reckless spending,
refocusing attention on improving bus service and beginning to
restore its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Julian Burke stands head and shoulders above anybody
who's been in that position before,'' said David Fleming, a member
of the state Transportation Commission and a Studio City attorney.
</P>
<P>
   But no one, especially not Burke himself, claims the agency's
troubles are anywhere near over.
</P>
<P>
   Amid a chorus that mixes outright praise of Burke with
wait-and-see caution, his loudest critic remains the Bus Riders
Union.
</P>
<P>
   The bus passengers' group accuses Burke of using ``smoke and
mirrors'' to make it seem as if the MTA is complying with a federal
court order, called a consent decree, to reduce bus overcrowding
and provide better service.
</P>
<P>
   In his first stint as a public servant, Burke said he has had to
adjust from the relative privacy of company boardrooms to the
constant glare of outside attention _ but he is enjoying the
challenge of the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I'm doing even though it's taken over my life. I
wake up making decisions, and I go to sleep making decisions,'' he
said a few days ago in an interview at MTA headquarters near Union
Station. ``It's rewarding to me because I think I'm helping make
progress.''
</P>
<P>
   While he initially thought he would stay only six to eight
months _ until a permanent CEO could be recruited _ the 71-year-old
Burke now has committed to stay on until April 2000, as long as his
health permits and he feels he is contributing.
</P>
<P>
   Crucial changes have taken place at the MTA since he arrived, he
said. ``I would characterize it as substantially different than it
was a year ago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Burke said years of criticism and finger-pointing directed at
the MTA by news media, critics and lawmakers gave him ``a staff
that is quite demoralized,'' but now the agency has more ``internal
confidence that we know what we're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has had to get involved at a fairly low staff level
to teach employees to think differently and not fear new ideas. At
the same time, ``issues are now discussed much more precisely in
terms of what we are able to do and less what the dreams might
be,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he brought folks down to reality,'' said U.S. Rep.
Xavier Becerra, D-Los Angeles, who keeps a close eye on regional
transportation issues.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan _ the MTA board chairman who lobbied the
board to bring in Burke to overhaul the agency _ credits him with
beginning to streamline operations, restructuring bus lines to
better serve customers and giving the MTA a better idea of its
capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``His main accomplishment by far is getting the financial house
in order,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1219EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
