<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 12:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5412 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-15 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ELECTION NEARS, BOTH PARTIES ANXIOUSLY AWAIT CLINTON TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-KENDALL, CLINTON-DEPOSE.) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As President Clinton prepares for his risk-fraught
testimony before a grand jury on Monday, both political parties _
and especially the Democrats _ are warily looking for signs of how
Kenneth Starr's endgame could change the dynamics of an otherwise
placid election year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's on hold until Monday,'' said Ralph Reed, a
Republican strategist, indicating how much rides politically on how
the president chooses to present himself.
</P>
<P>
   A critical question in off-year elections is voter turnout. And
a number of strategists from across the country, Democrats and
Republicans alike, said the greatest danger for Clinton's party is
that his troubles could keep disillusioned Democrats from the polls
and energize angry conservatives to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Schnur, a Republican consultant and a former senior aide to
California Gov. Pete Wilson, recalled the election of 1974, just
months after President Richard Nixon resigned in the Watergate
investigation, when the Republicans lost 43 House seats. ``After
Watergate, Republicans didn't switch sides,'' he said. ``They just
stayed home.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Secrest, a Democratic pollster for many candidates in the
South, said, ``The concern is that the president's problems could
depress Democratic turnout, and that's a legitimate concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Though far from certain about their predictions, strategists
from both parties say that there is unlikely to be an instant sharp
turn in public opinion against Clinton even if he changes from his
previous flat denial of having had ``sexual relations'' with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are still giving the president approval ratings of 60
percent or more, even as larger majorities of people tell pollsters
they think Clinton has lied about his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politicians are nervous,'' said Mark Mellman, a Democratic
pollster, ``but the truth is, the level of nervousness on this
issue has exceeded the level of damage by a factor of 100 to 1 so
far.''
</P>
<P>
   Any Democratic hopes of making gains in the House require
Clinton's approval ratings to remain strong and for him to rise
above the scandal and amplify the party's campaign themes in the
critical months of September and October.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, a number of Democrats, searching for a way to
put the controversy behind them, say that Clinton should move
swiftly after Monday's closed-circuit testimony before the grand
jury and speak directly to the American public.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point some communication with the American people is
necessary to write the final chapter,'' said Sen. Robert
Torricelli, D-N.J. ``There is not closure until at some point the
president makes a final statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans now think that the controversy is likely to cement
their hold on the House and enlarge their majority. But Republicans
acknowledge that they, too, face risks if they cause a national
backlash by appearing too partisan in handling an impeachment
report.
</P>
<P>
   They also say they cannot skate too much on Clinton's troubles
without putting forth a compelling agenda. And they are waiting to
see whether Clinton, always a resilient politician, chooses to
deliver a speech of apology and ask for the country's
understanding.
</P>
<P>
   For both parties, much will ride on how women, in particular,
react to whatever revelations emerge. Dianne Bystron, the director
of the Carrie Chapman Catt Center for Women and Politics at Iowa
State University, said various polls this summer had put Democrats
up 10 to 14 points among women, and Republicans up 9 to 13 points
among men.
</P>
<P>
   That means Democrats would be in great danger if women become
disaffected and stay home in November. ``Democrats have to be
concerned,'' Ms. Bystron said. ``As in 1996, they have to change
the discourse from personal behavior to issues affecting the
family. The Democrats have to make sure that women show up at the
polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidates have inveighed against the
moral tone Clinton has set, but the Lewinsky controversy has so far
been raised in few of this year's campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Massey, who recently won a Republican primary for a
Congressional seat in Tennessee, handed out fliers calling the
Clinton White House the ``scandal-a-day administration'' and
mentioning ``Monica'' in large print.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been the exception. Speaker Newt Gingrich counseled
House Republicans heading home for the Congressional vacation to
say nothing after Clinton's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, for their part, are not fleeing Clinton as they did
in 1994, the year the Republicans swept to control of Congress.
Just this week, Clinton raised $3 million for Lt. Gov. Gray Davis,
the Democratic nominee for governor in California, who spent nearly
two days basking at the president's side.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here feel pretty good about the president,'' said Bill
Carrick, a Los Angeles Democratic consultant who oversaw Clinton's
state operation in 1996. ``What you see in focus groups is the same
thing you see in polls nationally. People feel good about the
president and the the job he's doing. They don't have much interest
in talking in any great degree about Monica Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic strategist close to the Congressional Democratic
leadership said: ``Our candidates are not being asked about this by
local press. That's encouraging. That's one of the reasons why
we're not in a total state of panic. The public's largely tuned out
at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Democrats argue that the unfolding situation could yet
backfire against the Republicans if they look too partisan in
pursuit of impeachment hearings once Starr _ as is now expected _
reports to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if the Starr report deals only with the Lewinsky
matter and suffers from overreach and a continuing lack of
perspective that has characterized the Starr investigation, it is
fraught with danger for the Republicans,'' Torricelli said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Paxon, R-N.Y., who is helping with the House
Republican re-election effort, conceded that if the party began
tearing into Starr's report before November ``it could have the
potential of coming back to bite us.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said he did not expect Republicans to begin any possible
impeachment hearings before November. ``The calendar doesn't allow
that, and I don't think the leaders of the Congress will allow that
to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like other Republicans, he said his party would be protected by
the stature of Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., who as chairman of the
House Judiciary Committee would preside over impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   As both parties plan their final campaign appeals, they are
starting to factor in a Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear a lot of people arguing, `Is this election about the
do-nothing Congress or the Lewinsky matter?''' Torricelli said.
``It's about the nexus between the two,'' he said, contending that
Republicans had put their energy into investigations instead of
passing legislation on tobacco, health maintenance organizations
and education.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans said that rather than attacking Clinton
head-on, they could subtly capitalize on the idea that he was
untrustworthy and needed to be held in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't help to publicly bash Clinton,'' said Beth Smith,
executive director of the Nebraska Republican Party. ``People know
the probability they will be stuck with him for another two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   That, she said, argued for Republicans to return to the theme
that emerged late in 1996 when they conceded Bob Dole's defeat but
said a Republican Congress was needed to rein in Clinton's power
and ideological leanings. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
