<HEADER>
A5415 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GERMANY-VOGEL-600&AMP;ADD     08-15 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-VOGEL-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER IRON CURTAIN LAWYER CLEARED OF BLACKMAIL CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ For 25 years during the Cold War, Wolfgang Vogel
swapped spies and traded political prisoners from a law office in
East Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   A confidant of leaders in East and West Germany, Vogel was
trusted by the CIA as well as the KGB, earning a reputation as a
humanitarian for enabling 250,000 East Germans to get to freedom in
the West and becoming one of the communist world's few millionaires
in the process.
</P>
<P>
   But his world turned upside down after the Berlin wall fell in
1989. A few former clients complained he had swindled them, and
after unification in 1990 German prosecutors agreed, asserting that
his law practice had been just a Communist Party secret-police scam
to press his fellow citizens to give up their houses and property
at fire-sale prices in exchange for permission to leave East
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1996, a state court in Berlin found him guilty on
five counts of blackmail. He appealed the convictions, and the same
court acquitted him of 32 similar charges later the same year.
</P>
<P>
   Now Vogel, 73, has his good name back. Germany's highest court
found in his favor on two of the appealed cases and announced this
week that prosecutors had agreed to drop the others.
</P>
<P>
   He and his lawyers say they expect that next week a Berlin tax
court will drop parallel charges of evading $5.6 million in taxes
on money the West German authorities paid him for arranging secret
prisoner releases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made some mistakes, I admit that,'' Vogel said in a
telephone interview from the Bavarian Alps, where he and his wife
and longtime assistant, Helga, have retired. ``But dropping the
charges of blackmail removes the stain on my reputation.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all his critics see it that way. As part of the bargaining
that settled the criminal cases after a high-court decision that
removed the linchpin of the prosecution's case, he and his lawyers
agreed not to contest another conviction two years ago for perjury
and falsely swearing in notarized statements.
</P>
<P>
   That conviction stands, with a suspended 14-month jail sentence
and a $65,700 fine, so it would be impossible for Vogel to practice
law again even if he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never should have said I was in my office on the day the
statement was sworn _ I forgot I was in Israel trying to negotiate
a prisoner swap, and now I have to take the consequences,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, his unique role ended when the Iron Curtain came down.
Freedom threw a harsh new light on activities that, by common
consent of his former clients and fellow negotiators _ West Germans
as well as East Germans, Americans as well as Russians _ had long
been left in the shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Unification also highlighted the differences that 45 years of
division had created between the 16 million East Germans and their
more fortunate 64 million West German compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   In the freedom they have all enjoyed since 1990, some Germans on
both sides forgot that communism had institutionalized blackmail;
it was not a system of courts and laws like the one that, at first,
recast Vogel as an unethical lawyer and imprisoned him for more
than six months on the tax charges in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point came April 12, when a Leipzig panel of the
Bundesgerichtshof, Germany's highest court, found in a case
involving one of Vogel's associates that what Vogel had been
pleading all along was true.
</P>
<P>
   It had been state policy in East Germany, the court said, to
require people who wanted to leave for the West to sell or give
away their property before they could get permission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wolfgang Vogel could retain influence and succeed in
emigration cases only if he observed the rules'' set by the East
German government, the court ruled.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Therefore, telling his clients that they had to sell their
property before they could get out did not constitute blackmail _
even if he then bought the property himself at prices lower than
the assessed values.
</P>
<P>
   This removed the grounds for his 1996 blackmail conviction for
getting Vera and Waldemar Zapff, East German clients in 1980, to
sell their property to Vogel and a Communist secret-police colonel.
This summer, prosecutors agreed to drop that case and the other
convictions Vogel had appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad he's out of it,'' said one of Vogel's longest-lasting
negotiating partners, Francis Meehan, a retired U.S. ambassador who
first met him in 1962. Vogel emerged then as the lawyer for a
Russian spy convicted in New York, Rudolf Ivanovich Abel, and
helped arrange his exchange that year for Francis Gary Powers, the
American U-2 pilot who had been captured by the Russians in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan was also present at the last big spy swap, the release of
the Soviet dissident Anatoly Shcharansky, who as Natan Sharansky is
now a Cabinet minister in the Israeli government, and eight
imprisoned spies in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Vogel was doing was immensely useful to both sides,''
Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfgang Ziegler, one of Vogel's lawyers, said his client would
not try to claim damages for his six-month imprisonment. ``We
wanted to call an end to a nine-year ordeal,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
