<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-TANZANIA-545&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEHICLE DEBRIS OFFERS CLUES IN TANZANIA BOMB ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAR ES SALAAM, Tanzania _ Investigators have found parts of a
vehicle that they believe probably carried the bomb that exploded
at the U.S. Embassy here, American officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The parts were found in material excavated from the crater where
the bomb exploded just outside the embassy gates eight days ago,
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   There were indications that the investigators know from
preliminary tests what kind of vehicle the bomb was attached to,
but they declined to describe it specifically.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no information that would definitively identify any
vehicle,'' said Kenneth Piernick, the special assistant agent in
charge of the FBI's Washington field office, who is directing the
investigation here.
</P>
<P>
   Several officials in Washington said they believed the vehicle
may have been a delivery truck whose driver tried to rush the gate
of the embassy and get past the security guards.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the case, the modus operandi of delivering the bomb
in Dar es Salaam appears to have been similar to that in Nairobi,
Kenya, where security guards have told investigators that a pickup
truck, commonly used for deliveries, carried the explosives in the
attack on the U.S. Embassy there.
</P>
<P>
   In the attack in Tanzania, the five security guards posted at
the embassy gates were killed in the explosion, apparently leaving
the investigators without nearby witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents have begun interviewing Tanzanian employees of the
embassy and others about whom they saw outside the embassy building
and whether they noticed a strange car in the period before the
blast, which killed 10 people and wounded more than 70.
</P>
<P>
   But here the investigators _ bomb experts, laboratory
technicians and others armed with long sticks who are prodding the
charred ground around the embassy building _ have a big advantage
over their counterparts in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
   For gathering physical evidence, Piernick said, the site, which
is more suburban than urban, was nearly perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are delighted with the conditions,'' he said. There was
virtually no looting of the embassy grounds after the attack, and
because the rescue operation was relatively simple, the evidence
was not moved or destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   While investigators here remained guarded about what they had
found, they seemed relatively happy with their preliminary results.
A portable laboratory was testing for DNA material, among other
things, a U.S. official said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials have had nothing to say about what kind of
explosive was used in the bomb. Piernick dismissed as ``gross
speculation'' a report that it consisted of ammonium nitrate.
</P>
<P>
   There have also been reports that the explosive used in the
Nairobi bombing was ammonium nitrate. But an explosives expert
there, Capt. Ryle Jones of the British army, said that these early
suspicions of ammonium nitrate were based on searchers having found
a piece of plastic with a crystallized substance on it.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that the plastic came from the lamination between
the embassy's window panes and that the residue was the shattered
glass, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Given the amount of damage caused by the explosion in Nairobi,
there was little doubt that a commercially manufactured explosive
was used, he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Tanzanian police said Saturday that they had released all
but two of the 14 people they arrested soon after the attack. U.S.
officials have suggested they did not believe that any of those
arrested, who included six Sudanese and six Iraqis, were suspects
in the case.
</P>
<P>
   But the Americans have gone out of their way to stress the
cooperation they are receiving from Tanzania. The investigative
abilities of the police here are severely limited because of lack
of money and poor training.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and other U.S. agencies have flown in huge amounts of
equipment as well as more than 100 people ranging from
administrators to interviewers to technical specialists.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that the Tanzanians continue to give the Americans the
leeway to conduct the investigation in the way they want, Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright will visit government officials and the
bomb site Tuesday. She will also go to Nairobi.
</P>
</TEXT>
