<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KENDALL-ART-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYER KEEPS HIS CASES IN THE COURTROOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MELINDA HENNEBERGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's private lawyer, David Kendall,
has practically moved into the White House, prepping his client in
sessions at all hours in the days before Clinton tells a grand jury
about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. As chief architect of
Clinton's legal strategy, it is Kendall who will be at the
president's side as he testifies on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   And like his client, Kendall has his reputation on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some Clinton loyalists are questioning whether the
tight-lipped, take-no-prisoners attitude favored by Kendall's firm,
Williams &AMP; Connolly, was the smartest approach in a case that so
obviously required a public relations offensive as much as a legal
solution.
</P>
<P>
   For seven months, Kendall, along with other lawyers, including
Hillary Rodham Clinton, has insisted that Clinton's team stick to
the basic script of saying nothing and denying everything while
fighting Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, on every front,
Clinton advisers have said in interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Clinton is considering a strategy of acknowledging that he
had intimate sexual encounters with Ms. Lewinsky, senior advisers
have said. He is also weighing making a public statement, a gambit
that Kendall has opposed in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall has quickly become a lightning rod for Clinton
supporters critical of the handling of the case. Kendall said he
would not respond to the criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton may well repeat his original account of ``no improper
relationship'' with Ms. Lewinsky. If, however, he tells the grand
jury that he did have a sexual relationship with her and that his
previous denials were based on a narrow definition of sexual
relations, the president might avoid a perjury charge _ but he
could also come under considerable fire for having been technically
truthful but not fundamentally honest with the public. And if that
happens, Kendall would almost certainly take a large share of the
blame for any political fallout.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall would risk disbarment if Clinton tells the grand jury
anything that his lawyer knows to be false and Kendall does not
immediately withdraw from the case. This predicament is highly
unusual in a grand jury proceeding, since lawyers are not generally
allowed to accompany their clients when they testify.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Kendall could emerge as a legal genius if Clinton
survives the scandal more or less intact. And a number of friends
said that either way, despite his gentlemanly reserve, Kendall is
equipped to handle both the pressures now and any possible
repercussions later.
</P>
<P>
   ``You constantly have this profile of him as this Quaker choir
boy but he's a street fighter,'' said Steve Coz, editor of The
National Enquirer and a client of Kendall's for 15 years. ``He's a
polished version of James Carville.'' Carville is a Clinton ally
famous for his dead-on, no-holds-barred attacks in defense of the
president.
</P>
<P>
   The president's other private lawyer, Robert Bennett, who
represented Clinton in the civil sexual harassment suit brought by
Paula Corbin Jones, was also widely criticized for his handling of
the assignment _ right up until the day a federal judge in Little
Rock granted Bennett's motion and threw out the case.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall is seen as gentler and more genteel than Bennett, the
legal slugger with whom he is constantly compared. By contrast,
Kendall is considered rather prim, less prepared to get messy,
legally or any other way. And despite his First Amendment work,
Kendall is much less willing to mix it up with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Although he did go after Starr over news leaks, Kendall
generally sticks to his white-shoe firm's more traditional view
that cases are best tried in the courtroom. Bennett, on the other
hand, considers public advocacy part of his job, and deals with
questions both political and legal.
</P>
<P>
   On this case in particular, Kendall's close-to-the-vest behavior
has been criticized at various times. Many on the White House staff
were openly furious to have been left out of the loop about the
recent news that the president was subpoenaed in the Lewinsky
matter, and they blamed Kendall for not informing them of such an
important development.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kendall has worked for the president since 1993, when he
was brought in on the Whitewater case. He has lasted longer than
most of those on Clinton's current roster of advisers and has
weathered in-house criticism in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Though a number of Kendall's friends at Yale Law do not remember
him being especially close to the Clintons there, he is considered
a particular favorite of the first lady, with whom he seems to
share a dim view of unnecessary sharing with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A Quaker raised in the small town of Sheridan, Ind., David
Kendall's favorite childhood places were the local library and the
movie theater, where he and his grandfather would catch a double
feature just about every Saturday afternoon. Books _ Dickens, best
sellers and military histories _ and movies, from science fiction
to art films, have remained lifelong passions.
</P>
<P>
   He is married to Anne Laybourne Kendall, a psychologist who does
educational testing of children, and they have three children, the
youngest of whom is a senior at Sidwell Friends, where Chelsea
Clinton went to high school and Kendall is a former chairman of the
trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Now 54, he has turned into the sort of man who not only can
quote Yeats, but does. And even friends say his humor can be a
little rarefied, tending toward word play or elaborate practical
jokes, like sneaking off a plane during an unscheduled stop to give
a sleeping, slightly hung-over colleague who awoke next to an empty
seat at the final destination the impression that Kendall had
somehow fallen out of the plane.
</P>
<P>
   But no one can reasonably question his mental toughness; and the
pertinent question is not whether Kendall knows how to fight but
whether this particular battle is one he can win.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He was arrested 10 times while working in Mississippi during the
civil rights movement. After a Rhodes scholarship, Yale Law and a
Supreme Court clerkship with Justice Byron White, he spent five
years working on death penalty cases at the NAACP's Legal Defense
and Education Fund Inc. Since joining Williams &AMP; Connolly in 1978,
his First Amendment work has frequently required a strong stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Coz recalls a time back in 1987 when The National Enquirer was
about to publish its scoop of the week: ``Liberace's Secret Battle
with AIDS.'' On deadline, the tabloid's editors were nervous and
inclined to kill the story, worrying that if they were wrong,
Liberace would, quite literally, end up owning the place. Finally,
Kendall, who had vetted the piece, stood up at the meeting and
ended the debate. ``Go with it,'' he said. ``You have it.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at that Liberace cover, which also touts such stories as
``Expert Reveals Six Tips to Help You Get a Raise,'' ``Connie
Francis: I'm Singing Again and I Feel Like a Million,'' and ``Fact
About Colds That Will Surprise You'' is an almost poignant reminder
of the days before allegations of the president's Oval Office
assignations dominated not only tabloid but also mainstream news.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never looks ecstatic and he never looks beleaguered _ he
always just looks like David,'' said Carville, the Clinton ally,
who did a double take when he ran into Kendall at the airport, en
route to a family getaway to Canada, on the Friday afternoon that
Clinton's subpoena was disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of those who have been critical of Kendall's approach
allow that he does not seem to have taken on a particularly easy
case, from either a legal or a public relations standpoint.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Kendall does not have a particularly pliable
client in Clinton, whose own fine legal mind sometimes rejects his
lawyers' strategy. And no one in Clinton's tiny inner circle is
saying exactly how much of Kendall's advice the president has
actually accepted. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
