<SLUG> BC-CONGO-EVACUATE-ART-510&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIVILIANS FLEE CONGO CAPITAL IN FEAR OF REBEL ADVANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A locator map of Lubumbashi is being sent to NYT graphic
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(js) 
 By HOWARD W. FRENCH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo _ The United States, Britain, France and other
Western nations began a hurried final evacuation of their citizens
from this city on Saturday amid signs that African-led negotiations
to prevent a rebel assault on the capital would fail.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before noon Saturday, the U.S. Embassy, already
operating with only a skeleton staff, told Americans remaining in
Kinshasa that they had only about two hours to register for a final
flight out that afternoon. The embassy itself, officials said,
would be closing due to the heightened security risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the post-ultimate evacuation,'' said a senior official
at the embassy, who added that as recently as Friday night American
officials had expected to remain in the country. Instead,
Washington sent evacuation orders for the last 20 embassy staff
members early Saturday morning, suggesting, the official said, that
information about a growing risk for foreigners had been received
overnight.
</P>
<P>
   At the French Embassy, which built a protective barrier of
sandbags around its entrance on Friday in expectation of violence,
several dozen pro-government demonstrators denounced the West for
what they called its support of the rebels, and jeered France in
particular, urging its citizens to get out.
</P>
<P>
   Not far away, another anti-Western group marched down the city's
main boulevard, turning angry when it reached one of the two
international hotels, where many foreign journalists are staying.
The crowd accosted several reporters, and soldiers entered the
hotel briefly in what they said was a search for illegal equipment.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to chanting against Westerners, demonstrators again
denounced Rwanda, which is vehemently blamed both in the streets
and in official propaganda for sponsoring the rebels and, indeed,
for all of Congo's recent problems. Rwandans and Congolese
suspected of Rwandan ancestry have disappeared from this city since
the war began, many of them rounded up by security forces and
interned at a military camp in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all this, for a city facing what is expected to be a
rebel siege, Kinshasa was otherwise unusually calm here for the
second straight day on Saturday, with few signs of unusual military
activity and little sense of panic among ordinary citizens. Instead
there were many bitter complaints about being kept in the dark on
the direction of the war.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks now, Congo's president for the last 15 months,
Laurent Kabila, has been fighting for his political life against an
armed rebellion. It sprouted abruptly near the Rwandan border and
spread quickly to the strategically vital far west, near Kinshasa,
through the use of audacious tactics and, apparently, careful
planning.
</P>
<P>
   Kabila's prolonged absence from the capital has caused many in
Kinshasa to suggest that if the battle for the capital were lost,
he could continue the war from Lubumbashi, capital of his southern
homeland. If this were to happen, many commentators here have
speculated, Congo's breakup _ forever cited as a risk _ might
finally begin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the last several days, the rebels have broken out of
defensive positions near the western towns of Moanda, Kitona and
Banana, and claim to have seized total or partial control of the
major cities of Boma and Matadi, as well as of the huge Inga dam,
which supplies this country and much of the region with electrical
power.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest rebel claims, which are credited by
Western diplomats, the insurgents are advancing toward the capital
from positions less than 200 miles southwest.
</P>
<P>
   In response the government has denied losing control of any new
cities, and claimed Friday to have begun a bombardment campaign
against the rebels' principal western base, a captured army
training center at Kitona. A variety of people, from government
officials to foreign business people here, said that whatever the
truth, there was intense combat in the Matadi area since Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't fear anything,'' said Didier Mumengi, the information
minister. Other officials indicated that Kabila was meeting with
his war Cabinet in Lubumbashi and might address the nation Saturday
evening. Control of Lubumbashi, which dominates the mouth of the
Congo River, is widely viewed as critical to holding Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   Though ill prepared and often poorly commanded, government
troops are reportedly well armed and often motivated, and have
repeatedly rebounded from dramatic setbacks to mount
counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
   One possible reason for the relative calm here, even as
Westerners expecting the worst quit the city, is that with their
country's tumultuous history Kinshasans have experience of crises
like this. In fact, for many here the events of August give the
almost hallucinatory feeling of watching last year's history as if
rewound on tape and played back at fast-forward. At that time
Kabila was leading a rebellion sponsored by Rwanda, which took
seven months to overthrow the dictator Mobutu Sese Seko.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen all of this before with the fall of Mobutu,''
said Kibamba Lukoki, a Kinshasa newspaper vendor. ``Our fear is
less about the moment, which is serious enough, but familiar. Our
real fear is that our country, Congo, has fallen into a cycle from
which it won't be able to escape.''
</P>
<P>
   For now Kabila is cloistered in Lubumbashi, just as Mobutu, then
dying of cancer, spent much of the last war either in his native
far-northern city of Gbadolite or in Switzerland. Just as Mobutu
did in his final years, Kabila, in the second half of his brief
rule, has concentrated authority in the hands of ethnic kinsmen and
close relatives. And finally, just like the dictator he overthrew,
Kabila seemed to realize only late in the rebellion that he needed
to replace an ineffective army leader _ his brother-in-law Celestin
Kifwa, who it seems was chosen essentially out of personal trust.
</P>
<P>
   Until late in Mobutu's failed war, his entire general staff was
dominated by corrupt relatives. Kabila, in a twist not even
attempted by his predecessor, last week replaced Kifwa as chief of
staff with his son, Joseph Kabila, who has just returned from a
hasty course of military training in China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kabila was given power on a golden platter by the Rwandans,''
said one senior officer from Mobutu's army who has been placed in
reserve by the new government. ``Now he is losing it in the same
way Mobutu did. He is trying to implement the same failed system
that he supposedly came to sweep away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
