<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 13:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5442 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARMER-HAY-DONOR-ART-     08-15 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMER-HAY-DONOR-ART-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLINOIS FARMER AIDS DROUGHT-STRICKEN OKLAHOMA COLLEAGUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill, Okla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036.) 
(js) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARVARD, Ill. _ When a fellow farmer gets into straits, Keith
Kingsley knows, good neighbors come to the rescue with muscle,
machinery or feed.
</P>
<P>
   It should not matter whether the family in peril lives down the
road or 1,000 miles away, in the Chickasaw Nation in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got more hay than I can use,'' Kingsley told agriculture
officials on the telephone in grass-scorched Oklahoma, where
desperate farmers have resorted to feeding tree branches and leaves
to starving cows. ``Anybody who needs it can have it.''
</P>
<P>
   The agricultural official told Kingsley that the Chickasaw were
among those hit the hardest. Since the Illinois farmer made the
offer late last July, leaders of the Chickasaw Nation in
south-central Oklahoma have been sending big trucks once a week to
collect those bales of hay, which seem as precious as gold.
</P>
<P>
   The trucks have transported about 250 big, round bales, which
weigh 800 to 1,000 pounds. One bale can feed about 35 cows a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's just a drop in the bucket,'' said Kingsley, a
soft-spoken 40-year-old who runs a small dairy farm here with his
son, Darryl, 21. ``But maybe it will help a little.''
</P>
<P>
   When the trucks arrived, the men from Oklahoma looked with
astonishment at the rain-nourished pastures and tall cornfields of
the Upper Midwest. Kingsley remembered one of the Chickasaw
marveling: `` `It's so green. I can't believe it.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since Kingsley made his first donation of hay, eight or nine
other dairy farmers who live near Harvard have agreed to contribute
hay to the Chickasaw. Some local farmers, including Dan and Tom
Evers, Jeff Hawthorne and Christ Spiniolas, have also helped load
the bales onto trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Chickasaw in Oklahoma, where hay has been selling on
the roadside for as much as $150 a bale Kingsley's name has become
well known and warmly regarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody appreciates what Keith has done,'' said the
Chickasaw governor, Bill Anoatubby. ``It's nice to know there are
people out there with good hearts.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Kingsley, whose family has been raising cows in this hilly
countryside for six generations, said he knew the struggles of
family farmers to survive, even without a drought. The milk
produced on his farm is selling for only about $13 per
hundredweight on the market these days, no better than the price
paid to his late father, Harold, some 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsley's wife, Gail, who helps on the farm by milking cows and
running the hay baler, also works at the McHenry County nursing
home. Their son, Darryl, works nights as a bartender in nearby
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farming, like every sector of agriculture, has become
dominated by big operators. Kingsley recalled seeing a dairy farm
on every 80 acres when he was a boy. Many of those families have
given up.
</P>
<P>
   Now the countryside, just a mile or so from the Wisconsin state
line, is becoming a place for expensive houses that belong to
people who work in offices, not cow pastures. Residential growth
has been on the upswing since Motorola opened a huge plant here a
few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The land is just too valuable for farming anymore,'' Kingsley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some newcomers to rural life here complain about mud on the road
or the smells from the dairy barn. Kingsley, who has a gentle way
about him, just smiled and shrugged about the changes.
</P>
<P>
   Standing in a field with big bales of hay, a bountiful crop of
alfalfa and orchard grass, Kingsley said he was in no position to
complain.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the rain this spring,'' he said with a grateful smile,
``things just grew and grew and grew.''
</P>
<P>
   He mostly wanted to talk about the terrible problems of the
farmers in Oklahoma. ``Some of them have lost 25 percent of their
livestock,'' he said. ``The poor people are just sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farmers like Kingsley usually need to stay close to home,
tending to the animals. Vacation trips can become few and far
between. For that reason, he has never spent much time beyond this
pocket of the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   But next February, Keith and Gail Kingsley are going to take a
drive to Oklahoma. They're going to spend some time at the
Chickasaw Nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some friends there now, you know,'' he said &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
