<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5473 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-STERILIZE-2TAKE     08-15 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-STERILIZE-2TAKES(800)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTISTS DEBATE CHINA'S LAW ON STERILIZING CARRIERS OF GENETIC
DEFECTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ In an unusual move, the 2,000 scientists gathered here
this week for the 18th International Congress of Genetics took time
out from discussions of cloning and cancer genes to confront a
controversial Chinese law, one that many experts believe permits
doctors to require that people with serious genetic conditions be
sterilized.
</P>
<P>
   In several forums, and even at the closing ceremonies, some of
the world's foremost geneticists scrutinized, and sometimes
criticized, the vaguely worded 1994 law, debating whether it
intended to condone forced sterilization or was just so poorly
worded that it left that option open.
</P>
<P>
   China's Maternal Infant Health Care Law, originally known as the
Eugenics Law, had so offended some scientists that national
genetics societies from England, Holland and Argentina boycotted
their profession's most prestigious general meeting, held once
every five years.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of the International Genetics Federation remained
committed to the Beijing site _ on condition that the meeting
include a forum to discuss the issue of eugenics as well as this
law. And ultimately many scientists with misgivings decided to
attend, hoping that an open discussion on Chinese soil might
influence policy here and lend support to Chinese bioethicists and
geneticists who have themselves, with some recent success, pressed
the government for revisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eugenics has always been an issue for geneticists, but the
Chinese law has given this a razor-sharp edge,'' said Anthony
Griffiths, the Canadian secretary general of the federation, at a
packed, lively forum Wednesday evening titled ``The Science and
Ethics of Eugenics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in China. We are geneticists. I think we need to say
something on this issue,'' Griffiths said.
</P>
<P>
   In response, dozens of scientists from China and a dozen other
countries stepped up to the microphone for a wide-ranging and
remarkably frank debate. Excerpts from the law, projected on a
screen at the front of the room, served as a sort of Rorschach test
for some of the thorniest issues in bioethics.
</P>
<P>
   While there was general agreement that the wording of the law
should be improved, the debate also revealed considerable cultural
rifts. For example, ``eugenics,'' a term referring to improving the
human race through controlled breeding, has weighty negative
connotations in the West, where it evokes the Nazi campaign for
racial purification through forced sterilization and extermination
of the ostensibly unfit. The term has more positive associations in
China and in some other East Asian countries, where it retains much
of the original sense of ``excellent birth.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1994 law, whose main purpose is to guarantee prenatal and
pediatric health care to poor women and children, nonetheless
contains two small but controversial articles dealing with genetic
counseling. They stipulate that couples undergoing their required
premarital physical examination be informed of any genetic
problems.
</P>
<P>
   But articles 10 and 16 then direct doctors to ``take steps'' to
``prevent childbearing'' _ through sterilization or long-term
contraception _ should a problem be detected. And the law is
unclear as to who should make the decision regarding sterilization
_ the doctor or the couple. Griffiths said that many scientists and
human right advocates were concerned about the ambiguity,
particularly given the charges of forced sterilization that have
plagued China's one-child family program.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Chinese geneticists were clearly roiled that the
international community had singled out their country for
criticism. ``The goal of the session is to clarify the idea of
eugenics, not to discuss one country's or another country's law _
we should not discuss China's laws,'' said one angry scientist who
gave his surname as Zhang.
</P>
<P>
   But another Chinese scientist, Yang Huanming, quickly took the
microphone to disagree. ``I think a free atmosphere is very
important for this law,'' he said. ``I think everyone should be
encouraged to say what they are thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Qiu Renzong, a leading bioethicist at the Chinese
Academy of Social Sciences, helped organize the forum. Qiu, who
assisted in drafting the law and praises its overall intent, has
nonetheless criticized the wording of the two articles on genetic
counseling as well as their translation into English. He said that
decisions regarding marriage and childbearing for people with
genetic problems should be a matter of individual choice, and
worried that the law's vague and contradictory language might lead
doctors to conclude otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Qiu said that the Ministry of Health has been generally
sympathetic to his concerns and this week had ``confirmed the
principle of informed consent.'' But, he added, ``I still think we
need changes in the wording of some articles.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Article 10, for example, says that physicians must give
``medical advice'' to couples who have been ``diagnosed with
certain genetic diseases of serious nature which are considered
inappropriate for childbearing.'' It continues, ``The two may be
married only if both agree to take long-term contraceptive measures
or to take a ligation operation for sterility.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many people have been sterilized or forbidden
to marry under the law, since Qiu said that provinces were
generally still preparing to implement it. But local laws requiring
sterilization under narrower circumstances already exist. In 1988,
Gansu province in northwest China passed a law requiring compulsory
sterilization of people with IQ's under 49. Several other provinces
subsequently adopted similar provisions.
</P>
<P>
   At the conference, the debate over the national law turned
partly on semantics: Did it really intend to allow doctors to
prohibit people with genetic disease from having children and, if
so, what ``serious genetic diseases'' are included? Article 19, for
example, says that sterilization surgery must be ``agreed and
signed upon'' by the patient.
</P>
<P>
   And did the official English translation at the very least
misrepresent the law to the outside world? Although the law was
originally called the Eugenics Law, Qiu successfully pressed the
government to avoid using the word ``eugenics'' in part because of
its negative connotations in the West.
</P>
<P>
   But more substantive differences were also aired.
</P>
<P>
   ``In many countries people have been exterminated in the name of
eugenics,'' said Valery Soyfer, a Russian-born geneticist now at
George Mason University in Virginia, who lost his job in the former
Soviet Union when he spoke out in support of the dissident
scientist Andrei Sakharov. He added: ``That's why people in the
genetic community are concerned. What is this law? We're not going
to intervene, but we think we have a responsibility to share our
history.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many scientists said that genetic counseling should provide
individuals with impartial information to help them make their own
medical decisions, and not be an instrument of government policy,
coercion or social betterment _ an opinion that was pointedly made
by federation officials at Saturday's closing ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   But others noted that Asian and Western scientists were likely
to disagree somewhat on this issue since Asian societies tend to
place greater value on the collective good, while Western culture
focuses more on the individual.
</P>
<P>
   When Xin Mao, a Chinese geneticist now working in England,
polled genetic counselors from 37 countries on whether reducing
defective genes in the population was an important goal of their
work, all respondents in China said ``yes,'' while fewer than 6
percent in Canada and 5 percent in the United States agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, scientists from both the West and China pointed out
that sterilization of people with obvious handicaps was not an
effective way to ``cleanse the gene pool,'' as the survey put it,
since most potentially disease-causing genes are recessive and lie
silently in the cells of apparently healthy people.
</P>
<P>
   Qiu said that Chinese physicians are becoming more sophisticated
about genetics and patients' rights. Walter Bodmer, a leading
geneticist at Oxford University, reminded the audience that such
developments were fairly recent in the West as well. Canada
required sterilization of some mentally retarded people as recently
as the 1960s, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths said he was heartened that the Chinese government was
endorsing informed consent, but added: ``It all depends what they
mean by informed consent. That may mean the doctors tells you what
to do and you do it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
