<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5501 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DUTY-FREE-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-15 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DUTY-FREE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S SO FREE ABOUT DUTY FREE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By BETSY WADE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Duty free belongs with free lunch and free love as another
phantom freebie. As a phrase, it sounds as if it sprang from the
fertile mind of some marketing genius. As a concept, it is in fact
a morass where questions of import duties are tangled with domestic
luxury taxes, all of which may be undone elsewhere by regulations
to safeguard crops and livestock.
</P>
<P>
   Duty-free shopping can sometimes leave even veteran travelers
wondering where they went astray.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine you are leaving a country _ theirs or yours. Tickets in
hand, you hasten through the metal detector. Just beyond the
security barrier is a souk whose merchants have set up cupboards of
liquor and sprayed the air with French perfume, spreading their
rugs under the ``duty free'' banner. Sure enough, you can buy
merchandise without paying any duty, but only because you are
departing, purchases in hand, and the country at your back has no
way to nick you. So much for the ``duty'' part.
</P>
<P>
   What happens when you reach your next stop is another matter,
governed by what that country wants to tax or keep out, which can
depend on what products the country makes, or the state of its
agriculture. Unless you know the tax and agriculture rules, your
purchase may be subject to duty or even sales tax, seized, or, if
it is edible, ground to oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   Al Michaud of Tryon, N.C., was returning to the United States
from Amsterdam this spring when he said a delicious-looking salami
at the Schiphol duty-free shop ``rang my gastric bell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A salesclerk assured me that all was inspected and entry into
the U.S. would be no problem,'' Michaud said. ``At Customs in
Detroit, my salami was confiscated with many a tsk and harrumph.''
</P>
<P>
   Michaud avoided a fine because he had entered the salami on his
Customs declaration. But according to the Agriculture Department
inspectors at New York's Kennedy Airport, concealers of salami, or
other forbidden viands, who lie and act uncooperative can be fined
a maximum of $250. So much for the ``free'' part.
</P>
<P>
   Duty-free shops are big business for their owners, and for
airports that charge them rent linked to sales. Worldwide,
according to David Bernstein, president of the International
Association of Airport Duty Free Shops, the annual revenue in such
shops is $22 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Cigarettes, liquor, perfume, watches and cosmetics are standard
commodities in these shops; outside the airport their prices
include sin taxes or other excise taxes. Cameras are no longer
major items because shoppers can buy them at equivalent discount
prices in the city, said Helen Deknatel, commercial director of
shops at the International Arrivals Terminal at Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Because the duty-free shops' merchandise will not be drunk,
smoked or resold in the country, tax authorities waive their
percentage, which lowers the price _ although, again, duty has
nothing to do with it. Until they are sold, such goods, whether
Marlboro, Jack Daniel's or Cutty Sark, are stored ``in bond,''
meaning the management guarantees that they won't enter the
domestic market.
</P>
<P>
   Most travelers don't have a clue what they are allowed to carry
with them. Michael Halper, who operates seven duty-free shops at
Kennedy Airport, said that a recent customer on his way to Israel
bought a five-carton carrier of Marlboro cigarettes ($63.80 at last
check) but was unaware that the limit was 250 cigarettes to a
visitor. When the customer returned from Israel to complain, Halper
made good on the loss, as Schiphol did for Michaud when he wrote,
enclosing the receipt for his salami.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the confusion are the other shops in the airport.
Unlike the duty-free stores, they do not require passengers to
present an overseas ticket and they charge regular prices,
including local sales taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Halper says the magical phrase duty free lures customers but
convenience and price make the business thrive. It is convenient
not having to lug a bottle of whisky from home to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   Comparison shopping is still a good idea. Bourbon drinkers can
buy a liter of Jim Beam for about $11 at a duty-free shop at
Kennedy Airport, compared with about $14 in New York City. In
Britain, the home of scotch, tariffs run the price of the
American-produced Jim Beam up to about $31 a liter in a London
supermarket; local brown liquor, Bell's Scotch Whiskey, costs only
$23 a liter. So it pays to pack one's own when traveling to
Britain, and a liter of bourbon slides duty free through British
Customs. Travelers to Italy, on the other hand, need not bother to
take bourbon; Italians, who have no competing product, sell it at
roughly the same price as in America.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the salami syndrome that drives people batty. An
American traveler sees pate in a duty-free shop overseas, and the
price is better than an identical tin at home. She buys it, and on
arrival at home, she declares her food product. Zap! The pate joins
Michaud's sausage in the doom machine.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department says the pate imported into the
country in bulk for sale is processed by methods that have been
officially inspected and accepted. Not so the little tin from the
duty-free shop. What's the solution? Eat the pate on the plane
coming home.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
