<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Aug. 16, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867) 
(js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Breezy and cooler conditions will continue to spread across the
Northwestern States as a strong cold front moves into the northern
Rockies. Brisk onshore winds will promote clouds and showers near
the Washington coast and along the western slopes of the Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of the front, a few potent thunderstorms will develop in
the warm air over the Bitterroots as well as the higher terrain of
northern Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   The Southwest will have seasonal heat with ample sunshine,
although thundershowers will form near many mountain peaks during
the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Very humid air will surge into the northern parts of the Plains
and Mississippi Valley as winds from the south increase ahead of a
cold front. Broken bands of strong thunderstorms, some with
damaging winds and hail, will develop from the eastern Dakotas to
the central Missouri River Valley during the afternoon and evening.
</P>
<P>
   A weak front will stall near the northern Appalachians leaving
most of the Northeast and Middle Atlantic States humid with
variable clouds. Clusters of strong thunderstorms will develop
around a disturbance as it drifts from the southern Appalachians to
the Middle Atlantic Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, a few showers will develop east of the Appalachians,
especially in the afternoon. In the wake of the front, the eastern
Great Lakes and Ohio Valley will be mainly sunny.
</P>
<P>
   Slow-moving thunderstorms will erupt near the western Gulf of
Mexico coast. Meanwhile, most of the Southeast will be sultry with
scattered thunder.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SEARING SUMMER
</P>
<P>
   The arid, searing summer of 1998 in Texas is reaching historic
proportions around Brownsville. The period from March to the middle
of August has had only 0.97 inches of rain, the driest on record at
the southern Texas town. The average temperature of 87.3 made the
first month of summer the hottest June since records began. July
was the third hottest on record with each day achieving a
temperature of 90 degrees or greater. There have now been five
consecutive years when every day in July has reached 90 or higher,
an unprecedented event in Brownsville where records began in 1878. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1413EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
