<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5517 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DEPOSE-NYT &LR;      08-15 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DEPOSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RISKS ABOUND IN HOWEVER CLINTON TESTIFIES, LEGAL EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CLINTON-POLITICS, CLINTON-KENDALL.) 
(nk) 
 By NINA BERNSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Veteran prosecutors of perjury cases and professors of law see
legal risks for President Clinton whether he continues to say he
did not have sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky or acknowledges
a certain kind of sexual contact and tries to reconcile it with his
earlier testimony in the Paula Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, these legal experts said, there is a large
element of the surreal in the president's situation. The way the
case stands now, most agree, as a matter of both law and practice,
it is highly unlikely that any ordinary citizen would face charges
of perjury or obstruction of justice on the basis of the deposition
in the Jones case. Nor can the grand jury investigating the matter
actually level such charges against Clinton while he is still in
office, the way most legal scholars read both the Constitution and
the independent counsel law.
</P>
<P>
   Yet based on the specter of such charges, independent counsel
Kenneth Starr can now question Clinton in a new proceeding, a
federal grand jury, where the legal stakes are much higher, and
where anything he says can be used against him. If Starr has
convincing evidence that a continued denial is false _ including
any DNA evidence that might be obtained from a dress of Ms.
Lewinsky's _ it could make Clinton vulnerable to a much stronger
perjury case.
</P>
<P>
   The Fifth Amendment _ the right not to be compelled to bear
witness against oneself _ protects citizens against just this kind
of triple bind: Answer falsely, and risk charges of perjury; refuse
to answer, and be jailed for contempt of court; answer truthfully,
and provide prosecutors with ammunition for one's own criminal
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   But politically, most observers agree, taking the Fifth _
refusing to answer questions on the grounds the answers would tend
to be self-incriminating _ is not an option for a president,
especially since the official secrecy of grand jury proceedings is
unlikely to hold up against leaks.
</P>
<P>
   H. Richard Uviller, a professor of law at Columbia University,
likened the result to the ``perjury trap'' typically set for
racketeers when he was an assistant district attorney in Manhattan
under Frank Hogan, the best-known prosecutor of his time.
</P>
<P>
   Like many other former prosecutors interviewed, Uviller is
troubled at the idea that the kind of device used to catch mobsters
could force the president of the United States to answer graphic
questions about his private behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Others said it was unfair to Starr to say he was only
investigating sex. ``The sex is the subject matter of the lie, but
it's the perjury that's important here,'' countered John Fried,
head of the trial division of the Manhattan District Attorney's
office between 1985 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   But Fried, who rejected the term ``perjury trap'' to describe
Starr's tactics, also cringed at the kind of graphic questions
needed to lay the groundwork for a perjury case against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   It was the lack of such questions by the lawyer deposing the
president in the Jones case in January that has left Clinton the
possibility of telling the grand jury that he had sexual encounters
with Ms. Lewinsky, while making a case that he did not testify
falsely. Advisers to the president acknowledged on Thursday that
such a strategy was under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   If Clinton did not have sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky,
then, of course, no perjury was committed. But in legal terms,
perjury is not just lying under oath, but knowingly making a false
statement that is material to the inquiry at hand. In this case,
there is considerable doubt that a possible consensual sexual
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky was material to the Paula Jones
case, which was dismissed; legally, evidence that goes to character
or credibility is not considered material.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he believed his statements in the Jones deposition to be
false in strict legal terms is also in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   For the purposes of the deposition, the agreed-upon definition
of sexual relations was ``contact with the genitalia, anus, groin,
breast, inner thigh, or buttocks of any person with an intent to
arouse or gratify the sexual desire of any person.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So the record is completely clear,'' Clinton was asked, ``have
you ever had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky, as that term is
defined in Deposition Exhibit 1, as modified by the court?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton replied: ``I have never had sexual relations with Monica
Lewinsky. I've never had an affair with her.''
</P>
<P>
   But the questions about sex did not go beyond that. A leading
Supreme Court decision on perjury, Bronston vs. United States,
unanimously held in 1973 that although a witness' testimony might
be misleading or evasive, it was the responsibility of the
questioning lawyer to probe, and not to expect a jury to interpret
what the witness meant.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from opening the door to a degrading examination of the
details, Clinton's admitting to sexual encounters now would not be
without its legal perils, several law professors said. It
establishes what the prosecutor might have difficulty proving
beyond a reasonable doubt on his own: that there were sexual acts,
and a motive to hide them.
</P>
<P>
   Establishing that Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky had sex is the first
thing a prosecutor has to do to make a case of perjury or
obstruction of justice, noted Douglas Grover, a former federal
prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike perjury, the obstruction of justice statute is so broadly
drawn that any endeavor to influence the course of a proceeding, no
matter how immaterial to the inquiry or how unsuccessful, could
constitute obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Though reports are that Ms. Lewinsky has denied that Clinton
instructed her to lie, areas of potential danger might include any
``cover stories'' they are said to have discussed. Here too, if his
intent was to mislead his wife or the public rather than to change
the outcome of the Paula Jones case, Grover said, it is not legally
obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Like Professor Uviller at Columbia, Paul Rothstein, a law
professor at Georgetown University, cast about for some middle
ground. ``The best thing is only to answer some of the questions,
or a very fuzzy general mea culpa.''
</P>
<P>
   Others dismissed this middle road out of hand, as well as the
suggestion that Clinton could invoke a constitutional right to
privacy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
