A5520 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOMB-KENYA-FUNERAL-NY     08-15 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-KENYA-FUNERAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TWO TEEN-AGE SISTERS, FINAL TRIP TO KENYAN VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TIM WEINER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KATHERA, Kenya _ A long cortege bore the broken bodies of two
young sisters who died in the American Embassy bombing in Nairobi
up the lush slopes of Mount Kenya to their family's ancestral
village Saturday, far from the charred ruins at the capital's
heart.
</P>
<P>
   The journey began at dawn at a Nairobi mortuary, where their
family gathered to receive the twin coffins of Gloria and Caroline
Mutuiri, aged 16 and 17. They had gone to the embassy eight days
ago hoping for visas to the United States. Their mother, Virginia,
stood at the mortuary's steel doors wrapped in a white shawl of
mourning, saying, ``I have lost my light.''
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the terrorist bombing, which killed at least
247 Kenyans and 12 Americans, a seismic wave of suffering has
spread over the country. On Saturday, funerals were held all over
Kenya for the dead, some in Nairobi, some in the towns and tribal
villages from where people of all walks of life had come to the
capital to seek their fortunes. The village of Kathera, population
perhaps 500, has been preparing for three days to receive its slain
sisters.
</P>
<P>
   At the mortuary Saturday, Sister Adah Adoyo, who taught the
girls in high school, offered a short homily. Addressing God, she
said, ``We do not know where You are going,'' and concluded, ``We
do not want to pretend that it's an easy journey.''
</P>
<P>
   The caravan pulled out, headed for the girls' home village, 150
miles away. In one car in the long line, two cousins fell to
chatting, consoling themselves with stories of the miseries that
had befallen other people with the bombing _ the boy of 3 who lost
both parents, the friend blinded by flying glass _ and with
memories of Gloria and Caroline.
</P>
<P>
   As the city began falling away, one of the cousins, Wilson
Kinyua Ndambiri, a young chef, remembered the girls, dressed in
lavender gowns, as maids of honor at his wedding one year ago
Saturday. Caroline, he said, was ``perfect in poetry,'' and taped
her favorite verses to her bedroom wall. Gloria, he remembered, was
the queen of her drama class. The girls' father, Barnabas, is a
rich man by Kenyan standards, and Caroline and Gloria had dreams of
studying and working in the United States, which led them to the
American Embassy and their deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The road to Kathera rose out of the gray capital and into the
green world. It climbed past eucalyptus and hibiscus and
bougainvillea, past soaring hills and plunging waterfalls. A
wedding party overtook the funeral procession, the newlyweds
weaving in and out of the line of mourners.
</P>
<P>
   The cortege kept heading heavenward, and pines appeared among
the palms. Then the procession turned off the paved road, through
the ripening fruit on display at the lively market day in the town
of Nkubu, and down a rough track. Up the dirt road lay the village
of Kathera, five miles south of the Equator, ringed by plantations
of coffee and tea set in rich ochre earth.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the tiny tin-roofed Ntemwene Methodist Church here was
overflowing. People from the city and the countryside filled the
pews, spilled out a doorway hung with orchids and irises, sat
together on the ground. The service was conducted in English and in
two Kenyan dialects, Kikuyu and Kimeru. It was like any funeral
anywhere, with women hushing babies and weeping in silence.
</P>
<P>
   From memory, in Kimeru, the mourners sang from the Methodist
hymnal ``Hold the Fort,'' ``I am a Pilgrim and a Stranger'' and
``There is a Land of Pure Delight.'' For the first time in a week,
the sun came out.
</P>
<P>
   People rose to speak. One of the girls' many aunts, Nahason
Gitonga, spoke of enduring the unbearable, and said, ``We have no
choice but to keep our legs on the roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Shadrack Riungu, a lay preacher, pointed to the altar where the
girls' coffins lay shrouded in lace, and said, ``The person who did
this was possessed by the devil, and he must be defeated, in Jesus'
name.''
</P>
<P>
   The minister, the Rev. Thomas Gitobu, spoke at length of death
and resurrection, and said: ``Our minds are troubled. We don't know
what's next. These are days of sorrow, disillusion, despair,
broken-heartedness.''
</P>
<P>
   Strong women shouldered the coffin from the altar and took it
from the church. A hearse drove a short way down the dirt road to
the Mutuiris' house and farm, planted in tea as far as the eye
could see, and surrounded by palms. Behind the house, at the edge
of the greening tea, was a pile of newly dug earth, from which came
a coolness. The people from the city and the people from the
village gathered round, 300 strong.
</P>
<P>
   And then, singing old English hymns in an older tribal tongue,
they laid the girls in their graves. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
