<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-MONUMENT-WOES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUNDATION STRUGGLING TO PAY FOR MONUMENT TO MILITARY WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The nonprofit foundation that built and maintains
the monument to women who have served in the American military is
struggling to raise enough money to pay off construction costs and
other expenses.
</P>
<P>
   After drawing national praise for the first memorial honoring
military women amid the ever-increasing number of Washington
memorials and monuments, the foundation is unable to pay about $2
million in construction costs to Clark Construction Group Inc., and
$30,000 more for inaugural festivities.
</P>
<P>
   The October 1997 dedication at Arlington National Cemetery,
which drew about 30,000 people, including Vice President Al Gore,
culminated nearly 11 years of fund-raising and planning. President
Ronald Reagan signed legislation in 1986 approving the Women in
Military Service for America Memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Construction has thus far been willing to pay its
subcontractors out of pocket because the Women in Military Service
for America Memorial Foundation does not have the money to pay its
bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a legal matter right now,'' said Michael Alto, the
project executive with Clark Construction handling the memorial.
``We have a good relationship with the foundation and I understand
that they rely heavily upon donations. Some of their big donors
have just fallen through.''
</P>
<P>
   Alto, who continues to negotiate the bill with the foundation,
noted that monthly payments were made to Clark Construction through
September 1997; further payments, however, did not follow. Alto was
unaware then that the foundation was experiencing difficulties
raising money.
</P>
<P>
   Marilla Cushman, the director of public relations for the
foundation, said that groups seeking money to establish and
maintain monuments and memorials in Washington were forced to
``compete for the same piece of the pie.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation is competing for private donations with the
foundations that support at least a dozen other monuments in
varying stages of fund-raising or construction, said John Parsons,
associate superintendent of stewardships and partnerships for the
National Park Service.
</P>
<P>
   Proposals to build memorials are evaluated by the National Park
Service, the Commission of Fine Arts and the National Capital
Planning Commission. In a study released in November 1997, the
National Capital Planning Commission listed as many as 10 new
museums and 60 new monuments or memorials that will be searching
for sites in the coming years.
</P>
<P>
   There are already 154 memorials in the capital area.
</P>
<P>
   The military women's memorial and the U.S. Naval Memorial and
Naval Heritage Center, unlike most of the other monuments in the
Washington area, may be buoyed by their money-making abilities.
Both memorials can generate operating revenue by leasing its
facilities for receptions and conferences and by selling
educational items and memorabilia.
</P>
<P>
   The Women in Military Service memorial intends to catalog
servicewomen on a computer register, thus establishing a database
for women who have served in the armed forces. Donations are
requested for each listing. The foundation also prints several
newsletters, which are sent to servicewomen. Appeals for money
appear in the newsletters and in some veteran's publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great constituency that supports the memorial and
its activities,'' Ms. Cushman said. ``We can be an extraordinary
network and outreach resource for servicewomen and women veterans.
We are hopeful.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
