<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-SUSPECTS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN EMBASSY BOMBINGS, LINK EMERGES TO RICH SAUDI 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: Expands earlier story.)  (lb) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal law-enforcement officials said Saturday
that they had obtained information tentatively linking an associate
of Osama bin Laden, a wealthy Saudi-born businessman who has vowed
to wage a holy war against the United States, to the bombing of the
U.S. embassies in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   The officials declined to specify the nature of the evidence
connecting Bin Laden to the bombings. But Saturday's issue of
Newsday reported that a witness had identified an associate of Bin
Laden as having been in the truck carrying the bomb that heavily
damaged the U.S. Embassy in the capital of Kenya and killed more
than 200 people.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper identified the witness as one of the two privately
employed security guards working at the embassy gate at the time of
the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Saturday, intelligence and law-enforcement
officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said there was no
certain identification of the suspect, described as a relatively
low-level member of Bin Laden's circle.
</P>
<P>
   But officials indicated that this was the first potential
evidentiary link to Bin Laden, who the FBI and CIA have suspected
from the start was a key figure in the bombing plot.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have said since the early hours of the
investigation that the suspect at the top of their list was Bin
Laden, who this year renewed his vow to wage a holy war against the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Senior U.S. officials have said that he has a network in Africa,
and that U.S. intelligence had evidence that he has operatives in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   But officials previously cautioned that there has been no hard
evidence linking Bin Laden or his agents to the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, U.S. officials point to the nearly simultaneous bombings
at the U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania on Aug. 7 as indicating
that the attack was carried off by sophisticated terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden's network is one that has the financial resources and
the organizational skills for such a coordinated attack, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Another group under suspicion by the United States is the
Islamic Jihad, based in Cairo, Egypt, but that organization is also
financed by Bin Laden, U.S. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a wealthy Saudi family that made its money in the
construction business, Bin Laden is thought to have been involved
in the bombings of two U.S. military installations in Saudi Arabia.
But the United States has never issued an arrest warrant for Bin
Laden because of lack of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Bin Laden lived for a time in Sudan. He is said to live in
Afghanistan now, under the protection of the Taliban, the militant
Islamic group that controls most of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Law-enforcement officials said Bin Laden had become the subject
of an intense internal discussion at the FBI over whether the New
York office should take jurisdiction of the bombing case away from
the Washington field office, which has jurisdiction over crimes
against Americans in Africa.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials in New York have argued that they have
investigated Bin Laden in connection with the World Trade Center
bombing, and therefore should take over the Nairobi and Dar es
Salaam bombings in the event that he is found to be involved.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Saturday, a British newspaper, The Glasgow Herald,
reported that the Pakistani secret service is holding a suspect in
connection with the embassy bombings and is hunting two others. A
U.S. official in Pakistan said that a Pakistani newspaper had also
reported the arrest of a suspect.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper report cited unidentified Pakistani intelligence
officials as saying Mohammed Sadiq, 32, was detained at Karachi
international airport when he arrived on a Pakistan International
Airways flight from Kenya on Aug. 7, the day of the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Sadiq was held when he presented a false passport at customs,
the newspaper said. The officials were quoted as saying that
another suspect was in hiding in Pakistan and that a third was in
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   All three suspects were said to have been en route to
Afghanistan, having flown out of Kenya before the bombs went off.
</P>
<P>
   One of the three, suspected to be a bomb maker, was believed to
have left Kenya on Aug. 4, three days before the explosions and was
probably now in Afghanistan, The Glasgow Herald reported.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   President Clinton, in an address videotaped for broadcast
overseas, said that the Kenyans and Tanzanians killed in the
bombings ``were important to America because we cherish our
friendship with your peoples.'' At least 247 Kenyans and 10
Tanzanians died in the explosions. More than 5,000 people were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violent extremists try to use bullets and bombs to derail our
united efforts to bring peace to every part of the earth,'' Clinton
said. ``We grieve together, but I am proud that our nations have
also renewed our commitment to stand together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
