<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY IS SET FOR CLINTON TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Few details have been officially disclosed about
how President Clinton will testify by closed-circuit television on
Monday or how the broadcast will be protected from the inquiring
eyes and ears of people outside the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   But the use of cameras for testimony, common in federal civil
courts for the last five years, is slowly working its way into
criminal cases, and technical experts said the technology was well
established.
</P>
<P>
   Mike McCurry, the White House spokesman, said that the hookup
between the White House and the courthouse where the grand jury
meets would be set up by the White House Communications Agency,
with a ``one-way live feed.'' That means a camera at one end and a
monitor at the other, with one-way visual and audio communication.
</P>
<P>
   McCurry said the president would be in the Map Room, the same
place Clinton used when he testified in a Whitewater-related case
in 1996. The judge in that case ruled that if the president were to
testify on camera, the screen should not show him in a place that
included familiar trappings of his office.
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding will be covered by the normal rules of grand jury
secrecy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
