<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK SPORTS HISTORY  
 YOSHII BECOMES MOST FRUSTRATED PITCHER  
 DINGERS FOR LOSERS  
 MORE YANKEE FODDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   New York Sports History
</P>
<P>
   Although the chances would seem to be remote, it is possible
that Sunday, Oct. 4, could be the most momentous day in recent New
York sports history. Both the Yankees and the Mets could be playing
playoff games in the city that day.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, of course, have to win the National League wild-card
spot for that doubleheader even to be possible. Then they would
have to take the series to a fourth game because the Sunday game
would be their second home game.
</P>
<P>
   But the team playing the Yankees would have to do even better.
It would have to take the Yankees to a fifth and final game, a feat
that would seem highly unlikely the way the Yankees have breezed
through this season.
</P>
<P>
   Because tickets to the games of both teams would be scarce, few
fans would have the dilemma of deciding which game to attend if
those events did occur. There certainly would be no dilemma for the
city's mayor, Rudy Giuliani. The Mets would be far from his mind as
he sat in his box seat at Yankee Stadium, wearing his Yankees
jacket, of course.
</P>
<P>
   For the mayor's scheduling purposes, the Yankees will play the
first two games at home Tuesday and Wednesday evenings, Sept. 29
and 30, then play in their opponent's park Friday and Saturday. The
Mets' two home games would be Saturday and Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii Becomes Most Frustrated Pitcher
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday was a good day for Jason Schmidt of Pittsburgh
and Scott Eyre of the Chicago White Sox. Schmidt won for the first
time since June 1, ending a 12-start streak in which he suffered
eight losses that dropped his record to 8-9.
</P>
<P>
   Eyre won for the first time since April 25, ending a run of 10
starts without a victory. The only thing that interrupted the
streak was Eyre's disappearance from the starting rotation for
nearly two months.
</P>
<P>
   Their success left Masato Yoshii of the Mets as clearly the most
frustrated starting pitcher in the majors. Yoshii has started 14
times since May 27, the date of his last victory, and has emerged
with five losses and nine no-decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Next in line is Matt Beech of Philadelphia, who hasn't won in
nine starts since June 15. Carlos Perez, whom Montreal traded to
Los Angeles two weeks ago, has won one of his last 13 starts since
June 3. He has lost eight of the starts, and the Dodgers have lost
all three games he has started for them.
</P>
<P>
   Dingers for Losers
</P>
<P>
   Home runs are fun, especially when players hitting them are
chasing the home run record, but what do they mean?
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen players have hit 30 or more this season, and five play
for losing teams. Ken Griffey Jr. and Alex Rodriguez play for the
same losing team.
</P>
<P>
   Last season 28 players hit 30 or more. Only two of the 13
National League players played on teams with losing records, but
eight of the 14 American Leaguers played for losers. Then there was
Mark McGwire, the 28th player, who played in both leagues. Both of
his teams, Oakland and St. Louis, had losing records.
</P>
<P>
   More Yankee Fodder
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' remarkable season has focused attention on just
about every aspect of their organizational lives, but can't a
moratorium be declared on news about the latest feud between Reggie
Jackson and George Steinbrenner?
</P>
<P>
   Reggie knew from the first show that life with George would be
difficult. Furthermore, what else could he expect when he sold his
Hall of Fame identification for a front-office job with the club? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
