<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5534 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-PENNSTATION-RELICS     08-15 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PENNSTATION-RELICS-ART-540(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIECES OF OLD PENN STATION, SCATTERED TO THE WIND, ARE CALLED
BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 35-foot-high Doric column rises proudly _ if oddly
_ among a stand of birch trees on a hilltop in upstate New York. A
delicate maiden known as ``Day'' sits in a concrete recycling plant
in the Bronx. Great chunks of pink granite litter the New Jersey
Meadowlands, hidden by reeds, guarded by snapping turtles.
</P>
<P>
   These are the remains of the old Pennsylvania Station. And 35
years after their dispersal, many of the fragments may be coming
back to Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The Pennsylvania Station Redevelopment Corporation, a state
agency, hopes to use architectural remnants from the long-lost
building as decorative elements in a new passenger concourse and
ticketing hall it is planning in the General Post Office, directly
across Eighth Avenue from the station.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandros Washburn, the president of the corporation, and his
project associate, Marijke Smit, have tracked fragments as far as
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Their most poignant discovery, however, has not been granite and
marble but flesh and blood: the legion of preservationists _ some
known, many anonymous _ who struggled in the early 1960s, before
the New York City landmarks law was enacted, to save what they
could of McKim, Mead &AMP; White's masterpiece.
</P>
<P>
   There was the photographer Peter Moore and his wife, Barbara,
who visited the station repeatedly during demolition to record its
vanishing glory. There was Bayard Rustin, the civil rights leader,
who recovered several balusters for his art collection.
</P>
<P>
   And there was James Ahearn, a newspaper writer, who loaded his
Ford with pieces from the Meadowlands, where the stonework of
Pennsylvania Station had been hauled by the demolition contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``People _ not governments or corporations or institutions _
have been keeping the memory of Penn Station alive for 35 years,''
said Washburn, who was only 16 months old when the wreckers went to
work. ``We've found threads from the fabric of Penn Station
stretching across the country. Few buildings can inspire that
continuum. It makes you want to reweave those threads.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Pennsylvania Station concourse is to be built within the
General Post Office, an 84-year-old landmark that was also designed
by McKim, Mead &AMP; White. Formally known as the James A. Farley
Building, it sits directly over the Amtrak train platforms, between
31st and 33rd streets, almost like a western extension of the
station.
</P>
<P>
   ``By incorporating the fragments from the old station into the
new station, we are going to honor the past and hopefully set a
standard for the future,'' said Charles Gargano, the chairman of
Empire State Development Corp., of which the Pennsylvania Station
agency is a subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how the fragments will fit into the structure is not yet
clear. Architects at Skidmore, Owings &AMP; Merrill and Hardy Holzman
Pfeiffer Associates in Manhattan are working on preliminary designs
for the $315 million project. ``We're not hoping or expecting to
find a complete colonnade,'' Washburn said. ``We're hoping to find
a few choice fragments.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no budget line for archeological treasure. Instead,
state officials are counting on donations. ``We are not set up to
be buying back artifacts,'' Washburn said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   So far, the guardians of Pennsylvania Station's legacy have been
generous.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Moore, the proprietor of the Bound and Unbound bookshop
and gallery in Manhattan, has shared hundreds of haunting
photographs taken by her husband, who died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Moore, who was best known for chronicling performance art,
visited the station more than 30 times from 1963 to 1966, often
lugging a large-format camera. Viewed in sequence, his pictures
show a place of lyrical sculptural beauty slowly reduced to stark
structural bones. Meanwhile, commuters are seen in shocking
proximity to the wrecking cranes.
</P>
<P>
   Never before published, Moore's photographs have already
provided Washburn with a useful clue: there is no point searching
for the 60-foot-high Corinthian columns of the main waiting room,
since they were not solid stone but merely decorative casings over
steel.
</P>
<P>
   Photographs were not the only things taken by the Moores. They
also salvaged a half-dozen brass and leather stools from the
Savarin coffee shop. To this day, Ms. Moore is not sure why she and
her husband were carrying enough cash on them to pay the wreckers
$15 each for the stools. But she does know how they were able to
get them home: ``Checker cab.''
</P>
<P>
   Another visitor to the station was Rustin, not long after he
helped lead the 1963 March on Washington for Jobs and Freedom. He
dragged home a couple of balusters with the help of friends. His
executor, Walter Naegle, is considering donating them in honor of
Rustin and A. Philip Randolph, who organized the Brotherhood of
Sleeping Car Porters, a powerful voice for black workers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first donations _ two 29-inch granite balusters,
ornamental posts apparently from the attic of the station _ came
from Ahearn, who rescued them from the Meadowlands in 1968 and set
them up in front of his house in Ridgewood, N.J. as flower-pot
pedestals.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a field of neo-classical debris, Ahearn posed his
10-year-old son, Michael, atop an Ionic capital for a snapshot.
Then he set to the task of pushing the balusters up wood planks and
into his station wagon until it sagged to the rear axle.
</P>
<P>
   As an editorial writer for The Bergen Record, Ahearn had to
confront his conscience since he was, to be blunt, stealing. But He
consoled himself with the knowledge that the pieces would otherwise
be pounded into the foundation of a parking lot, although his
anxiety sharpened when a patrol car passed by with its roof light
flashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got home with our booty and exulted at rescuing objects of
beauty, fragments of history,'' Ahearn wrote to Washburn. ``They
have been waiting ever since for the undertaking on which you are
now embarked.''
</P>
<P>
   The least portable fragment found to date was a 35-foot Doric
column that was hauled to Woodridge, N.Y., in Sullivan County,
around 1963 and re-erected by cranes.
</P>
<P>
   It was intended as a beacon to spur development of Verrazano
College, a four-year, liberal-arts school that was being promoted
by a lawyer, Gilbert DiLucia, and others. But nothing more came of
the college than the column.
</P>
<P>
   Clifford Schwartz, a financial analyst in Manhattan, remembered
being taken as a child to see the column by his father, Martin. He
left a message in March with the Pennsylvania Station agency, not
sure whether anyone in the office would care. Within 30 minutes,
Ms. Smit called him back and scheduled a field trip for the next
day.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the obvious logistical challenge of moving the column,
Washburn said its return would be ``problematic,'' since the owner
wants to sell it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Washburn and Ms. Smit have focused their efforts on a
trucking company lot on Secaucus Road in the Meadowlands. One
expedition earlier this summer began at the Hackensack Meadowlands
Development Commission in Lyndhurst, where they asked to see
topographical maps and aerial photographs of the lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in search of Penn Station,'' Washburn explained to
Dennis Warren, a draftsman at the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, you're going to put that dinosaur back together again,''
Warren said, as he pulled out large sheets showing the intersection
of 74 degrees 3 minutes longitude, 40 degrees 46 minutes latitude.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at the site, Washburn and Ms. Smit donned hip waders
and weaved their way among 53-foot-long truck trailers and swamp
grasses 8 feet high. Suddenly came an exultant shout from Washburn:
``It looks like a piece of exterior cornice!''
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, under a small grove of box elders, partly submerged
in the mud at a crazy angle, there was a seven-foot-long chunk of
Pennsylvania Station's famously pink granite. The piece was shaped
like a fat comma, one side smooth as a table top, the other side
deeply pockmarked.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Washburn has had the lot examined by a
ground-penetrating radar device. His dearest wish is to find what
he calls the ``Holy Grail'' of Pennsylvania Station relics: a
missing pair of allegorical maidens by Adolph Weinman known as
``Day'' (her faced upraised and framed by sunflowers) and ``Night''
(her face hooded, clutching poppies).
</P>
<P>
   There were four ``Day'' and four ``Night'' figures on the
station, which opened in 1910, along with 14 large stone eagles.
Two eagles stayed at the station and can still be seen near the
Seventh Avenue entrance. The rest found homes from Maine to
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   One ``Day'' and ``Night'' pair were taken to Kansas City as the
centerpiece of the Eagle Scout Tribute Fountain. Another pair were
rescued from the Meadowlands and carted to Ringwood State Park in
northern New Jersey. A lone ``Night'' figure was saved by the
Brooklyn Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Five months ago, Con-Agg Recycling Corp. at East 149th Street
and Bruckner Boulevard in the Bronx let Washburn know that another
``Day'' had been sitting in its yard for years, damaged but not
lost. That leaves one ``Day'' and one ``Night'' unaccounted for.
Washburn is concentrating on the Meadowlands because that is where
most of the stonework was hauled by the Lipsett demolition company.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anybody seriously considered it art,'' Morris Lipsett, the
head of the company, said in 1964, ``they would have put up some
money to save it.''
</P>
<P>
   But somebody did consider it art. In 1965, Parks Commissioner
Newbold Morris wrote to Irving Felt, the chairman and president of
Madison Square Garden Corp., which had bought the air rights to the
station from the Pennsylvania Railroad and was building a new
arena.
</P>
<P>
   Morris told Felt that the Brooklyn Museum hoped to obtain a
figure of ``Night'' as a ``focal point'' for its sculpture garden,
but that the piece had already been consigned to the New Jersey
dump.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lady in question weighs 10 tons,'' Morris wrote. ``Time is
important because the demolition yard is continually being
bulldozed to make room for more Pennsylvania Station ruins.''
</P>
<P>
   With the assistance of Ivan Karp, founder of the Anonymous Arts
Recovery Society and the O.K. Harris Gallery in SoHo, the figure of
``Night'' and part of a monumental Ionic column were soon shipped
to Brooklyn. In 1966, the museum also obtained decorative granite
plaques from the station.
</P>
<P>
   True to Morris' word, they remain the focal points of the Frieda
Schiff Warburg Memorial Sculpture Garden. They are a reminder of
what New York lost and _ indirectly _ what it gained, since the
destruction spurred the landmarks law that helped preserve Grand
Central Terminal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a turning point in the way New Yorkers felt responsible
for what was going on in their city,'' said Barbara Head Millstein,
the curator of the sculpture garden. ``The Grand Central revival is
a direct result in every possible way of the demolition of Penn
Station.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
