<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FASSEL GETS UNWELCOME FLASHBACK FROM JAGUARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ For the third time in three meetings, the
Jacksonville Jaguars brought out the worst in the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   As they did in the preseason a year ago and in the 1997 regular
season, the Jaguars made the Giants look confused and unprepared in
a lopsided 24-10 defeat Friday night at Alltel Stadium. In three
games during the last two seasons, Jacksonville has outscored the
Giants by 104-39.
</P>
<P>
   On offense Friday, the Giants stumbled badly, picking up just
six first downs and failing to convert a first down on 12 of 13
third-down attempts.
</P>
<P>
   The starting quarterback, Danny Kanell, failed to complete his
first seven passes during a sloppy, penalty-filled first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' vaunted defense fared no better. The tackling was
careless and shoddy, and the defense was called for six first-half
penalties.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Giants were thoroughly dominated and looked flat,
something that has happened recently whenever the opponent is
Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was flashback for me from our game with them last year,''
Giants Coach Jim Fassel said. ``It's like we've reverted to last
year at this time. I'm not very happy right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, who eased to a 24-17 victory over the Cincinnati
Bengals last weekend, can now expect a week of harsh practices from
Fassel.
</P>
<P>
   The coach raged at his team when it played with similar
indifference last preseason against Jacksonville. He did not look
favorably Friday night on an offense that was out of sync and a
defense that put forth an inattentive effort.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell played the first half, finishing the game with 2
completions in 9 attempts for 47 yards. The Giants' rushing attack
was nearly as ineffective. Tiki Barber dropped another wide-open
pass _ as he did last week _ and ran 3 times for 11 yards. His
replacement, Tyrone Wheatley, came up with only 21 yards on 8
carries.
</P>
<P>
   Of Kanell's performance, Fassel pointed out that his quarterback
was given little time to throw because of poor protection from the
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the quarterback takes five steps into the pocket and
there's five guys on him, there's not much he can do,'' Fassel
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel also criticized Barber. ``I'm worried about Tiki right
now,'' he said. ``He's not showing me he can catch the ball in
games or in practices.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants kept the game close in the second half when both
teams played their second- and third-string units. A bizarre
touchdown scored by Giants receiver Amani Toomer cut the
Jacksonville lead to 17-10 with six seconds remaining in the third
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Toomer dived to the grass to make a shoestring catch on the
Giants' 37-yard line. As defensive back Kevin Devine passed Toomer,
he appeared to reach out to touch him down.
</P>
<P>
   But the officials ruled that no contact was made, no whistle
blew, and Toomer leaped to his feet and dashed into the end zone
untouched for a 73-yard score.
</P>
<P>
   But a touchdown pass from Jacksonville's third-string
quarterback Jonathan Quinn to Alvis Whitted restored the Jaguars'
two-touchdown lead.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the second half, Jacksonville scored on a 59-yard
touchdown run by Tavian Banks, a reserve running back.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, quarterback Mark Brunell led the Jaguars on
an 8-play, 73-yard drive culminating with a 5-yard touchdown pass
to Jimmy Smith.
</P>
<P>
   In the early going Friday, the Giants looked sloppy.
</P>
<P>
   There were penalties on both sides of the ball, two low snaps on
Giants punts and more missed Giants tackles in the first quarter
than one would normally have been seen in two Giants games last
season.
</P>
<P>
   On offense, the ease Kanell showed at the helm in last week's
game seemed a distant memory against the aggressive Jacksonville
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell missed Chris Calloway with his first pass of the evening,
badly overthrowing his receiver. Kanell would follow that up with
six successive incomplete passes.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants did not mount a scoring drive _ and Kanell did not
complete a pass _ until midway through the second quarter when
Jacksonville had removed most of its starting defensive players.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants moved into Jacksonville territory following a 31-yard
pass down the right sideline from Kanell to Ike Hilliard. It was
Kanell's first completion. But Kanell hit tight end Andy Haase for
a 16-yard gain on the next play, bringing the Giants to the
Jacksonville 18-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' drive stalled there, with kicker Brad Daluiso
converting on a 35-yard field goal, his first of the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Giants cornerback Jason Sehorn returned a deflected pass 30
yards for an apparent touchdown in the second quarter, a score that
was nullified when the Giants' Phillippi Sparks was called for
holding Jacksonville wide receiver Reggie Barlow.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of a variety of penalties called against the Giants'
defense on pass plays in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Percy Ellsworth and Jessie Armstead also drew penalties, and
Sparks had an unnecessary roughness penalty at the end of a play.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars' first-half lead was just 10-3, in part because
Jacksonville place-kicker Mike Hollis missed two first-half field
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Just before intermission, Hollis was successful on a field-goal
attempt from 26 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The scheduled 8 p.m. start of the game was delayed for an hour
because of thunderstorms and lightning in the Jacksonville area.
But an hour later, it had become another clear, humid Florida
night. The game was played in otherwise dry conditions.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' RYAN PHILLIPS, in his new position as a strongside
linebacker, had a sack of Jacksonville's backup quarterback, STEVE
MATTHEWS. Giants defensive end CEDRIC JONES also sacked Matthews in
the second quarter. It was Jones' first sack _ in the preseason or
regular season _ in his three seasons with the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Giants defensive end MICHAEL STRAHAN left the game briefly in
the first quarter with what the team called a neck burner, an
injury that is sometimes also called a pinched nerve. Strahan
returned to the game several plays later.
</P>
<P>
   CHRIS HUDSON, the Jaguars safety who delivered the hit that
injured IKE HILLIARD's neck in last year's game on Sept. 7 in
Jacksonville, was not active for Friday night's game because of an
injury to his right thumb. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
