<SLUG> BC-BBO-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEE FANS AGREE: SEASON IS A WASTE WITHOUT A TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like those formless creatures who lurk under our beds
in the night, dreadful thoughts now writhe in the minds of sentient
Yankee fans. What if something goes wrong? What if they don't win
it all? Fans talk about the nagging fears that not only might the
season end badly, like life itself, but also that post-season
defeat would negate this glorious regular season.
</P>
<P>
   The chill fingers of an unfriendly Fall have reached into the
dank dog days in Stuart, Fla., where Jane Heller is ``praying with
clammy hands.''
</P>
<P>
   She has been there before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a Ranger fan,'' Heller said last week. ``I remember the
best season ever, 50 wins, Messier, and then the Penguins waddled
in and it was over. And it was as if it had never happened at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   In the shank of this best season ever, when he should be feeling
only sweet pleasure, Roger Sims in Everett, Wash., has bad dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to eliminate the wild card,'' he said, ``and things go
wrong and we get eliminated. The whole season becomes a hideous
nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   Was love in vain? Was hope a fraud? Does there always have to be
a payoff?
</P>
<P>
   Why can't we just enjoy one sunset at a time?
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be enough, just the pleasure of the season,'' said
Sims, a former Air Force combat pilot and television producer.
``But it's not. It seems as though we should be able to file away
this season like a precious bijou, no matter how it turns out. But
I can't. That flawed idea of having to win everything is like a
cancer in my brain.''
</P>
<P>
   I asked Heller, who writes comic mysteries, to make a joke, to
tell me Sims was wrong. No matter how it ends, won't this be a
summer of dreams?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' she snapped. ``It would be a nightmare. You know how I
feel about happy endings; the couples in my books always go off in
the sunset. This is not just about being No. 1. It's about having
this all matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Bouton, the newest of Yankee old-timer, sighs at all this.
In his motivational speeches, he has always promoted process over
payoff, of deriving pleasure from chopping the wood rather than
imagining the fire. Since appearing at Old-Timers' Day at the
Stadium last month after a quarter century of exile for writing
``Ball Four,'' his Yankee interest has risen but his philosophy has
not changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Owners, sportswriters and fans think about winning as the only
payoff,'' he said from his home in the Berkshire Mountains of
western Massachusetts. ``But athletes have to think about playing
their best, playing boldly and courageously. Once they start
thinking about winning, about the end, they start playing to sit on
a lead, to avoid a mistake, to not lose, and that's when you
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that pressure from owners, fans and sportswriters,
particularly the ``hopeless win junkies'' who ``derived their
satisfaction from the trophy instead of the challenge,'' could
distract the players.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Sims nor Heller would accept such potential guilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's you scribes who will proclaim it's not enough,'' said
Sims, whose only regret in living near Seattle is watching fewer
Yankee games. ``You people will say that they'll have to sweep 11
in a row in the post-season to fulfill their destiny. But if they
don't win it all, what will I say to these latte-lapping jerks
around here?''
</P>
<P>
   Sims stays up late to dial up the results of Yankee games.
Heller wakes up early. And then calls fellow fans around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's in everyone's mind,'' she said. ``It's too perfect. You
lose a middle reliever and someone floats in on a raft.''
</P>
<P>
   Bouton thinks there could be a lesson in defeat. ``If they do
lose,'' he said, ``it might afford an opportunity for people to
talk about the values of doing a good job over a long period, which
is a real achievement, versus being hot for a short period, which
is winning mostly with luck and serendipity.''
</P>
<P>
   Heller agrees with Bouton's value system more than the playoff
system. ``The work ethic should mean something,'' she said. ``The
hardest worker over the longest period should win the prize. This
could all be wiped out. I mean, OK, if the Braves beat us in a
great Series, but what if, say, Boston slipped in? Not this season.
Even old wounds are mended. Even Bouton's finally back.''
</P>
<P>
   And Bouton remembers the best advice he ever got, just before
his first World Series start. He was nervous until his fellow
Yankee pitcher Ralph Terry told him that there were 500,000 Chinese
Communists who didn't care about this game at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``But no one will accept winning the pennant as enough,'' Bouton
said. ``If they win the World Series, the next day, people will
say, `Can they repeat?' The Yankees will never have a night's
sleep. They will be expected to start lifting weights for next
season during the victory parade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
