<HEADLINE>
TAWANA BRAWLEY STANDS BY HER STORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIRTA OJITO    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ending the silence that kept her away from the
courtroom during the recent trial of her former advisers, Tawana
Brawley said at a ceremony in Brooklyn Friday night that her fight
for justice is just beginning and insisted that 10 years ago she
was the victim of a vicious crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``A crime was committed to me,'' she said. ``A crime was
committed to the people. The press has lied to you. They have lied
on me. You should be upset cause I'm very upset. And I'm tired of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brawley, 25, spoke during a banquet in Fort Greene,
Brooklyn, to commemorate the 10th anniversary of the United African
Movement, an organization that was created as a protest group
supporting her cause.
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks, which were broadcast by New York 1, the cable news
channel, came less than a month after a jury in Dutchess County
ordered three of Ms. Brawley's advisers _ the Rev. Al Sharpton, C.
Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox Jr. _ to pay $345,000 to Steven
Pagones, a former prosecutor whom they had accused of being part of
a group of white men who they said kidnapped and raped Ms. Brawley
in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Brawley, whose story of being attacked when she was a
teen-ager was discredited by a special grand jury in 1988, said her
quest for justice is not over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a long way to go 'cause we're not going to stop
fighting,'' she said. ``We're not going to stop fighting for
justice until we get it.''
</P>
<P>
   She praised two of her advisers, Sharpton and Maddox, for
standing by her. ``I say it means so much when you've gone 10 years
in allowing the mass public and people all in your face saying,
`You lied, you lied,''' she said. ``And I said, `How could you say
I lied when I never said anything to you?'
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned so much about trust, about love, about
commitment, what a real strong black man is. I see that every day
in my father who stood by us every day, by Alton Maddox, by Rev. Al
Sharpton, by all these strong brothers you see on the side of us.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time Ms. Brawley had spoken publicly about her
case. Last December, she told a roaring audience of supporters in
Brooklyn that she has always told the truth about the attack. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1525EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
