<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-MONTGOMERIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTGOMERIE TRIES TO MOVE FROM SECOND FIDDLE TO FIRST CHAIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Scotland)  (bl) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Colin Montgomerie has been in this position
before, and it has never worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Major championships have ended cruelly for Montgomerie whenever
he has been in contention. He finished second at the 1994 U.S.
Open, losing in a playoff to Ernie Els. Montgomerie finished second
at the 1995 PGA Championship, losing in a playoff to Steve
Elkington. And last year at the U.S. Open, Montgomerie got a
refresher course in heartbreak, finishing second again to Els.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those bitter defeats, one can only imagine the
thoughts twisting through Montgomerie's mind when he teed off
Saturday afternoon for the third round of the PGA Championship.
Still in quest of his first major championship, Montgomerie began
Saturday at Sahalee Country Club in prime position at three under
par, one stroke behind the leader, Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend will provide the latest chapter in Montgomerie's
pursuit of a major. With players like Singh, Tiger Woods, Davis
Love 3d, and Mark O'Meara among those in contention, the weekend is
certain to be memorable, regardless of the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   But for Montgomerie, this weekend will be feast or famine.
</P>
<P>
   Either he will win his first major, ending his career-long wait
for a career-long goal, or he will fall short again, and be dealt
another crushing defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've come very close a number of times, more than most,'' said
Montgomerie, a native of Scotland, who has been the leading
money-winner on the European tour for the past five years.
``There's a reason why I've come over here, and I haven't come over
here to finish second.''
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts Montgomerie's desire to win, and he has constantly
searched for any edge. Dissatisfied with his putting the last two
years, Montgomerie prepared for the PGA by working with Dave Pelz,
the renowned putting teacher. The payoff has been immediate.
Friday, Montgomerie made birdie putts of 10 feet, 15 feet, 20 feet
and 25 feet. If Montgomerie's putter stays solid, he will remain on
the leader board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out here and worked a day and a half early with David,
who I really admire and respect,'' said Montgomerie, referring to
his sessions with Pelz. ``I hadn't met him before, and I had to do
something about my putting. He has been super, oozes confidence,
and that can only make you more confident. Ninety percent of it is
confidence. If you know you're going to hole it, 90 percent of the
time you will.''
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie, who is superbly accurate with his drives and long
irons, decided to address his putting woes after the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had 37 and 33 putts the first two days,'' said Montgomerie.
``That was about 10 shots too many, 10 putts too many to compete. I
was 10 shots off the lead. So I felt that was the time to call on
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Montgomerie has looked steady so far, it will be
interesting to see how he reacts as the pressure builds this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie plays with his emotions on his sleeve, and when he
hits a bad shot, you can tell by looking at his face.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomerie has become a favorite target for course hecklers,
but this week, he has heard few negative comments from the gallery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crowds here have been super, and I've enjoyed myself as I
always do in America,'' Montgomerie said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Montgomerie's resume will have a glaring hole until he wins
a major. Ten years ago, Montgomerie probably thought he would win
multiple majors, and he still might. But unless he wins the PGA on
Sunday, Montgomerie will have to wait until next year's Masters
before getting another chance. If Montgomerie does win here, it
will be interesting to see how he reacts. Will he shed tears, the
way he did last year after losing to Els the U.S. Open by one
stroke? Will he say, `I told you so' to his critics?' Or will he
simply savor the moment?
</P>
<P>
   Nine of the last 10 PGA champions have been first-time major
winners, so that could be a positive omen for him. In addition,
this seems to be a year for veteran players to win majors. O'Meara,
who won the Masters and the British Open this year at age 41, is
trying to become the first man since Ben Hogan to win three majors
in the same year. And Lee Janzen, who won his second U.S. Open in
June, is only two years younger than Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   But Sahalee's tight fairways and smooth, manicured greens seem
to suit Montgomerie's game. Could this finally be his breakthrough
year at a major? Montgomerie was eager to find out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a great plus in hitting the fairways in America, and I
tend to do that more than most,'' he said. ``I think I got the most
out of my first two rounds that I could. If I can putt anything
like I have the first two days, I have a chance.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1529EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
