<SLUG> BC-BOATING-AUTISSIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLOON ON BOAT HAS SAILOR FEELING MORE SECURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: R.I., France)  (bl) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, R.I. _ Isabelle Autissier is thinking like a
balloonist these days. But Autissier, a solo sailor from France,
has no intention of going airborne. The balloon she is talking
about fits in the back of her boat, and she has plans to inflate it
only to stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a calculation, but I'm sure it will work,'' the
41-year-old Autissier said of the balloon, which is 283 cubic feet
when inflated. She hopes it will remain folded up innocuously in
the stern of PRB, her 60-foot monohull race boat.
</P>
<P>
   The balloon may seem like a wacky idea. But for a yachtswoman
like Autissier, who has competed in three round-the-world sailboat
races, any kind of life-saving device has merit. Autissier was
rescued by helicopter after her boat lost its mast, was rolled over
and smashed by waves off Australia in the 1994-95 BOC
round-the-world race.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Autissier is preparing for the Around Alone, nee the BOC
Challenge, the solo sailing competition with a fresh set of
sponsors. Both Autissier and Jean-Pierre Mouligne, a yachtsman from
Newport, R.I., are getting ready here at Little Harbor Marina. The
competition, which will have three stops along the way, is
scheduled to begin Sept. 26 from Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   Autissier's stopgap balloon will remain no more than an
intriguing possibility unless she needs to inflate it. ``If you
think about it,'' she said recently, ``it will work.''
</P>
<P>
   That would only be likely if PRB turns over in a storm.
Autissier would then release a canister of compressed air into the
balloon. The inflated ball is designed to lift the back of her boat
up high and force the bow into the water. That should give the
yacht enough torque to allow its ballasted keel bulb to swing the
sailboat right-side-up again.
</P>
<P>
   Mouligne also subscribes to the idea, which was developed by
Groupe Finot of France, the designer of his and Autissier's boats.
</P>
<P>
   Single-handed sailors need all the quirky, resourceful equipment
they can muster. They are often forced to rely on themselves, or a
handful of others, to get out of trouble at sea. When they need to
be rescued, critics often complain about the governmental costs
involved. But long-distance sailors are frequently out of range of
help anyway. Autissier was 1,000 miles off shore when the
Australian navy and helicopters came to her aid.
</P>
<P>
   The Frenchwoman, far from being scared off, has proved to be as
strong and persistent as any solo sailor out there. ``These boats
are wonderful,'' she said. ``And even if it is sometimes
frightening and difficult, it is wonderful to be in nature, and to
be at the end of the world with all its wildlife.''
</P>
<P>
   Her outlook draws on uneven results. She was seventh in her
first BOC race in 1990-91 and counts her 1994-95 as only half a
race. Still, those who followed her thwarted efforts that season
know that she was five days ahead of her 19 male rivals in the
first leg from Charleston to Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
   She has also competed in the Vendee Globe Challenge, a nonstop
solo race around the world. In the 1996-97 Vendee, she broke her
boat's rudder near Cape Town and was forced to go ashore for
repairs. The landfall disqualified her from the race. Undaunted,
she finished in an unofficial second place anyway.
</P>
<P>
   It is around Cape Horn, an ominous reach of land and ocean at
the tip of South America, that Autissier has made her mark. It has
become so special that her boyfriend in France makes a habit of
chartering a boat out of Ushuaia, Argentina, the nearest port town
near Cape Horn, and waves to her as she passes.
</P>
<P>
   On April 23, 1994, Autissier sailed into San Francisco after
having rounded Cape Horn in a 62-day passage from New York. The
voyage stripped the old record, set in 1989, by an astounding 14
days. An attempt at setting another New York-San Francisco record
left Autissier in second place last spring. Yves Parlier of France
shaved five more days off the 1989 record.
</P>
<P>
   And so it is with Autissier's ocean racing log, a series of
highs and lows as undulating as the sea itself. ``One year on the
water is like 10 years of your life,'' she said. ``It is very, very
demanding and stressful. But I'm not doing it for money or to be
well-known. It is something inside of me, and I really want to do
it. If I ever lose that, I will do something else.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
