u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WOODSTOCK-ENCORE-5     08-15 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WOODSTOCK-ENCORE-550&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELL PHONES ARE PART OF THE BACKDROP FOR THE NEW WOODSTOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETHEL, N.Y. _ The rolling fields of Max Yasgur's farm are again
swathed in a psychedelic quilt of tie-dye-clad music fans. This
time, though, the fans are carrying cellular telephones, and the
automatic teller machines are just a few steps away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think high-tech is kind of infringing on the hippies,'' said
Kevin Carter, who was working at a one-hour photo development stand
in one of the many vendor tents on the site of the original
Woodstock concert. ``Some of the die-hard Woodies are having
problems with it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was 29 years ago this weekend that hundreds of thousands of
flower children flocked here for a three-day festival of free love
and music.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, they drove, walked or danced right into the fields,
guided only by the spirit of the moment and the age. On Saturday, a
fluorescent highway sign beckoned concertgoers off the proper exit
of Route 17, onto a road lined with orange cones. Traffic was
carefully controlled by the New York State Police.
</P>
<P>
   The edge of the concert area was marked by a long cordon of
ticket booths, where the Gerry Foundation, which now owns the
Yasgur fields and organized this weekend's event, charged a $35
daily admission per person. (Admission was free for children under
12.)
</P>
<P>
   Event organizers said that 12,000 tickets had been sold for
Friday and that 4,000 to 6,000 children had come in free. As it is
currently set up, the Woodstock site can accommodate 30,000 fans.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers said they expected the numbers to grow as the
weekend wore on. The performers Saturday included some brand-name
1960s rockers like Richie Havens, Lou Reed, Joni Mitchell and Pete
Townshend. Organizers, however, said they expected the largest
attendance on Sunday when '90s bands, including the Goo Goo Dolls
and Third Eye Blind, are scheduled to play.
</P>
<P>
   To get down the hill to where the musicians were performing on a
state-of-the-art sound stage (the same stage that Garth Brooks
performed on in Central Park), audience members had to pass by a
wide area of vendor tents where booths hawked an array of '60s
memorabilia and all types of food.
</P>
<P>
   For $20, Cornelius Alexy was selling peace sign necklaces
fashioned from pieces of the ``original'' chain-link fence that
surrounded the Yasgur property in 1969 _ complete with a
certificate of authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Across the way, pastrami and corned beef sandwiches could be
purchased for $7 each. A combination plate of Chinese food cost $6.
For the more health conscious, there was also a fruit and juice
bar.
</P>
<P>
   As the folk singer Melanie began to play Saturday morning,
opening the second day of this event, which is being called ``A Day
in the Garden,'' there were already lines at a bank of Bell
Atlantic public telephones and at the portable automatic teller
machines that were trucked in by Fleet Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Krier, 21, of Milltown, N.J., who was waiting to withdraw
money, said he and his friends had made been making an annual
camping trip to the Woodstock site here since the summer of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not real big on the vendors and stuff, and the ticket
prices are expensive,'' Krier said. He said rules banning audience
members from bringing in food and refreshments had forced him to
get cash from the ATM.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Many people, however, said the event was well-organized and
despite the commercialism, it offered comforts _ like dozens and
dozens of portable toilets _ that were not available at the '69
Woodstock. Organizers said they tried to modernize without
undermining the event's hippie soul.
</P>
<P>
   Changes were made above and below ground. ``We built six miles
of interior roads,'' explained Michael DiTullo, a vice president of
the Gerry Foundation, adding that wells were drilled, an
underground water system was installed and five miles of split-rail
fence were put up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We developed 10,000 parking spaces,'' DiTullo said. ``Not with
blacktop of course, with green, with grass.'' He said the
foundation has big dreams for Bethel including the possible
development of rock-and-roll resort hotels. ``This will be the
venue of the next millennium,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most importantly, the fans said they came for the music. ``We
came in on Thursday and set up the tent, and Don Henley was tuning
up,'' said Mike McGrath, of Newburgh, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great,'' he said. ``I went out fishing, just sat on the
boat and listened to tunes for three hours.'' The commercialism, he
said, ``is bound to happen over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   A few miles from the concert site, at Max Yasgur's old
farmhouse, some stalwart defenders of Woodstock Nation held a rally
to protest the commercialism and corporate invasion of Woodstock.
Several hundred aging hippies camped in the field and woods
surrounding the house.
</P>
<P>
   But such politicking was not going to keep Gwynne Watkins, an
18-year-old Joni Mitchell fan from Richmond, N.J., from recapturing
the essence of a bygone era. ``There aren't enough concerts like
this,'' she said. ``Everything is always enclosed, where you can't
meet anybody and you can't see anybody.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
