<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SEAMAN-SLAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLITARY EX-SEAMAN, 81, FOUND SLAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA STEWART    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a half-century at sea, circling the globe on
merchant ships, Harold Williams had finally found a safe harbor in
his ramshackle house on a quiet street on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   There, he lived a life as unhidden and uneventful as that of a
goldfish in a bowl. In fact, it was because his always-open front
door was unaccountably closed that a neighbor went to check on him
Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   She found Williams, 81, lying near the door, his face bloodied
from several blows to the head. Police have made no arrests in the
slaying, though they say Williams probably knew his attacker.
</P>
<P>
   Officers do not know the motive for the killing, said Detective
Robert Walsh of the New York City Police Department. Perhaps it was
robbery, but Williams had little to be stolen.
</P>
<P>
   And on South Avenue, in Mariners Harbor, where he lived,
violence and serious crimes ``are highly unusual,'' Walsh said.
``These are working people who own their homes and are very
concerned about keeping up the neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   For about 15 years, since his retirement as a merchant seaman,
Williams was a fixture on the little street. Shortly before noon
every morning, he would open the front door and sit just inside to
wait for the mail and the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mail was the highlight of his day,'' said the neighbor who
found him, a 44-year-old woman living in the other side of his
duplex, who spoke on the condition that her name not be used. In
return for free housing, she cleaned his house once a week and
drove him to the grocery store every two weeks for the dozens of
frozen dinners he heated twice a day in the microwave. ``The dog in
the yard and the mail in the box _ that's what he lived for.''
</P>
<P>
   A taciturn man who devoured paperback mysteries and war tales,
he apparently enjoyed discussing a few topics with a neighbor,
Martin Vuvek, 47. ``Warfare and tanks, especially Russian tanks,''
Vuvek, 47, said. ``And dinosaurs. He had a whole thick set of books
on dinosaurs.''
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, Williams nearly lost a hand when his ship
was torpedoed near Murmansk, in the Soviet Union. After the war,
his work took him from England to Portugal, from Hong Kong to
Borneo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He visited all the things that were worthwhile seeing _
bullfights, statues in cities, museums,'' said David Bruce, an old
friend.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a printer who grew up in the Hell's Kitchen section
of Manhattan, Williams was a seaman before he was 20, said Bruce,
87, who was his best friend for nearly 70 years. The two met in
Hell's Kitchen, where they played ball in the streets and ``hung
around together,'' said Bruce, a retired electrician in Kingston,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd go out on ships for two, three months,'' Bruce said. ``He
tended the water, fired the boilers, watched the gauges. He liked
coming home and getting off the ship with a pocketful of money.
We'd have a few beers, go to cowboy movies on 42nd Street. Double
date.''
</P>
<P>
   Over beers, they would talk about women. ``He was kind of shy,
but he figured someday she'd come along,'' said Bruce, a widower.
Years later, Williams told his housekeeper that he had once met
someone special during a layover in Portugal. But he never married.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was afraid to get married _ afraid he'd not be treated
right,'' Bruce said. ``He was afraid of getting hurt by a friend or
a woman. He wouldn't take no chances. He wouldn't even take a
promotion on a better job. He stayed with the things he could do.''
</P>
<P>
   Worried about being cheated, he hoarded his money, Bruce said.
Though Williams could be unexpectedly kind, adding $20 to his
housekeeper's $5-an-hour wages on her birthday, he was suspicious
of strangers and worried about crime.
</P>
<P>
   But when he was well into his 70s, he finally gave his heart
away without reserve _ to a stray puppy he found on South Avenue
and named Brownie. ``He loved that dog so much,'' Bruce said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams gave Brownie a bed _ a mattress, box springs and frame
_ and fed him the most expensive dog food. When Brownie became so
frail that he had to be put down, Williams was depressed for
months, said Bruce, who visited to cheer up his old friend.
``Brownie did so many things for him. When the phone rang, he'd
bark and run over to him. That dog would sort of talk to him.''
</P>
<P>
   About a year after Brownie's death, Williams finally settled on
a replacement, a smart and sweet-tempered mongrel with long black
hair. He bought the dog, named Manatee, for $50, and he never
closed the door between him and the dog. When Williams' body was
discovered, Manatee was alone in the front yard. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
