<HEADLINE>
ANNA HARRISON, 85, WHO LED U.S. CHEMICAL SOCIETY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Mo.)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anna Jane Harrison, an emeritus professor of chemistry at Mount
Holyoke College and the first woman to be president of the
150,000-member American Chemical Society, died on Aug. 8 at Holyoke
Hospital. She was 85 and lived in nearby South Hadley, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a stroke, the college said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harrison was born on a farm in Benton City, Mo. Her early
education was in a one-room country school, and she returned to
teach there for two years after graduating from the University of
Missouri in 1933.
</P>
<P>
   She then earned an M.A. and a Ph.D. in physical chemistry, also
at Missouri, and started her college teaching career at Sophie
Newcomb College of Tulane University in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   She joined the faculty at Mount Holyoke College as an assistant
professor in 1945, rose to professor in 1950 and headed the
department of chemistry from 1960 to 1966.
</P>
<P>
   She became the William R. Kenan Jr. Professor of Chemistry in
1976 and held that post until she retired in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harrison received 20 honorary degrees and won awards from
the American Chemical Society in 1977 and 1982 for her
contributions as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   She was active in the society for 62 years and became its
president, for a one-year term, in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harrison also served on the National Science Board in the
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she was a longtime board member of the American
Association for the Advancement of Science and in 1984 became its
president.
</P>
<P>
   She has no immediate survivors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-JAIL-BRUTALITY-ART     08-15 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-JAIL-BRUTALITY-ART-660(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUARDS BRUTALIZED INMATES AT RIKERS ISLAND, SUIT SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CHRISTOPHER DREW    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When prisoners entered the special disciplinary ward,
they often received ``greeting beatings'' from the guards as a
portent of the brutality to come. At other times, jail supervisors
ordered assaults on antagonistic inmates, and serious head
injuries, bone fractures and broken eardrums were common. One
prisoner died from an avalanche of blows.
</P>
<P>
   This gruesome litany sounds like an Amnesty International report
on a backwater country. But it all happened in the past decade at
New York City's massive jail complex on Rikers Island, as
correction officers and inmates battled for control of the most
violent section, informally dubbed the ``House of Pain.''
</P>
<P>
   And the full picture of the bare-knuckled punishment meted out
by the guards, including some who laughed about it over beer, is
only now emerging from court records, mainly as a result of a legal
settlement last month spelling out a series of reforms.
</P>
<P>
   Top officials at the city's Department of Correction say they
have wiped out the worst problems, and they agreed to settle a
class-action lawsuit by 15 prisoners to avoid greater restrictions
on the jail. Bernard Kerik, the department's commissioner,
acknowledged in an interview last week that abuses had occurred and
that jail officers had covered them up. But he said that over the
last three years, the agency had cleaned up its operations as part
of an effort to reduce tensions and improve security within city
jails.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past,'' he said, ``there was never the internal
oversight and control that there is today.'' Injuries to prisoners
have been ``substantially reduced,'' he said, adding: ``Are
prisoners being beaten into submission? Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   But advocates for the rights of prisoners say there are
lingering problems at Rikers' disciplinary ward, the Central
Punitive Segregation Unit, which houses a constantly changing cast
of more than 400 inmates who have committed infractions in the
island's 10 jails. Some national prison analysts said they had
never seen a jail where excessive force was so routine, and one
expert, Vincent Nathan, said in a report that at least through the
mid-1990s Rikers' punitive unit occupied ``the third ring of hell
in the field of corrections in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Given the combustible atmosphere in many prisons and jails, and
the fact that force is often justified in subduing inmates, it is
not clear how many Rikers inmates were injured as a result of
deliberate beatings. But court records show that since the central
disciplinary unit opened in 1988, guards have used force to control
inmates more than 1,500 times, and at least 300 prisoners have
suffered serious injuries, many from blows to the head or to the
body that damaged internal organs.
</P>
<P>
   Medical records show that more than 50 of them had broken bones,
and up to 35 had perforated eardrums _ a painful injury that often
causes hearing loss. Doctors say it normally takes a hard punch or
kick directly to the ear to cause that type of injury.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the damaged eardrums, Kerik said, ``That kind of
thing doesn't happen here any more.'' Still, the settlement of the
prisoners' suit, approved by a federal court on July 10, requires
the city to expand training in ways to subdue inmates without using
force and to do more to root out improper behavior by correction
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're dealing with a culture as deeply imbedded as this
one, it's going to take a strong commitment by the agency to
identify wrongdoing and impose discipline where appropriate,'' said
Jonathan Chasan, a Legal Aid Society lawyer who represented the
prisoners in the suit. But given the department's willingness to
settle the case, he said, ``This is something we expect to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Chasan said he was concerned about several incidents in
June and July in which prisoners in the disciplinary unit were
injured in the face and head in altercations with guards. Kerik
said the department is investigating the incidents.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Records from the Legal Aid Society suit, including depositions
and city documents that had not previously been released, show that
the allegations of abuse first surfaced within the agency shortly
after Rikers' officials opened the central disciplinary unit. One
prisoner died in 1990, and medical examiners concluded that it was
the result of a severe beating he had received from several guards.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the city also has paid more than $2 million to
settle lawsuits by prisoners who claimed they were improperly
beaten in the unit, and several correction officers have been
convicted of criminal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   But other officers were acquitted of similar charges, and the
extent of the abuse has always seemed murky. And while there is no
question that the disciplinary unit was a tough setting, a close
review of the court documents, including more than a dozen
depositions of former guards, wardens and other correction
officials, suggests that for years, poor training and weak
supervision left many guards with the feeling that they could rough
up recalcitrant inmates whenever they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   The documents show that some inmates received multiple head
wounds in beatings that occurred even though they were wearing
handcuffs. Many were ``beaten down,'' as the guards put it, in
isolated locations, sometimes for mouthing off. A few had their
heads held in toilet bowls while guards flushed the toilets.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, some of the guards' actions to cover up what they
did were so transparent that they were almost comical. Besides
routinely filing false reports, some correction officers punched
and kicked one another _ or rubbed carbon paper on their cheeks to
create ``bruises'' _ to support claims that they had been acting in
self-defense, the documents show. After the city began to clamp
down in the mid-1990s, the guards sometimes disabled video cameras
that monitored the jail by pointing them at the ceiling or floor.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while a few were disciplined, most were able to get away
with this rough-hewn approach because their bosses felt it was
necessary to keep control of the often-rebellious crowd of inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Phoenix, who was the warden of the jail that housed the
disciplinary unit, said he periodically heard allegations that some
guards had repeatedly beaten inmates, and ``I had some suspicion
that they were overreacting in some instances.'' But he ``couldn't
get a grip'' on halting the brutality, he said, adding that it was
``ingrained in the culture because it's a natural reaction because
of the element that you're dealing with.''
</P>
<P>
   One result of that hands-off approach was evident when a
prisoner in the disciplinary unit, Anthony Bryant, died in May 1990
shortly after he was beaten by guards. According to Phoenix's
deposition, one of his subordinates asked a supervisor who had a
reputation for being overzealous to investigate the case. Even
Phoenix said the result was ludicrous: the supervisor turned in a
report three days after the death saying that Bryant should be
arrested for assaulting the staff.
</P>
<P>
   The Legal Aid Society filed its lawsuit on behalf of the 15
prisoners in 1993, and the city agreed in February 1996 to pay $1.6
million in damages to them. The second phase of the suit, settled
last month, focused on reforms. Starting in March 1996, the
Correction Department tried to fix the problems by moving the
disciplinary unit to a newer facility at Rikers, where it mounted
nearly 300 cameras on the walls.
</P>
<P>
   But the court records show _ and department officials
acknowledge _ that the first several months in the new building
marked a difficult period. Prisoners were injured in altercations
with guards outside the range of the cameras. When squads of
officers extracted rebellious inmates from their cells, they were
supposed to record the events with hand-held video cameras, but
often failed to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Kerik said, the department has taken additional
steps, from changing leadership at the jail to giving guards better
training in using nonviolent holds and pepper spray to disable
hostile inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, who became the commissioner in January after serving as
first deputy commissioner for three years, said conditions also
have improved as part of an effort by the Giuliani administration
to reduce all kinds of violence in the jails. Department statistics
show that though the number of inmates in the city's system is
rising, the number of stabbings and slashings among prisoners has
declined by more than 80 percent since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik said the city had stepped up searches for weapons and
begun charging violent inmates with new crimes, instead of just
giving them detention. He said this has made the jails safer for
guards and inmates alike.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Kerik tries to resolve the legacy of problems at the
central disciplinary unit, he faces hurdles.
</P>
<P>
   Chasan, the Legal Aid lawyer, said he remains concerned about
whether the cameras in the jail are being used properly. He said
that in late July, after the final settlement of the Legal Aid
Society suit, a prisoner's face was lacerated in a fight with
guards right after a hand-held camera was turned off.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the unions that represent correction officers and
captains are worried about some aspects of the court settlement.
Peter Meringolo, the president of the Correction Captains
Association, said he was trying to negotiate to have his members
rotated out of duty in the disciplinary unit every 12 to 14 months
to reduce the stress.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, approved by Judge Robert P. Patterson Jr. of
U.S. District Court in Manhattan, includes a provision for two
outside consultants to advise the department on changes and monitor
what goes on in the disciplinary unit over the next two years. The
judge could intervene again if the city fails to fix the problems,
but Kerik said he was determined not to let that happen. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1552EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
