<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTH-CLUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC-AREA HEALTH CLUBS CONSOLIDATE AS MEMBERSHIP GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By TERRY PRISTIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Spurred by the rising popularity of health clubs
among people more interested in improving cardiovascular fitness
than parading toned pecs, two companies are aggressively expanding
in the New York City area. With investment dollars pouring into the
industry, scores of independent gyms and smaller chains are likely
to be absorbed by major chains over the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   One fast-growing company, Town Sports International, the owner
of New York Sports Clubs, acquired 18 gyms in the area in recent
weeks _ 6 of them this month _ and is building or planning to build
7 more. The company, which is based in Manhattan and is the largest
owner of gyms in the city, now has 59 clubs in the area and 17
others throughout the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Bally Total Fitness, the nation's largest chain, runs 37 clubs
in the area and will soon open 7 more.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to build a dozen clubs in the area within two
years, part of a national strategy that calls for adding 22 new
clubs and buying 25 more each year, said company president Lee
Hillman.
</P>
<P>
   The rapid expansion of these companies comes at a time when
growing numbers of mom and pop operations and less-successful
smaller chains across the country are eagerly seizing their first
opportunity to sell.
</P>
<P>
   The industry is so fragmented that only about a third of the
nation's 13,799 commercial health clubs are owned by companies with
2 or more clubs, according to analysts. (Even Bally has only 325.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Smaller operators have been waiting for years for the
opportunity to sell out,'' said Naomi Talish, an analyst at Merrill
Lynch. Until now, she said, ``there was no one out there with the
capital to buy them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other industries undergoing consolidation, the $9 billion
health club business is not considered ``mature,'' meaning that
there appears to be plenty of room for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Club membership nationwide has increased sharply in recent years
_ to 22.4 million in 1997 from 13.8 million in 1987, according to
American Sports Data of Hartsdale, N.Y., a company that specializes
in sports and fitness research. But those figures represent only a
fraction of the potential market, analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Health clubs are more popular in urban areas _ where the major
chains are concentrating their expansion drives _ but in the New
York area, only 1.6 million people are members, about 11.2 percent
of the population.
</P>
<P>
   With the mountain of research emphasizing the health benefits of
exercise, including a 1996 report by the surgeon general, club
operators say they believe that membership will continue to grow as
more people are recruited from what they euphemistically refer to
as the ``deconditioned'' market.
</P>
<P>
   Health clubs used to draw primarily from the 20-something age
group, but today, the members' average age is 35, said Cathy
Masterson McNeil, a spokeswoman for the International Health,
Racquet &AMP; Sportsclub Association, based in Boston. Last year, 8.5
million people ages 35 to 54 belonged to health clubs, an increase
of 103.3 percent over the 1987 figure. And the clubs had 2.7
million members age 55 or older, an increase of 123.5 percent over
the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Some older club members began working out years ago and have
continued to stay fit, said Harvey Lauer, the president of American
Sports Data. But others have been lured by the development of
effective low-impact activities that are easy on the joints, he
said. ``I think there has been a general elevation of fitness
consciousness,'' Lauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting that heightened consciousness, Adele Bacon, 78, goes
to the David Barton Gym on Manhattan's Upper East Side four times a
week. Joining a gym with so many younger members made her feel
awkward at first, she said, but she quickly adjusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a couple of people who walk around like prima
donnas,'' Mrs. Bacon said. But most people, she said, go to work
out. ``They're not here for a fashion show.'' Indeed, at many gyms,
form-fitting leotards and tights are far less prevalent than loose
track pants and baggy T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   The health club industry has also caught the eye of investors,
because it has dropped some of its questionable business practices.
The days when operators made their money by signing up members who
could be counted on as no-shows are largely over.
</P>
<P>
   ``They realized it was a very shortsighted strategy,'' said
Vincent Zinno, the editor of Club Industry magazine, a trade
publication. ``They were not growing their business doing that. It
was like selling a newspaper subscription to people who can't
read.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two companies, Bally and Sports Club Company, which owns
the luxurious Reebok Sports Club New York (with an initiation fee
of $1,100 and monthly dues of $150), are publicly traded. But
several other companies, including Town Sports International, are
expected to go public soon.
</P>
<P>
   With Reebok Sports Club New York at the wealthier end of the
clientele spectrum and muscle gyms at the other, Town Sports has
positioned itself in the middle, drawing college-educated people
between 25 and 40 who earn more than $50,000 a year, said Mark
Smith, the company's chairman and chief executive. Members who wish
to travel freely among various clubs pay $76 a month, he said, and
can cancel with 30 days' notice.
</P>
<P>
   To finance its expansion, Town Sports raised $100 million from
the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of its clubs are equipped with pools and
racquetball courts, the company is focusing on machines like
treadmills and stair climbers and popular activities like weight
training and spinning, a high-intensity workout using a stationary
bicycle.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's company is buying clubs from people like Christian
Pacifico, who entered the business in 1991, eventually becoming the
co-owner of Gold's Gym franchises on Staten Island and in Brooklyn
and Fort Lee, N.J., employing a total of 150 people.
</P>
<P>
   This year Pacifico decided it was time to sell because it was
getting harder to compete for employees and to keep updating
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's only so much a small business can do,'' said Pacifico,
who now works for Bally as an area manager. ``We were losing
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   At Bally, part of the strategy is to diversify its membership.
Known for operating at the lower end of the market, the company
recently opened a slightly more high-end health club in Manhattan's
financial district and is upgrading several others in midtown. Fees
range from $25 to $45 a month at the typical Bally clubs, and from
$49 to $69 a month at the fancier ones, called Bally Sports Clubs.
</P>
<P>
   As the industry grows, club operators will inevitably be more
conscious of the bottom line, said Paul Roukis, an analyst at
Schroder &AMP; Company. But he said that the corporations would benefit
from economies of scale in marketing and acquiring equipment and
that consumers were not likely to feel that pennies were being
pinched because of consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the contrary,'' Roukis said, ``it's going to give people a
lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Gary Prince, a chiropractor who owns Prescriptive
Fitness, an independent club on West 54th Street that charges its
members $60 a month, said that consolidation would deprive
consumers of the personal touch and hands-on management he is able
to offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the local bar on the corner, where everyone knows your
name,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
