u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-PLEASANT-NYT     08-15 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-PLEASANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS LOOK TO PLEASANT FOR QUIET GUIDANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Anthony Pleasant does not sound like the
name of a defensive end, the mean guy who rushes the quarterback
from the blind side. He does not have the growling demeanor of one,
either. He is a quiet, albeit 6-foot-5-inch, 278-pound man in a
theatrical position.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant attended Tennessee State, a school that has produced
such outstanding defensive linemen as Ed (Too Tall) Jones and
Richard Dent. He may be in a boisterous position in football, but
he is far from flamboyant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say much,'' Pleasant said.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday night, as the New York Jets face the Baltimore
Ravens in preseason play, Pleasant is to be matched against one of
the more intimidating players in the National Football League:
Jonathan Ogden, a 6-8, 318-pound left tackle.
</P>
<P>
   It is just another obstacle on the road back for Pleasant, who
has gone from being a potential Pro Bowl player with the Browns _
he had eight sacks in 1995 _ to diminishing seasons because of
injury. But of all the Jets' off-season pickups, Pleasant is the
only defender who has cracked the starting lineup. He is the right
end in the Jets' new 4-3 alignment.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive line is a potentially solid if unspectacular group
_ or one that could prove problematic. Pleasant and left end Rick
Lyle were both jettisoned by the Ravens, while the 1998 Jets
tackles' production is yet to be proved: Jason Ferguson is in his
second season with the team and Ernie Logan, who is entering his
eighth season in the league, was not a starter until last year.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant, Lyle and Logan all played under Bill Belichick at
Cleveland. Behind them, the Jets' depth is thin.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Parcells wishes he knew more about Pleasant and what
to expect from him.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells' hopes were raised when the Jets defeated the
Philadelphia Eagles in their preseason opener.
</P>
<P>
   But then Pleasant sustained an ankle injury in practice.
Parcells growled at the strength coach, John Lott, who was working
with Pleasant, invoking the name of the Ravens' mountainous
offensive tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got the Ogden flu,'' a disgruntled Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant was back on the line two days later.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he seemed angered that Pleasant was hurt, Parcells
said: ``I'm just counting on him to do well. His play against the
Eagles raised my expectation level, which is a bad thing to do
around me.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Jets altered their defense, they needed someone who
could play right end _ and quickly. The coaching hierarchy knew
about Pleasant even if Bill Parcells did not. Belichick, now
Parcells' assistant, was Cleveland's head coach when Pleasant
starred there, and Scott Pioli, now in charge of the Jets' pro
personnel, was in a similar position with the Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Belichick hoped, however, that Pleasant, who is 30 years old,
was more like his Browns self than he had been his last two seasons
at Baltimore and Atlanta. Pleasant had an ankle injury in Baltimore
and was a part-time player in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a solid guy and a good guy,'' Belichick said.
</P>
<P>
   Romeo Crennel, the defensive line coach, said of Pleasant: ``We
felt he would be a very consistent and good addition. What you
didn't know about was the last two years. It's always the question
mark. Can he get back to what he was?''
</P>
<P>
   If he does, then the Jets have made a significant move. They
would have a player who not only can rush the passer but is a solid
run stopper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our first team is stronger because all of them have
experience in the system,'' Crennel said. ``They play well
together, which is important, as opposed to having the one guy who
can star for you.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, stardom is not very likely. Pleasant has had his
moments, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Parcells didn't tell me much,'' Pleasant said. ``He just
told me he has a lot of expectations from me.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant also has a lot of expectations for himself. He
describes it as part of an overall ``way of life, not just being a
football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleasant is thinking of becoming a minister when his football
career ends, and he has also worked on special-education projects.
His wife, Renita, has a master's degree in urban planning and
psychology from the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you carry yourself in a certain way,'' Pleasant said,
``guys respect you.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Jets did not seem like the perfect fit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was skeptical about coming here,'' Pleasant said. ``I
thought Long Island was like New York City, traffic and all. And I
didn't really know what kind of coach he was. I have a different
perception now.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Pleasant thought Parcells was worse than he is?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, shaking off the Ogden flu.
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The Ravens-Jets connection is wide-ranging. For starters, the
Jets' assistant head coach, BILL BELICHICK, coached the Browns for
five seasons. In addition to three members of the Jets' defensive
line who played for Cleveland or the Ravens, there was also
linebacker PEPPER JOHNSON, punter BRIAN HANSEN and the Jets' player
development director, CARL BANKS, who was a linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   On the Ravens, meanwhile, the pro personnel director JAMES
HARRIS was a Jets assistant general manager. And the Ravens'
receivers coach, RICHARD MANN, had that position with the Jets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
