<SLUG> BC-NY-STATEN-DEVELOP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH NICE VIEW AMID RUINS, RAIL YARD TO GET UPGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A rubble-strewn, overgrown Staten Island rail yard
with a postcard view of the Statue of Liberty and New York's
financial district could become an attraction itself under plans
announced Saturday by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the city had agreed to pay $13 million for 52
acres next to the St. George Ferry Terminal, and was considering
development that could include a minor-league baseball park, an
entertainment complex and restaurants and stores.
</P>
<P>
   Staten Island Borough President Guy Molinari said the purchase
would create an attractive new face for the area, which many
residents consider the gateway to Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this stuff had been going to rack and ruin,''
Molinari said. ``This represents a new day for Staten Island. This
will have an enormous positive impact for Staten Island in the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said that 18 million people passed through the ferry
terminal each year, providing a base of potential customers
``bigger than most cities.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials said they had not decided how they would use the
land, but Giuliani mentioned a retail complex and said a ballpark
would be one of the most attractive options.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone can see if they can hit home runs between the World
Trade Center towers,'' he joked. ``I can't think of anything better
than hitting home runs to Wall Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible use would be additional space for two museums
now planned for the site: a national museum planned by lighthouse
preservation groups and a cultural center planned when the terminal
is expanded. The city also may continue to use part of the land for
parking, Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we do will be a tremendous improvement over what's
there,'' said Charles Millard, president of the Economic
Development Corp.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said the land, which runs 3,000 feet along the
waterfront, was first used as a rail yard near the turn of the
century, a use that continued into the 1960s. Now, part of it is a
1,000-space commuter parking lot and the rest is covered with scrap
and scrub, along with a few rusty flat-bed cars.
</P>
<P>
   The city's Economic Development Corp. is buying the land from
CSX Realty Development, a subsidiary of CSX Corp., the
international transportation giant. The city has 90 days to
complete the offer, which must be approved by the CSX board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever we do will be a tremendous improvement over what's
there,'' said Charles Millard, president of the development agency.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the $13 million price was a good deal for the
city, since CSX had a contract to sell the land 10 years ago for
$18.5 million, although the deal did not go through. He said CSX
was now collecting $750,000 a year in parking fees from the
property, and had planned to double that to $1.5 million with the
opening of two museums nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I photographed this view myself, so I know how inspiring it
can be,'' said the mayor, who was dressed in a polo shirt as he
made the announcement on a sidewalk overlooking the property near
Borough Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Molinari said he was delighted and relieved by the purchase. In
the past, he said, developers and the city had considered using the
land for housing or a jail. ``Now the city is preserving it for
community use,'' Molinari said.
</P>
<P>
   About half the property, which sits just north of the ferry
terminal, is under water. The city is considering plans to renovate
the docks and shorefront.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
