<SLUG> BC-NY-PEDESTRIAN-KILLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSCHWITZ SURVIVOR FATALLY STRUCK BY CAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 76-year-old Brooklyn woman who survived the
Auschwitz concentration camp died late Friday after being hit by a
car near her home, police said. The driver fled in the car.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Rifka Franzos, was trying to cross Wythe Avenue at
Rodney Street in Williamsburg shortly after 9:30 p.m. on Friday,
when a red car traveling north on Wythe hit her, said Officer
Dennis Laffin, a Police Department spokesman. An investigator who
spoke on condition of anonymity said that witnesses described the
car as a Ford Thunderbird, though they could not see the driver as
the car passed.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Franzos later died at Woodhull Medical and Mental Health
Center, Laffin said.
</P>
<P>
   With her husband, Joel, the victim had been a longtime resident
of the heavily Jewish Orthodox neighborhood on the edge of the
Brooklyn Navy Yard and once owned a bakery on Broadway, neighbors
said. Police said the family lived on Ross Street, one block from
where Mrs. Franzos was killed as she took a walk on the Jewish
Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Franzos, who was born in Hungary, emigrated to Brooklyn in
1947, family members said, adding that she had been interred in the
Auschwitz death camp in Poland during World War II. She met her
husband, who was in a labor camp during the war, shortly before
they both moved to the United States, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   Franzos opened a bakery on Grand Street in Williamsburg, while
his wife worked as a seamstress in a sweater factory, they said.
She worked in the factory, Dan Wall Finishing Co., until her death.
</P>
<P>
   She was on her way to pick up her husband from a relative's
house when the car struck her, family members said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a horrible way for her to go after surviving the
Holocaust,'' Phil Franzos, her 45-year-old son, said. ``I'm still
in shock. My mother was a very strong, happy person who never
complained. She suffered a lot in the war, but you would never know
it by speaking with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She will be dearly missed,'' he said. Mrs. Franzos is survived
by six children, 41 grandchildren and nine great-grandchildren,
Franzos said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents said the intersection where Mrs. Franzos died was
especially dangerous because no traffic lights had been installed.
``A few months ago, a car came flying around that corner and
knocked into my car where it was parked and totaled it,'' said one
man near the scene, who refused to give his name because of the
holy day. ``They need to put a light over there because people just
speed all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
