<SLUG> BC-NY-STRIPCLUBS-ASSESS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: STRIP CLUB CRACKDOWN SUCCEEDS, AND RANKLES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Judges in Brooklyn, Staten Island and the Bronx grant
requests from the Giuliani administration to padlock strip clubs
and adult video stores immediately. But judges in Manhattan and
Queens, confronted with nearly identical requests, refuse and
instead hold long hearings.
</P>
<P>
   The contradictory responses are, in part, the result of novel
and aggressive legal tactics the Giuliani administration is using
to close sex shops under a new zoning law.
</P>
<P>
   To administration supporters, the tactics are producing the
first concrete results in efforts to restrict the shops to
manufacturing areas. To critics, however, the crackdown is the
latest example of the Giuliani administration's use of
heavy-handed, publicity-driven tactics to bully opponents into
submission.
</P>
<P>
   With seven judges in five boroughs wrestling with 18 requests
from the Giuliani administration to close sex shops, a series of
seemingly contradictory rulings regarding the new law could emerge
over the next several weeks. And rulings from state and federal
appeals courts on whether the enforcement tactics are legal _ as
well as on sex shops' efforts to stay in business by limiting adult
entertainment to less than 40 percent of their floor space _ are
not expected for up to a year.
</P>
<P>
   But in the short term, the Giuliani administration, by peppering
the courts with requests to close sex shops, is producing the
picture of an administration succeeding where other mayors have
failed since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The Giuliani administration's zoning law to restrict adult
entertainment mirrors sex-shop regulations in other cities. But
what is unusual, critics say, is the combative way the mayor is
going about closing the clubs.
</P>
<P>
   City officials who spoke on condition of anonymity said that the
mayor is bypassing the usual method for closing a business
illegally operating in a residential area. Typically, in a process
that can take months, city officials first issue a notice of
violation to the business owner. Hearings are then held, and a
business can be ordered to move or find a way to comply with the
law.
</P>
<P>
   But in shutting the sex shops, the Giuliani administration is
using a legal procedure usually reserved for closing crack houses
and brothels. Requesting the padlockings under the city's nuisance
abatement law, city lawyers argue that the sex shops should be
immediately closed because they represent a threat to the public
``health, safety and welfare.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the strategy is working. The city has won 11 immediate
padlockings since the law took effect July 22. But other judges,
mainly in Manhattan and Queens, are taking longer to decide whether
to padlock, saying a zoning violation does not necessarily warrant
immediately closing a business.
</P>
<P>
   Administration critics say the long-running businesses are no
threat to public welfare. The city is distorting the issue, they
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do it this way is really Gestapo-like tactics,'' said
Herald Price Fahringer, the lawyer representing 107 of the 144 sex
shops affected by the new law. ``There isn't any question that it's
more volatile from a publicity standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   But Steven Fishner, the mayor's criminal justice coordinator,
said the shops do pose a threat to public welfare by inhibiting
economic growth and reducing the quality of life in their
neighborhoods. The businesses are free to move to manufacturing
areas where they are allowed to operate under the new law, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have a strategy, and it is an aggressive strategy,'' he
said. ``But everything we're doing is being done in full compliance
with the law.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lawyers for the sex shops also complained that the city was
filing its requests for immediate padlockings with no warning. They
said judges in the Bronx, Brooklyn and Staten Island were granting
the requests without lawyers for the sex shops being present to
argue their case.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Siegel, executive director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, contended that the city was focusing on strip
clubs in counties where judges were most likely to issue immediate
padlock orders. He pointed out that since the judges handling the
sex shop cases in Manhattan and Queens turned down requests for
immediate closings, six of the last seven requests have been in the
Bronx, Brooklyn and Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's orchestrated,'' he said. ``The whole push is
gauged toward getting headlines to give the impression that he's
closing them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Fahringer said that since he sent a letter out asking judges not
to issue immediate padlock orders against his clients without his
presence, the city has not tried to padlock any of his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Fishner denied that the city was tailoring its padlocking
requests. ``It will become apparent over time that we are not
selecting any counties or avoiding any counties,'' Fishner said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the strip clubs also complained that the city was
using underhanded tactics. After Judge Steven Fisher turned down
the city's request for an immediate padlocking of Wiggles strip
club in Queens, the city produced a two-month-old affidavit from a
police officer who said that a dancer in the club solicited him.
</P>
<P>
   The judge cited the assertion of criminal activity as grounds
for padlocking the club.
</P>
<P>
   New York University law professor Michael Schill said the city
has the right to aggressively enforce a zoning law that has
withstood numerous challenges on its constitutionality.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that the city feels that having an enforcement
action against one business is not going to lead to everyone
pulling down the shutters and giving up,'' he said. ``And they're
probably right.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's opponents concede that even if his tactics are later
overturned by higher courts, he is in a win-win situation. Owners
of padlocked businesses may eventually give up and move to
manufacturing zones, as permitted under the new law. The short-term
closings, they said, will also play well with the Republican
audiences the mayor will be addressing around the country in the
next few weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1647EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
