<HEADER>
A5593 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-RUBEN-NYT &LR;      08-15 0241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RUBEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 RICHARDS RUBEN, 72, PAINTER AND TEACHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richards Ruben, an abstract painter and teacher, died on July 21
in Venice, Italy, where he was teaching in the summer art program
of the Pratt Institute. He was 72 and lived in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, his wife, Gail Divan, said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben's heavily worked surfaces tended to be dominated by one
color and one shape, a burly, wedgelike form that seemed to emerge
from a field of brushwork. Neither geometric nor gestural, his
style aligned him with the second generation of Abstract
Expressionism.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Los Angeles in 1925 and after serving in the U.S.
Army from 1942 to 1944, returned there to study art at the
Chouinard Art Institute. In the 1950s and early '60s, he was part
of the growing Los Angeles art world, exhibiting his work at two of
its most prominent galleries, Paul Kantor and Ferus. He moved to
New York in the early 1960s, exhibiting at the Poindexter Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben's teaching career began in the late 1940s and included
stints at Chouinard, the Pasadena Art Museum, Pomona College,
Claremont Graduate School, Cooper Union, New York University,
Columbia University and Pratt.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Ruben is survived by their daughter,
Caitlin Feron of Sag Harbor, N.Y.; a son from his first marriage,
John Ruben of Austin, Texas; and one grandchild.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 16:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5594 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CHEFS-FILM-400&AMP;ADD     08-15 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CHEFS-FILM-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CINEMATIC TRUTH FOR YOUNG CHEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Also moved in ``d'' category.) 
(js) 
 BY CLAUDIA ROWE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HYDE PARK, N.Y. _ At the Culinary Institute of America, where
chefs in training happily wake before dawn to chop onions and stay
up all night discussing the vagaries of risotto, the students were
rapt. The celebrity who left them stammering with awe was not Julia
Child nor any of her kind, but Stanley Tucci, co-writer,
co-director and star of the 1996 food-orgy film ``Big Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucci, with bleached-white hair and a studiously casual pose,
was at the United States' premier cooking school showing scenes
from his movie at the request of the student-run Saucier Club and
Giovanni Scappin, a chef and a professor at the institute who acted
as consultant to the film.
</P>
<P>
   Tucci, 38, and the students spoke for an hour and a half about
art, commerce, the immigrant experience and American culture _
anything but the eye-popping food scenes in ``Big Night'' that drew
so many gourmands into theaters. The film, which focuses on the
struggle of a businessman trying to keep his Italian restaurant
afloat and his brother, the chef, who refuses to compromise, was
never directed at food-lovers in particular, Tucci said. He said it
used food simply ``as a metaphor for the struggle of the artist in
contemporary society.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he hung his head and said with a sigh, ``That sounds so
much like Woody Allen.''
</P>
<P>
   The actor said he learned how to chop vegetables and flip
frittatas when his friend and co-star, Isabella Rossellini,
introduced him to Scappin. Still, he was blunt about his own
culinary tastes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll eat anything,'' he said. ``A fish filet at McDonald's is
good enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   The students were far more interested in Tucci, the filmmaker.
After his presentation, they asked him to pose for pictures and
autograph their ``Big Night'' videocassettes. Their only
food-related question focused on how many eggs Tucci had eaten
while shooting the final sequence, in which his character, Secondo,
the struggling restaurateur, reconciles with his brother Primo over
an omelet (about 15 in five takes).
</P>
<P>
   It was a seafood risotto, among other things, that had nearly
driven the two apart, and this the students understood implicitly.
As Tucci spoke, some of them served plates of the tricky, demanding
rice dish to colleagues in the audience, who analyzed it afterward
the way literature majors might deconstruct a thesis on
``Ulysses.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``A little too al dente, but it had good flavor,'' said Marla
Kiel, 22, of Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely a labor of love,'' nodded 26-year-old Tasha Garcia,
from Miami. ``When I was in `Basic Skills,' my risotto wasn't
nearly as good.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sat talking outside the auditorium late into the
evening. At 5:30 a.m., they would be rising for ``Meat
Identification,'' the morning's first class, but said the chance to
listen to someone speak about something other than food had been
well worth staying up for.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of ``Big Night'' may find it hard to believe just how
little good eating took place during the film. The culminating
15-course dinner was little more than a nightmare for Tucci. His
actors were tired, the food (which appeared sumptuous) was actually
horrible and the studio was unbearably hot, he said. Shooting the
creation of a timpano _ an elaborate construction of meats,
vegetables and sauce, which is something of a culinary decathlon _
nearly drove him crazy.
</P>
<P>
   With so much aggravation, viewers might imagine that Tucci and
Tony Shalhoub, who played his brother, would have had little
trouble portraying the tension inside a restaurant kitchen. But
that, too, was a carefully crafted illusion with gestures
choreographed by Scappin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I showed them about the movement of the cooks in the kitchen,
the chopping, the wiping your hands constantly, all those things
that make you feel like you've been in the kitchen a long time,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The chef, who became friendly with Tucci's family during the
production, is now working on a cookbook with Tucci's mother. But
it will not be a compilation of recipes from the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``There could never be such a thing,'' Tucci said. ``That would
be anathema to the moral center of the film. `Big Night' was never
intended to be a food movie, though I'm glad people thought of it
that way because, well, people like food and they all went to see
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1657EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
