<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WESTCHESTER-REAL-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISK SALES FOR HIGH-END HOMES IN WESTCHESTER COUNTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARY McALEER VIZARD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In his 93-unit Hardscrabble Lake luxury detached-house
development in the town of Mount Pleasant, N.Y., Jeffery Doynow has
sold almost as many homes in the first seven months of this year as
he did in all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``To date, we've sold 15,'' said Doynow, managing partner of
Fortune Home Builders. ``Last year we sold 18, which was still
good, since these are mostly million-dollar homes.''
</P>
<P>
   Since starting Hardscrabble Lake four years ago, Doynow has sold
a total of 60 homes. ``The pace has picked up each year, and prices
have increased by 30 percent,'' he said, noting that the project's
four-bedroom colonial and French Provencial-style houses now range
from $850,000 to more than $1 million, depending on size and
special features.
</P>
<P>
   Doynow said that projects like Hardscrabble Lake had benefited
not only by the bull market on Wall Street, combined with low
interest rates, but also from ``a scarcity of such developments
compared to the number of people who can now afford them.''
</P>
<P>
   All over Westchester County, N.Y., real estate agencies and
developers report brisk sales overall, with a higher proportion of
houses selling at the high end, or over $700,000, than in previous
years. The latest county Board of Realtors report, which does not
categorize sales in particular price ranges, nevertheless reported
a record-breaking second quarter for detached-house sales.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 1,708 homes were sold, the most ever recorded for a
second quarter, compared with 1,465 the same quarter last year, an
increase of 17 percent. The average price of $410,344 was 5 percent
higher than for last year's second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   P. Gilbert Mercurio, executive vice president of the County
Board of Realtors, said that the second quarter was a ``very
powerful punctuation'' to a three-year trend of brisk sales across
the board, but with more attention being paid to high-end
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Cohen, president of Cohen Properties in White Plains, N.Y.,
has enough faith in the continuing health of the market to build an
8,000-square-foot speculative house in Bedford, N.Y., that he hopes
to sell for $2.3 million. In addition, he recently acquired three
lots at Purchase Estates, N.Y., a 73-unit development, around a
golf course, where the homes sell for $2.5 million and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The upper end of the market is so strong right now, I wanted
to make sure I had some property to build on,'' Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
   When Christa Hyde, a division president with Liz Claiborne, and
her husband, David, whose company rents and sets up lighting
equipment for television commercials, wanted to move from Rockland
to Westchester County, they wanted a large home in a good school
district.
</P>
<P>
   The couple started out looking at houses in the $600,000 to
$700,000 price range, Ms. Hyde said, ``but we realized we'd have to
go up to the $750,000 to $900,000 range in order to get what we
wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   They wound up buying the four-year-old model house at
Hardscrabble Lake. ``It was exactly what we wanted if we were to
build a house ourselves,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Paulsen, a sales agent with Holmes &AMP; Kennedy's Chappaqua
office, which handled the sale for the Hydes, said she had
encountered many buyers who start out at one price range, then go
beyond it to get what they want. ``People today want bigger homes
than their parents had, with a lot of bedrooms,'' she said.
``Sometimes I think a house is overpriced, and then it goes for
more than the asking price.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Even the summer doldrums haven't placed a pall over sales,
according to Barbie Haynes, a sales associate for Merritt
Associates in Rye. ``I've been incredibly busy this summer,'' Ms.
Haynes said. ``Usually after Christmas you feel the propeller
starting and it catches that first crest. Then it dies down again
after spring. But it's been nonstop since the beginning of June.''
</P>
<P>
   According to real estate brokers, the only thing that slows the
market down is the lack of inventory. At the end of the second
quarter, the inventory of detached houses dropped 28 percent to
3,912 units, a level not seen since the mid-80s, according to the
Board of Realtors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been expecting to get a lot more inventory, but it
hasn't happened,'' Ms. Paulsen said. ``If I had the houses, I know
I could sell them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
