A5598 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-ELEVATORS-REAL-54     08-15 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-ELEVATORS-REAL-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFEGUARDING AGAINST YEAR 2000 PROBLEM IN RESIDENTIAL BUILDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By now most people are probably aware of the term ``millennium
bug'' _ meaning that because of the way dates were represented in
early computer programs, some computers may collapse at the start
of the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   There have been predictions of potential technological problems
ranging from worldwide banking and securities disasters to
elevators that go up but refuse to come down. And while no one can
accurately predict what will happen, some computer-knowledgeable
real estate experts say that those responsible for multiunit
buildings _ apartment houses, co-ops and condominiums _ should take
basic action now to avoid the need for more drastic remedies later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, every building has to have a plan,'' said Peter
Goodman, a New York real estate lawyer specializing in keeping
co-op and condominium clients ahead of the year 2000 problem, also
known as Y2K. ``Every building needs to conduct a comprehensive
audit of all date-sensitive functions.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Goodman said, the problem needs to be addressed
by co-op and condominium boards both internally and externally _
they need to scrutinize internal building systems and systems used
by outside companies and vendors that provide essential services.
</P>
<P>
   ``The elevator problem is only one of many issues,'' he said,
referring to one of the more frequently cited problems that could
occur at midnight at the beginning of 2000: Some computer-guided
elevators could simply stop in their tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can also have problems with security systems, fire alarms,
smoke alarms, thermostats and even heating, ventilation and
air-conditioning equipment,'' Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter de Jager, a Canadian computer consultant who was one of
the first experts to call attention to the year 2000 problem,
described its cause in 1993 in an article in Computer World
magazine. He wrote that when computer programmers were parsimonious
about how much storage space their programs used, they allocated
only two digits rather than four to represent the year. The year
``1993'' became ``93,'' and any calculations involving the date
would use that number.
</P>
<P>
   So, for example, de Jager wrote, if a computer was asked to
calculate the age of someone born in 1955, the computer would
simply subtract the 55 in the birth date from the last two digits
of the current year. That works until the year 2000. In 2000, using
the same formula would make the person minus 55 years old.
</P>
<P>
   As whimsical as that may seem, de Jager said, it is a real
problem for a computer, which, if confused enough, promptly
crashes. ``The crisis is very real and potentially very costly,''
de Jager wrote in his article. And while there are others whose
assessments of the problem range from dubious to dire, de Jager,
who testified before Congress in 1996, remains one of the more
respected consultants on the year 2000 problem. His Web site, the
Year 2000 Information Center (www.year2000.com), recorded 558,894
hits last month alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the year 2000 problem, perhaps the largest part, is
that we don't know in advance what will fail,'' de Jager said
recently. ``So we have to fix everything that might break.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Goodman said that in many buildings, security, fire-alarm and
power systems, and even backup electrical generators, are
controlled by computers. To assure the safety and security of
residents, he said, boards should contact the vendor who sold or
services the system to determine whether the system is year-2000
compliant.
</P>
<P>
   If it is not, he said, it should be made compliant if possible
and, if not, provisions should be made to do without the system in
the event it fails. The same, he said, would apply to any other
critical systems, such as heating or air-conditioning plants, that
rely on computer programs to function properly.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Goodman said, it is also possible that systems not
directly controlled by a computer running a software program could
be vulnerable to year 2000 problems. That is because some building
systems are made of mechanisms controlled by computer chips
directly embedded in their designs. A building-wide intercom or
telephone system, for example, may be susceptible to failure if
individual devices have built-in computer chips that rely, for one
reason or another, on an accurate time or date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoke alarms, lighting systems and even thermostats in
individual apartments may have chips in them that could stop
working on Jan. 1, 2000,'' he said. ``Every board should appoint a
committee to go through every piece of equipment in the building
and take inventory of every system that could possibly be
affected.''
</P>
<P>
   Any potential problems identified, he said, should be rectified
as soon as possible. (A list of year 2000 problem consultants and
experts can be found at de Jager's Year 2000 Web site.)
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said that buildings should make sure that their
suppliers, vendors and managing agents are correcting the problem
as well. Many heating-oil vendors, for example, use computer
programs to schedule deliveries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way to start checking would be to sit down with the
managing agent, look at each and every bill the co-op gets
throughout the year, and tick off each one after you have
ascertained that that vendor is or is not Y2K compliant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many managing agents themselves use computers to keep track of
the most sensitive and essential financial information, including
maintenance rolls, invoices received and payment records. ``You
might want to get a representation from them _ in writing, if
possible _ that their systems have all been checked,'' he said.
``Because there will no doubt be a lot of disputes that will arise
about systems that people thought were compliant but weren't.''
</P>
<P>
   Errol Brett, another New York co-op lawyer, agreed. ``Nobody's
suggesting that this year 2000 thing is going to be all doom and
gloom,'' he said. ``But it can't hurt to have a computer expert
come in and talk to you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
