<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-FLYFISHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: HONEYMOON HOMAGE: DO YOU TAKE THIS FISHERMAN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By PETE BODO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WOLF CREEK, Mont. _ For the angler, the act of fly-fishing is
usually a celebration in and of itself. So it's doubly agreeable
when a cast of friends commemorates an event of greater
significance than your basic sick day by going fishing. A group of
us recently did this when our friends Greg Hubert and Julie Sanker
got married.
</P>
<P>
   The day after the wedding, which took place outside of
Cleveland, 18 of us convened on the banks of the Missouri River
near Helena, Mont. The Lewis and Clark expedition had also
assembled on these high and windy plains about a century ago. Of
course, Lewis and Clark did not arrive in cherry red rental cars,
as we did; they came on their own raft.
</P>
<P>
   Greg and Julie had rented the Wolf Creek lodge, a contemporary
log home that served as our base station for the trip. The lodge
sits high on a bluff high above the Missouri, overlooking a famous
stretch of water called the Bull Pit. Julie is an amenable soul _
you'd have to be to share your husband with a group of his lifetime
fishing buddies on a honeymoon in the Bull Pit.
</P>
<P>
   The Missouri below the massive impoundment of Holter Lake is a
fabulous cold-water fishery, loaded with rainbow and brown trout
that rise freely to feed on the surface of this wide and
even-tempered river. But because of unusually heavy rains, the
river was running high and fast. The Missouri fishes best when the
flow rate is between 5,000 and 8,000 cubic feet a second. On the
day we arrived, the river was virtually impossible to wade.
</P>
<P>
   We had to content ourselves with sitting on the deck of the
lodge, reconnecting with friends and toasting Greg and Julie. It
was fine, but it wasn't fishing. The anglers among us cast covert,
longing glances at the drowned willows and flooded islands of the
Bull Pit. Fortunately, the flow rate diminished daily. By the third
evening of the trip, Chris von Strasser, Glyn Vincent and I decided
to venture into the watery braids of the Bull Pit. We found a
shallow bar to cross and slogged against the current, crossing a
small, flooded island. The next channel over was a permanent
feature of the Missouri, on the inside of a large island.
</P>
<P>
   To fish in it, we had to stand waist deep among the willows. One
of the sturdier branches held a bird's nest. If the water did not
drop quickly, the peeping chicks in the nest would not enjoy the
customary luxury of testing their wings. One crash landing on the
water and their downy wings would be too wet to get them back off
the surface. I wondered if their mother knew this.
</P>
<P>
   Glyn, who never saw a bend that he did not eventually go around,
disappeared downstream. Chris remained nearby and tied on a dry fly
of his own design, a caddis. It was meant to imitate the insects
that drifted on the dark water like tan husks of wheat. A few large
fish were rising in the channel, but none of them was working
steadily.
</P>
<P>
   Although I far prefer to fish the dry fly, the truth is that I
really wanted to catch a trout. And the high water conditions
dictated fishing below the surface with some type of wet fly. I
tied on a bead-head nymph, a size 12 Prince. I added a foot of
tippet material, securing it to the Prince at the bend of the hook.
I attached a smaller, olive bead-head caddis larvae imitation as
the point fly.
</P>
<P>
   The bead-head fly is a staple on western waters. It is
distinguished by a small gold or silver metal bead that resembles a
tiny gleaming cannonball, right up at the head of the fly. The
additional weight and sparkle added by the bead help to insure that
it gets down to where the trout live, and then catches their eye.
</P>
<P>
   The final element in my rig was a florescent, yellow-foam strike
indicator, about the size of a dime and folded onto the leader
about four feet above the Prince.
</P>
<P>
   When you fish this kind of rig, you just cast the whole works
upstream and allow the flies to drift naturally in the current,
watching the strike indicator for any twitch, blip or hesitation.
When it occurs, you strike. Occasionally, you find yourself fast to
a trout, rather than a drowned stick or clump of weed. I made only
a dozen or so casts before the strike indicator jerked and I hooked
a 16-inch rainbow trout. The reel screamed and I guess I did, too.
</P>
<P>
   The water continued to drop over the next few days and we
eventually had terrific fishing, mostly with dry flies. The Bull
Pit ultimately gave Greg a fine wedding present, a 22-inch rainbow
trout shaped like a football, only fatter. All that, and a bride
willing to spend her honeymoon in the Bull Pit. Lewis and Clark
were not the only ones to show undaunted courage on the banks of
the Missouri.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
