<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DDN-COX-CHIRO _ DAYTON _ From a nondescript clinic in tiny
Medway, Dr. David E. Polen has attracted a loyal following of
patients who say he's helped them when conventional medicine has
failed. But a Dayton Daily News examination of lawsuits, bankruptcy
records and a transcript of a deposition a cancer victim gave
before a regulatory board just before her death show Polen's
unconventional practices have also attracted the scrutiny of
regulators and brought complaints from patients and family members
alleging the Medway chiropractor exploited their trust. Polen
treated two other patients who delayed getting medical treatment
that may have extended or saved their lives, including a woman who
died of breast cancer in 1980. Her daughter, in a lawsuit filed a
year later, alleged that Polen told her mother the lump on her
breast was caused by infection and hookworm, and treated her for
seven months with poultices of buckwheat, flour, grated potatoes,
castor oil and vitamins. (Hundley/Hills, Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   PBP-GAMBLE _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ More than 200 years ago,
the framers of the Constitution cut a deal with the nation's
Indians that today may clear the way for 24-hour casinos featuring
booze, blackjack, lotteries, parimutuels and other games of chance
year round. It's a deal that has brought negotiations for tribal
casinos to the table and thrust the issue into courtrooms around
the state. Now, seven years after the Seminole Tribe of Florida
first asked to open full-blown casinos, maneuvering over the issue
is intensifying. (Staletovich, Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL _ If she were President Bill Clinton's lawyer, Susan
Brenner says she would advise him to tell the truth. Brenner, a
professor of law at the University of Dayton, doesn't say that in
an old-fashioned, all-American, cannot-tell-a-lie tone. She says it
because she feels the president is in grave danger of being hung
out to dry by Special Prosecutor Kenneth Starr, which could happen
if he lies and perjures himself. (Kline, Dayton Daily News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   For release Sunday, Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   BOWERSKKK _ Mississippi is preparing yet again to open old
wounds and air out dirty laundry - KKK leader Sam Bowers is going
on trial August 17 - for the fifth time - for the murder of Vernon
Dahmer Sr. A Hattiesburg civil rights activist who died in 1966
when he tried to protect his family from a band of about 16
klansmen torching his home. The Dahmer family has waited a long
time for this day; meanwhile, Bowers and his co-defendants are
cocky. Bowers has said he wants to get in court as soon as
possible. And Devours Nix, who was arrested and will stand trial
later this year, got out of jail by claiming he was too ill for it,
and then was caught teeing off at a golf course. Will the state
finally put these men in jail? (Rochell, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). For release Sunday, Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE-MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   CHIRO _ From a nondescript clinic in tiny Medway, Dr. David E.
Polen has attracted a loyal following of patients who say he's
helped them when conventional medicine has failed. But a Dayton
Daily News examination of lawsuits, bankruptcy records and a
transcript of a deposition a cancer victim gave before a regulatory
board just before her death show Polen's unconventional practices
have also attracted the scrutiny of regulators and brought
complaints from patients and family members alleging the Medway
chiropractor exploited their trust. Polen treated two other
patients who delayed getting medical treatment that may have
extended or saved their lives, including a woman who died of breast
cancer in 1980. Her daughter, in a lawsuit filed a year later,
alleged that Polen told her mother the lump on her breast was
caused by infection and hookworm, and treated her for seven months
with poultices of buckwheat, flour, grated potatoes, castor oil and
vitamins. (Hundley, Hills/Dayton Daily News). 70.
</P>
<P>
   For release Sunday, Aug. 16.
