<P>
   PERSPECTIVE
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STAKES _ WASHINGTON _ His advisors are among the wisest
that money and prestige can secure. He commands the mightiest army
the world has ever known, and he's the undisputed and twice-elected
leader of the last remaining superpower. And yet, on the eve of
what history may well record as the defining moment of his complex
career, William Jefferson Clinton is a man largely on his own,
soberly pondering an excruciating political, legal and moral
calculus upon which may rest his presidency and his legacy. (Deans,
Cox News Service) WITH ILLUSTRATION. This story is part of an AJC
Perspective page and a CoxNet repackaged page posted on the server.
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCEKIDS _Lethal entertainment doesn't confuse nonviolent
children and teens, (Williams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   The following stories have moved earlier in the week and are
still good for use on Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ISLAM-WEDDING_ NABLUS, West Bank _ Standing before a soccer
stadium packed with about 15,000 people, 35 men stand in black
suits holding red Korans and the green Islamic flag. They are young
Palestinian grooms, expressing what for many is a new attachment to
Islam in a public wedding celebration that glorifies the religion
and, indirectly, Hamas. One Hamas spokesman calls the young
believers the ``raw material'' for his movement. For the second
year, Islamic groups in this large West Bank city are reviving
their faith with a strong dose of politics and by helping young
couples navigate the complexities of Islamic courtship. These
weddings keep men and women guests separated, offer no alcohol or
hedonistic music and they're catching on. (Kaplow, Cox News
Service).
</P>
