<P>
   CLINTON-SCANDAL-FOREIGN _ MOSCOW _ It's time once again to take
the pulse of the foreign media on President Clinton's alleged
sexual relationship with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
Are the newspapers, magazines and television in Moscow, Mexico
City, London and Jerusalem as insatiable about this tawdry mess as
the U.S. media? We shall see. (Holmes w/foreign staff).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: To move by 3 p.m. EDT Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For release Saturday, Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-PRESIDENCY _ WASHINGTON _ The prolonged investigations
into President Clinton's personal life and his past financial
dealings have forever changed the presidency. Experts believe that
court decisions requiring the testimony of Secret Service agents
assigned to the president, as well as rulings stripping away
executive privilege from top presidential aides, will cause future
presidents to alter their conduct, making them unreasonably
cautious about everything they say or do while in the White House.
And forcing the commander-in-chief to testify in civil trials and
grand juries, as Clinton must do on Monday, could signal a future
in which presidents spend much of their time with lawyers prepping
to take part in court proceedings. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Moving in advance on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For release Saturday, Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-JURY _ WASHINGTON _ Live from the White House! It's
President Clinton _ testifying truthfully and completely about his
combustible relationship with former intern Monica Lewinsky and
he'll take questions from the audience in a televised show that
would be a programmer's dream. In fact, Clinton's testimony will
have a very small but influential audience: a grand jury sitting in
a federal building not far away and seeing the president via video
feed (presumably encrypted to prevent intercept by some clever
video hacker). What, exactly, is this select group that will hear
Clinton's testimony, how will their questions be conveyed to the
president and just what will they ultimately do with the
information? A primer on the president's unprecedented testimony by
closed-circuit television. (DEANS, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   EDS: Atlanta is preparing a graphic to accompany this story. If
interested, please contact Gail Towns at 404-582-7008.
</P>
<P>
   For release Saturday, Aug. 15.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STAKES _ WASHINGTON _ It has come down to this. The
president of the United States, the most powerful man in the world,
the commander-in-chief, master of the bully pulpit, will sit down
Monday in front of a television camera to do what no American
president has ever done before: answer questions about his own
conduct before a grand jury. Clinton's dilemma, the stakes for the
country and the mood of the public on the eve of the testimony.
(Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moved Thursday in (w) Washington and (k) commentary categories.
