u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-RANGERS-N     08-15 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-RANGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODD AND RANGERS WALLOP MEL AND YANKS, 16-5 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He didn't do it artistically or impressively, but he
did it in difficult circumstances, and his effort said enough about
him and his upbringing. Todd Stottlemyre, pitching for the first
time with his father in the other dugout, momentarily delayed the
Yankees' runaway spaceship Saturday and added to the record that he
and Mel Stottlemyre hold.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming a four-run first-inning deficit, the Texas Rangers
outslugged the Yankees, 16-5, stopped their latest winning streak
at nine games and prevented them from reaching the 90-victory mark
faster than any team in major league history.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers rescued Stottlemyre with a six-run flurry against
Hideki Irabu in the second inning, the last four scoring on a grand
slam by Rusty Greer. Mike Simms hit a three-run home run in the
eighth inning against Ramiro Mendoza that sealed the victory for
Stottlemyre, who allowed five runs while giving up nine hits and
walking six in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 283rd victory for the Stottlemyres, the most ever by
a father and son, who also are the only father (164) and son (119)
with 100 or more victories each.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome, which left the Yankees with an 89-30 record, kept
them from eclipsing the 1944 St. Louis Cardinals (90-30) as the
team to reach 90 victories in the fewest games. The best the
Yankees can do is match the Cardinals with a victory Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   This was one day in the Yankees' fantasy season when their
incredible record and methodical, relentless success could take a
back seat to a more personal day for the Stottlemyres. ``Two days
ago, I was nervous; now I'm anxious to see how he does,'' Mel
Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, said before the game. He
viewed his rooting interest with ambivalence. ``Blood is thick,''
the father acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   So thick that no sooner had the game started than the elder
Stottlemyre was sitting in the dugout ripped apart by mixed
feelings. Batting against Stottlemyre the son in the first inning,
the Yankees erupted.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher might have escaped with one run had his middle
infielders performed more adroitly. Second baseman Luis Alicea
mishandled two grounders that were ruled singles, and another
grounder scooted under the glove of a diving Royce Clayton between
shortstop and second for a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch created trouble for Stottlemyre instantly,
lining a leadoff double to left field. He moved to third as Derek
Jeter grounded out, then scored on Paul O'Neill's grounder between
first and second. Alicea, moving toward first, momentarily got his
glove in the way of the ball, but it deflected into right field for
a hit.
</P>
<P>
   After Bernie Williams walked, Tino Martinez hit a grounder up
the middle. Alicea fielded it behind second and tried to toss the
ball to Clayton for a forceout. But Alicea made a poor throw, and
the Yankees had the bases loaded on another tainted single.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines then looped a soft single to left that produced the
second run and left the bases loaded. Jorge Posada was the next
batter, and he reverted to the ground attack, rapping a grounder
between short and second. Clayton dived for the ball, but it dipped
under his glove and into center field for two more runs.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, was discussing
his pitching coach's plight and said, ``Mel's temptation will be to
go out and talk to Todd if he gets into trouble.'' If ever there
was a time a pitcher could use a word or two of advice and comfort
from a pitching coach, this was it.
</P>
<P>
   But the father remained in the dugout, and the son, working
solo, induced Chad Curtis to ground into an inning-ending double
play.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates, happy to be only four runs down, proceeded to
give the 33-year-old right-hander more comfort than even his father
could have provided. They exploded against Irabu in the second
inning, with the final four runs of the six-run burst coming on
Greer's grand slam into the first row of the left field stands
behind the 318-foot mark next to the foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the inning, Irabu walked Todd Zeile and gave up
a single to Mike Simms. Clayton, the ninth hitter in one of the
league's most explosive lineups, then lined a double to right
field, driving in the Rangers' first run. Tom Goodwin followed with
a single to center, and the Rangers had two runs.
</P>
<P>
   Like Stottlemyre in the previous inning, Irabu contributed to
his problems with a walk, this one to Alicea that loaded the bases.
Irabu then threw a first-pitch strike to Greer and a second pitch
that Greer lofted just barely behind the fence. Just like that,
Stottlemyre had a 6-4 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mel Stottlemyre, working for his employer, not his son, did go
to the mound at that juncture, and his advice and comfort appeared
to work because Irabu retired the next two batters, ending the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   That, however, was only the signal for Todd Stottlemyre to
encounter more problems. With one out in the second, Knoblauch got
an infield single, went to second as Jeter singled and walked to
third as O'Neill walked.
</P>
<P>
   Williams then hit a fly ball to center field, but the Rangers'
defense helped Stottlemyre this time.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch scored on the sacrifice fly, but when Goodwin's throw
to the infield got away from Clayton, Jeter tried to score, too,
and Clayton threw him out as Ivan Rodriguez blocked the plate. The
double play ended the inning and prevented more trouble for
Stottlemyre.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers rebuilt their lead to two runs with another run in
the third inning. Rodriguez singled, stole second one out later and
scored as Simms singled to left. The hit marked the end of Irabu's
performance, his briefest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez led off the Yankees' half of the third with a double to
left-center field, but Stottlemyre toughened, retired the next
three batters and allowed the Yankees no more runs in his
six-inning effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
