<SLUG> BC-NY-SMALL-BUSINESS-REAL-795(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: PROVIDING PLACES TO WORK, PLACES TO LIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DENNIS HEVESI   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Back in Trinidad, a half-century ago, Ortner Murray
``never dreamed'' that some day he might actually own property.
</P>
<P>
   The only real estate Murray knew anything about then were the
acres that he and his 11 brothers and sisters worked alongside
their father, a sharecropper, urging bananas, coconuts and corn
from earth belonging to an English landlord.
</P>
<P>
   Now, because of an innovative program called Storeworks that
tries to bolster the fortunes of less-than-affluent New York City
neighborhoods, Murray is about to double the size of his sportswear
business in Queens, and, to boot, become the landlord of several
rental apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say we were poor,'' Murray, now 60, said in
rose-tinted recollection of his boyhood days, working the fields
with a machete and living in a spare house by a rutted, rural road.
``We were happy with what we had, wearing worn shirts,'' he said.
``My mother kept us clean.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, Murray and his son, Gerard, 31, ship 20,000 crisp
new T-shirts a year, as well as jeans, jackets, shorts and socks _
most emblazoned with their self-designed logo, ``School of Hard
Knocks'' _ to distributors as far-flung as Japan, Germany, England
and the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   And soon, thanks to potent doses of support from New York City
and a not-for-profit group, the Murrays will expand their business
in a mixed-use commercial and residential building along an
increasingly bustling stretch of Northern Boulevard in Corona.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is gold for me, owning properties back to back on this
boulevard here,'' Murray said. ``This is for my son, and he knows
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Murrays, owners of Von's Sportswear at 106-11 Northern
Blvd., will soon take over 106-13, the building next door, with
commercial space below and apartments above, that has been vacant
for 34 years. They, along with 30 other prospective property
buyers, are the first beneficiaries of Storeworks, a program
created by Neighborhood Housing Services, the not-for-profit group,
in partnership with the city's Department of Housing Preservation
and Development.
</P>
<P>
   The program allows small-business people and first-time home
buyers to take title to deserted, ramshackle buildings in
struggling neighborhoods by offering low purchase prices, favorable
mortgage rates and, in particular, a city subsidy covering the
difference between the purchase price and the cost of a complete
rehabilitation _ a ``gut rehab,'' in real-estate parlance.
</P>
<P>
   Storeworks, based on another, more extensive program called
Homeworks that is operated by the city and eight not-for-profit
groups, seeks to take advantage of the current real-estate boom in
many areas in hopes of seeing the opportunities filter out, even
into the poorest sections of the city.
</P>
<P>
   It is, to be sure, a small start _ with only 40 buildings in the
initial phase, 31 of which have been purchased by individuals, so
far _ while hundreds of abandoned, so-called ``in rem,'' buildings
are still held by the city after foreclosure because previous
owners failed to pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But it comes at a time when signs of vitality are apparent in
once-desolate neighborhoods. Crime is down. Rents are up, evidence
of opportunity for some and _ with $700 to $900 for a two-bedroom
apartment no longer uncommon _ a harsh squeeze for others.
</P>
<P>
   Main thoroughfares are cleaner, though many side streets and
vacant lots remain littered and rubble-strewn. The bricked-up
buildings of the South Bronx, including those that not too long ago
bore cartoonish decals pretending to be real windows, are slowly
coming back on line.
</P>
<P>
   In East New York and Brownsville, Brooklyn _ still shadowed, of
course, by phalanxes of public-housing towers _ affordable-housing
groups are building new homes and private investors are renovating
old ones, so that whole blocks resonate with the clang and clatter
of construction.
</P>
<P>
   According to Department of Housing Preservation and Development
statistics, there are currently 2,232 buildings containing 19,084
apartments held in rem by the city. The department had no
breakdown, however, for how many of those buildings are of the
mixed-use type targeted by the Storeworks program.
</P>
<P>
   Storeworks, as it grows, said Richard Roberts, the commissioner
of Housing Preservation and Development, could be ``one of the
linchpins'' in the city's efforts to ``revitalize communities by
renovating properties and returning them to the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   ``That creates,'' he said, ``a platform not only for the
properties themselves, but also for adjacent buildings. These
properties become a catalyst. When a city-owned building is
rehabbed, the adjacent owner feels an initiative to upgrade as
well, attracting other investment, and helping to create a real
environment for stability.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The underlying concept, said Francine Justa, executive director
of Neighborhood Housing Services, ``is to target an area with as
many resources, human and capital, as possible. And if it works
well, we'll do more of them across the city _ house by house, block
by block.''
</P>
<P>
   A key component of the strategy, Dr. Justa said, is a study
course for the fledgling landlords. ``It builds people's capacity
to help themselves,'' she said, ``kind of an insurance. If you go
to our home-maintenance training programs and learn how to install
dry wall, understand BX cable, learn carpentry and plumbing, it's
insurance for your investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Woodford has already had hands-on experience as a
landlord, and at 73, is about to give it another try. In fact,
Woodford has a variety of experience: merchant mariner, postal
worker, freight handler for the New York Central Railroad, taxi
owner and, currently, bus driver for special-education children.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the '70s that Woodford first became a landlord. ``I
had a couple of apartment houses, 16-family,'' he said, sitting in
his minibus outside the three-story building at 524 Sutter Ave. in
East New York that he is buying through Storeworks.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, workers carried debris from the now-cavernous
commercial space of the gutted building _ across from a weeded lot
and down the block from the storefront Roca de Salvacio Church _
leaving only bare beams and rafters eerily lit by a string of
bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did that for 15 years,'' Woodford said of being a landlord.
``Had enough trouble with tenants.''
</P>
<P>
   Then why try again? ``I'm 22 years older than my wife, Clara,''
he said. ``So I'm trying to create some income for when I'm gone.''
The Woodfords plan to open a laundromat in the commercial space on
Sutter Avenue. ``We love cleanliness,'' Woodford said. ``She
believes laundry should be done correctly.''
</P>
<P>
   Observing that the neighborhood ``has come back a great deal,''
Woodford said, ``As people come in, they're going to have to get
their clothes cleaned.'' The Woodfords do not intend to live in the
building right away, ``but I intend to be around,'' he said. ``And
having experience, I know you've got to get good tenants.'' He
expects to charge $750 or $800 in rent for the two apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got into real estate they were practically giving these
buildings away _ $65,000 for a 16-family building,'' he said. The
purchase price for the Sutter Avenue building is $135,000, with a 5
percent down payment of $6,750 on a 7.875 percent, 30-year
fixed-rate mortgage. The gut rehab on the building, paid for by the
city, is costing $261,148.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city realizes that in the failure of these neighborhoods
is the failure to collect taxes,'' Woodford said.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Robbins, project manager for Storeworks, said the city
sells the properties to Neighborhood Housing Services for $1 each.
It has, so far, allocated $4 million to rehabilitate the first 40
buildings _ 31 in Brooklyn, nine in Queens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old procedure was to auction off abandoned properties, and
what you had was a bunch of starry-eyed entrepreneurs who thought
they could make a killing buying cheap and doing an inexpensive
rehab,'' Robbins said. ``What they encountered was buildings in far
worse shape than they imagined. So they couldn't rehab because they
didn't have the cash, and the banks wouldn't lend because the rehab
cost exceeded the property's market value. These guys would stop
paying taxes, and the city had to take the building back again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Storeworks program is designed to find buyers who have a
stake in the community, and it includes a mechanism to deter those
trying to turn a quick profit _ requiring those who do to pay off
substantial portions of the rehabilitation costs. And the program
favors buyers who will either live or set up businesses in their
building.
</P>
<P>
   Denise George and Phillip Ashby, soon to be neighbors, fit that
double bill. They will both live and work next door to each other _
she at 710, he at 712 Washington Avenue _ in two of three adjacent
buildings that Storeworks has acquired at the corner of a hopefully
appropriately named street, Prospect Place, in Prospect Heights,
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   As Robbins pointed out: ``The commercial strip is dense and
dynamic south of Prospect Place, and we hope to bring that vitality
to the other half of Washington Avenue. We're lucky we got three
buildings together, because people will see that a lot of money is
being invested here.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. George, 30, an office manager with an architecture firm, is
paying $180,000 for a building with 800 square feet of commercial
space on the first floor, will live upstairs in one two-bedroom
apartment and rent the other for $700 or $800. She plans to open a
financial counseling business downstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my first time in business for myself, and as a first-time
homeowner,'' she said, ``it's a huge step, a little scary, but also
a new-found opportunity.'' The rehab is costing $234,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby, 29, a Fire Department paramedic, is also paying $180,000.
He, along with a cousin, plans to relocate their currently
home-based Internet business, New York City Web Corp. _ ``we
publish Web pages'' _ to the renovated ground floor, and move in
upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a stepping stone that affords me the opportunity to have
a commercial storefront and to market the way companies my size
would, but without the overhead,'' Ashby said. ``I won't have to
deal with the exorbitant rent of a commercial space these days,
being that I own the building.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby estimated the market rate for the building at $380,000,
``and a commercial mortgage would be incredibly difficult because
you'd be putting down 25 percent up front.'' Under Storeworks, the
down payment is 3 percent, or $5,400, with the rate on the 30-year
mortgage at 7.875 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It was in January 1997 that Robbins and other staff members at
Storeworks began ``windshield tours'' of neighborhoods, stopping to
knock on doors and talking to merchants, in search of the first 40
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   After advertising for potential buyers in daily and weekly
newspapers, the organization received about 500 applications.
``They had to be city residents to qualify, and they had to qualify
for a mortgage,'' Robbins said. ``We asked everyone to send in
documents, reams of paper, tax returns, bank statements, pay
stubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 500 initial applicants, about 125 completed the process
and were deemed qualified. And on Aug. 6, 1997, a lottery was held
to pick 40 finalists. Those 40 were then ranked according to
criteria established by the city, giving priority to residents of
the communities where the buildings were situated and,
particularly, to those who live or operate businesses in the
building. ``Of those, 31 have signed on the dotted line,'' Robbins
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Two types of mortgages are available to would-be buyers.
</P>
<P>
   One is a Federal Housing Administration-insured loan offered
through the Bank of New York that is usually limited to residential
transactions. ``If you are a first-time home buyer and you intend
to occupy either the residential or the commercial space,'' Robbins
said, ``you can qualify for a 3 percent down payment. If you are
not a first-time home buyer but still intend to occupy the
property, the down payment is 5 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The rate for that 30-year loan is 7.875 percent, ``which is
phenomenal as far as commercial buildings are concerned,'' Robbins
said. Typically, commercial loans for the type of properties in the
program have 15-year terms at 9.5 percent, with 30 percent to 40
percent down, depending on the financial condition of the borrower.
</P>
<P>
   For an investor who will not occupy space in the building, the
same loan program requires 15 percent down and the same rate and
term.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Bank of New York loan is government-insured, it
carries rigorous underwriting standards and is document-intensive.
``Often we have people conducting small cash businesses who don't
show enough income to qualify,'' Robbins said. ``We didn't want to
exclude those people we felt would have the best use for the
property.''
</P>
<P>
   And so a second type of loan, not federally insured, was
arranged through Greenpoint Bank Community Development Corp. ``It's
a no-doc loan,'' Robbins said _ no documents. ``All they verify is
the availability of the down payment; they don't check income.''
For that loan, the term is 15 years, the rate is 9.375 percent and
the down payment 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   To discourage ``flipping'' _ buying and selling for a quick
profit _ the city places a non-interest-bearing second mortgage on
the property in the amount of the rehab cost. If the buyer sells
within three years, 100 percent of the profit goes to pay down that
second mortgage. If the property is sold between years four and 25,
the lesser of 50 percent of the profit or the balance of the second
mortgage is due to the city from the owner.
</P>
<P>
   As a compensating benefit, the city provides a real-estate tax
abatement. For the first 10 years, the building is taxed at its
pre-rehabbed assessed value. For years 11 through 20, the assessed
value increases by one-tenth of the difference between its
pre-rehab and post-rehab value. So at the end of 20 years, it will
be taxed at full value.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal read of these two subsidy mechanisms is that they
make the building more affordable to people with lower incomes,
because their annual expenses are reduced by the tax abatement,''
Robbins said.
</P>
<P>
   All of which sounded like a good deal to Michael Tate and his
family in Brownsville, Brooklyn _ his wife, Wanda; his father, Bill
Carr, and his three daughters, Asia, 17, Miasia, 9, and Nigeria, 4
_ all of whom pitch in to keep the family businesses going,
particularly when Tate is shoveling coal into the furnace at nearby
Public School 150.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shovels 400 tons of coal a season, and has the hands to
prove it,'' Carr said of his son. ``Just look at those hands.''
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years, the family has operated Touch of Beauty, renting a
storefront at 107 Belmont St., where the sign says: ``Curls, Dry
Press, Neighborhood Florist, Funeral Designs, Balloons, Fruit
Baskets.''
</P>
<P>
   It started as a beauty salon, but over the years diversified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do everything,'' Mrs. Tate said, ``hair stylist, barber,
nail technician, body waxing, gift baskets, corsages.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to Sarah J. Hale High School in downtown Brooklyn,'' said
Asia. ``In college, I'm going to learn chemistry so I can make my
own product _ stuff to strengthen the nails. Since I was 11, I was
passing rollers to mom, washing towels, being the gofer.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr, the grandfather, works with flowers. ``I do bleeding
hearts for funerals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The family had been renting the store for $700. ``The landlord
stopped paying taxes,'' Tate said. ``And when HPD took over, the
rent decreased to $500. But it was month-to-month; they wouldn't
give us a long-term lease.''
</P>
<P>
   Then one day, Mrs. Tate said, ``Peter Robbins paid a visit and
told us about the program.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the lottery,'' Carr piped in.
</P>
<P>
   Diversification was about to become expansion.
</P>
<P>
   After winning the lottery, the Tates paid $125,000 for 107
Belmont, with a 3 percent down payment of $3,750. And last
November, in anticipation of the $216,643 rehabilitation, they
moved their business to a nearby store _ ``next to the
check-cashing place, which is booming,'' said Tate, ``near a
laundry, a cleaner, a bank, a bus stop.''
</P>
<P>
   So, come October, there will be two Touches of Beauty in the
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as a double opportunity,'' Tate said. ``We come
from this neighborhood. We've seen it coming up. Now we see
ourselves going from nothing, a hole in the wall, to like the
establishment of a mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel victorious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
