<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-METS-BAERGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAERGA PERFORMING SOLIDLY, EVEN WHILE HE'S ON THIN ICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Even though the Mets are in the midst of a wild-card
race, if Carlos Baerga feels a little unwanted right now, it is
more than understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Mets declined last winter to pick up the $4.5
million option for 1999 in the second baseman's contract, Baerga's
future after this season has been cloudy, to say the least. He has
heard the whispers for the last two years that he is no longer the
player he was in Cleveland in the mid-1990s. And Baerga, who turns
30 on Nov. 4, is well aware that the Mets discussed trading him to
Baltimore for Roberto Alomar earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But if it were up to Baerga, who is currently hitting .286 in
the final year of a deal that will pay him $4.67 million this
season, he would be back next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to stay,'' Baerga said here late Friday night,
after helping _ with his glove _ the Mets to a 3-2 decision over
the Arizona Diamondbacks. With the victory, the Mets kept pace,
one-half game behind the Chicago Cubs in the National League
wild-card race. ``That's my first priority,'' Baerga said. ``My
family likes it here. I really love this team. And I know we're
going in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether the Mets feel the same way about Baerga is another
question. But while manager Bobby Valentine stressed that it is
general manager Steve Phillips' job to conduct any negotiations,
Valentine sounded as if he would not mind having Baerga back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Carlos is very valuable,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Valentine brought up three defensive plays that occurred
late in Friday's game, while the Mets were clinging to the one-run
lead. With two out and a man on first in the eighth, Baerga went
far to his left to field a tricky ground ball and throw out Karim
Garcia to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth, after Turk Wendell walked the first two batters of
the inning to put the tying and winning runs on base, Valentine put
on a play called the fake wheel in a situation obviously calling
for the Diamondbacks to bunt. The play is designed to lure the base
runners and the hitter _ in this case, pinch-hitter Andy
Stankiewicz _ into the false belief that the defense is
aggressively defending against the bunt.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Valentine said he will only put the play on when Rey
Ordonez and Baerga are in the field. ``I can make it work with
Carlos and Rey, because they sell it,'' Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   They sold it not once, but twice. Even though Arizona manager
Buck Showalter cautioned Stankiewicz that the fake wheel might be
on, hitters are supposed to instinctively react to the wheel play
by pulling back their bats and swinging away. Which is exactly what
Stankiewicz did on two successive pitches. Stankiewicz fouled off
the first pitch, then grounded hard to Ordonez at short, who tagged
out the lead runner for the first out of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But Ordonez, who initially appeared to have a shot at an
inning-ending triple play, fumbled the exchange after tagging Jay
Bell out between second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Another pinch-hitter, Hanley Frias, responded to the fake wheel
by grounding right back to Ordonez. The shortstop flipped to
Baerga. With the game on the line, Baerga stood his ground at
second and turned the double play, making it look easy. The Mets
thus won for the fifth time in seven games on this road trip and
for the 17th time in their last 25 games over all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos gets no credit for that, except from me,'' Valentine
said, referring to Baerga's defense. ``And I can't give him credit.
I can only give him appreciation. I know there are a lot of
opinions out there. But that double play in the ninth is what he
has done for us for two years. And he made that play going to his
left in the eighth even though people always question his range.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, Baerga is doing about what he did last season, when
he hit .281 with 9 homers and 52 runs batted in. Actually, Baerga,
who has 5 homers and 46 runs batted in this season, is on a pace to
drive in more runs. And though it is easy to say Baerga is hitting
a soft .286, he is quick to point out that he has 24 doubles this
season, not far off his career high of 32.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means I'm hitting the ball hard,'' Baerga said. Still,
because he averaged 19 homers and 97 r.b.i. from 1992 to '95 (not
to mention a .315 batting average), Baerga's critics argue he is
not nearly the player he once was.
</P>
<P>
   But Valentine isn't complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos is hitting .290, and he's going to have 70 r.b.i. or
more,'' Valentine said. ``Whatever you expect from a second
baseman, he's going to have to give something to top what Carlos
can give us. Now, it's not my decision. And it's not the time for
Carlos to worry about it. But for me, he's as good a second baseman
as any I've ever had play for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Mets watchers know Alomar is a free agent after this
season. Many believe he would like to join his brother, Sandy, in
Cleveland. However, in this scenario, Edgardo Alfonzo would be able
to shift from third to second, and the Mets could then make a run
at a power-hitting third baseman during the off season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe he can,'' Valentine said, when asked if he thought
Alfonzo could play second. ``I like Fonzie as a third baseman. I'd
probably like him as a second baseman, too. But I'm not going to
get into that.''
</P>
<P>
   There are also psychological implications to a Baerga departure.
Alfonzo looks up to Baerga as something of a big brother _ another
intangible that Valentine points to when explaining why Baerga is
so valuable.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, Baerga is not exactly sure where he stands with
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve Phillips, he doesn't really communicate a lot,'' Baerga
said. ``So we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   What Baerga does know is that he is not finished, even if others
don't believe him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't feel that I could play anymore, I'm going to say
it,'' he said. ``I'm not going to embarrass myself. But I think,
for me, it's been a good year. We're having fun. We're winning. And
that's the key.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1813EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
