<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5611 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESIDENTIAL-REAL-1     08-15 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESIDENTIAL-REAL-1,000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTIAL REAL ESTATE: BOSTON'S SOUTH END 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When Kimberlee Eveland and her husband, Andrew Lewis,
moved here from Washington five years ago, they looked for housing
in an environment that offered urban excitement yet seemed friendly
to families.
</P>
<P>
   They found what they were looking for in the South End, a
neighborhood filled with gracious Victorian houses, gardens, hidden
parks, bistros and a human melange of races, classes and
occupations.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, they have ridden the wave of rising real estate
values. They were renters in the beginning, first in one apartment,
then in another. Then they bought a condominium apartment and,
finally, three months ago, they bought a 4,000-square-foot town
house, which they plan to renovate, decorate, and remain in as they
start a family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call it House 2000,'' said Ms. Eveland, because they
calculate that it will take about two years, and an investment of
an additional $200,000 over the $675,000 purchase price, to
complete the work.
</P>
<P>
   The progression of Ms. Eveland and Lewis from renters to the
longterm commitment of home ownership is characteristic of the
transition currently under way in the South End, a neighborhood
that has been accustomed to transition since the mid-19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow isthmus that linked the hinterlands to the City of
Boston was originally developed into a 500-acre haven for affluent
mercantile families. But by the turn of the 20th century it had
entered a long period of decline. Not until the late 1950s were
there the first stirrings of a turnaround. It burst ahead for a
while in the mid-'80s, subsided, and re-emerged with greater vigor
in the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   Now new homes _ from artists' lofts to luxury condominium
apartments _ are going up and a stream of renovations are under
way. In the wake of all this development, longtime residents and
workers, as well as newcomers, are buying in the neighborhood,
which is a few blocks from Back Bay's Copley Square and about a
mile west of the downtown financial and theater districts.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Russell, a 35-year-old fabric maker, is an example of the
transition. She rents an apartment in Jamaica Plain, a mixed-income
neighborhood about two miles to the west. For 12 years she has also
rented South End studio space in a Washington Street building
surrounded by a few dozen lofts that artists occupied when others
shunned such spaces. Next spring, Ms. Russell will purchase a
live/work loft in a building being built to provide low-cost space
for artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a lot of sweat equity into the South End and watched it
change from a red-light district with power shortages and bad
landlord behavior to a thriving artist-design community,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the oldtime residents and the newcomers worked to improve the
neighborhood, they also have seen values rise. The average sale
price for condominium apartments this year has been $334 a square
foot, an increase of 56 percent since 1993, said Deborah Taylor,
president of Link, a condominium listing and information service.
</P>
<P>
   In the last six months, according to Paul Rinkulis, a broker
with Keliher Real Estate, residential prices have hit historic
highs, with single-family row houses selling for $1 million or more
for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   In large measure, the South End is sought after for its
convenient location and as one of the city's few truly diverse
communities. There is a mix of races, and about a third of the
owners and renters have incomes in the low to moderate range, said
Rinkulis.
</P>
<P>
   Bustling South End streets reflect the mix. On one block is a
park for the local baseball league. Nearby, trendy new restaurants
and boutiques emerge monthly. While prices have risen, they are
still below those in Back Bay or Beacon Hill. As far as Ms. Eveland
is concerned, the South End, which with 3,000 period buildings is
among the nation's largest Victorian districts, ``holds together as
a neighborhood and it's an affordable opportunity to have a real
house in the city with a truly delightful garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Ms. Eveland, 36, and Lewis, 42, are in the advertising
business, she as a freelance account manager and he as the
associate creative director of the firm of Mullen Advertising and
Public Relations. Their housing saga had the good fortune to be
well timed. In 1993 they sold a town house in DuPont Circle in
Washington, basically breaking even despite the relatively poor
housing market of the time.
</P>
<P>
   They had already moved into a furnished one-bedroom apartment in
the South End, planning to rent for at least as long as it took to
sell their Washington house. After the sale, they rented a
two-bedroom triplex for $1,800 a month _ ``an outrageous price,''
Ms. Eveland said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, as the Boston market was stabilizing from the punishing
decline of the early 1990s, the couple purchased a three-bedroom
condominium on the top floor of a town house, with a roof garden,
for $270,000.
</P>
<P>
   They invested about $55,000 in renovations, which they completed
last fall. But then they found their 4,000-square-foot
single-family town house. They sold their apartment for $455,000
and bought the house on West Newton Street for $675,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the right place at the right time,'' Ms. Eveland
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the number of condominium sales have
risen to 568 a year from 240 in 1993, while the average number of
days in which a property is on the market before it sells has
declined to 72 days from 117. The inventory of available
condominiums, which was 350 in 1993 and about 600 in 1990, is down
to 143, according to Ms. Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   The South End has experienced wrenching changes since World War
II. In the early postwar period, about 1,000 Victorian houses were
demolished in urban renewal redevelopment that brought in new
housing, stores, a park and a rapid transit line.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But in 1972 those blocks with the remaining 3,000 Victorian
houses became one of the first American neighborhoods to be placed
on the National Register of Historic Places. And in 1983 the
historic district became a Boston landmark district. Owners need
city permission to do exterior alterations that are visible from
the street.
</P>
<P>
   During those years artists and others helped restore existing
lower-priced housing, while the new stock of housing affordable to
low-to-moderate-income people expanded. Hundreds of apartments and
homes were built in two widely acclaimed developments, Tent City
and Villa Victoria. Last July, the Anna Bissonette House for the
homeless elderly opened on Washington Street. The $5.2 million
renovation and expansion of an 1869 warehouse created 61 apartments
with financing from federal, state and private sources.
</P>
<P>
   With housing demand now outstripping supply, developers are
expanding the borders of the South End. On the western edge, near
Roxbury, 65 condominiums, a mix of apartments and town houses, are
being developed in three projects. On the northern edge, abutting
Back Bay, a large new project is planned _ a $61 million complex of
105 condominium apartments, 66,000 square feet of retail space and
a $9 million improvement of the Boston Center for the Arts.
Construction should start next spring, according to the developer,
Druker Co. of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   New artists' residences are part of the mix also. Laconia
Associates, of Boston, has begun construction of a 99-unit loft
building for artists on land purchased from the city. About 45
units have sold for $90 a square foot, said John McLaughlin, the
developer, and 54 others have sold in the range of $140 to $200 a
square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Russell, the fabric maker, has agreed to buy a
1,500-square-foot live/work loft there for $155,000. ``I'm
enthusiastic about being part of the revival,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
