<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5614 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-GOV-PRIMARY-NYT &LR;      08-15 0253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-PRIMARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FUND RAISING, A LOPSIDED GUBERNATORIAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lt. Gov. Betsy McCaughey Ross and Peter Vallone, the
city council speaker, have each stockpiled more than $2 million as
they enter the final month before the Democratic gubernatorial
primary on Sept. 15, according to disclosure reports their
campaigns filed Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The two have far more than their rivals, Charles Hynes, the
Brooklyn district attorney, and James Larocca, a former state
transportation commissioner. Hynes has $84,000, while Larocca has
$5,500.
</P>
<P>
   Unless they can find a way to raise a lot of money very quickly,
Hynes and Larocca will almost certainly be unable to buy campaign
commercials in the days before the primary, ceding that front to
Ms. McCaughey Ross and Vallone.
</P>
<P>
   The coffers of all four Democrats are dwarfed by that of the
Republican incumbent, George Pataki, whose campaign reported last
month that it had more than $12 million. The Pataki campaign was
not required to file a disclosure statement Saturday because the
governor is not facing a primary challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross has $2.6 million in the bank, most of it
donated by her husband, Wilbur Ross Jr., a financier. She reported
raising $500,000 in the last month, largely from her and Ross'
personal funds. She spent $375,000 in that period.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, who has $2.1 million in campaign funds, reported
raising $83,000 and spending $350,000 in the last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 1834EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
