<P>
   (NYT10) EUREKA, Calif. -- Aug. 15, 1998 --
CA-NUKE-DECOMMISSION-NYTR-3, 8-15 -- A schmatic of The Pacific Gas
&AMP; Electric Co.'s Humboldt Bay Nuclear Power Plant reactor, left,
with photos of it's construction which was completed in 1963. The
plant, just south of Eureka, which stopped operating in 1976, and
sits only a few hundred yards from a network of earthquake faults
called the Cascadia, is in the process of being decommissioned.
(Mary Gardella/Santa Rosa Press Democrat Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) EUREKA, Calif. -- Aug. 15, 1998 --
CA-NUKE-DECOMMISSION-NYTR-2, 8-15 -- Humboldt Bay Nuclear Power
Plant employees perform a routine check in the fuel pool where
spent radioactive nuclear rods are stored. This routine check is
done every five years. The plant, just south of Eureka, which
stopped operating in 1976, and sits only a few hundred yards from a
network of earthquake faults called the Cascadia, is in the process
of being decommissioned. (Mary Gardella/Santa Rosa Press Democrat
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) EUREKA, Calif. -- Aug. 15, 1998 --
CA-NUKE-DECOMMISSION-NYTR-1, 8-15 -- The Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric
Co.'s Humboldt Bay Nuclear Power Plant, just south of Eureka, which
stopped operating in 1976, and is in the process of being
decommissioned. After decades of controversy over what to do with
the aging facility that sits only a few hundred yards from a
network of earthquake faults called the Cascadia, plant managers
now agree with activists that the radioactive waste from the
complex should be removed and the building taken apart as soon as
possible. (Mary Gardella/Santa Rosa Press Democrat Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. -- Aug. 15, 1998 --
NY-PENNSTATION-RELICS, 8-15 -- Nancy Brighton, left, an
archeologist, Marijke Smit and Alexandros Washburn recovering
granite from the old Pennsylvania Station at the New Jersey
Meadowlands, in East Rutherford, N.J. The Pennsylvania Station
Redevelopment Corporation, a state agency, hopes to use
architectural remnants from the long-lost building as decorative
elements in a new passenger concourse and ticketing hall it is
planning in Manhattan. (Nancy Siesel//New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 15, 1998 -- NY-JAIL-BRUTALITY, 8-15 --
At Rikers Island, the special disciplinary ward, informally dubbed
the ``House of Pain,'' is now located in a new facility, where
nearly 300 cameras are mounted on the walls, in an effort to
monitor and prevent abusive behavior by guards towards prisoners.
Over the years, New York City has paid more than $2 million to
settle lawsuits by prisoners who claimed they were improperly
beaten in the unit, and several correction officers have been
convicted of criminal abuse. (Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HARVARD, Ill. -- Aug. 15, 1998 -- FARMER-HAY-DONOR, 8-15
-- Keith Kingsley, 40, left, who runs a small dairy farm in
Harvard, Ill., and his son, Darryl, 21, have donated hay to the
Chickasaw Nation in south-central Oklahoma, which has been hit hard
by drought. In grass-scorched Oklahoma, desperate farmers are
resorting to feeding tree branches and leaves to starving cows. ``I
know it's just a drop in the bucket,'' says Kingsley. ``But maybe
it will help a little.'' (Todd Buchanan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 15, 1998 -- SANFRAN-HOMELESS-2,
8-15 -- Larry King, taking a different approach to panhandling,
unlike many other homeless people in San Francisco who often carry
signs that describe their dire need or misfortune. San Francisco's
history of tolerance and social services, combined with a lack of
affordable housing, has led to a homeless population of 16,000 on
any given night, and experts say many of them have mental
disorders, physical disabilities and diseases like AIDS. (Darcy
Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 15, 1998 -- SANFRAN-HOMELESS-1,
8-15 -- Angie, 43, who is homeless, panhandling to get the $10
guest fee at a hotel in San Francisco. San Francisco's history of
tolerance and social services, combined with a lack of affordable
housing, has led to a homeless population of 16,000 on any given
night. Experts contend that the city's history of tolerance,
benefits and support programs serve as a magnet for homeless people
at a time when the city cannot meet the demand for affordable
housing and housing costs overall have become the highest of any
city in the country. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) UNDATED -- Aug. 15, 1998 -- KOSOVO-SERBS, 8-15 -- A house
near Decane, 55 miles southwest of Pristina, burned by Serbian
policemen and Yugoslav army soldiers, and later bulldozed. Tens of
thousands ethnic Albanian civilians in Kosovo are fleeing as
government forces shell and burn their homes, in an effort to
regain control of major roads and push rebel fighters from many
areas. Once civilians leave an area, police often loot and then
burn homes, farms and businesses. (Staton R. Winter/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- Aug. 15, 1998 -- CLINTON-KENDALL, 8-15 --
David Kendall, President Clinton's private lawyer, is the chief
architect of the White House legal strategy on the testimony on
Monica Lewinsky. And like his client, Kendall, 54, has his
reputation on the line. Some Clinton loyalists are questioning
whether the tight-lipped, take-no-prisoners attitude favored by
Kendall's firm, Williams &AMP; Connolly, was the smartest approach in a
case that so obviously required a public relations offensive as
much as a legal solution. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
