<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0172 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5627 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOGGING-COX     08-15 1576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOGGING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Forest Keeper
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deep in the highlands of western North Carolina along a tumbling
creek is a forest primeval, a stand of giant trees that somehow
escaped the rape of the ancient groves that once mantled the
Southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   In a rugged corner of North Georgia and Tennessee, the Conasauga
River flows pristine and wild, home to more endangered fish and
mussel species than just about any other stream in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   And up in the rumpled ridges of Tennessee not far from the
Virginia line is Slide Hollow, a 4,200-acre fragment of wild that
was cut almost a century ago but has slowly healed into a mature
hardwood ecosystem of rich biodiversity.
</P>
<P>
   These three unique places within national forests of the
Southern Appalachians all were threatened with logging this year.
But in a signal that the U.S. Forest Service is changing its prime
mission from producing timber to protecting ecosystems, senior
officials pulled the plug on the logging proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeping winds of change are buffeting the Forest Service, an
agency long accused of being cozy with the timber industry. The
director of the change is Chief Mike Dombeck, 49, a soft-spoken
Wisconsin native who was a science teacher and fishing guide in his
home state before joining the service. Unlike most of his
predecessors, he is not a forester, but a fisheries biologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to move out of the era where the primary focus was
timber harvesting and other things were secondary'' because society
no longer favors that course, Dombeck said in a recent interview in
Atlanta. ``We need to realize the land will produce water, it will
provide recreation and it will produce fiber, but timber should no
longer dominate.''
</P>
<P>
   With 187 million acres in 155 national forests, the Forest
Service manages more wild places than any public agency.
Increasingly an urban America hungry for outdoor recreation covets
these forests. From backpacking to mountain biking, fishing to
autumn leaf-looking, the national forests entertain three times
more visitors each year _ 341 million people in 1996 _ than the
National Parks system.
</P>
<P>
   In the South, national forests comprise 12.7 million acres in 13
states, embracing half the region's public lands and some of its
most endangered habitats. And nowhere could Dombeck's vision have
more impact than in the Southern Highlands.
</P>
<P>
   From the knobby ridges of northeastern Alabama to the majestic
Blue Ridge of central Virginia, eight forests totaling 4.5 million
acres are the largest block of public lands east of the Rocky
Mountains. Included in this mosaic of misty peaks and crystal
streams is North Georgia's 750,000-acre Chattahoochee National
Forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are changing their management from an economic model to
an aesthetic and ecological model,'' says Warren Flick, a forest
economist at the University of Georgia. ``It's a profound change.
And to a large extent, it's a reflection of the growing wealth of
the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists have charged that letting private companies
cut timber on public lands has cost taxpayers millions of dollars
and amounts to a subsidy for the timber industry. A General
Accounting Office examination found the agency's timber sales
program cost taxpayers $245 million between 1992 and 1994 _ to mark
the trees, build the roads, replant trees afterward and otherwise
cover expenses not paid by the private companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service also has been chastised repeatedly in recent
years by federal courts for allowing the felling of trees critical
to fish and wildlife. To meet court mandates and growing public
environmental concerns, the Forest Service now allows only about
three to four billion board feet of timber to be taken by private
logging companies from national forests annually _ down from the
peak of 10 billion to 11 billion throughout the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   To accommodate hauling out that timber over the decades the
Forest Service has built more than 380,000 miles of roads. Those
roads, say Dombeck and many scientists, have caused great harm to
aquatic species by producing smothering silt that oozes into
streams.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing such concerns has become the main mission for
Dombeck, who was appointed Forest Service chief by President
Clinton in January 1997. Dombeck has his sights on fundamentally
changing how the Forest Service operates.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the first chief we've ever seen that is really trying to
reform the Forest Service,'' says Andy Stahl, executive director of
Forest Service Employees for Environmental Ethics. ``Where he falls
short is, I don't think he understands how pernicious the timber
dollars are. All of the Forest Service financial incentives are to
log.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1950s, when the Forest Service began to manage the
forests more like tree farms, a complex web of incentives to cut
timber has been spun by Congress and the Forest Service. It has
been a tangled web for the Forest Service, which was charged by
Congress with the often conflicting duties of providing a steady
stream of timber, while also protecting watersheds and wildlife and
providing recreation opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service managers still are rated by whether their
districts meet their timber quotas. Much of the timber money goes
back to the agency to pay overhead not only for timber but also for
wildlife and recreation programs. Twenty-five percent of timber
receipts are funneled directly to local counties with federal
forest land to subsidize roads and schools. In the process, the
service has grown into the largest agency in the Department of
Agriculture with a $3.3 billion budget and 30,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the board-foot is the driver or management, we're
going to have controversy,'' admits Dombeck. ``If you are a
district ranger or a forest supervisor, you ought to be rewarded
for trends and conditions on that landscape, which will include
water quality, land stability, forest health _ not just the board
feet you harvest.''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, members loyal to the timber industry have sought to
discredit Dombeck and have threatened to drastically cut his budget
if the agency does not get back to the business of producing more
timber.
</P>
<P>
   Dombeck also has detractors within the Forest Service, where
many foresters for decades have been conditioned to push
clearcutting. Although harvest reductions have triggered the loss
of thousands of jobs in the West, the industry by and large has
been able to adjust by turning to privately-owned timberlands.
According to the government, only 3 to 4 percent of America's wood
comes from federal lands.
</P>
<P>
   ``But 50 percent of all the softwood reserves, mostly material
for building, is on federal forests,'' says Henson Moore, president
of the American Forest and Paper Association, a leading industry
group. ``If you're never going to touch it, it means two things
will happen: We'll have to cut more off the private lands, and
import more. And neither one is good for our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, environmentalists are offering faint praise for
Dombeck. ``His rhetoric is impressive, but the real question is how
and when Dombeck will actively implant on-the-ground changes,''
observes Lark Hayes of the Southern Environmental Law Center, a
legal advocacy group that has fought a number of logging projects
in the Appalachians. ``The head and the feet are not together.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans to log sensitive areas like the Conasauga River, Slide
Hollow and the old-growth along North Carolina's Big Choga Creek
were pushed by Forest Service district rangers in spite of stiff
opposition from environmentalists, before being vetoed from above,
Hayes points out. But Dombeck did shift policy in January when he
tackled the forest road issue, proposing an 18-month moratorium on
all new road construction in ``roadless'' areas of national forests
in the lower 48 states. The moratorium was to give agency officials
time to draw up drastically new rules for road building ``based on
the best science.'' Dombeck says he will issue final rules in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Although the proposal does not rule out logging, the prohibition
on road building will significantly hamper tree cutting. Roadless
places are pristine enough to qualify for the federal wilderness
system but are not permanently protected from logging or road
construction. Environmental groups have argued for years that the
Forest Service should preserve these areas. On the ground in the
ranger districts where timber was not long ago king, some Forest
Service rangers who have long made decisions on when and where to
cut are frustrated with the abrupt change in direction. As recently
as January, Southern Regional Forester Elizabeth Estill wrote a
stinging memo to forest supervisors and rangers, threatening them
with poor performance reviews for failures to meet the timber
production goals the agency annually sets
</P>
<P>
   Estill says the memo was ``taken out of context'' and that she
merely wanted to impress upon them that ``we do what we say we are
going to do.'' Despite the memo, it appears that Dombeck's vision
is taking hold in the region. Estill has ordered no road building
or logging in more than 100 roadless areas totaling more than
500,000 acres in the Southern Appalachians, some of the largest
unprotected wildlands in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
