<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOGLIFE-COX     08-15 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOGLIFE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To loggers, the forest is home
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Barnardsville, N.C. _ When Ed Jones looks up at the mountains,
he doesn't see wild untouched land, as do so many backpackers who
climb North Carolina's emerald peaks. He sees the places where his
ancestors cut timber, farmed and lived in remote communities in
high valleys.
</P>
<P>
   A third-generation logger who at age 66 still puts in his day's
work in the woods, Jones is angered by what he now sees happening
to the national forests that include about 4.5 million acres in the
Southern Appalachians from the knobby ridges of northeastern
Alabama to the saddle-backed Blue Ridge of central Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Citing efforts to better protect and restore natural ecosystems,
in recent years the U.S. Forest Service has drastically reduced the
amount of trees it allows to be cut on its lands.
</P>
<P>
   But to Jones, these mountains are not a virgin preserve, but a
forest that for more than 100 years has produced timber to cut,
wildlife to hunt and herbs for medicine and food. And it could
produce more timber, he argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say we're destroying the mountains when we cut timber,''
says Jones, a slight, nimble man who can still climb a steep trail
or saw logs with a massive 24-inch chain saw. ``Well, my
grandfather cut timber off these mountains and then sold the land
to the Forest Service for 50 cents an acre. And there is fine
timber there now. Cutting timber didn't destroy the mountains then
and it doesn't destroy them now.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones and the company he operates with his son David,
Southwestern Logging of Sylva, typifies the small, family
operations that cut most of the mountain timber. The five-man crew
includes son-in-law Alfred Watson, cousin Keith Brooks and good
friend Gerald ``Possum'' Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``The small family operations are the backbone of the logging
industry in the mountains,'' says Jack Swanner, general manager of
T&AMP;S Hardwoods in Sylva, N.C. ``These are proud people. They want to
work.''
</P>
<P>
   It's tough, dangerous work. Jones' brother was killed more than
10 years ago when a log fell from a truck and smashed his head.
</P>
<P>
   Jones himself wears many scars. A stitch line across his left
hand shows where a surgeon reattached three fingers and a thumb
left dangling by a chainsaw; his left ankle is a prosthesis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could be retired, but I can't stay out of the woods,'' he
says. ``I love it too much. If I quit, I would die.''
</P>
<P>
   And he and other loggers do it because the money is good. A
logger in these parts earns $100 a day, decent wages in an area
where workers commonly earn less than $300 a week.
</P>
<P>
   To native mountaineer loggers such as Jones, the debate over the
fate of public lands such as the 1.1-million acre Nantahala and
Pisgah national forests across western Carolina is a sign that they
are losing their mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want us to cut timber. They don't want us to hunt
bears. They don't want us to do nothing,'' argues Jones. ``Well,
when they cut out the logging and the hunting, what's going to be
left for us old mountain hoodlums?''
</P>
<P>
   As more and more people from the congested cities and suburbs
seek escape in the cool highlands _ either moving here or rafting
on the rivers, hiking the trails and camping in the forest _ the
Forest Service is responding to louder calls for preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changing demographics,'' observes Gary Pierson, the chief
planner for the Forest Service's Southern region. ``We're seeing
different values being put on the resources. What people want is
changing.'' The national forests of the East were created after
1911 when Congress authorized the Forest Service to purchase
cutover lands and old farms. Then in the 1960s, prompted by
Congress to increase timber production throughout all of America's
national forests, the Forest Service aggressively adopted
industrial forestry methods to increase production to fuel the
housing boom.
</P>
<P>
   Massive clear-cuts, some 200 acres or more, scarred the
mountainsides, where loggers like Jones had traditionally used
selection-cutting where the bigger trees were thinned, leaving the
rest to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to tell the Forest Service that clear-cutting was
bad,'' Jones recalls. ``But they did it anyway. It has turned the
public against us.''
</P>
<P>
   While national forest land in the South produces less than 2
percent of all the timber cut in the region, the Forest Service has
a much stronger presence in the Appalachians. In the highlands 17
percent of the timberlands are in national forests. Despite a
reduction of about 50 percent of harvesting from Appalachian
national forest over the past decade, timber industry employment
has grown slightly, according to the Southern Appalachian
Assessment, a landmark 1997 government inventory of the region's
public and private forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the longest time the timber industry has claimed the sky
would fall on the loggers if harvest levels dropped on national
forests,'' says Peter Kirby, southeast regional director for the
Wilderness Society. ``But what has happened is they have shifted to
private lands, and that has more than made up the difference.''
Considered among the most valuable hardwoods in the nation, a lot
of Appalachian oak, maple, cherry and ash is exported to Europe and
made into fine furniture, musical instruments and even billiards
tables, says Ray Harbin, a veteran lumber exporter based in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, we're going to run out of private lands to log
because those lands are being converted to subdivisions,'' says
Swanner, whose mill in Sylva contracts with the Jones family to cut
the timber. ``Also, we're getting a new generation of landowners
who are not like the old farmers were. They are not interested in
managing their lands for timber. They just want to leave it
alone.''
</P>
<P>
   To just leave alone a mature hardwood forest seems like a sin at
worst, a waste at best, to the Jones family loggers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like people who grow corn,'' explains son David
Jones, 37, who quit a job as a high school home-building instructor
several years ago to return to the woods with his dad. ``You can't
just let the weeds grow up with the corn. It ruins it. With a
forest it's the same way. We cut out some older trees to let in
light that allows the younger trees to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't cut them,'' he adds, ``they are just going to die
and rot and not be any good to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Jones never learned to read or write. He went to work in the
woods at age 15, using a team of oxen to drag the logs. He later
bought a used GMC truck to haul the logs to the mill.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time when almost all the men, and some of the women,
who lived in the mountains around Franklin, N.C., where he grew up,
cut timber or sawmilled at one time or another. He shakes his head
when he talks about how bitter the argument over logging of the
mountains has become.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year at a Forest Service job along
recreation-popular Kimsey Creek, near the Appalachian Trail, the
Joneses were hit by vandals who poured dirt into the fuel tank of a
diesel-powered skidder. The result was a $4,000 engine rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen scattered vandalism of logging equipment in recent
years,'' says Terry Seyden, a spokesman for the Nantahala and
Pisgah national forest. ``And in the past year or two we've seen
more local protesters at logging sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the hazards, the controversy and the hard labor are worth it
to Jones. As he pauses to admire a full load of cherry logs stacked
high on his truck, he says, ``That sure is a pretty sight. A load
of good saw logs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
