<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOGRAGE-COX     08-15 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOGRAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Guardian angel of the wildlands
 &HT;    By John Harmon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toccoa , Ga._ Nowhere else in the Chattahoochee National Forest
is there a larger wealth of rare plants than in the foothills
between Toccoa and Cornelia. Perhaps no one knows the Gainesville
Ridges better than James Sullivan, 46, a self-taught botanist,
expert orienteerer, canoe builder and environmental activist.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, the Stephens County resident has walked almost every
foot of this unique area where the Piedmont swells into waves of
low ridges at the base of the far grander Blue Ridge in northeast
Georgia. What he has found is a treasure trove of plants, from
massive beech trees in damp, cool woods to endangered purple cone
flowers along hot, dusty roads.
</P>
<P>
   It is a land also rich with timber. At times, Sullivan observes,
it seemed the U.S. Forest Service was bent on destroying the rare
natural ecosystems of the Gainesville Ridges by building more
roads, cutting hardwoods and replanting with pine tree plantations.
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan and people like him have helped nudge the federal
agency away from serving timber and toward protecting the
ecosystem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for us to protect large blocks of
wildlands, not just because they are reserves for species not
commonly found, but it's important to our mental health just
knowing they are there,'' argues Sullivan. ``I've had people tell
me, `I can't go through those places like you do. But I'm sure glad
they are there.'''
</P>
<P>
   To Sullivan and a growing chorus that means further reducing
logging of national forests. From the mid-1980s to the mid-1990s,
as environmentalists pushed for more protection of the high
mountains of Georgia, Sullivan documented that the government was
looking more and more to the Gainesville Ridges to make up timber
losses in the national forest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be argued that this is the most endangered ecosystem
in Georgia, and yet the Forest Service has failed to recognize it
as a special place,'' Sullivan argues.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan's activism has won the respect of one of the people he
was often most critical of, District Ranger Tom Hawks, who retired
early this year after 23 years as the head ranger of the Chattooga
Ranger District.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't just preach a party line like some paid person,''
Hawks says. ``He gets out there and studies the situation to learn
what is going on. He's very knowledgeable.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan is one of the most senior members of Georgia
ForestWatch, which assigns members to monitor each district of the
Chattahoochee forest.
</P>
<P>
   ForestWatch was formed in 1986 as part of an agreement between
the Forest Service and a coalition of Georgia environmental groups
that had filed an administrative appeal of the Chattahoochee forest
plan as being too timber oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``ForestWatch and groups like them in other states have changed
the way the public interacts with the Forest Service,'' says Taylor
Barnhill, director of the Southern Appalachian Forest Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
