<HEADER>
A5630 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIOLENCEKIDS-COX     08-15 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIOLENCEKIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lethal entertainment doesn't confuse nonviolent kids
 &HT;    By Damien Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bang! Oh, I'm sorry. I'm not usually a violent person. But when
I saw this particularly violent TV show, I just had to kill
somebody.
</P>
<P>
   Does that make any sense to you? Me neither.
</P>
<P>
   Just because I saw a violent act on TV doesn't dictate that I go
and do it.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the fact that kids around the country have been going
to school and pulling rifles instead of rulers out of their book
bags is disturbing. I speak from experience, though, when I say,
``He didn't do it 'cause TV said it was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   I watch violent shows and movies, and I listen to music with
violent content, but I have never run out and committed violent
acts based on the lyrics or from watching ``Lethal Weapon 4,''
``Dark City,'' ``Fallen'' or ``South Park.''
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, if some kid sees his favorite TV hero punching
some guy in the head, he's more likely to punch some kid on the
playground than if he had watched Mr. Rogers. That's one of the few
things on which studies agree. On the other hand, what kind of
environment is that kid living in that he doesn't know that the
things that may be seen on TV don't always translate into real
life?
</P>
<P>
   Some people might say, ``Well, you're just a kid, what do you
know?'' Fine. There are professors who can back me up.
</P>
<P>
   Emory University sociology professor Robert Agnew says studies
show that entertainment media violence is more likely to be
emulated when the violence is committed by the hero. That makes
sense; who wants to take after the loser?
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the studies tend to suggest that exposure to violence,
especially on TV, has a small to moderate effect on kids,'' says
Agnew, who is director of violence studies at Emory. Perhaps, he
says, these studies showing that kids who watch violent programming
become violent might mean that kids who are violent like violent
shows.
</P>
<P>
   Media violence may contribute to a minimal increase of violence
in our society, but it's not the most important factor, says Agnew.
Some people, though, talk about TV violence as if it were, by and
large, the cause of the downfall of the civilized world.
</P>
<P>
   I'm 16. I have been in the Atlanta public schools and I have
seen violence. Nothing I've seen has ever gone as far off the
handle as TV shows. And there is the point. TV is used to inform
and entertain. The entertainment part should not be confused with
the information part. They are different animals.
</P>
<P>
   I have this shirt, my favorite shirt actually. It says, ``I do
what the voices in my head tell me.'' I love the reactions I get
when I wear this shirt. I've seen people cross the street after
looking at my shirt and seeing me lost in a Stephen King book. I
had a vendor at Six Flags Over Georgia ask me, ``You hear voices,
too?'' I don't know whether she was joking.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, the shirt is a joke. There are people out there
with schizophrenia who never harm a fly, but Hollywood always has
them burning down buildings. I'm poking fun at the sheer
preposterousness of that idea.
</P>
<P>
   Psychological predisposition is also a factor in kids who commit
violent acts. A person could just be messed up in the head. Every
day he could think about what he could do to the people who have
done him petty injustices.
</P>
<P>
   I think social status is a major factor in the level of violence
in a kid. If he is ``Mr. Popular,'' then he is a lot less likely to
get into fights than if he's the pariah, the outcast. He might be
watching violent entertainment to get ideas.
</P>
<P>
   He could try watching the news; it gives instruction _ detailed
descriptions about how murders were committed. This is by no means
saying that TV news should be censored, only that even the concept
of ``the public has a right to know'' has its costs.
</P>
<P>
   Don't just pick one thing to attack. Take your pick of the
hierarchy in the teen social system, the news, bad home training.
They're all to blame.
</P>
<P>
   I don't take Hollywood seriously; why should anyone else? Who
remembers the ``Jaws'' movies? Has anyone ever seen a great white
shark that big or vicious? For the most part, Hollywood distorts
stuff to the point where it can no longer be taken seriously. And
that, ladies and gentlemen, is entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Damien Williams, a rising junior at Horizon School in Atlanta,
is a writer with ``Vox,'' a newspaper by and about Atlanta-area
teenagers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
