<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5632 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COL-TEX     08-15 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIXES GRAF, ``NO, I DON'T REGRET THAT...'' 
AS RUMORS SWIRL ON OUTSIDE, CHAN KEEPS AIR CLEAR ON INSIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hello, plus a sincere thanks to a multitude of people who made
this move possible.
</P>
<P>
   With that, it's time to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   As training camp in Wichita Falls closed this weekend, the
Cowboys were a mere slashed neck and a thousand ``no comments''
away from saying a wonderful time was had by all.
</P>
<P>
   This is an organization where winning is no longer a sure
fix-all for credibility and image gaffes. Actually, winning is no
longer even a probability, which means credibility and image are
now in danger of being fed to the wolves or Michael Irvin.
</P>
<P>
   So with due respect to Everett McIver _ it was, after all, his
neck _ there is a more significant wound the Cowboys, as an
organization, bring back from Wichita Falls.
</P>
<P>
   Chan Gailey was not bloodied in the McIver dorm-room incident,
but where being believable is concerned, he has at least been
bruised.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey as the right choice to coach the Cowboys has yet to be
decided. Give it a season or two. But Gailey as the right kind of
human being to lead the Cowboys, that has been unanimously hailed
as Jerry Jones' shrewd or lucky move. Without ever having coached a
game in the NFL, Gailey made everyone _ players, fans and media _
feel good about an organization that has not been easy to like or
respect over the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks ago, unfortunately, there was Chan being sucked
right into another mess apparently created by the master of the
non-football-related mess, Michael himself.
</P>
<P>
   In front of the minicams, Gailey spent several days verbally
fumbling his way through repeated ``no comments.'' Watching Gailey,
there was certainly the thought of a cover-up, or worse, the
thought of a Jones puppet. Which could have meant there had been no
change from the previous overmatched Howdy Doody who answered to
``head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones can try, try, try to get on even terms with the truth _
and to his credit, he is trying. But as long as there is the
continuing perception that Jerry is running a protection racket for
Irvin and other team members in trouble, it's a hopeless cause.
</P>
<P>
   What Gailey's hire meant to Jones, however, was an alternative
to that perception. This was good for Jerry, good for the Cowboys,
good for everyone. But when the first major crisis arrived, well,
doubt about Chan surfaced, at least to a certain degree among some
media and some fans.
</P>
<P>
   Through all this, however, there has been a third party much
more directly involved in how Gailey ``handled'' the McIver
slashing. If the players, who were also watching and waiting on
Gailey to react, are convinced a strong head coach emerged, then
what anyone else thinks doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   And, frankly, this is the good news attached to this stinko
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only did \RGailey\S handle it right in the beginning, he's
still handling it right,'' said safety Darren Woodson. ``This is a
good man. I can't stress enough how he kept it from being a
distraction. There is not a dark cloud in this at all for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   One player, who asked that his name not be used, said Gailey
gathered a roomful of team leaders immediately after the slashing,
explained the entire matter, and then told them how he would
approach it with the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it may have looked bad for him at times,'' said the
player, ``but he showed us not only that he was right on top of it,
but that he would be strong. This is not a cover-up, and he didn't
lie to anyone. It was simply handled within the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this,'' he said, ``there is no question in anyone's mind
who is running this team and who is in control. This was not easy,
and I know some people are doubting him a bit, particularly the
media. But within the team, Chan put it to rest quickly and
effectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Would a complete public disclosure of the truth have been
better? Yes, but that also depends on what happened in that dorm
room, and no media member knows, except that a neck was slashed.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey, for his part, apologizes for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I came out of this viewed in a negative light, then being
human, I regret that,'' he said. ``Then again, it comes with the
territory. What I did was best for the team. The way I will always
handle things is what's best for the overall group. What I believe
in, and my values, those haven't changed. In making the decisions I
made about this, those values didn't have to change.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was Gailey who initially described the incident as
``horseplay,'' and even nationally, that has brought ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I don't regret that either,'' he said. ``My next sentence
was it could have resulted in a very serious accident. What I
wanted to do was stress this was not a vendetta or simmering feud
between players. It was spur of the moment. If horseplay applies
again, I will use horseplay again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take very seriously this kind of wound for one of our
players. It's dangerous and it shouldn't have happened. But at the
same time there were a lot of other factors that went into it other
than that end result.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the locker room, doubts linger about Gailey's role.
Inside, however, he apparently never allowed a doubt to surface.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Galloway is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
