<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRISH-BOMB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRA SPLINTER GROUP BLAMED IN ULSTER BOMBING THAT KILLS 26
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ A car bomb exploded Saturday in the
middle of the shopping district of this market town, killing at
least 26 people and injuring about 200 in what officials said was
the worst atrocity in Northern Ireland in the last 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those killed and seriously injured unintentionally had
been moved closer to the bomb. Police said the bombers in a
telephone warning about 40 minutes before the explosion had given
them inaccurate information. Officials said they expected the death
toll to climb because of the seriousness of some injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the blast victims were women and children doing
back-to-school shopping. The blast occurred shortly before the
start of a carnival in the town center, which had attracted
hundreds of children. Among the dead were a pregnant woman and five
children, including a baby. Witnesses described a scene of carnage,
as the injured and dying lay moaning for help.
</P>
<P>
   Police said they suspect the bomb, estimated to have weighed 500
pounds, was the work of Irish republican dissidents who are
determined to wreck the peace process. Ulster Television received
two calls prior to the explosion from someone claiming to represent
the ``Real IRA,'' one of the dissident groups that broke from the
Irish Republican Army because of the IRA's declaration of a
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing, which represents the greatest loss of life in
Northern Ireland during three decades of violence over British
rule, is the most serious blow to the newfound stability created by
the political settlement that was overwhelmingly approved in May by
voters, north and south.
</P>
<P>
   Republican dissidents have been trying for months to mount a
spectacular attack, although they have almost always given warnings
prior to bomb attacks, suggesting they had wanted to destroy
property and support for the peace process rather than kill
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether the vague or inaccurate warning given by
the bombers was simply a failure of communication or was meant to
inflict the highest number of casualties.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the casualty figures were unusually high because
they had moved people to an area away from the town courthouse,
where a telephone caller had claimed the bomb was planted. The
blast occurred 400 yards from the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Flanagan, chief of the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
speaking near the bombing site, said he believed the warning was
deliberately misleading to ensure a maximum number of casualties:
``Children with their mothers, shopping for school uniforms,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   As Flanagan spoke, a uniformed officer stood next to him, his
lip trembling.
</P>
<P>
   Seamus Mallon, the deputy leader of the new Northern Ireland
Assembly, went to the local police station for a briefing. ``I saw
grown men, their uniforms covered with blood, crying,'' said
Mallon.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman at Tyrone County Hospital said five people had
died at the hospital, which admitted a total of 108 people after
the bombing. More than 40 of the most seriously injured were
airlifted to hospitals in Belfast, Derry, and Enniskillen.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair, who was on vacation in
France, was visibly shaken when he gave a televised interview last
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an appalling act of savagery and evil by people
detemined to wreck the peace process,'' said Blair. ``The bombers
will be pursued to the utmost in order to bring them to justice.
These people will never be allowed to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertie Ahern, the Irish premier, called the bombing ``an attack
on democracy.'' He hinted at a crackdown on those suspected in the
bombing, a group that is allegedly led by a man who lives in the
Irish Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must ruthlessly suppress these people,'' said Ahern.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the White House condemned the bombing and said
President Clinton is determined to carry out his visit to Northern
Ireland the first week of September.
</P>
<P>
   Martin McGuinness, the chief negotiator for Sinn Fein, the IRA's
political wing, said he was ``appalled and disgusted'' by the
attack. He called on those continuing to carry out republican
violence to end it.
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, the Social Democratic and Labor Party leader who was
the chief architect of the Good Friday agreement, called the
bombers ``undiluted fascists.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Robinson, deputy leader of the Democratic Unionist Party,
which opposed the political settlement, blamed the British
government for the bombing, saying its policy of ``appeasing
terrorists'' had emboldened the bombers.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mo Mowlam, the British secretary of state in Northern
Ireland, and David Trimble, the newly elected leader of the
Northern Ireland Assembly, broke off their vacations and were
heading back to Belfast. In a statement, Trimble said the bombing
would not have occurred if the IRA had turned in its weapons, as he
and his Ulster Unionist Party have urged.
</P>
<P>
   But others said the bombing was the result of a growing
determination by republican splinter groups to carry on the war
that many people here thought was over after the passage of the
referendums in May and the establishment in June of the first local
government in 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   The group believed responsible for Saturday's bombing detonated
a car bomb in the center of Banbridge, a mostly Protestant town
just south of Belfast, on Aug. 1. But the area had been evacuated
and no one was injured. The warning in Banbridge came only 20
minutes before the explosion, but it was accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Flanagan said Saturday's warning was ``totally inaccurate'' and
was tragically misleading. He said his officers were searching for
the bomb which the caller had said was ``near the courthouse.''
Police, meanwhile, had shepherded hundreds of shoppers about a
quarter-mile from the courthouse to the corner of Market Street and
Dublin Road. It was at that very corner that the maroon Vauxhall
sedan exploded.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Banbridge and Portadown, towns with large Protestant
majorities that were targeted by dissidents in earlier attacks,
Omagh is a mixed town where Protestant unionists and Catholic
nationalists have relatively good relations.
</P>
<P>
   Several hours after the bombing, the usually quiet town had a
surreal feel to it, as car and building alarms activated by the
blast wailed, and British army helicopters hovered overhead.
Hysterical men and women looked for information on missing loved
ones, both at the scene and at Tyrone County Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Byrne, the newly elected assembly member for the area, said
he was at the blast site within 10 minutes of the explosion. He
said it was a scene of utter devastation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ran past me, bloodied,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone County Hospital, a small provincial hospital, was
overwhelmed by the biggest disaster it has ever seen, a flood of
victims and loved ones looking for them. At one point, there was a
traffic jam outside the hospital as local people rushed to donate
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Among those hurt were teenage Spanish students who had come to
Ireland to study English and were visiting Omagh for the day. But
most of the dead and injured were local people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is horrible, beyond words,'' said Byrne.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
