<SLUG> BC-IRISH-MICKEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLINTER GROUP'S LEADER MAY BE SOUGHT IN INVESTIGATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OMAGH, Northern Ireland _ In an instant, Omagh joined the list
of towns in Northern Ireland that by their mere mention conjure
images of bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   And in an instant, Mickey McKevitt became the most wanted man in
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   McKevitt, reputedly the former quartermaster in charge of
weapons for the Irish Republican Army, is the alleged leader of the
``Real IRA,'' a splinter group based in the Irish Republic that is
being blamed for Saturday's bombing that killed dozens and injured
about 200.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the Irish premier, Bertie Ahern, vowed to
``ruthlessly suppress'' those dissident republican groups that are
continuing violence.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean rounding up McKevitt, who is married to the
sister of the dead IRA icon Bobby Sands, and a group of about 100
hard-liners.
</P>
<P>
   Internment without trial was a disaster when it was tried
against the IRA in 1971 by the British Army. So many innocents were
caught in the dragnet that it merely alienated ordinary Catholics
and helped the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   But there were suggestions last night that the Irish police, the
Garda Siochana, have a good idea who the leaders of the ``Real
IRA'' are, and that the atrocity in Omagh could trigger a roundup.
</P>
<P>
   Such a roundup, however, could give the dissidents an issue to
rally support. However, so widespread was the revulsion last night
that it was hard to imagine huge numbers of people feeling sorry
for McKevitt and anyone else who is detained because of Saturday's
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   The Omagh bombing marked the greatest loss of life in Northern
Ireland during the last 30 years of violence. The highest previous
toll in a single attack connected to the Troubles occurred in 1974,
when 28 people were killed in Dublin by a bomb planted by
Protestant extremists. A simultaneous bomb attack in Monaghan
killed five others.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the previous bombings targeted either Protestant
unionists or Catholic nationalists, Saturday's blast was noteworthy
for being indiscriminate in its killing. Omagh is a mixed town,
where the two communities generally get along.
</P>
<P>
   SaturdaySaturday
</P>
</TEXT>
