<HEADER>
A5636 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS &LR;      08-15 1663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR, CLINTON READY FOR MONDAY'S CONFRONTATION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton sits down Monday in the
White House Map Room to deliver closed-circuit testimony to a grand
jury, perhaps one of the questions he will face is what has been
posed for months: Did he have a sexual relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky?
</P>
<P>
   Before that general query is raised, lawyers from independent
counsel Kenneth W. Starr's office are likely to ask the president a
series of narrow and highly specific questions designed to develop
a chronology of events, many of which were not asked in Clinton's
deposition in the Paula Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's strategy is to check parts of Clinton's story, and to
determine whether he is telling small lies that could expose bigger
ones, former federal prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he is going to lie, it gets very complicated when you have
to give a great deal of specific answers,'' said a former federal
prosecutor, Joseph diGenova, who once questioned President Bush in
an independent counsel inquiry. ``You can get tripped up relatively
easily.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged on July 31 to testify ``completely and
truthfully.'' Aides say that only the president, Hillary Clinton,
and personal advisers know what his testimony will be.
</P>
<P>
   After years of investigation into a variety of allegations,
after nearly seven months on the Lewinsky inquiry, this may be
Starr's last chance to prove his theory that Clinton has obstructed
justice.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether Starr is going in with plenty of
evidence in hand, or whether he is fishing for new clues from
Clinton that could prove the president's guilt.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected that Starr will submit a report to Congress.
Ultimately, the report could lead to impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is not talking about his tactics. But the tenor of his
investigation is clear to those who have watched the parade of
witnesses file into the federal courthouse on Pennsylvania Avenue,
between the White House and the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has queried everyone from Linda R. Tripp, who taped 20
hours of conversations with Lewinsky, to several dozen Secret
Service agents who protect Clinton, to the president's closest
confidants. Lewinsky, who worked at the White House as an intern
from July 1995 to April 1996, visited the White House on 37
occasions after April 1996, most recently in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has been preparing for the session with his
personal lawyers, is expected to be pressed on his assertions that
he does not remember a private meeting with Lewinsky. If Starr has
evidence that Clinton met with Lewinsky privately on more than a
dozen occasions, as Lewinsky reportedly has testified, then Clinton
is likely to be asked to explain what he was doing on each day in
question.
</P>
<P>
   At some point, Starr probably will outline a broad definition of
sexual relations, and probably will ask Clinton whether he had sex
with Lewinsky. That would determine whether Clinton lied in the
Jones sexual harassment case when he said he had no ``affair'' with
Lewinsky. Then Starr would try to build an obstruction-of-justice
case by questioning whether Clinton or his allies had urged
Lewinsky to lie about the alleged relationship.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is unusual, and not just because Clinton will be the
first president to testify before a grand jury. While prosecutors
routinely call witnesses before a grand jury, it is rare for the
target of an investigation to testify. Most defense lawyers advise
their clients to cite their Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination, and then refuse to testify. Clinton has agreed
to testify because his political advisers thought a refusal to
cooperate would look bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is enormous risk and little practical benefit, because
by the time you are a target, the prosecutor believes you have
committed a crime, and it is highly unlikely your words can
convince him otherwise,'' said a former federal prosecutor, Robert
Ullmann of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It is also unusual for a witness to have lawyers present for a
grand jury appearance. The White House announced on Friday that
Clinton will be accompanied by his personal attorneys, David E.
Kendall and Nicole Seligman, as well as the White House counsel,
Charles Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest concern for Clinton is that Starr may have evidence
to corroborate Lewinsky's reported testimony that she had sexual
relations with the president. Clinton can only wonder what evidence
Starr may have, especially if tests have determined that Clinton's
DNA is on Lewinsky's dress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers may try to attack Lewinsky's credibility by
referring to reports that she contradicted her sworn denial of an
affair with Clinton after she received immunity from prosecution.
Kendall reportedly has spent much time collecting evidence that
could hurt Lewinsky's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   But White House officials have insisted for months that they
would not attack Lewinsky, in contrast to their effort to undermine
the credibility of Jones and Kathleen Willey, a former White House
volunteer who said Clinton had made an unwanted sexual advance.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides insist that Clinton will tell the truth about
his relationship with Lewinsky. But analysts noted that for years,
Clinton denied having an affair with Gennifer Flowers, then
admitted in January under oath that he had had sex with her on one
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials have said there is no contradiction
between Clinton's initial denial of an affair with Flowers and his
admission of one sexual encounter. That has prompted court
observers to wonder if Clinton will use a similar semantic tactic
in the Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyers said Clinton's testimony could take several
paths. The president might insist that there was no affair and that
Lewinsky is lying. He might argue that his definition of sexual
relations does not include oral sex or other contact, if any, that
occurred between him and Lewinsky. He might say the details of a
personal relationship are private, while swearing that he never
told Lewinsky to lie. Or, he could issue a mea culpa and say that
his denials of a sexual relationship were intended to protect his
wife and daughter.
</P>
<P>
   One way to gauge what could occur during Clinton's testimony
might be to review what the president said when asked about
Lewinsky in his Jan. 17 deposition for the Jones lawsuit. The
transcript shows that Clinton often was vague and said he could not
remember.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Clinton testified that it was ``possible'' that he
was alone with Lewinsky. ``I could have'' given her gifts, Clinton
also said. But asked if he had met with Lewinsky several times, he
replied, ``I don't know about several times.'' Asked if he had been
alone with Lewinsky, he said, ``I don't recall ... It seems to me
she brought things to me once or twice on weekends.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also was asked whether anything ``remarkable'' would
have occurred if he met with Lewinsky between midnight and 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, nothing remarkable,'' Clinton replied. ``I don't remember
it.'' No definition of a ``remarkable'' event was discussed.
</P>
<P>
   A former federal prosecutor, Bruce Yannett, said he expects
Starr to ask a series of questions that will leave Clinton with no
chance to reply vaguely to key questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would build up to the ultimate issues, including the
precise nature of the relationship between the president and Ms.
Lewinsky,'' Yannett said. ``It is very likely that Starr will ask
essentially the same kinds of questions that were asked of the
president during the Paula Jones deposition, with a greater level
of specificity and detail.''
</P>
<P>
   Yannett said Starr would focus on why Clinton gave gifts to
Lewinsky and why she returned them to Clinton's secretary, Betty
Currie. Starr will then try to determine whether Clinton urged
Lewinsky to lie about the relationship, which could be subornation
of perjury, or whether the two had simply agreed not to talk about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is also likely to probe into why and how Lewinsky received
help from Clinton's friend, Vernon E. Jordan Jr., and then-UN
Ambassador Bill Richardson, to find a job.
</P>
<P>
   Starr also will grill Clinton on whether he or his associates
had anything to do with the ``talking points,'' a document that
Lewinsky gave to Tripp in January. The talking points urged Tripp
to say she was unaware of Clinton making an alleged sexual advance
to Willey.
</P>
<P>
   While the vague nature of Clinton's responses in the Jones
deposition might make it difficult to pin down the president about
gifts and about Lewinsky visits to the White House, it will be much
trickier for Clinton to change his denial of having sexual
relations with Lewinsky. When Clinton gave his deposition in
January, Jones's lawyers gave Clinton a broad definition of what
would constitute sexual relations. Clinton was unequivocal with his
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky,''
Clinton said in the deposition. ``I've never had an affair with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton testifies, Starr may recall Lewinsky or others
before the grand jury, and then he is expected to turn over a
report to the House of Representatives. The House then would decide
whether there is enough evidence to hold impeachment hearings,
thereby interjecting politics into the legal issue.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, the Lowell Democrat who sits on
the House Judiciary Committee that could hear the impeachment case,
said that a Clinton lie in the Jones deposition would not
necessarily result in impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be disappointed,'' Meehan, a former prosecutor, said of
such a revelation. ``But it doesn't rise to high crimes and
misdemeanors,'' the Constitution's definition of impeachable
offenses. But Meehan said it would be much more serious if Clinton
lies before the grand jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
