<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONGRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS PREPARES FOR SPECIAL PROSECUTOR'S REPORT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is quietly preparing for the potential
tumult of having the independent counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, drop
his investigation of President Clinton on its doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks of Clinton's grand jury testimony tomorrow, Starr
is expected to report his findings in the Monica S. Lewinsky matter
to the House for possible action, including the most extreme
possibility: a push for the president's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   For many members of Congress, uncertainty is tinged with concern
about ramifications for the presidency, for their parties in the
November elections, and for their careers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton's most partisan rivals sense danger. ``It's like
pulling the pin out of a hand grenade,'' said Representative John
A. Boehner of Ohio, chairman of the House Republican Conference.
``It may blow up on you.''
</P>
<P>
   No previous Congress has been confronted with a special
prosecutor's report on a criminal investigation of a president. And
there is little precedent for how Congress should fulfill its
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the nature of the case, with its allegations of a
sexual relationship between Clinton and Lewinsky, strikes many
members of Congress as potentially more delicate than the Senate's
confirmation hearings on Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a big mess, and I think Democrats and Republicans both
would like it to go away,'' said Representative Martin T. Meehan, a
Lowell Democrat who serves on the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich has said that the 36-member
Judiciary Committee will be responsible for reviewing Starr's
report, deciding whether hearings are warranted, and making a
recommendation to the House. The recommendations could range from
taking no action to seeking Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Under the independent counsel law, which was enacted in 1978
after the Watergate scandal, Starr is required to ``advise the
House of Representatives of any substantial and credible
information ... that may constitute grounds for an impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr has said he will provide his findings to the House so it
can decide how to proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The Constitution grants the House the sole power to impeach a
president for ``treason, bribery, or other high crimes and
misdemeanors.'' An impeachment is the rough equivalent of an
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   In case of House approval of articles of impeachment against a
president, the Senate would conduct a trial, presided over by the
chief justice of the Supreme Court. If the defendant is found
guilty by two-thirds of the Senate, the president is removed from
office.
</P>
<P>
   The Judiciary Committee has prepared for Starr's report by
hiring 14 lawyers and investigators, nine for the Republican
majority, five for the Democratic minority.
</P>
<P>
   Party leaders also are holding regular strategy sessions. But
Representative Barney Frank of Newton, who participates in the
Democratic meetings, said the gatherings focus largely on how to
handle news media questions concerning the impending report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole process is wide open because there is no precedent
for it,'' said Frank, a senior member of the Judiciary Committee.
``But there is not much else to do until we see the report.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The panel's chairman, Representative Henry J. Hyde, an Illinois
Republican, has said he hopes to curb leaks of Starr's report to
the news media by limiting the number of committee members who will
be permitted to see the material.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, committee members are weighing possible scenarios,
including the unlikely prospect that the panel will hold hearings
into the allegations involving Clinton and Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Members of both parties said they oppose holding hearings before
the November elections, for fear of a potential backlash from
voters.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   However, many lawmakers are particularly skittish about holding
hearings any time. ``The reality is, if the whole thing comes down
to whether or not the president had consensual sex with Monica
Lewinsky and whether he lied about it, it would be difficult for a
lot of members to serve as judge and jury on that kind of matter,''
Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, members of both parties have urged Clinton to apologize
publicly as a way to resolve the matter without congressional
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Only a few lawmakers have expressed preliminary support for
possible impeachment hearings. Notable among them is Senator John
Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican and presidential aspirant, who
raised the possibility that Republican leaders would block
impeachment proceedings to prevent Vice President Al Gore from
getting a ``a jump-start on the next election.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in that,'' Ashcroft said last month on the
Senate floor. ``I believe that if there has been a serious
infraction that merits impeachment, the inquiry must take place.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Clinton plans to testify before the grand jury via
closed-circuit television.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the new lawyers and investigators on the
Judiciary Committee are reviewing the history of impeachments, even
though the history is brief.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Congress has brought impeachment charges against only one
president: Andrew Johnson, in 1868. Although the case stemmed
specifically from Johnson's dismissal of War Secretary Edwin M.
Stanton, historians said the impeachment effort reflected a much
larger struggle for power between Congress and the executive branch
after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In partisan proceedings, the House recommended Johnson's
impeachment. But Johnson prevailed in the Senate, as his foes fell
one vote short of the two-thirds majority needed to convict him.
</P>
<P>
   The only other time Congress seriously considered impeaching a
president, the House Judiciary Committee approved three articles of
impeachment against President Richard M. Nixon in 1974. But as the
panel weighed additional charges, Nixon resigned rather than face a
likely trial in the Senate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
