<HEADLINE>
AS THE PACE HURTS CHIEF BEARHART, CETEWAYO ROLLS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Pace makes the race, and a slow pace
can ruin the race for a fast-closing horse. That's what happened
Saturday to Chief Bearhart, the 1997 turf champion, who ran fifth
while Cetewayo, with energy to spare, was winning the Sword Dancer
Invitational and outrunning the champion for the second race in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pace did us in,'' said Jose Santos, who rides Chief
Bearhart. ``They were crawling on the front, and they kick in at
the end. Unfortunately, my horse didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Frostad, who trains Chief Bearhart for Canada's Sam-Son
Farm, put it this way: ``When you go that slow on the front,
everybody has a lot left for the end. The race was really a sprint
for the last half-mile.''
</P>
<P>
   Chief Bearhart has now lost two straight races and three of his
last four, a reversal of fortune from last year, when he won five
of his seven races and finished second the other two times. When he
ran third behind Cetewayo in the Bowling Green Handicap at Belmont
Park last month, people said that the pace was too slow and
predicted that it would not happen again.
</P>
<P>
   But the die was cast earlier Saturday when Buck's Boy was
scratched from the Sword Dancer with a cough. He had been
considered the lone speed in the race, the horse who would force a
speedy pace and allow Chief Bearhart to unleash his finishing kick
with telling effect.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the lead was inherited by Val's Prince, who held it for
more than a mile. But he was crawling. He dawdled the first
quarter-mile in 26 seconds, half a mile in 52 3/5 seconds,
three-quarters in 1:18 2/5 and one mile in 1:43 1/5.
</P>
<P>
   Then everybody started to run fast, including Chief Bearhart,
who had been stalking the leaders from third place. But Cetewayo
had more speed left than the Chief, and he shot from fourth place
into the lead in the homestretch to win by three-quarters of a
length over Val's Prince, who took second by a neck over
Dushyantor.
</P>
<P>
   The winner ran the mile and a half on the grass under John
Velazquez in 2:29 2/5, which was six seconds slower than the track
record, and paid $10.20 for a $2 bet to win.
</P>
<P>
   He went home with $180,000, bringing his career earnings to
$350,000 _ not bad for a onetime $13,000 claimer.
</P>
<P>
   Cetewayo has soared into prominence with a success story of his
own. He won only one of five starts last year, but has won four of
five this year under his trainer, Michael Dickinson, and he scored
Saturday in a Grade I stakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pulled him out,'' Velazquez said, ``and he exploded from the
eighth pole to the wire. Boy, he can kick.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   If you ever wondered why they called Saratoga the house of
racing upsets, consider Saturday's fifth race: Unbridled Express is
a 5-year-old gelded son of Unbridled who had run five times in his
career and never finished better than fourth. But in his sixth
start, he won Saturday at 69-1 and paid $140.50 for a $2 bet. He
also paid $61.50 to place and $13.40 to show and, with the 15-1
long shot Red Hawk finishing second, returned an exacta payoff of
$1,654. Jose Espinoza was the rider and Dominick Schettino the
trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the horses in the barn can be Skip Away, but sometimes
they hit the jackpot, anyway. Sonny Hine's Spendable, who ran
eighth in his last start, reached for the stars in the seventh race
when he scored at 37-1. The payoff: $76 for a $2 bet to win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
