<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REACTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY ABROAD ARE BAFFLED BY PURSUIT OF CLINTON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From Tokyo to Ottawa, from Moscow to Seoul,
governments have a question for Americans: Why does anyone care
about the former intern and the cocktail dress?
</P>
<P>
   Officials of friendly governments have warned that President
Clinton, Congress, and many Americans are allowing pressing
problems of war, terrorism, a renewed nuclear arms race, and
spreading economic contagion to be overshadowed by the Monica S.
Lewinsky case.
</P>
<P>
   This is a strange time: The information that embassies in
Washington send to far-flung capitals often corroborates reports in
the most lurid tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   By now, most officials say they have heard _ and read _ more
than enough.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, Russia, and Mexico, officials worry about plunging
currencies. In Ireland, they fear that Clinton will be distracted
or discredited a visit next month.
</P>
<P>
   And just across the northern border, when developments in the
White House scandal nudged up, with a nice bump for the Canadian
dollar, someone coined the term ``Lewinsky effect.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States and Canada are locked in a bitter row over
which country has the right to fish for the Pacific salmon, now
being heavily harvested by Alaskan fishermen. Canada wants the
president to intervene in the issue. In Ottawa, officials are
trying to entice someone _ anyone _ to resolve it.
</P>
<P>
   With a political crisis looming, though, Clinton is unlikely to
offend powerful congressional leaders from Alaska and the Pacific
Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Across the southern border, Mexican officials talk about
tensions between Mexico City and Washington, including
disagreements over the guerrilla uprising in Chiapas, and the US
inquiry into Mexican banks.
</P>
<P>
   Specialists wonder whether the US president now has the
political capital to help with issues such as the plunging peso,
which fell to a record low against the dollar last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have many institutionalized channels of communications
between our governments, but there are things that frequently
require the attention of the head of state,'' said a former top
aide to Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo, who asked not to be
named. ``It's hard to understand a country that gives so much
attention to something that would be so meaningless for many of
us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the privacy of presidential palaces and legislative chambers,
the officials alternate between bewildered shrugs and bitter asides
when discussing the eight-month scandal that has led to President
Clinton's grand jury testimony tomorrow. They say that America is
forgetting about the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``If American standards of morality were to be adopted in India,
most politicians here would be out of work,'' said Jairan Ramesh,
secretary of the powerful Congress Party in New Delhi. ``The longer
this festers, the more damaging it'll be for the president and ...
the moral loft of the office.''
</P>
<P>
   India, the world's largest democracy, is preoccupied with
tensions with Pakistan that led to nuclear tests and economic
sanctions imposed by Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in Asia, politicians have overwhelming concerns of
their own, such as whether economic chaos will topple their
governments.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the United States' key ally and still the financial
engine of the region, policy makers say they are more interested in
how many yen the dollar will buy tomorrow than about what Clinton
will say in his closed-circuit television testimony.
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, long the bridge between Washington and Beijing,
the government was heartened by Clinton's recent trip to China. No
one relishes the thought of a White House tainted by a lingering
scandal. ``US-China relations are finally back on track, or at
least heading in the right direction,'' said a senior Hong Kong
government official who asked not to be named. ``It would be a
shame to see them stuck on the shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   In many countries, officials' upbeat comments in public differed
sharply from remarks behind closed doors. In South Korea, for
example, Cho Tae Yong, head of the North America division at the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs, said that the Clinton administration
has handled both foreign policy and controversies for years.
</P>
<P>
   But not far away, an official in another ministry mentioned
unease about ``the leadership problem.'' A fight between
Republicans and Democrats is expected to hurt efforts to persuade
the United States to lend billions of dollars to the International
Monetary Fund to help Asian countries in their economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Even the moralistic and conservative city-state of Singapore
seemed surprised at the dimensions to which this scandal has grown.
The Straits Times newspaper, which often echoes the government
view, editorialized that adultery is ``not a good idea, but
unfortunately, not uncommon. For that reason, one hardly expects it
to become the occasion of a constitutional crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, too, officials and outside advisers see in the
Lewinsky case a looming threat to US relations, which have depended
in recent years on Clinton's friendship with Yeltsin. Last month,
at Yeltsin's request, Clinton supported the $22.6 billion rescue
package Russia won from the International Monetary Fund and other
lenders.
</P>
<P>
   As the two countries prepare for a summit next month in Moscow,
officials worry that a US president enmeshed in domestic scandal
would be less likely to counterbalance the American Congress, which
many consider unfriendly toward Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could cause trouble for Russian-American relations, since
the main proponent of the positive approach to Russian-American
relations is the Clinton administration and not Congress,'' said
Vladimir Averchev, a pro-government member of the Foreign Relations
Committee in the lower house of Parliament, the State Duma.
</P>
<P>
   In Israel, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu might be one of the
few allies who senses a reprieve as the American scandal continues.
Beleaguered at home, Clinton might not have the stature, or the
time, to force Israel to make concessions to Palestinians in peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli government scoffs at such a notion. But Yaron
Ezrahi, a Hebrew University political scientist who has conducted
numerous studies of the American political system, put it this way:
``There is definitely a group of people here, especially the prime
minister and his party, who believe that they can benefit greatly
from Clinton's weakness, because a weak president will not be able
to empower the United States presence and role in the Arab-Israeli
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadians counted their good fortune when Lewinsky agreed to
testify against Clinton. Nothing against Clinton, mind you, but
Lewinsky's decision briefly rescued the tumbling Canadian dollar.
In the weird world of currency trading, the announcement made the
United States _ and the US dollar _ appear a bit less stable, while
Canadian currency suddenly seemed a slightly safer bet.
</P>
<P>
   It was short-lived: The Canadian dollar rallied by less than 1
percent, then dropped to a record low.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufauthor &LR;  &UR; gfspanish &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to this report were Globe staff members Richard
Chacon in Mexico City, Kevin Cullen in Ireland, David Filipov in
Moscow, Indira A.R. Lakshmanan in Hong Kong, Colin Nickerson in
Montreal, and correspondents Bonnie Rochman in Jerusalem and Kate
Wiltrout in Seoul.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
