<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'MEARA WON'T DISCOUNT COMEBACK FOR 3RD MAJOR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ If Mark O'Meara is to win his third major
championship this year on Sunday, he will need a brilliant comeback
to do it.
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara shot a one-under-par 69 in the third round Saturday,
leaving him at two-under 208 in the PGA Championship and tied for
sixth place, five strokes off the lead. While O'Meara's situation
is not impossible, it will be extremely difficult to overtake so
many contenders with just 18 holes left.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Meara won both the Masters and the British Open in
comeback fashion, trailing in both tournaments by two strokes
heading into the final round. Drawing on the strength of those
experiences, and feeling that he is hitting the ball solidly,
O'Meara refused to concede after Saturday's round.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can never complain after shooting a 69, but I know the
leaders are making some birdies, and that's what I'll have to do
tomorrow,'' said O'Meara, who is trying to become the first man
since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three majors in the same year. ``I
don't think I'm out of the tournament by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do the fans in O'Meara's gallery, who shouted constant
encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``People keep saying things like, `Good things come in
threes,''' O'Meara said. ``I appreciate the support, and I'm trying
to feed off that. Hopefully, I won't let them down tomorrow.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Course Record
</P>
<P>
   Greg Kraft shot a course-record 65 Saturday and shot himself
into position to win a nice paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   In a round that included seven birdies and just two bogeys,
Kraft moved to one under par for the tournament and broke the
Sahalee Country Club record of 66, set by Tiger Woods on Thursday
and equaled by Vijay Singh on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   With cooler temperatures, overnight rain and cloudy skies
combining to make the course softer and easier, Kraft took full
advantage, shooting a 34 on the front nine and a 31 on the back.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft almost shot a 64, but he missed a five-foot birdie attempt
on No. 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a day where everything seemed to go right,'' said
Kraft, a 34-year-old tour veteran who has enjoyed a solid year,
with two top-10 finishes. ``I made a lot of right decisions and
holed a lot of putts.
</P>
<P>
   ``These greens are perfect. I think the whole golf course is
perfect. My expectations weren't for a 65. But I'm where I thought
I should have been at the beginning of the week, around par.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft has bounced back after a subpar 1997, when he fell to
139th on the PGA Tour money list.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest, I haven't been as sound as I am now,
and I haven't been as focused and dedicated as I am now,'' Kraft
said. ``I really didn't prepare for last year. I figured I was on
the right track and I just assumed some things. I kind of fell on
my face and realized that my mechanics weren't as good as I thought
they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``So this off season I worked out, started working with Robert
Baker who works with Ernie Els and Frank Nobilo. For the first time
in my life, I can see the results as I play and see it on video as
well.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Couples Rebounds
</P>
<P>
   After almost missing the cut, Fred Couples had his best round of
the tournament, shooting a 67 and moving to two over par. Couples,
who grew up in nearby Seattle, was five over par through two rounds
and finished Friday's second round right on the 145 cut line. But
he bounced back Saturday, cheered on by an enthusiastic gallery
that included many friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have made the cut,'' said Couples, who built
momentum by making a 30-foot birdie putt on No.3. ``When I finished
yesterday, I didn't think I had a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were more people today than yesterday. I had a
big crowd, a lot of people cheering and yelling. I hit a lot of
great shots and felt like I earned a 67.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just in Time
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Kelly made it home in time to witness the birth of his
son, Cooper Patrick, who was born Saturday morning weighing 7
pounds 9 ounces. Kelly withdrew after Thursday's opening round when
his wife, Carol, went into labor in Hobe Sound, Fla. Both the baby
and Carol were doing fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
