<HEADLINE>
STRICKER AND SINGH IN A DUEL  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Vijay Singh and Steve Stricker went back and
forth Saturday, like two boxers trading punches.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker snatched the lead from Singh on the front nine,
building a three-stroke lead. Singh responded with a brilliant back
nine, making birdies on Nos. 11, 13, 14 and 15 to take a one-stroke
lead over Stricker.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was Stricker's turn. He made a birdie on No. 16 to tie
Singh, then saved par at the 18th with a spectacular recovery shot.
And when the Singh-Stricker duel had ended at Sahalee Country Club,
both players had separated themselves from the field and stood in
prime position to win the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tied at seven-under-par 203 after three rounds of the year's
final major, Stricker and Singh were four strokes ahead of their
closest pursuers heading into Sunday's final round. Davis Love III,
the defending champion, was one of three players tied for third
place at three under par, along with Steve Elkington, the 1995 PGA
champion, and Billy Mayfair, a two-time winner this year.
</P>
<P>
   With nine players at two under par or better, including Mark
O'Meara and Tiger Woods, neither Stricker nor Singh could start
writing a victory speech. But both leaders were impressive
Saturday, playing with the poise and confidence of golfers who had
been there before, even though neither Singh nor Stricker has ever
won a major.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker shot a four-under-par 66, including a 32 on the front
nine, while Singh shot a 67, including a 31 on the back nine. Can
Stricker and Singh play the final 18 holes as fluidly as they
played the first 54? Or will someone else emerge for an improbable
comeback victory? The answers will come Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But Stricker sounded eager for the challenge. ``I hope I come
out like I did today,'' said Stricker, who was one of the tour's
best players in 1996, slumped badly in 1997 and then rebounded this
year with 10 top-10 finishes to date. ``I was real aggressive,
played really solid, hit a lot of fairways and greens. Hopefully
I'll have those some feelings tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting the day one stroke behind Singh, Stricker made an early
statement that he was a man in charge of his game, with birdies on
No. 2, No. 3 and No. 8, to surge to the front of the leader board.
Stricker split the fairways with pinpoint tee shots, avoiding the
trees and rough, putting himself in position for aggressive
approach shots and birdie opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker's early charge left everyone else behind except Singh,
who responded with eye-opening pressure shots of his own. On No.
13, Singh hit an 8-iron to 5 feet to set up a birdie opportunity,
and he hit close approach shots on No. 14 and No. 15 to set up
close birdie putts.
</P>
<P>
   But Stricker had the shot of the day on No.18, after hitting a
bad second shot into the deep right rough, under a group of trees.
Stricker, about 30 yards from the pin, recovered with a great shot
to within 8 feet, then made the putt to save par and retain a share
of the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pressure circumstances, Stricker's chip shot was
impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might have been the best shot I hit all day,'' he said.
``That just keeps me going into tomorrow with a positive thought. I
didn't hit that bad a 4-wood off the fairway, but I kind of
protected against hitting it left and pushed it right. But that
chip is something that will make dinner taste a little bit
better.''
</P>
<P>
   While the leaders left the course Saturday with great
expectations, others left with bitter memories. Several would-be
contenders shot themselves out of it Saturday, including Colin
Montgomerie, who started the day just one stroke off the lead but
shot a 77 to fall out of contention at four over par. At age 35,
Montgomerie will watch another year pass without winning his first
major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Woods struggled to an even-par 70, once again having
trouble with his swing, leading to erratic shots off the tee. Woods
will need a memorable round to win.
</P>
<P>
   Woods is tied at two under par with O'Meara, who is trying to
become the first player since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three majors
in the same year, and two long-shot contenders _ Skip Kendall and
Frank Lickliter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long day for me,'' said Woods, who had just two
birdies and two bogeys. ``I made some good up-and-downs, and I'm
pleased to be even par for the day. It could have been a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm going to knock down the putts tomorrow because I'm
putting well. I just need to hit some good shots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
