<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS BREAK CAMP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys and the fans at
Midwestern State University ended training camp like they started _
with strong showings yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it was the final day, Cowboys coach Chan Gailey
didn't let up on the players, taking them through a two-hour
practice. Considering the Cowboys play on Monday, Gailey said ``we
needed to get work some in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a credit to them,'' Gailey said. ``All realized the road
\Rhome\S was just 15 or 20 minutes away. And to come out and have a
good practice was impressive on their part. It was a good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Also a good sign was the attendance, as an astonishing 2,900
fans came out to say goodbye to the Cowboys. During practice, they
sang happy birthday to linebacker Fred Strickland, who turned 32
yesterday. They gave the entire team a standing ovation when
practice ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fans have been impressive from the beginning,'' Gailey
said.
Emmitt doubtful
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said yesterday that the team probably would hold running
back Emmitt Smith out of tomorrow night's American Bowl game
against the New England Patriots in Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who sustained a thigh bruise in Tuesday's scrimmage
against the New Orleans Saints, has not missed practice. However,
Gailey said there was ``still some blood'' in his thigh, causing
the team to take a cautious approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not going to take a chance with the thigh, unless he
makes a great recovery the next two days,'' Gailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Gailey said the team will make a final decision about Smith at
game time. However, it's unlikely the Cowboys will take a chance on
playing Smith because of the expected sloppy turf at Azteca
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The same holds true for backup running back Chris Warren, whom
the Cowboys list as questionable because of a groin injury. Gailey
said the team probably will start rookie Tarik Smith at tailback.
</P>
<P>
   Fullbacks Nicky Sualua and Dwayne Chandler could also see time
at tailback against the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive end Kavika Pittman, who is hampered by a sprained
ankle sustained against the Oakland Raiders on Aug. 8, will not
play against the Patriots.
Hellestrae's father dies
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys deep snapper Dale Hellestrae will not make the trip to
Mexico City because of the death of his father.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys spokesman Rich Dalrymple said Larry Hellestrae, who had
been in Wichita Falls visiting his son last week, died of a heart
attack Friday night in his hometown of Phoenix.
Chan's Corner
</P>
<P>
   ``''The work has been very good here. The facilities are really
good. We've answered a ton of questions, more about our 53-man
roster. But the mental aspect is everybody is ready to go back home
and sleep in their own bed. I would be one of those.'''' _Chan
Gailey Cowboys coach
Play of the day
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receivers Michael Irvin and Billy Davis have been making
spectacular plays every day throughout training camp. So, it's no
surprise that a catch was the highlight of the day on the final day
of camp.
</P>
<P>
   However, the key figure is a surprise. While Irvin and Davis
supplied their usual outstanding efforts _ especially Davis, who
burned cornerback Kevin Smith on an out-and-up route _ it was video
intern Jim Seeley who stole the show.
</P>
<P>
   Seeley was perched high above the goal posts shooting practice
when kicker Richie Cunningham launched a football directly at him
during field-goal drills. Seeley, never taking his eye from the
camera, stuck one hand out and effortlessly caught the ball.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining his heroic efforts, Seeley said, ``I had to make
sure I had the shot'' and ``I had to protect the camera.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Seeley, interested in the job at No. 2 receiver?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
