<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-QUESTIONS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS QUESTIONS, ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS, Texas _ The Cowboys went into training camp with
several questions to be answered. Staff writer Kevin Lyons looks at
the key ones and provides some possible answers:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which young players emerged as future starters?
</P>
<P>
   A: Offensive lineman Flozell Adams and defensive tackle Michael
Myers will soon be starters in the NFL. Adams is 6-foot-7 and 335
pounds, but has the agility and quickness to play four positions on
the offensive line, although he'll probably make his mark at right
tackle. Myers started camp slowly, and he still doesn't stand out a
whole lot in practices. But he is always around the ball carrier or
the quarterback in practice and in games. He'll get to show what
he's made of as Leon Lett sits out the rest of the preseason with a
sprained left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who is this year's non-drafted free agent with the best
chance to make the team?
</P>
<P>
   A: Herman Smith. The defensive end has been in three previous
training camps, with San Francisco last year, Tampa Bay from
1995-96, and Philadelphia in 1994. He has also played in the CFL
and NFL Europe. Right now, Smith, 27, is the Cowboys' oldest
defensive end. He has seen all of the first-team repetitions with
Kavika Pittman nursing a sprained ankle, and he has played at least
as well as Pittman. He's a lock to make the team, and no one should
be surprised if Smith makes a start or two this year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How will Chan Gailey utilize Emmitt Smith and Chris Warren?
</P>
<P>
   A: To steal an old line from several of Gailey's news
conferences, ``Emmitt is the starter, and Chris will come in on
third downs.''
</P>
<P>
   Simple as that.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What veteran starters benefited the most from training camp?
</P>
<P>
   A: Guard Nate Newton and middle linebacker Fred Strickland. Had
Newton, 37, not showed up in shape this summer, he could very well
be running second string behind Flozell Adams. Strickland, on the
other hand, began training camp in intense competition with Randall
Godfrey, who is a lot more athletic than Strickland. But the
season-ending injury to Broderick Thomas made the Cowboys change
their plans. Godfrey was moved back outside, where he started in
his first two seasons in the league, and Strickland will start in
the middle. Strickland has not really stood out this summer, but he
has also not made the kind of glaring mistakes that plagued his
game in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does Gailey have more control of this team than Barry Switzer
had?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes and no. Team owner Jerry Jones still has the final say-so
on a lot of matters. The way the club handled the Michael
Irvin-Everett McIver incident was a Jones production all the way.
But on the field, Gailey has complete control. Players who make
mental mistakes in practice must run laps after practice. And we're
not talking about rookie free agents here. Daryl Johnston, Troy
Aikman, Larry Allen and Michael Irvin are among the Cowboys'
superstars who've run laps after committing errors in a workout.
This is a far cry from the way Switzer ran practice, where Switzer
rarely dealt with insubordinate players.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
