u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-ISRAEL-B     08-15 2170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-ISRAEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL CAN'T SEEM TO BREAK INJURY CYCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ He knows what people are thinking as he
pedals along, day after day, logging more miles on a bicycle than
Greg LeMond. He knows, but he cannot worry about it, because he has
something more important to worry about at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Israel knows it's time to worry about himself.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, when he suffered his first knee injury, Israel has
started in only four NFL games and played in only 37 of a possible
64. The reason is simple. His body deserted him.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happened again last year after he left the 49ers to
rejoin Pete Carroll, who had been Israel's boss in San Francisco.
He brought his world-class speed and superior size (5 feet 11
inches, 194 pounds) to help the Patriots where they have been
hurting, seemingly for quite some time.
</P>
<P>
   He was brought in to play right cornerback, but 13 months later,
he's still waiting for his body to give him that chance.
</P>
<P>
   After signing a million-dollar contract, Israel tore the patella
tendon in his left knee in training camp last year and was out all
summer. But as the pressure to perform mounted and more and more
questions were raised on his whereabouts, Israel decided to put
aside what his body was telling him and suit up last Sept. 14 after
missing the entire preseason and the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   He played that day against the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't play again for 11 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Israel played sparingly and always in pain, although
he did enough in the playoffs to convince Carroll that he could
safely trade starter Jimmy Hitchcock for a third-round draft choice
this spring. Carroll looked at that speed and size and still saw
the kind of corner he likes, a physical one who can play a receiver
at the line of scrimmage without fear.
</P>
<P>
   Problem is, this corner hasn't been able to get back anywhere
near the line of scrimmage. He has been able to get back only on
the bike for what now must seem like an endless ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``This situation is not new,'' Israel said. ``Everybody knows
what I can do with it and what I can't. We've all been educated to
it. It only makes sense for me to get in position to contribute
every week, not one week and then take three weeks off.''
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, he pedals on every day and goes to meetings
every night. He does not separate himself from the team, as some
injured players do. Steve Israel is still a Patriot. He's just the
wounded one.
</P>
<P>
   To some, what he has been doing seems easy. The skeptics mutter
that he gets paid for riding an exercise bike, something many
people have to pay to do at a health club. But it is not easy to
ride when you want to play, and it is harder still to watch a job
opening sit right there in front of you and believe you can fill
it.
</P>
<P>
   It is not easy to hear about Beth Israel, the Boston hospital,
when your name comes up, and it's worse not to read your name at
all because that means you're in limbo, which has been Israel's
mailing address for longer than he cares to remember.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he endures, somehow pedaling on, studying his playbook,
hoping that when his chance finally comes again, his body will not
again turn out to be Benedict Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this injury had just popped up, it would be different, but
I'm not in danger of trying to do again what I know I can't,''
Israel said. ``It's not fair to my teammates to go out and play a
week or two and then reinjure myself and be out again. You're
supposed to learn from your mistakes and your experiences in life,
whether they turn out great or not. I have.''
</P>
<P>
   In the offseason, doctors went back into his knee and finally
found what he knew was there all along but nobody else seemed to
believe. They found a cause for his debilitation and, for some, a
cause for celebration. They found a problem, and that solved a
different problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy they found something and corrected it,''
Carroll said this summer. ``Steve was having a lot of problems and
no one could figure out why, so it was a relief to me for them to
go in there and find something and fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a relief because it was tangible evidence to the Patriots
that this was not simply about pain but about injury. In the NFL,
all players, at some point, are required to play with pain. They do
not, however, have to play with injury.
</P>
<P>
   Israel needed no such evidence then nor does he need it now,
when he knows more and more people are looking at him riding that
bike and shaking their heads.
</P>
<P>
   He knows how he feels and he knows how they feel, and this time
he'll go with what he knows best. He'll go with himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew something was wrong with it last year because it wasn't
healing, so it wasn't a relief to me,'' Israel said. ``I knew
something was wrong with my leg. I was just happy to get it taken
care of.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I come back, the decision has to be mutual. They don't
play, I do. If you tell the doctors you can play and they feel
you're sincere and not just a guy wanting to play when he's hurt,
they'll make that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be out, but I don't think about the
frustrating side of this because it leads to negative thoughts and
not smiling. I'm happy because I'm doing all I can and it's
healing. It's taking longer than I thought, but I know it's
healing. So I'm smiling.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel was not smiling as he said those words last week. Rather,
he was asking why he needed to talk about not playing when ``a lot
of guys are doing a lot of good things. Why talk to me? I
understand you've got a job to do, but why talk to me?''
</P>
<P>
   The why is simpler than any of the other questions about him
that need to be answered. Carroll was counting on him this summer,
and so were his teammates and Patriot fans from Augusta to Acton.
He was counting on himself as well. But his knee is counting him
out, and so the people wonder why he is out so long and when he
will be back.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be in time for the Monday night opener in Denver, or
will second-year man Chris Canty be on that corner then? Will it be
in time enough to allow No. 1 draft choice Tebucky Jones to develop
slowly, the way the Giants got to allow Jason Seahorn to do? Or
will someone have to be rushed into the breach?
</P>
<P>
   Steve Israel can't answer those questions, but as he pedals mile
after mile, he surely has to be thinking about them. But he can't
think about them for long because if he does he knows he won't be
smiling anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he pedals on and prays his ride is almost over.
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone with those prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, you may recall, Green Bay coach  &UR; Mike Holmgren
 &LR; garnered a lot of good publicity for giving up his weekly TV show
to spend more time with his family, demonstrating to his players
the kind of focus that was necessary to repeat as Super Bowl
champions. Well, it didn't help them repeat, so Holmgren will be
back on the air this fall. Holmgren was quite public about his
decision a year ago but mum about his turnaround this season ...
Speaking of Holmgren, it was learned last week that while he is
free to leave the Packers at the end of this season despite having
a contract for several more years as head coach, he won't be going
to the expansion Cleveland Browns, as many thought he might. That's
because the league's stocking plan for the Cleveland franchise
includes a prohibition against them trading draft choices to any
team as compensation for signing a head coach with a valid contract
... It's early, but the Cowboys have been particularly pleased with
the play of fifth-round draft choice  &UR; Darren Hambrick &LR; , &UR;  &LR; a
weak-side linebacker, and the discipline of new head coach  &UR; Chan
Gailey &LR; . Gailey, unlike predecessor  &UR; Barry Switzer &LR; , &UR;  &LR; is not a
laissez-faire kind of guy. Among his additions to the Cowboys has
been the shotgun formation and the penalty lap. The latter goes
into effect when a player commits a stupid penalty in practice. If
that had been in effect when Switzer was around, the Cowboys would
have had a half-dozen guys ready for the Boston Marathon. Of
course, all has not been smooth in this transition. The sliced neck
of free agent guard  &UR; Everett McIver  &LR; is a case in point. Rumors
have swirled for weeks that wide receiver  &UR; Michael Irvin  &LR; was
involved in the incident that left a gash in McIver's neck. Irvin
has never been charged with anything, but it has been reported that
he paid McIver a six-figure sum as hush money in a deal brokered by
owner  &UR; Jerry Jones &LR; . Jones has said nothing about the situation,
and players such as outspoken guard  &UR; Nate Newton  &LR; acknowledge that
they have been ordered by the team's public relations department to
refuse comment. All the Cowboys will say is that the incident was a
result of ``horseplay'' in the dorms. Perhaps, but only if you're
from The Godfather School of Negotiations. As for Irvin, he told
Dallas reporters recently, ``You guys are trying harder to put me
in jail than the police.'' The story believed to be the closest to
the truth is that this was a case of a haircut gone bad, a haircut
done by an amateur barber in the dorm suite of  &UR; Kavika Pittman  &LR; at
Cowboy training camp. Pittman claims he was not in the room when
McIver tried to defend the barber after an argument broke out. Last
Thursday, McIver spoke with representatives of the Dallas probation
department, which could send Irvin away for up to 20 years if it
revokes his probation that resulted from the bizarre case involving
strippers, drugs, and death threats a year ago ... Gailey recently
showed that he can be a diplomat. On a questionnaire given to all
new head coaches by the NFL, they are asked to name the most
knowledgeable football writer they've ever met. Gailey's reply?
``The one I'm talking to.''
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   The Bears have finally had it with No. 1 draft choice  &UR; Curtis
Enis &LR; . Vice president for personnel  &UR; Ted Phillips  &LR; informed Enis's
agent,  &UR; Greg Feste &LR; , that the Penn State running back has until
noon Sunday to accept either a five-year deal with a $5.5 million
signing bonus or a six-year one with a slightly higher bonus.
Otherwise, no more than a three-year contract worth far less money
will be offered. The Bears fear that if Enis misses any more time
from training camp, he will be all but useless for much of his
rookie year. Enis claims he might sit out the season and reenter
the draft next year if Chicago doesn't do something to make it
easier for him to void the final three years of the present
six-year offer. If Enis doesn't sign by noon  &UR; today &LR; , he will have
voided out those three years _ and a lot of money _ himself ...
Steelers quarterback  &UR; Kordell Stewart  &LR; is threatening a
little-known NFL record. If he rushes for five touchdowns in this,
his fourth, NFL season, he will surpass former Patriot quarterback
 &UR; Steve Grogan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who rushed for 21 TDs in his first four years ...
Quarterback  &UR; Steve DeBerg &LR; , 44, &UR;  &LR; hadn't played in an NFL game since
1993, and it looked like it last week when he saw his first action
with Atlanta. Signed as insurance after  &UR; Mark Rypien  &LR; was forced to
retire because of family illnesses, DeBerg was sacked three times,
fumbled, and completed only 6 of 11 passes for only 39 yards ...
San Francisco quarterback  &UR; Steve Young  &LR; says he has seen many
changes in the game over the years, but none more than in
conditioning. ``I remember my first year guys were smoking in the
locker room,'' Young recalled. ``I was shocked. You'd never see
that today. If you did that today, guys would look at you like you
were insane.'' ... This will make  &UR; Tom Finneran  &LR; nod his head, I'm
sure. Out in Oakland, the cost of bailing out the Oakland Alameda
County Coliseum will grow to $21 million this year, up $5.4 million
from a year ago, according to estimates from the Alameda County
auditor's office. Nearly all of that red ink has resulted from the
deal cut to lure the Raiders back from Los Angeles. The bailout
money is to cover payments on $198 million in bonds that were
issued to finance renovating and operating the stadium to the
Raiders' satisfaction ... Conversely, things in Tampa have gone so
well with the construction of Raymond James Stadium that the
Buccaneers have added 89 suites to the original 75 because of
demand. The suites will sell for $70,000-$120,000 a year ... The
49ers paid a king's ransom to Green Bay free agent  &UR; Gabe Wilkins
 &LR; in hopes he would bolster their defensive line. But he will miss
at least the first month of the season because of continuing
problems with a torn knee ligament that had bothered him during
last year's Super Bowl ... New England running back  &UR; Robert Edwards
 &LR; isn't the only No. 1 draft pick limping. So, too, is Miami runner
 &UR; John Avery &LR; . After a fast start, Avery has been hobbled with a
strained hamstring, and head coach  &UR; Jimmy Johnson  &LR; is growing
impatient. Last week Johnson publicly chastised Avery, saying it
was time for people to win jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
