<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-CARROLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARROLL HAD CAMP FIRE BURNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, R.I. _ There is a swagger to him now that was
missing in his first year. Not to the point where he'd give someone
the ``choke'' sign, as he did to Miami kicker Pete Stoyanovich when
he was head coach of the New York Jets during a key 1995 AFC East
clash. That wasn't so much swagger as immaturity. But now there's
no denying that Pete Carroll, as former Red Sox manager Joe Morgan
might put it, is the skipper of this 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to give him the benefit of the doubt on everything he
decided last year because I knew how difficult of a situation he
was getting himself into,'' said Patriots defensive back Ty Law.
``But now it's a year later. He knows his players, and his players
know him. We know how he wants things done, and now the
communication is better than ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll said he has spent a lot of time during training camp
with the receivers and defensive backs because ``those are highly
competitive areas and I've needed to pay attention to those to make
the best evaluation there and really see which guys are ahead of
some others.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the difference between this year's camp and last year's,
Carroll said, ``I was able to work with individual guys more this
year than I was last year. What I mean is, I was pushing them
along, communicating with them about things they were doing, trying
to keep them going, challenging guys on an individual basis.
Because I know them a little more, I also know what they need and
how they need to be treated to motivate them. That's been a much
bigger part of my participation.''
</P>
<P>
   However, as training camp ended Saturday at Bryant College,
Carroll still faced big issues, such as, who will be the starting
running back? Can the offensive line run-block effectively? Who
will start at right cornerback while Tebucky Jones learns the job?
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has three weeks to find the answers in time for the
season opener. His hope is that by then Robert Edwards will have
healed from his groin injury and won the running back job and
veteran Steve Israel will be back on the field.
</P>
<P>
   In assessing camp, Carroll said, ``I was pleased with everything
except the results of the last game (a 28-0 loss to Minnesota last
Sunday). The camp went well. It was taxing. We made it through
relatively healthy. We feel pretty good about where we are right
now. I'd like us to have a nice game Monday and show the progress I
think we've made.''
</P>
<P>
   How does his team compare with last season's at this stage?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're much further along,'' said the coach. ``We got more out
of the work because the players understand what we're doing. They
have a better feel for it. It's certainly been more competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll feels no need to soothe the concerns of media and fans
about the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care to do that,'' he said. ``We just need to keep
working. The fans are only going to gauge us on what happens in the
games and not the whole picture of what we've done in the entire
training camp. The fans are only seeing the first unit in the game
for a little more than a quarter in the first two games. For
Dallas, we're going to test them, in that they're going to have to
play a full half in a high altitude. So, physically, they're going
to be taxed.''
</P>
<P>
   It is clear from Carroll's demeanor at practice that he's in
charge. He's liable to chew out a player in front of fans and the
media, something he might have done only in private a year ago. For
example, when he didn't like Jones's coverage on Terry Glenn one
day, he yelled, ``That's college stuff! That's not the way we do it
here!'' At his press conferences, Carroll isn't afraid to say who's
hot and who's not.
</P>
<P>
   And when an ex-Patriot is quoted making a disparaging comment,
Carroll declines to respond, as if that player never existed. For
example, Sam Gash recently popped off about how much he hated New
England and how his new coach in Buffalo, Wade Phillips, was so
organized in training camp and such a great coach. (Gash probably
didn't look at Phillips's coaching record before making such
statements.) Carroll offered no counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not going to get into that stuff,'' the coach said.
``It does you no good to get involved. Those players are out of our
picture. We might have to play against them, but we'll play them on
the field, not off it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has begun to get more involved in personnel matters. He
has stuck out his neck in expressing a fondness of Jones. He has
told some of his high-priced offensive linemen, such as Todd Rucci,
Max Lane, and Zefross Moss, that their jobs are not protected by
their paychecks and that younger linemen could supplant them.
Despite Shawn Jefferson's fine season a year ago, Carroll has told
Vincent Brisby that he can beat Jefferson out for a job. And the
coach has chosen his words carefully concerning Glenn, praising his
work in camp but going no further, hoping the receiver will make a
personal commitment to being an impact player again.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll has put his faith in new offensive coordinator Ernie
Zampese to run the show on that side of the ball. But Carroll has
been more hands-on with the defensive backfield, which is his area
of expertise. He produced excellent secondaries while working as an
assistant in Minnesota and New York, and if Jones turns out to be
the missing link at right corner, Carroll will have created another
solid group.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's definitely in charge,'' said linebacker Chris Slade.
``He's demanding in that he never wants you to get complacent. We
hear a lot of good things about our defense, with the way it played
at the end last year, but he's been quick to remind us that we
haven't done anything yet this year, and he's right. We have to
prove ourselves all over again. It's a new season.''
</P>
<P>
   The consensus among the players was that it was a tough camp,
with Carroll demanding more from them physically than last year,
when there was more classroom training.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he went at us pretty good,'' said Law. ``Everybody
should be in good shape to start the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Including Carroll.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
