<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSTONCOLLEGE-DEFENSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC'S HOVAN READY FOR HEAVY DUTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Hovan was hard to miss at Boston College's Media Day
Friday afternoon. As he walked around the new artificial turf at
Alumni Stadium, his confident strut was unmistakable. So, too, were
his massive arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks like he's got a pair of small Virginia hams hanging
out his jersey,'' marveled Peter Cronan, BC's radio color analyst.
</P>
<P>
   Page 64 of the BC football media guide will tell you that Hovan
is a 285-pound junior from Rocky River, Ohio, who was an All-Big
East first-teamer last season. But what it doesn't mention is the
10 pounds of muscle he added over the summer. When you take full
measure of Hovan's bulked-up, 6-foot-3-inch, 295-pound physique _
and, of course, those Arm &AMP; Hammer arms _ you get the distinct
impression that no one is going to be kicking sand in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Or running roughshod on BC's defense. Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, the Eagles allowed an average of 200.1 yards per
game, ranging from a season-low of 96 vs. Army to a season-high of
360 vs. Big East foe Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the way Hovan and his defensive teammates hit the
weights over the summer, there is every indication that they intend
to rectify their porous run defense, particularly on the boundary,
where the Eagles appeared so vulnerable last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``You saw how teams ran against us on the boundary last year,''
Hovan said. ``But now we've got some big guys out there. When we
have a guy that's 270 out there. I don't think we're going to have
too many teams running into the boundary that much anymore. I think
we're going to cause a lot of problems for teams that are going to
want to establish the running game.''
</P>
<P>
   As one of eight returning defensive starters, Hovan will be the
strong man at the point of attack from his nose guard spot. Last
season, Hovan registered 58 tackles, including eight for losses of
20 yards, and had four sacks. Certainly, having 10 pounds of added
muscle will help Hovan in the trenches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of size you need to compete at the level we're
going to compete at,'' said coach Tom O'Brien. ``But you need all
22 guys you're going to be playing with to be like that. You can't
just have five or six.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the coaching staff recruited size and speed.
Antonio Garay, a highly touted 6-4, 265-pound defensive lineman
from Rahway, N.J., was one player who caught Hovan's attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got one recruit from New Jersey who looks pretty good,''
Hovan said. ``But I like seeing how new recruits do in camp. It'll
be nice to see what they do. It's a little bit different in high
school when you're going up against kids. When you get up here, and
go against guys like Damien Woody and Doug Brzezinski, it's a
little different story.''
</P>
<P>
   But was it Hovan's goal to come into camp as BC's strongest
player?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I push myself more,'' he said. ``Before the summer
started, I set goals for myself. I'm not competing against
Brzezinski and I'm not competing against Damien Woody or any of the
strong kids on the team. I know what I have to do. It's a
competition between me and trying to get my goals.''
</P>
<P>
   So did he achieve them?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so, but it all goes back to last year when I had a
couple of missed tackles here and there,'' Hovan said. ``When I
trained, it made me want to do that much better to be able to make
that sack or to make that tackle for a loss. That was in the back
of my mind every time I trained.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to be the best D-line in the Big East, and we had
the whole starting lineup here training all summer. This year,
we're not going to be pushed around. They're going to have to run
through us. We are the strength of the defense this year and we
know it, so we're going to have to perform at that level.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
