<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MARIS-REMEMBRANCE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MARIS, RECORD WAS BARELY WORTH THE HASSLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE DONDONEAU 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FARGO, N.D. _ There were no guarantees as to what Bill Weaver
would find in the local sports pages when he was working as a
sportscaster here in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it was a late game you'd maybe get the box score and that's
it,'' Weaver said. ``And back then, you didn't have highlights on
TV or updates on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   What Weaver did have was a Western Union tickertape machine in
the offices of TV station WDAY/Ch. 6. Every time the New York
Yankees would play, Weaver would invite Rudy Maris, father of New
York Yankees slugger Roger Maris, to the station to sit and watch
the tickertape.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd just sit there and wait for the updates,'' Weaver said.
``Tick ... tick ... tick ... HR ... tick ... tick ... tick ... NYY
... tick ... tick ... M ... tick ... A ... tick ... it drove us
crazy waiting to see if the next letter would be an N or an R.''
</P>
<P>
   There were more R's than N's that season, but most baseball fans
hoped for more home runs by Mickey Mantle than Roger Maris.
</P>
<P>
   Not Weaver, however, and not North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   Maris was the state's claim to fame long before the movie
``Fargo'' with its ``yahs'' and ``you betchas.''
</P>
<P>
   In a state where character is shaped by long winter months and
rainy springs, Maris excelled in a sport more or less looked upon
as something to do between football, fishing and hunting seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1961, this seemed to be the one place where everybody was
pulling for more R's than N's on that tickertape. And if the next
letter was indeed an R, Weaver would break into whatever was being
telecast with a Maris update: ``''Former Fargo Shanley High School
star Roger Maris of the New York Yankees has just hit his 52nd home
run off Frank Lary of the Detroit Tigers ...''''
</P>
<P>
   Back to the regularly scheduled programming.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver, 78, smiles when he talks about Maris and his 61 home
runs in 1961. He calls it the most exciting year in sports he's
ever been involved with. And when asked what he thinks of the
assault Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa and Ken Griffey Jr. are waging on
Maris' record, Weaver takes the cigar from his mouth, cracks a wry
smile and taps the ``61 in '61'' moniker on the golf shirt covering
his chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Pat Maris (Roger's widow) a few weeks ago that if they
break this record it's going to break my heart,'' Weaver said.
``But you have to be realistic. It looks like it could happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``And knowing Roger, I think he'd be happy to know if it was
going to fall it would be to someone like McGwire. He respects the
game, he's a good family man, he seems like a good person from
everything I've read about him.'' Was it worth it? Roger Eugene
Maris was born Sept. 10, 1931. He died of lymphoma cancer in
Houston on Dec. 14, 1985. The inscription on the diamond-shaped
headstone at Maris' gravesite in Fargo reads ``Against All Odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris didn't get much support in his record-setting
season. For starters, he wasn't viewed as a true Yankee _ he was
traded to New York in 1959 from Kansas City. Secondly, he was
chasing ``the'' Yankee immortal, Babe Ruth, and nobody, ``nobody''
beats the Babe.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Mickey, his teammate. When Maris and Mantle found
themselves locked in a race for Babe's record, it was Mantle, the
homegrown Yankee, who stole the fans' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who say Roger didn't get along with his teammates, that
they wanted Mickey to break the record and those two didn't get
along, they should have been at Roger's funeral,'' Weaver said. ``I
sat right across from Mickey, and he cried the whole time. The
``whole'' time. They were close.''
</P>
<P>
   And the press? By all accounts Maris never did figure out this
crew. Bill ``Moose'' Skowron, a Yankee teammate in 1961, said the
media put Maris through more hell than he deserved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't leave him alone,'' Skowron said. ``He'd go
0-for-4 and they'd all be around his locker and he'd yell, `Go talk
to Moose or Bobby Richardson, they hit the home runs today!'
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd wish the record was broken today. The damn thing wasn't
worth what he went through.''
</P>
<P>
   There was the time a magazine writer asked Maris if he fooled
around on the road. His wife was home in Kansas City pregnant with
the fourth of their six children, making the question doubly
offensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was anything for a story,'' Skowron said. ``Mick and Roger,
they would sit in the training room to get away from everyone. The
press used to write that they hated each other. They were
roommates! He shouldn't have had to go through all that.''
Keeping it in
</P>
<P>
   Maris probably endured more than most of his hometown friends
imagined, if for no other reason than Maris rarely talked about
baseball away from the diamond.
</P>
<P>
   He was a private man, married to his high-school sweetheart, Pat
Carvell. He paid for some of his Fargo friends to attend his World
Series games. In a perfect world, he would have gone about his
home-run business in relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   He used to call Sid Cichy, his high school football coach, to
talk about hunting and see how his alma mater, Fargo Shanley, was
doing. Rarely, Cichy said, would Maris even mention the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't any one thing that got to Roger,'' Cichy said. ``It
was the same old questions, over and over. Yak-yak-yak. Every town
was like a circus, over and over. They'd ask him questions just to
ask questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different now. the Cardinals helped McGwire set up rules
when the press can talk to him and for how long. Roger never had
any of that with the Yankees. He was pretty much left alone to deal
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cichy's football teams won 15 state titles in 23 seasons.
Ironically, he says one of his worst teams came when Maris played
in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just a natural athlete,'' Cichy said. ``There was a
game against Devils Lake where he returned five kickoffs for
touchdowns. After the game the opposing coach said they were afraid
to score because of him. I thought, `Why not just on-side kick?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger was good. He could have played football at a major
college. Baseball was just something he kept getting better at.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver and Cichy are two of a handful of Maris' friends who've
worked to keep his legacy alive. Every year, they help organize the
Roger Maris Celebrity Golf Tournament played in the last week of
June. Whitey Ford, Whitey Herzog, Mickey Mantle, Skowron, Hank
Bauer, Bob Costas and Bobby Knight are just a few of the
celebrities who have come to Fargo to play golf and help raise more
than $500,000 for cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   You can also visit the Roger Maris Museum, stroll down Maris
Drive near a local ballpark, or visit the Roger Maris Cancer
Center.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's what it will take for people to understand the type
of person Maris really was. Don Gooselaw, Maris' childhood friend,
said the idea for the Maris Museum blossomed when another local,
Jim McLaughlin, wrote to Maris asking for some of his memorabilia
so they could display it in his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   He gave them everything he had that Cooperstown didn't want.
</P>
<P>
   Typical Maris, his friends say.
Changing attitudes
</P>
<P>
   Roger Maris will always be a hero in his hometown, no matter how
many home runs McGwire or Griffey or Sosa hits this season. Outside
North Dakota, however, maybe this year's spotlight on the home run
chase will change some opinions about Maris.
</P>
<P>
   His friends hope so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll always remember going to Yankee Stadium in 1984 to watch
Roger get his number retired,'' Cichy said. ``The old-timers game
was pretty boring, so I walked up the steps at Yankee Stadium to
stretch my legs and I ran across a very tall, dour looking usher.
When I told him I was from Fargo he got this ... look. He started
shaking his head. `Nobody,' he said, `nobody should have ever
broken the Babe's record.' Then he turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really how everyone seemed to feel about Roger back
then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
