</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-FALMOUTH-ROADRACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALMOUTH DRAWS MANY TO THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget the truck rollovers, four-car accidents, and disabled
vehicles that are often sprinkled into the
``traffic-on-the-threes'' report. The three words on the car radio
that will cause drivers to shudder this morning are ``Falmouth Road
Race.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday is the one day a year when traffic on the Sagamore and
Bourne Bridges is even worse than usual, virtually grinding to a
stop as thousands of people flock to the Lower Cape to watch or run
the Harvard Pilgrim Health Care Falmouth Road Race.
</P>
<P>
   In its 26th year, the 7.1-mile race _ barely longer than a
10-kilometer run _ has mushroomed in popularity to the point where
it now attracts 9,000 runners and 75,000 spectators. And stops
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a mini-Boston Marathon,'' said Bill Rodgers. ``It's
tradition, no race can reproduce it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he's biased about the race, having won it three
times. In fact, it was Rodgers's victory in 1974 that put Falmouth
on the international racing calendar.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the race's second year, when this unknown kid named
Will Rodgers _ that's what he was called then _ won the race and
beat Marty Liquori,'' said co-director Rich Sherman. ``That was big
news and got a lot of press.''
</P>
<P>
   The following year, Olympic gold medalist Frank Shorter won, and
the race has been snowballing ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's field includes the defending champions, Khalid
Khannouchi of Morocco and Colleen De Reuck of South Africa, women's
course record-holder Catherine Ndereba of Kenya, three-time Boston
Marathon winner Uta Pippig, six-time women's champion _ and
defending masters champ _ Joan Benoit Samuelson, plus Rodgers and
Shorter, who will be vying for the seniors title (50-and-over).
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the elite runners, you can add the
mother-daughter-granddaughter team, the 17 members of the ``65-Plus
Running Club'' (spearheaded by an 80-year-old), the cancer survivor
and her son, the six runners from Hawaii and three from Alaska, and
you have the mix that makes up Falmouth.
</P>
<P>
   A little, but not much, has changed since the first race.
Results that were compiled by hand for the 90 runners in 1973 are
now done by computer. The Brothers Four bar that was the landmark
at the finish line is gone, but the race still starts from Captain
Kidd's in Woods Hole. And the starting time stubbornly remains at
10 a.m., despite the fact that most summer races begin two hours
earlier because of heat and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have so many people driving in from off Cape, and there are
so many logistics to deal with that we have to,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   When Tommy Leonard, the former bartender at Boston's Eliot
Lounge, came up with the brainstorm for a race 26 years ago, he
approached Carroll, who was the girls' track coach at Falmouth
High, and Sherman, who was the town's recreation director.
</P>
<P>
   Like kids planning a play, the three thought about it, looked at
each other, and said, ``Let's put on a race!''
</P>
<P>
   So they did, and on a Wednesday afternoon in August, in
near-hurricane weather _ high winds and driving rain _ 90 runners
made the dash from one bar in Woods Hole to another one in Falmouth
Heights. The Falmouth Road Race was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way it was then, we could have done it in a week,'' said
Carroll. Now he and Sherman, along with their wives, co-directors
Lucia Carroll and Kathleen Sherman, will barely take a breath
before they start thinking about next year's race.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 16,000 entries start going out on May 1 and start
coming back almost immediately; the first 8,000 are accepted on a
first-come, first-return basis. The directors do give some extra
consideration to Falmouth residents and they look over late entries
asking for special attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they're valid, and sometimes not,'' Carroll said.
``If we could accept everybody, we'd have 25,000.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those who got a special waiver this year is Joyce Supple,
of Hampton Falls, N.H. Supple, 68, didn't start running until she
was 47 years old, when she trained for the Marine Corps Marathon,
then entered the Boston Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Supple hasn't run any marathons since 1979, but she still runs 6
miles five times a week ``just to keep in shape.'' So when her
46-year-old daughter, Robin, and 22-year-old granddaughter, Kelsa,
entered Falmouth, Supple wrote to the directors to let her in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I could do pretty good in my age bracket,'' her letter
said in part. ``PLEASE let me run.''
</P>
<P>
   They did, so the three generations can run side by side.
</P>
<P>
   Another family affair involves 51-year-old Jim Kelley, of
Wakefield, R.I., and his 24-year-old daughter Beth, of Washington,
D.C. It'll be his 20th Falmouth race, her 16th.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman and Carroll sound upbeat about this ``job,'' despite the
fact that they've been devoting 18 hours a day to it for the past
week, and that they'll get up at 5 a.m. Sunday to get ready to face
the throngs.
</P>
<P>
   But they do have real jobs to go back to, Sherman as an
insurance agent and Carroll as an English teacher and track coach.
Carroll allows that the race eventually will take its toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm `50-ish,''' he said, ``but I'm not going to get another 26
years out of this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 2025EDT &QL; 
