<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-LIBERTY-COMETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY BEATS HOUSTON, 70-54  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ED GUZMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Liberty point guard Teresa Weatherspoon left
Saturday afternoon's home game against the Houston Comets with 1
minute 34 seconds to go, she pumped her fist in the air. It was a
celebration not only of the Liberty's victory, but also an
acknowledgment of the first Liberty sell-out crowd of 19,563 _ the
third-largest in Women's National Basketball Association history _
at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Weatherspoon's gesture punctuated what had been a remarkable
performance by the Liberty as they jumped all over Houston (15-3),
routing the defending WNBA champions, 70-54.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty (18-10) outrebounded Houston by 41-25, holding the
Comets to only 30 percent shooting from the field, including 5 of
19 from behind the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty guard Sophia Witherspoon scored a game-high 21 points to
lead four Liberty players in double figures. Houston guard Cynthia
Cooper finished with 17 points to lead the Comets.
</P>
<P>
   The victory keeps the Liberty in first place in the Eastern
Conference with the Cleveland Rockers, who played the Washington
Mystics Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   If the Liberty beats Cleveland at home Monday night, it will
clinch a playoff spot regardless of what other teams do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team was just very determined,'' Liberty Coach Nancy
Darsch said. ``We just said nobody was taking this away from us
right now. This was our game.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game was about more than staying in the WNBA playoff
race.
</P>
<P>
   It was also about finding out if the Liberty, with the end of
the regular season near, could play with Houston, a team that
Darsch says is in a class by itself.
</P>
<P>
   From the moment Liberty forward Vickie Johnson opened the game
with a 3-pointer from the right side, there was no backing down.
The Liberty was not about to have a repeat of last month's debacle,
when it fell behind by 13-0 and 40-12, losing the game by 79-54. In
fact, the lead only grew, as Johnson came back with another
3-pointer to give the Liberty a 21-9 lead with 12:33 to go in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   But this was Houston, a team that features Cooper, Sheryl
Swoopes and Tina Thompson, three of the best offensive players in
the WNBA. A Houston run seemed inevitable, especially when Swoopes
nailed a long 3-pointer from the top of the key with 3:32 in the
half that closed the Liberty's lead to 6 at 31-25. They drew no
closer, however, as the Liberty took a 35-27 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Houston desperately tried to claw back into the game early in
the second half when Weatherspoon drove hard on forward Janeth
Arcain and was called for an offensive foul with 11:07 to go in the
game. Weatherspoon protested, and she promptly drew a technical
foul. This sparked a brief Houston run that was capped by a Cooper
3-pointer. It was 50-42 with 9:46 to go, and Houston seemed to be
threatening.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Lobo, who had 13 points and 12 rebounds for the Liberty,
said: ``I said to Weatherspoon when we were shooting around before
the game that last time we played Houston, our team had a different
look about them. I sensed that our team couldn't wait to get out
there and play and show our fans the difference in this team.''
</P>
<P>
   A little more than five minutes later, Johnson found herself
behind the 3-point line on the left side with the ball in her
hands. The Liberty was ahead by 59-46 and a 3-pointer would dash
Houston's comeback hopes. Her shot swished through the basket with
4:13 left, bringing the crowd to its feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into the game wanting to play good basketball and
wanting to win,'' Weatherspoon said. ``Now we have to move on to
the next game _ be happy for what we did today but leave it here
and prepare for the next game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
