<SLUG> BC-FBN-MEXICO-AMERICANFOOTBALL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICAN FOOTBALL A WINNER IN MEXICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Diego Perez, a lanky and slightly cocky
17-year-old quarterback, wears a faded New England Patriots cap and
calls himself ``the Mexican Bledsoe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivan de la Fuente Rodriguez, 12, another quarterback, dreams of
one day playing for a professional team, just like his idol, Dan
Marino.
</P>
<P>
   And 11-year-old Jose Antonio Ramirez, an offensive guard who
looks like a big lime in his bright green uniform when he squats
for a block, wants to be good enough to earn a college scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   In a country better known for its love of soccer and loyalty to
baseball, these are the dreams of a growing number of Mexican boys:
to play American-style football. It's one sign of the surge in
popularity the sport is enjoying south of the border, according to
sports promoters in both Mexico and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Another sign will be visible Monday night, when the Patriots
face the Dallas Cowboys in an exhibition game at Azteca Stadium
here that will be broadcast internationally and is expected to draw
the largest crowd ever to see an NFL game. The previous record of
112,000 was set here four years ago for an exhibition game between
the Cowboys and Houston Oilers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interest in football is all over the country,'' said
Miguel Angel Mesa, director of Mexico's National Sports Commission,
a federal government agency that oversees most of the country's
amateur and professional sports leagues. ``And the growth is
especially strong among our youth.''
</P>
<P>
   The interest in American football has grown so much in recent
years that last week the NFL announced it will open an office in
Mexico City this fall. The one-person operation will work mostly on
licensing and promotion but will also develop new flag-football
leagues throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is the largest population of new football fans in the
world,'' said Pete Abitante, a league spokesman. ``You can't find
anyplace outside the US where there is so much enthusiasm for
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, according to Mexican government estimates, there are more
than 20 football associations that field about 4,000 teams for
almost 150,000 players, most of them between ages 5 to 19. And
about one-third of the $260 million the NFL earns in international
merchandising every year comes from Mexico, according to league
figures.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt television and radio have had much to do with the
sport's rising popularity. On any weekend in Mexico during football
season, an armchair quarterback can watch as many as a dozen
telecasts, including local college games, the NCAA, and NFL. More
NFL franchises are also broadcasting their games here on
Spanish-language radio.
</P>
<P>
   The marketing efforts by the NFL to tap a larger audience are
similar to those recently developed by both Major League Baseball
and the National Basketball Association to cultivate larger
audiences in Mexico, where all three leagues have played either
exhibition or regular-season games during the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Played for decades
</P>
<P>
   Football is not new to Mexico. From Chihuahua to Chiapas, the
sport has been played on dirt playgrounds, streets, and old soccer
fields for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Constantine, a Yale graduate and US businessman,
organized the country's first formal team in 1927 at the National
Autonomous University, a public institution in Mexico City. A few
years later, an American priest, Fr. Lambert J. Dennis, organized
another team at Politechnic Institute, a crosstown private
university. Every November, both teams play ``El Clasico,'' the
country's most storied college football rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s, another annual football matchup was created _ the
Aztec Bowl, featuring All-American college players from the US and
a team from Mexico, and the games were played in a new field _
known today as Olympic Stadium _ in the southern part of Mexico
City.
</P>
<P>
   The country has flirted with professional football but has never
formed its own league or managed to land a coveted NFL franchise.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL played its first game here in 1978, between the
Philadelphia Eagles and New Orleans Saints at Olympic Stadium.
During the 1980s, a semi-pro league made up mostly of
post-collegiate players was formed, Mesa said, but the effort
failed to attract enough corporate sponsorship. The players, who
were paid roughly $100 per game, left the league.
</P>
<P>
   But football supporters here say the climate today is much
different for cultivating a professional team or even another
league. The growth of multinational corporations looking for
cross-border promotion and more flexible labor laws as a result of
the North American Free Trade Agreement signed earlier this decade
would make such an investment more possible, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, we can play football all year long _ that is a very
attractive factor,'' said Enrique Estanol, a spokesman for the
country's American Football Federation.
</P>
<P>
   Football's image has also changed in the eyes of many Mexicans.
Though the game once was seen as a graceless and brutal sport that
lacked the finesse of soccer or the strategy of baseball, coaches,
supporters, and even the players themselves now use terms like
``discipline,'' ``teamwork,'' and ``character building'' when
describing the virtues of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it's an aggressive sport, but it's aggression only for
that play and for that moment,'' said Saul Shmulkovsky, 29, the
coordinator of a youth league in the Coyoacan neighborhood of the
city. ``These players are taught to leave it on the field and not
take those feelings on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Same colors, strict rules
</P>
<P>
   Youth football leagues are among the most organized and
structured sports activities in Mexico, Mesa said, even when
compared with some of the older soccer and baseball leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The rules are strict. The self-congratulatory dancing and
showboating done by professionals and some college players is
forbidden in the youth leagues. Some teams even prohibit players
from giving high-fives to each other.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the other youth teams in Mexico, Shmulkovsky's
team, ``Los Huracanes,'' (the Hurricanes), adopts mascots and team
colors identical to many US teams. The Hurricanes, for example,
wear the same neon green and orange uniforms used by the University
of Miami Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   For most Mexicans, the favorite NFL team is the Cowboys, who
have developed a fan base partly out of geographic proximity but
also because of their pioneering efforts in the 1970s to market
heavily to Hispanic and Mexican audiences. Today a teenager is just
as likely to be wearing an Emmitt Smith or Deion Sanders jersey as
one for Cruz Azul, Toluca, or any other Mexican soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   Other favorite NFL teams mentioned often by fans here are the
San Francisco 49ers, the Pittsburgh Steelers, the Miami Dolphins,
and the Oakland Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the Buffalo Bills the best,'' said Ramirez, an
11-year-old guard for the Hurricanes. Although he couldn't name a
single Bills player, he was certain of his reason why.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played in the first Super Bowl I ever saw on
television,'' he added. ``And they've been my favorite team ever
since.''
</P>
<P>
   An NFL dream
</P>
<P>
   Mexican sports promoters and government officials hope that one
day soon the NFL will approve a franchise in Mexico City. But
league officials aren't offering any immediate signs that will
happen. Mexico City applied during the last expansion round but
lost to Jacksonville and Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the city's continuing battles with an unstable
economy and rising crime have undermined its image for tourism and
investment. In interviews published in Mexican newspapers late last
week, players and coaches from the Cowboys and Patriots sounded
less than enthusiastic about playing here.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexican football fans keep dreaming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having a team here would be something of a risk, but I think
it would be an excellent idea and very popular,'' said Mesa, the
government sports commission official. ``It would have to be an
American team with a Mexican point of view, like the name or the
colors or the coaches. It must be distinctly Mexican.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 2026EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
