<HEADER>
A5660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TYSON-BO     08-15 1800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON DUCKS A PUNCH IN NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the pressure on and his chances growing bleaker by the
minute, Mike Tyson stayed true to form this past week. He quit
rather than fight.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the strong possibility of a second straight defeat to
boxing authorities, Tyson did the same thing before the New Jersey
State Athletic Control Board that he did when facing Evander
Holyfield in their tawdry rematch 14 months ago. He disqualified
himself.
</P>
<P>
   At least the members of the licensing body in New Jersey left
with their ears intact, which is more than Holyfield could say.
Only days after that sorry disqualification caused a near-riot in
the MGM Grand Casino, Tyson's license to box was revoked in Nevada
and he has not fought since.
</P>
<P>
   When he was eligible to reapply on July 9, Tyson ignored the
state that had penalized him and instead asked New Jersey to grant
him a license with a promise to bring his lucrative first bout to
Atlantic City. That was like committing a bank robbery in
Massachusetts and asking for a parole hearing in California, but
Tyson and his chief adviser, Shelly Finkel, concluded that
everybody is as callous and money-hungry as they are and the board
would roll over for the bribe Finkel guaranteed New Jersey's tax
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   But they didn't roll over. Faced with a fight, Tyson pulled out
Thursday afternoon and asked for a hearing in Nevada, which will be
granted within three weeks. That action came less than 24 hours
before Tyson was to have learned his fate, although several sources
said Friday that the media and political pressure on the board's
two voting members had grown so intense that the former heavyweight
champion was tipped off that it was unlikely he would gain
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, it appeared the skids had been well greased for
Tyson's return, but media pressure began to build after New Jersey
agreed to grant Tyson a hearing on his application by citing a
legal loophole that allowed the state to ignore Nevada's ruling
because it had revoked, not suspended, his license.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism escalated when Tyson appeared to lose his cool
during the July 29 hearing, cursing to his lawyer when questioned
again by a New Jersey assistant state attorney about his actions in
the Holyfield fight. That led New Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman to
privately make clear how closely she would be watching the vote of
the two appointed board members.
</P>
<P>
   Then New Jersey State Sen. William Gormley came out heavily
against granting Tyson a license, saying the fighter should return
to Nevada before seeking to fight in another state. The fact that
Gormley is the brother of one of the two men who would have voted
on Tyson's application only heightened the glare.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, US Sen. John McCain, a strong friend of boxing who is
seeking federal regulation of the sport, blasted the idea of Tyson
seeking a license anywhere but the state in which he had been
disciplined, saying, ``I don't believe Tyson should be licensed. I
think he should go back to Nevada and ask for a hearing and ask for
his license to be restored there.''
</P>
<P>
   That is precisely what Tyson did Thursday afternoon, a move his
lawyer claimed was a shock but one that others said was a product
of learning that the scam he was trying to run in New Jersey was
about to come to an ignominious end.
</P>
<P>
   In typical fashion, huckster Jeff Wald, another Tyson adviser,
told The New York Times Thursday that ``Sen. John McCain has been a
real friend of boxing in Washington. He came out this week and said
he was dismayed that Mike Tyson was going around the law he had
written. We have enough respect for Sen. McCain not to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's law requires that all states honor suspensions against
fighters made in other states, but since Nevada had revoked Tyson's
license, his attorneys found a legal loophole and tried to exploit
it. Apparently nobody told them about all the respect Wald, Finkel,
and Tyson have for Sen. McCain's law. My guess is nobody mentioned
it to Tyson, either.
</P>
<P>
   Gormley, Whitman, and McCain all said they were elated by
Tyson's ``decision'' and Whitman denied that Tyson had been leaked
information that he would not be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased Mr. Tyson has decided to bring his request for
reinstatement back to the Nevada State Athletic Commission,''
McCain said. ``This is where the decision properly rests.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Ratner, executive director of the Nevada Commission, said
it would take two to three weeks to get a hearing set up and that
he wanted the full five-person board on hand to hear the case.
Unlike New Jersey, Nevada will vote on Tyson's application the same
day as the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, assumes that Tyson doesn't pull out of that
fight _ or bite off a commissioner's ear _ if it gets tough.
</P>
<P>
   When told of Tyson's decision, the man who disqualified him
against Holyfield, Mills Lane, said the former champion had done
the right thing by going back to the scene of the crime and now
would ``face the music. They'll make him answer some tough
questions. He's going to have to stand there and take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The question is, can he?
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Chances of an  &UR; Ike Quartey &LR; - &UR; Felix Trinidad  &LR; fight in November
continued to fade, even though no decision has been made by federal
judge  &UR; Lawrence McKenna  &LR; on the validity of a new promotional
contract signed by Trinidad with Quartey's promoter,  &UR; Dino Duva &LR; .
That's because Quartey is claiming he has contracted malaria and
will be unable to fight  &UR; Andrei Pestriaev  &LR; this month in France.
Quartey, the story goes, was the subject of death threats during a
visit to France for a press conference announcing the fight and is
reluctant to return. That's the World Boxing Association
welterweight champion's story, at least. Others believe the malaria
story is merely his latest shot in an ongoing dispute with his
former promoters, the Acaries brothers. The French-based promoters
are suing Quartey to retain control of his contract and many in
boxing believe Quartey's claim of malaria is merely a way to avoid
putting his title at risk in a country where his enemies have a
good deal of power to manipulate fight officials ... Although
attorneys for the Duvas publicly remained optimistic about their
chances in the Trinidad contract dispute with rival promoter  &UR; Don
King &LR; , &UR;  &LR; privately they have told associates their chances are no
better than 50-50 because Trinidad signed a bout agreement for a
fight with  &UR; Troy Waters  &LR; that included a clause extending his
promotional contract with King. When Trinidad produced that bout
agreement only days before the one-day trial was to begin _ after
having assured Duva he had turned over all of his paperwork
involving King _ Duva's longtime attorney  &UR; Pat English  &LR; allegedly
went ballistic. English still believes King has breached the
contract but he also knows the existence of a new agreement between
Trinidad and King is a major legal obstacle ... At a press
conference last week in Atlanta to announce the  &UR; Evander
Holyfield &LR; - &UR; Vaughn Bean  &LR; International Boxing Federation
heavyweight title fight at the Georgia Dome, King looked down at
the soft-spoken Bean and said of his chances, ``He's going to be
charging and trying to hit the lottery. Powerball! Now you know the
number is my game. Now they line up for Powerball but when I was
doing it they were trying to put you in jail for it.'' King is an
old numbers runner from Cleveland ... Holyfield stands to make at
least $3.5 million for the Bean fight, while the IBF's No. 1
contender will receive just under $2 million. That is nearly a
million less than Bean could have earned fighting Tyson ... Aware
that Bean brings little to the table beyond a No. 1 ranking few
people can understand, King has priced the 42,000-seat Georgia Dome
to sell. More than 25,000 of the seats will go for $50, $35, or
$25, unheard of prices for a heavyweight title fight. The hope is
that local corporations will buy blocks of cheap seats and give
them to charities and youth groups to paper the house with faces
... Heavyweight prospect  &UR; Kirk Johnson  &LR; improved to 26-0 by easily
handling trial horse  &UR; Levi Billups  &LR; at the Cour D'Alene Tribal
Bingo Hall in Worley, Idaho, recently ... A big shakeup is rumored
to be in the works at ESPN, with longtime fight manager  &UR; Bill
Cayton  &LR; moving in as a consultant and possibly veteran Philadelphia
fight promoter  &UR; J. Russell Peltz  &LR; taking over as matchmaker. Where
this would leave  &UR; Bob Yalen &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has been running ESPN's boxing
shows for some time, is unclear. ESPN recently purchased the rights
to Cayton's vast library of fight films, which is believed to be
the largest in the world, to use on its Classic Sports Network. It
made that move to block a similar plan by Fox, which was close to a
deal with Cayton. Reportedly, part of the ESPN deal is for Cayton
to serve as a consultant. Cayton has been advocating a shakeup in
the network's lineup of broadcasters as well as bringing in Peltz
... Speaking of televised boxing, as USA Network's final show
approaches on Aug. 25, word is TNT will televise not only a
September fight card but also one in December or January while
ESPN2 continues plans for a 40-show series with a new format that
would mix a live fight with a classic one from Cayton's library.
The latter is an idea that could sell ...  &UR; Andrew Golota's  &LR; Sept. 4
fight in Poland vs.  &UR; Tim Witherspoon  &LR; has been postponed until Oct.
2 because of the cut Golota sustained in his win over  &UR; Corey
Sanders &LR;  ... Former heavyweight champion  &UR; Michael Moorer  &LR; is
involved in one of the most dangerous endeavors imaginable for a
guy with his problems. He's in cooking school ... Old friend  &UR; Doug
Pendarvis  &LR; is back in the boxing business with a show set for
Saturday night at the Wallace Civic Center in Fitchburg that
features fast-rising  &UR; Jason Pires &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the undefeated New Bedford
junior featherweight, who will make his first step into the big
time against  &UR; Shawn Powell  &LR; in a 12-round fight for the vacant US
Boxing Association junior featherweight title. Pires (11-0, 7 KOs)
is being handled by  &UR; Jim Troy  &LR; and promoter  &UR; Cedric Kushner  &LR; and
has shown enough promise to be considered possibly the next
world-class New England fighter. A win Saturday night would assure
him of a world rating after just 12 professional fights. The
undercard will feature another Troy fighter of promise, Atlanta
mid-dleweight  &UR; Lawrence Chapman  &LR; (10-0, 8 KOs), a member of a
boxing team sponsored by Holyfield. The  &UR; Sims  &LR; twins,  &UR; Trave  &LR; (5-0)
and  &UR; Travis  &LR; (3-0) of Norwalk, Conn., are also on the card. Tickets
are $30 ringside, $20 general admission. For info, call
978-345-7300, ext. 615, or 617-825-3283.
</P>
</TEXT>
