<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5661 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-BOSTONCUP-WTA-BOS     08-15 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-BOSTONCUP-WTA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP FINAL DOUBLY CHARMED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY _ She's been to a shopping mall or two along Route 9
(``Shopping, that's what I really enjoy to do''), feasted at the
Cheesecake Factory, tapped into the Young Ladies Network about how
to play an opponent unknown to her, and even showed up a few hours
early to scout her possible opponent if she made it into the final.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Schett made it to the Boston Cup final, all right,
beating Cara Black, 6-2, 2-6, 6-2, Saturday at Babson College.
</P>
<P>
   And Schett, bubbly and bright, is excited that she's in her
first final on the WTA circuit. ``It would be fantastic,'' she
said, ``to win my first tournament on the hardcourt.''
</P>
<P>
   Schett, a 22-year-old Austrian, was aided in the semifinal by
tips from Elena Likhovtseva, who had lost to Black in a
quarterfinal Friday night. ``Elena told me she'd had so many
chances, that she was up in every game against (Black), and she
told me I just had to play aggressive,'' said Schett, who never had
played Black. ``Elena told me Black was not playing very fast, and
she was right, I would say. And Elena told me (Black's) forehand
was a little weak. Elena gave me good tips.''
</P>
<P>
   A confident Schett used those tips to easily dispose of Black, a
19-year-old from Zimbabwe, mixing her serves, smashing her overhand
shots, and deftly slipping her backhands an inch or two inside the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's 2 p.m. final, Schett will meet Mariaan de Swardt,
who defeated third-seeded Lisa Raymond, 4-6, 6-4, 7-5, in the other
semifinal. The powerful de Swardt happily acknowledges that she
``runs around'' her backhand _ a no-no even on the public courts _
because her forehand is so strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her whole game is basically to set up her forehand,'' Raymond
said of de Swardt. ``That's her entire game, really ... her
forehand.''
</P>
<P>
   Absolutely, agreed de Swardt, who was ranked 50th in the world
coming into the Boston Cup. ``I know the other players are always
coming after my backhand,'' she said. ``One of my biggest goals is
to run around my backhands and hit forehands, my strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Schett, ``Mariaan is playing very well and I'm going to
expect a couple of aces (Sunday) from her ... like, 30 or 40. My
strategy, I think, will be to make her run.''
</P>
<P>
   Schett had Black constantly on the run Saturday, Schett in full
control of her shots and the pace of play most suitable to her.
``For me, it's always nice that someone doesn't play very fast,''
said Schett, the 29th-ranked woman in the world, ``because I have
the time and I can set the point. That's what I like.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though she won the first set easily, Schett lost her focus
in the second game of the second set, when she thought three calls
went against her. What was so difficult about the calls, explained
Schett, ``is that you can't do anything about them. Clay court, you
can go and show the mark, but on hardcourt, you just have to accept
it. But it's so hard to accept it.''
</P>
<P>
   After what she considered ``really bad calls against me,''
Schett said she wasn't able to concentrate. ``My head wasn't on the
court any more,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schett said she didn't regain her composure until three games
later _ ``at love-4, I started to play again and I told myself,
`Well, now this is your chance again; you start again''' _ but by
then the second set was beyond recall. So her strategy was to
position herself so that she would be on serve to open the third
set. ``That was very big for her,'' said Black, ``to start with the
serve.'' Schett did so, and coasted home.
</P>
<P>
   Black, for her part, was thinking at the start of that third set
how she had come back the previous night and won the third after
starting poorly. ``I was trying to repeat that,'' she said. ``But
when things didn't work well (such as Schett breaking her serve in
the second game), I started getting nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   Schett's only worry in that final set came when two birds
perched on the net while she was serving in the fifth game (``I
didn't want to kill a bird''). Best of all, she said, ``I felt very
comfortable out there. I was pretty sure I'd win the match.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   ``I will try very hard,'' said the Austrian. ``I will fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
