<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-SPONSORSHIP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAMING SHAMELESS UNOFFICIAL SPONSORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Olympic Committee is using a new weapon in its fight
against ``ambush marketers'' who try to wrap themselves with the
Olympic rings without paying sponsorship fees: public shame.
</P>
<P>
   The USOC plans to name violators and list their phone numbers in
print ads that ask readers: ``How do you feel about cheating in the
Olympic Games?''
</P>
<P>
   The latest tiff involves Utah's Wasatch Brewery, which is
billing itself ``the unofficial beer, 2002 Winter Games.'' Since
Anheuser-Busch is paying $50 million for the right to be the
official beer, the USOC has gone to war.
</P>
<P>
   Wasatch says it's doing nothing wrong, since it isn't using the
word ``Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has claim on 2002,'' says brewery owner Greg Schirf,
``and everyone uses the word `games.'''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Michelle Smith's  &LR; four-year ban for dumping whiskey in her
urine sample, which keeps her out of the 2000 Olympics and 2001
World Championships, is essentially a life sentence. By the 2004
Games, Smith will be 34, a grandma in swimming terms. Meanwhile her
rivals, who always suspected the Irish swimmer was doped, are
cackling. ``What goes around comes around,'' says  &UR; Cristina
Teuscher &LR; , &UR;  &LR; whom Smith beat in the 400 freestyle in Atlanta.
Smith's disgrace isn't even the worst scandal for Irish swimming. A
recent government report concluded that two former national coaches
(one of whom is serving a 12-year prison sentence) sexually abused
teenage swimmers for years, and it has recommended nearly 100
reforms ... Though US swimmer  &UR; Gary Hall  &LR; ducked a possible
two-year ban for marijuana use last week when the international
federation lifted its provisional suspension, he'll essentially be
on the sidelines for a year anyway. Because the ban was lifted
after the deadline for last week's US championships, Hall couldn't
qualify for four international meets next year, including the Pan
American Games and the Pan Pacific meet, which will be held in
Sydney's Olympic pool. Hall, who tested positive for marijuana for
the second time in a May meet, had argued that his first test (at
the 1996 Olympics) shouldn't count because the drug wasn't
officially on the banned list until after the Games.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Unless the NBA players want to play in Guadalajara in July to
qualify for the 2000 Olympics, the US may want to stick with the
plucky band of CBAers, European pros, and collegians that managed a
bronze medal last weekend at the World Championships in Athens.
Though the Yanks have never failed to qualify for the Games, the
zonal qualifier won't be a gimme: Only the top two teams make it to
Sydney. The Olympic field will also include world champion
Yugoslavia (i.e. Greater Serbia), host Australia, five teams from
Europe, and one apiece from Africa, Asia, and Oceania. The
Americans are automatic for the next world event in 2002, though,
since Indianapolis is host. The US women, who beat Russia for the
world title in June, have qualified for both the Olympics and
worlds ... As predicted after the fiasco in Nagano, the
International Skating Union has shaken up ice dancing to make it
closer to an actual sport. Starting next season, difficult elements
such as lifts, pirouettes, and step sequences will be required in
the free dance, judges will make specific deductions for mistakes
both there and in the original dance, and the technical mark will
break ties in the compulsories. Also, to reduce the chance that
judges play Let's Make a Deal before the competition, a new panel
will judge each stage.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Whoever ends up coaching the US men's national soccer team may
also coach the 2000 Olympic team, which will likely provide the
bulk of the players for the 2002 World Cup squad. That could give
an edge to D.C. United coach  &UR; Bruce Arena &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who directed the
Olympic (i.e. under-23) team two years ago in Atlanta and
reportedly is one of two finalists for the national job ...  &UR; Blaine
Wilson  &LR; will try to become the first man since  &UR; Kurt Thomas  &LR; in
1978 to win three straight US gymnastics titles in Indianapolis
this week. Top rivals will be four-time champ  &UR; John Roethlisberger
 &LR; and  &UR; Chainey Umphrey &LR; , &UR;  &LR; both Olympians, and 18-year-old  &UR; Jason
Gatson &LR; . Defending women's champion  &UR; Vanessa Atler  &LR; will be
challenged by  &UR; Kristen Maloney  &LR; and Olympians  &UR; Dominique
Moceanu &LR; , &UR; Dominique Dawes &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Kim Zmeskal &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who hasn't
competed in a major meet since the 1992 Barcelona Games ... Newest
inductees for the US Gymnastics Hall of Fame include the
Magnificent Seven (the 1996 Olympic women's champions),  &UR; Tim
Daggett  &LR; and  &UR; Mitch Gaylord  &LR; from the 1984 men's gold-medal team,
and  &UR; Julianne McNamara Ziele  &LR; and  &UR; Tracee Talavera  &LR; from the 1984
women's silver-medal team ... If the Goodwill Games add a winter
version for 2000, odds are the event will be held in Lake Placid,
which hasn't hosted anything that large since the 1980 Olympics.
Though the Adirondack hamlet has the skiing and skating facilities,
it needs a new bobsled/luge run, which it hopes the state will pay
for ... US Speedskating, which has lived on meager sponsorship
rations for years despite winning more Olympic medals than any
other winter sport, has hit the jackpot with Nike, which will
provide everything from skates to goggles plus cash through 2002.
The hook for Nike is the untapped crossover market with in-line
skating, which now provides most of the team's new talent ...
Though US boxers now have to compete in a regional qualifier for
the right to send a full Olympic team to Sydney (since the IOC is
limiting entries), at least they can count on home cookin'. Uncle
Sam will be hosting the tournament ... Final trials to pick the US
team for next month's world rowing championships in Cologne are
being held this weekend in Princeton. Up for grabs are the men's
coxed pair and four, lightweight pair and quad, and the women's
pair, lightweight pair, and lightweight quad. Boats from the US
national training centers are heavy favorites in every case ...
Slim pickings _ a silver medal by the men's coxed four _ for the US
in last weekend's world junior rowing championships in Austria. The
eights, both of which made the podium last year, ended up fourth
(men) and fifth (women, with Newton's  &UR; Liz Nelson  &LR; aboard) ... No
more free cyberlunch for the Lords of the Rings. IBM, which spent
more than $100 million on the Nagano Games and provided tech
services gratis, is calling it quits after Sydney because the IOC
wanted to up the ante for 2002 and beyond. That means that the Salt
Lake City organizers may have to cut deals with several providers.
</P>
</TEXT>
