<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEAMBOAT ARABIA MUSEUM AN INCREDIBLE EXAMPLE OF SMALL-BUSINESS
SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The 1 millionth visitor to the Steamboat
Arabia Museum didn't elicit much media attention last month, but it
was an impressive milestone in the short history of one of Kansas
City's most incredible small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The millionth was a member of an Oklahoma family, mom and dad
and three children, but it wasn't as though 1 million different
people have toured the frontier shrine.
</P>
<P>
   That's how many tour tickets the Arabia has sold since its
opening in the City Market complex in November 1991. As for how
many individuals have been through the turnstile, it's hard to say
because Arabia has created so many superfans.
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Ebert, for instance, has visited the Arabia 20 times, as
far as she can remember and the museum's guest book can determine.
Her love affair began one Sunday afternoon shortly after the Arabia
opened and her late husband was engrossed in pro football on the
tube.
</P>
<P>
   Her first look at the Arabia's collection of artifacts left her
``awestruck,'' she said, and ``the more I saw, the more enthralled
I became.'' Since then, a trip to the Arabia is usually high on the
to-do list when entertaining visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Obermann, who has been to Arabia eight times, says it gives
him a tremendous sense of pride in being able to show visitors how
``people in our community have been able to put something like this
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think about everything Kansas City has to offer _ and
there's a lot _ the museum is one of the crown jewels,'' Obermann
says.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-towners find the Arabia on their own, too. While
interviewing members of the Arabia's founding family recently in
the museum's food court, a family from Buffalo, N.Y., came by the
table. Their enthusiasm palpable, they wanted to thank to those who
``put it together.''
</P>
<P>
   The museum's history is well known by now. The Hawley family of
Independence got interested in salvaging a steamboat that foundered
in 1856 while plying the Missouri River near Kansas City. Family
and friends spent the winter of 1988-89 going 50 feet into a farm
field that was once river channel to dig out the Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo trove is said to be the greatest aggregation of
frontier-era artifacts ever brought together in one place. What
began as an adventure has long since been transformed into highly
successful business as well as a leading Kansas City tourist
attraction.
</P>
<P>
   The spirit of adventure hasn't died, though. Father Bob Hawley
and sons Dave and Greg still talk seriously of going into the earth
again to retrieve another 19th century steamboat. Unlike the
Arabia, core samples indicate the one they've got their eye on
still has a mostly salvageable upper structure.
</P>
<P>
   That's down the road, if ever, though. In the here and now, they
build on their museum's growing popularity. They not only have a
website, but also are participating in Internet history-teaching
initiatives focusing on frontier America.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most amazing thing about this business is that
despite its ardent embrace by its tens of thousands of local fans,
that enthusiasm hasn't translated into any business community
recognition worth mentioning.
</P>
<P>
   It has never, for instance, been so much as a contender for the
annual Small Business of the Year award. Given the Arabia's immense
hometown popularity and track record as a leading Kansas City
enterprise, this is curious indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, well, maybe next year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
