<SLUG> BC-RAC-PACIFIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE HOUSE COMES OF AGE, BEATING A TOP FIELD IN PACIFIC  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JAY PRIVMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ Free House was the overlooked horse in last
year's Triple Crown races, when the glory belonged to Silver Charm
and Touch Gold. But Saturday at Del Mar Race Track, Free House
proved that he had grown up from a good 3-year-old to a sensational
4-year-old. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Making his second start of the year, and facing a top group of
older horses _ including Touch Gold, last year's winner of the
Belmont Stakes _ Free House ran away to an authoritative,
four-length victory in the &QC; $1million Pacific Classic, the
championship race of the meet here. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen, last year's winner of this race, tried to match
strides with Free House on the final turn but proved no match for
him in the stretch and had to settle for second. Pacificbounty
rallied for third.
</P>
<P>
   Touch Gold, sent off as the 3-2 second choice, never fired and
finished fifth. Puerto Madero, who was coupled in the wagering with
Gentlemen, was sixth. The entry, trained by Richard Mandella, was
sent off as the favorite at 6-5. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm missed the race because he is still recovering from
his poor last-place finish in the San Diego Handicap three weeks
ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free House was timed in 2:00 1/5 for a mile and one quarter on
the fast main track. He paid $9 for a $2 wager to win and earned
$600,000 for his owners, Trudy McCaffery and John Toffan. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The victory was seen by McCaffery and Free House's trainer, Paco
Gonzalez, as vindication for their colt, who has been under a cloud
of suspicion since a victory in last month's Bel Air Handicap at
Hollywood Park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to the California Horse Racing Board's official
testing laboratory, Truesdail Laboratories of Tustin, Calif., Free
House tested positive for the prohibited bronchodilator Clenbuterol
after the Bel Air. Clenbuterol is approved for training, but not
for competition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under state rules, however, a horse must have a positive test
for a prohibited drug confirmed by a second, independent lab. That
second test has yet to be conducted. Gonzalez, who has a clean
reputation, maintains that he has never given the drug to Free
House. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This makes up for all we've been through the past few weeks,''
McCaffery said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free House got a perfect trip under the jockey Chris McCarron.
The hopeless long shot Ayrton S made a dash for the lead and set a
solid pace of 22 4/5 seconds for the quarter-mile and 46 seconds
for the half-mile. Another long shot, Albaha, was right on his
heels, with Gentlemen and Free House next. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the field moved to the far turn, the two long shots faded as
Gentlemen and Free House roared past them.
</P>
<P>
   Touch Gold, who had been fifth, was asked for his best by his
rider, Pat Day, but he was empty. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen led Free House by a half-length with a quarter-mile
remaining, after a mile in 1:34 4/5, but Free House moved past him
powerfully after turning into the lane and drew away while ducking
out and then back in the final furlong. He was well clear of
Gentlemen while doing the cha-cha. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCaffery and Toffan are the breeders and owners of Free House,
an obscurely bred colt by Smokester out of the mare Fountain Lake,
by Vigors.
</P>
<P>
   Free House has outrun his pedigree from the start. He won last
year's Santa Anita Derby, then distinguished himself in the Triple
Crown by finishing second in the Preakness Stakes and third in both
the Kentucky Derby and the Belmont Stakes. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But after a poor performance in last fall's Super Derby, Free
House was given a lengthy vacation. He was off for nine and a half
months before returning for his victory in the Bel Air. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``He just needed time,'' Gonzalez said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Free House, who was bred in California, has now won 7 of 17
starts and $2,181,371.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
