<SLUG> BC-TEN-WTA-DESWARDT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DE SWARDT FINALLY BREAKS AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GREENIDGE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WELLESLEY _ Both players had expected that their match might go
the full three sets. And the semifinal started out true to form,
with just one service break in each of the first two sets.
</P>
<P>
   But Mariaan de Swardt got the break she needed in the third set,
and it propelled the unseeded 27-year-old from South Africa to
Sunday's final of the Boston Cup.
</P>
<P>
   De Swardt was ahead of Lisa Raymond in games, 6-5, and had just
hit a winning forehand up the line to create the break point, at
30-40.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond, a 27-year-old from Wayne, Pa., then appeared to survive
by hammering a serve that skipped off the baseline. However, it was
ruled out by the baseline umpire, and even though chair umpire
Stephanie Reidy overruled, that only gave Raymond back her first
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond then proceeded to double-fault, and de Swardt was a 4-6,
6-4, 7-5 winner _ and a WTA Tour event finalist for the first time
in 10 years as a pro. She will meet another first-time finalist,
Barbara Schett, at Babson College at 2 p.m., $27,000 going to the
winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you make a final in singles or doubles, it means
you're playing well,'' said de Swardt, who won the singles title on
the International Tennis Federation's satellite circuit two weeks
ago in Salt Lake City. ``I've been playing for 10 years, but with a
couple of years off due to injury, I don't see myself as a pro for
10 years. It's been more like five or six years.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond's plan was to stay away from de Swardt's forehand.
``It's like playing a man,'' Raymond, the third seed, said. ``It's
a big forehand. Her whole game is to set up her forehand. She was
hitting (them) to allow her to get to the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond did not have any complaints about the baseline call that
was overruled. Especially after she sealed her own fate by faulting
on her next serve. ``I knew I was going to be in trouble,'' Raymond
said. ``She put a lot of pressure on my second serve. If she's
going to crank that forehand, it's probably going to be a winner or
it's going to be a very tough shot for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond said the two-hour-12-minute match kept her off balance.
``It was a crazy match; we had very few rallies,'' she said. ``I
had no rhythm in the whole match. It was a long match, but there
weren't long points. She either misses or hits a winner. When she's
on, the ball's going in, and when she's off, they rarely went in _
they usually hit the fence. Whoever took the opportunity and
consolidated them, they were going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   De Swardt concentrated on Raymond's serve in that final game,
after having difficulty with it earlier in the match. ``I wanted to
be aggressive and, hopefully, to see a second serve,'' de Swardt
said. ``I had to be aggressive and make the play. I was trying to
stay with her and, when I had an opportunity, to use it to my
advantage. I stayed with her. I could have easily lost in straight
sets.''
</P>
<P>
   De Swardt changed strategy midway through, opting to go to the
net whenever possible. ``Lisa was putting pressure on me, and I
looked at the percentage that she was winning at by coming to the
net _ she was taking a lot of points,'' said de Swardt, who has
elevated her rank to 50th from the low 300s last spring. ``If I
didn't put pressure on her, I was going to be in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   De Swardt enters Sunday's final feeling good, with no problems
with the right shoulder that caused her to take time away from the
tour at the conclusion of the 1996 season. ``This is the best I've
felt in 10 years,'' she said. ``I'm, like, wired. The older I get,
the better I feel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
