u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-PGAOPEN     08-15 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-PGAOPEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PGA BECOMING TOUR'S CROWN JEWEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; REDMOND, Wash. _ There is increasing sentiment, at least in
this corner, that professonal golf's two most captivating major
championships are not the Masters and US Open. True, the Masters
was a marvelous show this year, and the US Open was an encore for
Lee Janzen. But the atmosphere at Augusta National is enough to
turn off the average guy, and the US Open has become too stifling
in its rigidity.
</P>
<P>
   This brings us to the second world. The British Open, with its
wild weather at Royal Birkdale last month, was a marvelous event.
And the PGA of America scored a major coup by bringing its
championship to the Pacific Northwest at Sahalee CC. The club name
is derived from a Chinook phrase meaning ``high, heavenly ground,''
and the course was in immaculate condition, a cathedral amid the
pines.
</P>
<P>
   Sahalee CC sits on the eastern shores of Lake Sammamish on what
is known as the Sammamish Plateau. Five days of splendid weather
leading into the weekend have made this a golfing paradise.
</P>
<P>
   The last time the PGA Championship was contested in this part of
the country was 1946, when Ben Hogan won a 6-and-4 match-play
decision over Porky Oliver at Portland (Ore.) GC. The only other
time it was in Washington was 1944, when Bob Hamilton edged Byron
Nelson, 1-up, at Manito CC in Spokane.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA of America decided several years ago to move its
championships to parts of the country that don't usually see
majors. They picked a gem in Sahalee CC, which may become part of
the rota.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural setting that the golf course sits in, with the
pines and the trees, is very unique and very beautiful,'' said Mark
O'Meara. ``I think all of the players who hadn't had an opportunity
to play Sahalee are very excited about what they've seen. The golf
course is in beautiful shape. The greens are as nice as you could
ever want to putt on. It's nice to be up in the Pacific
Northwest.''
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Championship has frequently suffered from an identity
crisis, even leading the PGA of America to move the 1971 event to
February in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla., so it would be the first of
the majors. Jack Nicklaus won it that year, but it returned to
August the next year at Southern Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Annually, the PGA field is the best of the majors, and it
continues to provide the best theater. Who will forget the chip of
Stuart Appleby _ whose wife was killed by a car on a London street
after the British Open last month _ going in for birdie on the 18th
hole Friday? Appleby missed the cut, but he had that moment to
celebrate as the crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   It may be tough Sunday to top the performance of O'Meara at the
Masters and British Open, or Janzen at the US Open, but who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Just one year from Monday, US captain  &UR; Ben Crenshaw  &LR; will name
the final two members of the Ryder Cup team that will meet the
defending champion Europeans at The Country Club. Next month,
Crenshaw will meet with the European captain at the course in
Brookline, Mass., where he went to the quarterfinals of the US
Juniors in 1968. ``I've flown to Boston twice already and I expect
to be there twice in September,'' said Crenshaw. ``There's a myriad
of details, but it's fun. It's just really started. They've done a
wonderful job at Brookline. It couldn't be a prettier place to have
the matches. It means a lot to me personally and to those players
who played in the US Open in 1988. It's one of those places where
there's a special atmosphere. I don't know how you can conjure up a
better place as a venue.'' ... Crenshaw was asked about Nicklaus's
absence from the British Open and PGA Championship. ``Players of my
vintage will feel a void not watching Jack compete and playing
against him,'' said Crenshaw. ``It was a little sad that he's not
going to play and his string is broken. He's going to play again,
but not to have him around at a major is something I'm not used to
and I know a lot of people aren't. We've put our eyeballs on the
most efficient performer in the majors there probably will ever be.
He could break down a golf course and assess its weaknesses and
stick to a plan. That's very difficult to do over 72 holes. The
competition today prevents someone from getting anywhere close to
it. We were lucky to have seen it all this time.'' ...  &UR; Davis Love
 &LR; returned to Sahalee as defending champion and his friend, Seattle
native  &UR; Fred Couples &LR; , &UR;  &LR; returned to his roots. Couples had already
played 18 holes last Monday when Love approached him. ``I said,
`Come on. Go out on the course with me. Just play a couple of
holes,''' said Love. ``So we went out 1, 2, and 3 and came in 7, 8,
and 9. It was good because he showed me a little bit about the golf
course. He also showed me how excited he was to be playing here. If
I can't win, it sure would be great if Freddie plays well because
the tournament he has here has done a lot for charity in this
town.'' ... Janzen on the impact of his Isleworth neighbor,  &UR; Tiger
Woods &LR; : &UR;  &LR; ``It's probably influenced a lot of players since he came
out on tour,'' said Janzen. ``He's got great talent, and I think in
his mind he expects a lot of himself. I think he also thinks he can
do just about anything. I think this challenged the rest of us to
start thinking a little higher and setting higher goals. That's one
reason why the younger players won last year. Just playing with him
at Isleworth I've realized that I can be better than I was. Just
mentally. Just by desire alone. I think his desire is great. He
wants to be the greatest player who ever lived. When you see
somebody with those kind of aspirations, you think, `I certainly
can expect more of myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Paul Runyan &LR; , who won the PGA Championship twice and was the
first head professional at Sahalee CC in 1969, received the PGA of
America's Distinguished Service Award on the eve of the
championship. ``Certainly I'm indebted to golf for allowing me to
earn a better-than-average living under the most pleasant
circumstances known to mankind,'' said Runyan. ``I've traveled very
widely. I'm sure as an Arkansas farm kid I never would have had any
chance to approach the pleasant way of earning a livelihood that
I'm blessed to have with golf itself. I'm only an eighth grade
graduate in the public school system, but I feel that I'm a
reasonably well-educated person because of the wonderful people
that I've met and the close association with people that were
well-educated. So to that degree I think I'm maybe a 12th grade
student instead of an eighth grade student.'' ... The New England
Pro-Assistant championship was won by  &UR; Gary Young  &LR; and  &UR; Tom Gilbert
 &LR; of Pleasant Valley last Tuesday at Wachusett CC. Young and Gilbert
finished tied with  &UR; John Scheffler  &LR; and  &UR; Tim McLaughlin  &LR; of
Eastward Ho!, then won on the second hole of the playoff. Young had
won with former assistant  &UR; Scott Trethewey  &LR; two years ago ...  &UR; Kirk
Hanefeld  &LR; of Salem CC, who won the recent Rhode Island Open, has
pulled within 4 points of Woburn's  &UR; Paul Parajeckas  &LR; in the Wogan
Award standings for NEPGA Player of the Year ...  &UR; Tom Lehman &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
won the British Open two years ago but injured his shoulder while
cavorting with his children at an amusement park before this year's
tournament, said, ``I had an MRI done on my shoulder as soon as I
got back from the British Open. They immediately ruled surgery out.
I have had treatment this week, and it doesn't feel too bad right
now.'' ...  &UR; Steve Elkington &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who won the 1995 PGA in a playoff
with  &UR; Colin Montgomerie &LR;  at Riviera, &UR;  &LR; has had his problems, too.
``It's been a frustrating year healthwise,'' he said. ``I think I
would have been fine if I just had sinus problems. But I got
meningitis, which I had forgotten how hard that was to come back
from. I had it in 1986. I think I'm only now just getting over
it.'' ... The PGA of America said it will change its format for the
four-man Grand Slam of Golf from 36 holes of stroke play to match
play: two matches on Nov. 17, with the winners playing for the
title the next day at the Poipu Bay Resort GC in Hawaii. The winner
will earn $400,000. The winners of the four majors qualify, but
O'Meara has already won two. The first alternate, also based on
performance in the majors, was Woods as of Friday, and the second
alternate was  &UR; Jose Maria Olazabal &LR; . You also have to have won a
major to qualify ... Remember when dates were being shuffled
around, affecting the CVS Charity Classic at Pleasant Valley? Word
was the PGA Tour would set up shop in Seattle, at a new TPC at
Snowqualmie Ridge about 5 miles east of Sahalee. Organizers were
offered the same dates open to Pleasant Valley, which just happened
to be opposite the new NEC Invitational that will bring the members
of the last Ryder Cup and Presidents Cup teams to Akron, Ohio. So
the PGA Tour reportedly asked for a $2 million purse. With the
world's top players scheduled to be in Akron that week, nobody has
come forward with the $2 million in Seattle, even though the dates
were guaranteed. Sound familiar?
</P>
</TEXT>
