<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-RAPE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER TEACHER CHARGED WITH STATUTORY RAPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN HOFFMANN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A 38-year-old former teacher was charged with
statutory rape Friday after she allegedly had sex with a
sixth-grade student from Raymore-Peculiar Middle School.
</P>
<P>
   Amy M. Rodriguez of Greenwood was arraigned in Jackson County
Circuit Court on three counts of statutory rape. She pleaded not
guilty to all the charges and was released on $25,000 bond. A judge
ordered her to avoid contact with the 12-year-old boy and other
youths younger than 17.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Rodriguez faces a prison sentence of five years to
life on each count.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was a student in Rodriguez's class at Raymore-Peculiar
Middle School during the 1997-98 school year. The incidents
allegedly occurred in May and June at the teacher's home.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said Rodriguez voluntarily resigned several
days ago.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Angles, an attorney for Rodriguez, said he intends
to ``present an aggressive defense.'' He said he and his client are
``looking forward to our day in court.''
</P>
<P>
   According to court documents, the relationship began late in the
school year when Rodriguez told the boy that she needed to talk to
him and suggested that he spend the night at her house.
</P>
<P>
   She told him to tell his mother that he was spending the night
with a friend from school, prosecutors said, and even called the
boy's house and pretended to be the friend's mother.
</P>
<P>
   On May 8, the student stayed after school and was driven by
Rodriguez to her home, the documents say. Rodriguez and the boy
talked for several hours, ordered a pizza and talked some more.
Investigators believe the teacher then showed the student around
her house, with the tour ending in the master bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   The documents allege that the teacher unfastened the boy's
pants, undressed him and herself, and then had intercourse with
him.
</P>
<P>
   On at least two other occasions, prosecutors said, the teacher
drove the boy to her home and had sex with him.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the boy accurately described the inside of
Rodriguez's home.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors said Rodriguez had lived there with her husband and
two children. A neighbor said the husband had moved out but
recently was seen at the house.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents say the student's mother became suspicious June
12 after the boy had told her he was going skating with friends.
When Rodriguez picked him up at his house, she identified herself
as the mother of a friend. But when she dropped the boy back home
later, she gave a different name and quickly left.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, according to court records, the mother
received a call from a woman who identified herself as Amy
Rodriguez and said she was the person who had dropped off her son
the night before. The teacher went to the boy's home, admitted she
had lied and said she had picked her son up only once.
</P>
<P>
   Her story did not match the boy's. He said Rodriguez had picked
him up more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents say the mother also found romantic notes,
including one that read: ``I can't wait to be with you forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said a handwriting expert determined that the
writing on the notes matched that of Rodriguez on other documents.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's mother, reached Friday night at home, declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Court records also allege that Rodriguez met in mid-June with
Terri Jamison, principal at the middle school, and told her that a
friendship other than teacher//student had developed with the boy
and that she had lied to the student's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Jamison could not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Lyle E. Boyles, assistant superintendent of the Raymore-Peculiar
School District, said he was unsure how long Rodriguez had taught
at the school or what subject she taught.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really have any direct involvement in this,'' he
said. ``As I understand it, this took place away from school during
nonschool hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Another district official said Rodriguez had been a substitute
teacher at the middle school but had gained ``teacher'' status
before she resigned.
</P>
</TEXT>
