u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     08-15 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO VAUGHN FROM THE MOUTH OF A BABE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In conjunction with HBO, which is airing a Babe Ruth special
tonight at 8:01, the Red Sox celebrated ``Remember Babe Ruth Day''
at Fenway Park Saturday before playing the Minnesota Twins. Bambino
videos were shown on the big board and Ruth's daughter, Julia Ruth
Stevens, threw out the ceremonial first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Babe, who died 50 years ago Sunday, visited me in my sleep
Friday night, and asked me to deliver this message to Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Maurice,
</P>
<P>
   I see where things have been a bit rough for you around old
Fenway this year. I remember it well. You should have seen the
stuff that came down on my big head in my last year with the Sox in
1919.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, lemme tell ya, I hated leaving Boston. I loved the
city, the ballpark, and the fans. Most of all, I loved the kids.
There was nothing I wouldn't do for the kids of Boston. And they
loved me back. I know.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, the Red Sox have never understood players like you
and me. They've never liked colorful guys with big appetites and
opinions. You think you felt bad when the Sox got rid of Clemens?
You'll never know how I felt when we dumped Carl Mays in the middle
of the 1919 season. Carl was The Franchise for us. He won the
clinch game of the 1918 World Series against the Cubs. I called him
``Bazookaman.'' But he couldn't get along with management and they
let him go to New York. Yeesh. GM Eddie Barrow and owner Harry
Frazee were such dolts. I called 'em ``the joint chiefs of staff.''
</P>
<P>
   I have to admit that a lot of my woes occurred off the field. I
crashed my motorcar into a Boston trolley one night. The flatfoots
put me in the clink, it made the papers, and all hell broke loose.
You'd have thought I killed somebody. When they found out I was
with a chick who wasn't my wife, it got even worse for me. Geez, if
we'd had a Foxy Lady to visit in those days, I could have avoided
all kinds of trouble. All we had was Scollay Square and I
practically owned the place.
</P>
<P>
   Sox management didn't trust me. That was the bottom line. They
asked me to submit to alcohol evaluation before the 1919 season.
What a joke. Can you imagine? I mean, there were nights when that
booze-measuring machine would have exploded if I blew into it, but
I never had a problem. Never missed a game. Never let the team
down. And they didn't ask anyone else on the club to agree to such
a clause.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the thing about my big gut. The Sox were always
on me about being out of shape but I told 'em I didn't look too fat
circling the bases after my tape-measure homers. Didn't matter.
Barrow, the dorky GM, was always talking about how Wally Schang was
a ``real baseball player who always keeps himself in shape.'' I
knew what that meant. It was Barrow's way of saying, ``Schang isn't
a fat slob like Ruth.'' I hear that's what they're doing when they
compare you to this whiz kid, Nomar.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know about your situation, but the last straw was when
Frazee hired a private detective to follow me home to Sudbury at
night. It was pathetic. The poor guy wasn't much of a sleuth. I
knew he was trying to catch me going into a speakeasy, but I lost
him every time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the smear campaign was on. The Sox were floating
rumors that I was using illegal substances. That was pretty low. A
little bathtub gin never hurt anybody. I explained all this in an
exclusive interview with Steve Murton of the old Boston Record. All
the rest of the reporters got mad at me and Murton. Glenn Mordway
and those nitwits on sports talk radio were killing me, too.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, after all this came down, I told the Sox in the spring
of 1919 that the price was going to go up every day. And it did. I
kept crushing homers and by the end of the year I decided I wanted
$30,000 spread over two years. I told Frazee I wanted market value
and would not take any hometown discount. It made all the papers
and a lot of the fans didn't understand. I tried to explain that it
wasn't about the money. It was about respect. But it's hard for
fans to understand when you're talking about that kind of dough.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the fans were fickle. I hit 29 bombs in my last
season with the Sox, but they still booed me half the time. They
didn't like it when I held out for the big bucks or when I told the
papers that I wanted to play for the Toronto Maple Leafs baseball
team of the International League.
</P>
<P>
   You've no doubt noticed that the Sox haven't had much luck since
I left. People blame me, but I never cursed the team. It's just
been bad management. I hope you guys win everything this year. I
still have a soft spot for Boston. I still love the park and the
fans.
</P>
<P>
   And the kids. Think about them before you decide to leave, Mo.
If you love playing baseball, Boston's a tough town to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Yours truly,
</P>
<P>
   The Babe
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
