<HEADER>
A5674 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-LADN     08-15 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-KRIKORIAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STEAMER' HEATING UP DESERT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM SPRINGS There he is in a small studio at a small radio
station on a sweltering day, the old Los Angeles journalistic icon
talking about sports in a gentle and professional manner that has
become almost extinct in his trade.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Furillo is as passionate as ever about the topics he's
discussing, but it's all different for him now.
</P>
<P>
   He is far removed from the bright lights of his beloved Los
Angeles, but the advancing years and the low profile venue haven't
dimmed his fabled enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love it here ... happy as I've ever been,'' says Bud Furillo,
and he joyfully resumes speaking into a microphone about Michael
Irvin and the Coliseum and USC football and the passing of Sam
Balter and various other subjects.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Bud Furillo was president of the Southern
California chapter of the Baseball Writers of America, and he had
Frank Sinatra, Dean Martin and Sammy Davis Jr. perform skits and
Nancy Wilson sing songs and Phil Silvers tell jokes as master of
ceremonies at the organization's big off-season dinner gathering.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Bud Furillo possessed the influence to
turn gambling bustouts like Jimmy Snyder into national figures
known as Jimmy the Greek.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Bud Furillo could phone Sinatra and Elvis
Presley and Marilyn Monroe and Jayne Mansfield and Mamie Van Doren
and a lot of other entertainment types any time he so pleased.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Bud Furillo was on a first-name basis with
gangsters like Sam Giancana, John Roselli, Joe Sica, Fred Sica and
Mickey Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Bud Furillo would show up at the Olympic
Auditorium at a big boxing show with an entourage that had more
members in it than Muhammad Ali's.
</P>
<P>
   But the spotlight no longer glares on Bud Furillo, who ranks
among the most colorful if not most talented journalists in Los
Angeles history.
</P>
<P>
   The frantic existence he once lived as a young reporter with the
Los Angeles Herald Express, and then as the sports editor of the
Los Angeles Herald Examiner, has now been replaced by relative
tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe I'm going to be 73 on August 19?'' says
Furillo, shaking his head slowly during a break on his 4 to 6 p.m.
sports talk show he does daily here on KPSI (920 AM) with Steve
Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   No, I can't.
</P>
<P>
   I've known Bud Furillo, a 1943 Bell High School graduate, since
he was in his early 40s, worked under him, lived near him in
Downey, endured his infamous tirades, partied with him, learned so
much of my newspapering from a man who had almost a mystical knack
for it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm one of his acolytes, as was the late Allan Malamud, as are
Bob Keisser, Steve Bisheff, Steve Harvey, Mitch Chortkoff, Larry
Stewart, Jack Disney, Richard Levin, Tom Singer, Jim Perry, John
Beyrooty, Lyle Spencer, sportscaster Steve Hartman and countless
others.
</P>
<P>
   When I first worked for him, I was a beginner in awe of Furillo,
who molded me and scolded me and inspired me with the toughest love
imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   The column he then wrote for the Herald Examiner was called the
Steam Room, and it was one of the most popular in L.A. and there
was no one more powerful in the sportswriting fraternity in L.A.
when I arrived than Bud Furillo.
</P>
<P>
   When you went out with him to a restaurant in those days, you
would be treated like a celebrity and a steady stream of important
people always would stop by and pay their respects to him.
</P>
<P>
   To me, a wide-eyed youngster who grew up reading him, Bud
Furillo was a larger-than-life character, a charismatic person who
worked extremely hard at his craft and played just as hard when off
duty at the tavern he owned in Downey.
</P>
<P>
   He drank too much and gambled too much, but there was never a
dull moment with him, and there were plenty of laughs because he
forever was surrounded by an interesting cast of hangers-on that
always had an arm out for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   He was a sport who would pick up all tabs even at a time when he
was earning a modest income and and even at a time when he was a
single parent raising six kids.
</P>
<P>
   He could be mean-spirted when he was in one of his foul moods,
but he also was the most generous man I've ever known, giving
lavish wedding gifts to his writers and often loaning money to
people he knew couldn't pay him back.
</P>
<P>
   He was a strong-willed man who evoked ambivalent feelings among
both friends and foes, but everyone agreed that Bud Furillo had
style.
</P>
<P>
   He was known as The Steamer and he and Melvin Durslag put
together one of the great metropolitan sports sections at the
Herald Examiner, but he left the old paper in June of 1974 when he
got into a salary beef with the publisher, George Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   He would become an L.A. radio fixture throughout the 1970s and
1980s during tours at KABC and KIIS, and would spend a few years up
in Sacramento before settling down in this oasis 5{ years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He has had serious health problems, but he is a durable survivor
who has never come unraveled by adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to keep fighting in life,'' says Bud Furillo,
and he's still fighting his causes as he has been doing since the
legendary Herald Express editor, Aggie Underwood, pulled him off
the copy boy desk and made him a reporter in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   He would become a columnist for the Herald Express in 1958, but
he had been ghost-writing articles for people named George T.
Davis, John B. Old and Harry Culver ever since he joined the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``The old reporters liked to drink in those days, and when they
went on the road they sometimes failed to file their stories,''
relates Furillo. ``So I wrote a lot of stories under other guys'
names. I remember one time when Hary Culver was up in Berkeley
covering a showdown between Cal and UCLA. Both teams were
undefeated, and Cal won easily. Culver sent the score on the wires
with this aside, `Pick up details.' That was all he sent. So I
wrote the story for him. This was a fairly common newspaper
practice in those days.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud Furillo lives alone now in Palm Desert with his dog Rip, and
he seems quite content.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love what I'm doing,'' he says. ``And I don't plan to
retire soon. I'm having too much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first started working with Bud Furillo, I really didn't
know that much about him,'' says Steve Kelly, his 39-year-old
partner who's a Rutgers graduate. ``If I knew then what I know now,
I'd have been tongue-tied. I never realized just how many people
Bud knows and just how famous he was until I started spending a lot
of time around him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud Furillo's juices still flow wildly when he's involved in a
big story.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to find out who was responsible for the recent
firings of Bill Russell and Fred Claire, Furillo had on his program
Claire, Lasorda and Dodger president Bob Graziano.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to the conclusion that Tommy had nothing to do with the
firings and that it was Graziano who made the decisions,'' says
Furillo.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Furillo is an early riser these days because he goes to bed
early, a ritual he never followed when he was boss at the Herald
Examiner barking out orders to young sportswriters, and when his
presence often inspired terror among his troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I miss the newspaper game,'' he says. ``But this radio
isn't too bad. I like what I'm doing. The people I work for are
very nice to me. I recently had what I thought was the best radio
show I've ever had.''
</P>
<P>
   Bud Furillo pauses with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm going to have a better one pretty soon,'' promises
Furillo, still fiercely competing in the dusk of a memorable
career.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PRESS TELEGRAM, LONG BEACH, CALIFORNIA
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
