<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-PEPSI400-SPEEDWAY     08-15 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PEPSI400-SPEEDWAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Michigan Speedway maintains reputation despite tragedy
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
BROOKLYN, Mich. _ More than 150,000 people will fill the stands at
Michigan Speedway for today's Pepsi 400, and three of those people
will be sitting in the exact seats where three spectators lost
their lives only three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just one of those fluke deals,'' said John McDermont, a
41-year-old postal worker who made the trip from Cincinnati and is
sitting in the turn 4 area where the tragedy occurred. ``I'm not
worried about something like that happening, but I am glad they did
some things to protect the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Speedway officials added four feet to the top of the debris
fencing around the two-mile oval, along with additional cable for
reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place has a great safety record,'' said Greg Penske,
director of the Michigan Speedway and the other tracks owned by his
father, Roger. ``Last month was the first incident we've had, but
it still was one too many. That's why we made these changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The additional fencing raises the height of the debris fence to
17 feet above the track surface and angles out toward the track,
providing an overhang to catch flying debris.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Speedway always has been considered one of the best and
safest tracks in America. It doesn't have the reputation of places
like Talladega and Darlington, where danger to the drivers lurks in
every turn of every lap.
</P>
<P>
   But Michigan is a wide, fast racing surface that has been the
site of some shocking crashes in its 29-year history. The one
accident that still is fresh in the minds of many was the
terrifying crash that almost killed Ernie Irvan in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan lost control of the car, which slid into the turn 2 wall
at more than 170 mph. The car bounced off the wall, and little was
left of the body of the car when it finally came to a stop. Irvan
suffered a critical head injury and was in a coma. Doctors gave him
a 10 percent chance of survival, but he made a miraculous recovery
and returned to racing 14 months later.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan was a rising star at the time of the crash. He was only 27
points behind Dale Earnhardt, who would go on to win his seventh
title.
</P>
<P>
   Irvan hasn't been that close to the top since the crash. He has
no recollection of the accident, saying his only memory is waking
up in the hospital days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my wife still gets tears in her eyes when a helicopter
flies in here,'' Irvan said. ``I can look at her and realize how
bad it must have been, but thankfully, I don't have any of those
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvan said he has no fear of racing at Michigan, but the feeling
isn't the same for some of the fans who were involved in the
tragedy at speedway three weeks ago. Gerald Bramer, who injured his
left arm when he used it to block the tire, said he has nightmares
about what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dream the tire is coming at me again,'' Bramer told the
Detroit News. ``I understand now what Vietnam vets go through. Not
a day goes by that I don't think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Several drivers over the years have been left with bad memories
about Michigan Speedway, including Houston's A.J. Foyt.
</P>
<P>
   A crash in 1990 caused multiple fractures in his feet and legs,
leaving his racing career in doubt. Foyt endured a painful
rehabilitation process, often spending time at the Oilers' training
facility to work with strength coach Steve Watterson.
</P>
<P>
   Foyt came back to race again, but for a man in his mid-50s at
the time, it was the beginning of the end to a Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   Merle Bettenhausen's career came to an end at Michigan when he
lost an arm in a horrifying crash, and Rick Mears was seriously
burned in an accident at Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some of these tragic incidents, Michigan is a race track
most drivers love because of its wide surface and ample passing
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But some of the Winston Cup drivers are concerned that the new
air dam and spoiler rules NASCAR implemented this year (which gives
the cars less downforce) make the constant passing at Michigan a
dangerous proposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admit I'm pretty nervous about it,'' said Jeff Burton, who
won the Busch Grand National race Saturday at Michigan. ``We could
have incidents because of people getting their air (downforce on
the car) taken off. The key is to be able to drive deep into the
corner and not get loose. It's a great race track, but you have to
respect it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
