<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5685 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-STRIKEOUTS-LEAD-H     08-15 2045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-STRIKEOUTS-LEAD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Strikeout pitchers a special blend of raw power, grace
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For all its perfect, timeless symmetry and graceful
choreography, baseball is most compelling when it's a
brute-strength, mano-a-mano battle, lightning vs. thunder.
</P>
<P>
   What fans most love to see is a strikeout-minded pitcher
reaching far back and heaving lasers at a muscle-packed batsman
trying to return serve to the upper deck.
</P>
<P>
   In this, baseball's comeback season (labor pains finally
subsiding, attendance rising), the nation is captivated by the
Daily Home Run Watch, the likes of which it hasn't seen since Roger
Maris and Mickey Mantle were alive and chasing the ghost of home
run deity Babe Ruth some 37 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But if the frequent rocket launches by Mark McGwire, Sammy Sosa
and Ken Griffey Jr. weren't enough to draw media salutes _ the
cover of Time magazine _ Major League Baseball now brings its fans
another bonus: strikeout glory.
</P>
<P>
   The physics of the sport dictate that strikeouts proliferate
about the same time home runs do. Astros manager Larry Dierker
observes: ``The two things go together. Home run hitters swing
hard, and they strike out a lot _ except for Joe DiMaggio (who
never struck out more than 39 times in a season).
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys are trying to be home run hitters these days.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros shared, unwittingly, in one of baseball's special
moments, on May 6 in Wrigley Field. Kerry Wood, the precocious,
21-year-old Chicago Cub who is scheduled to pitch today in the
Astrodome, struck out 20 the last time he faced the Astros. He tied
the single-game major-league strikeout record set _ and later
matched _ by Roger Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   This year the major leagues have two pitchers on pace for 300
strikeouts, Curt Schilling, a former Astro, and Randy Johnson, the
newly hired _ or rented _ gun who has won his first three starts
for the Astros, with two of them shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   Strikeouts are trendy. National League games last season
averaged an all-time high 13.7 of them. The average increased every
year from 1992 (11.7) through '97, with this year's average down
only slightly, to 13.4.
</P>
<P>
   It's the batters who aren't obsessed with distance who are
difficult to overpower. San Diego's short-swinging Tony Gwynn is
the bane of the strikeout pitcher. He has fanned only once every 32
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a pitch that crosses the plate that he can't put
his bat on,'' Schilling says. ``He's the one guy with a runner on
third and less than two outs that I feel I wouldn't have much
chance to strike out.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are not many Gwynns. So any time a Wood or a Johnson
or a Schilling takes the mound, the possibility lurks for a
20-strikeout gem or a no-hitter. Which is why Johnson, who no-hit
Detroit in 1990, is accustomed to seeing crowds increase 10,000 and
more on nights he pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's a novelty going to a game when you can watch a
guy strike out a lot of people,'' Johnson says. ``Much like it's
fun to watch Mark McGwire have a chance to hit a home run farther
than you've ever seen.'' &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If Houston has any baseball tradition of note, it's that of
power arms.
</P>
<P>
   The tradition dates to Don Wilson (18 strikeouts in one game,
two no-hitters) in the 1960s. It continued with the imposing J.R.
Richard (two 300-strikeout seasons) in the '70s and Nolan Ryan (the
all-time strikeout king) and Mike Scott (300 K's, a Cy Young Award)
in the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   The torch of fire is carried now by Johnson and Billy Wagner,
baseball's hardest-throwing lefthanders of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans like that style of pitching, and I enjoy watching
that style of pitcher,'' says Ryan, who retired in 1993 with 5,174
strikeouts. ``I've always enjoyed watching Billy Wagner and the way
he's gone about his business.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner last year had the highest strikeout average in
major-league history (minimum of 50 innings), with 14.4 for nine
innings. This year he's about the same, at 14.1.
</P>
<P>
   But for those who actually try to last nine innings, Wood and
Johnson are tops, averaging 12 per game, followed by Philadelphia's
Schilling at 10.2.
</P>
<P>
   The one asset virtually all strikeout artists share is 95
mph-plus heat. Dierker, who had 232 strikeouts in 1969, says one
thing hasn't changed since his playing days: ``The guys who strike
out a lot of people are the guys who throw hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wood, Johnson, Wagner, Schilling, (Robb) Nen _ they have
overpowering stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   All rely primarily on their fastball, though none to the extent
Schilling does. Scouts report more than 90 percent of his pitches
are fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling justifies his fastball fascination: ``There's never
been a pitcher in the history of the game who's been successful
without command of his fastball, whether it's John Tudor (known for
his off-speed style) or Randy Johnson.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling figures the more he uses his fastball, the more
control he'll have of it. He throws only the hard, straight,
four-seamer _ ``because I want to know where the ball will be when
it crosses the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   He averages just 2.0 walks per nine innings. He deftly moves the
ball in and out, keeping the batter guessing where it will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most pitchers have one corner they can work pretty well, but
they have a little trouble finding the other corner,'' Dierker
says. ``Schilling can hit both corners at will. He's proof that the
best pitch in baseball is a well controlled fastball.'' &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Schilling was MVP of the '93 NL Championship Series, but he
didn't blossom into a 300-strikeout ace until last year. He credits
his newfound power to shoulder surgery by Dr. Craig Morgan in
Wilmington, Del. Schilling claims the repair of a frayed labrum
made his arm stronger than it had ever been.
</P>
<P>
   ``That made things different for me in my approach,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   With his shoulder strengthened and his confidence raised, he
became much more aggressive, consciously pursuing stikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Most pitchers find it makes more sense to induce batters into
hitting bouncy grounders than to try to blow fastballs by them. But
the super-power throwers, such as Schilling and Johnson,
incorporate strikeouts into their strategy, depending on the game
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I'll start an at-bat thinking I want a strikeout,
but that's rare,'' Schilling says. ``I've noticed with Randy, he'll
get ahead in the count and then he'll air it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Johnson throws 93-95 much of the time. But he ratchets
it up 2-3 mph when a strikeout is in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very different guy when he has two strikes,'' Schilling
says. ``I think I have somewhat the same philosophy. When I get
ahead in the count and find myself with two strikes, I will go for
the strikeout, because the strikeout eliminates any chance of the
runner reaching base.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson says he's ``not looking for a strikeout, but I just want
to put him away, whether it's a groundout or a flyout or a
strikeout. I don't want to lose him after all the hard work to put
him in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But yeah, I think my adrenaline, my intensity rises when I get
a guy 0-2, 1-2 and I have a chance to put him away.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tries to minimize the significance of strikeout numbers.
He doesn't want to violate the code that says winning is the only
thing that matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think about records; I don't try to strike people
out,'' he insists. ``In a couple of my games where I struck out 19,
I did try to strike out some people, and I couldn't do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Strikeouts and home runs are things that just develop.'' &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Phil Garner, manager of the Milwaukee Brewers, faced Ryan in his
prime and has seen Wood pitch twice and Johnson many times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ryan had the best fastball of anyone I've seen,'' Garner says.
``When he was putting everything into it, he'd grunt, expel the air
out of his body, and the next thing you'd hear was `Pow,' in the
mitt. You wouldn't even see the ball, like you would on everyone
else. His was just a blur.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Randy Johnson, because of his size, might be the most
intimidating of the pitchers I've known. You're never sure whether
he's going to let one up and in. He makes you want to back away
just a little bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of his height (6-10),'' Garner says, ``Johnson's ball
powers down, and the angle makes it very tough to hit. A hitter
likes to get his eye on the same plane as the ball, to track it,
and you can't do that with him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Johnson has such a good breaking ball that lefthanders
don't have a chance against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Although an explosive fastball is essential for high strikeout
totals, a reliable second pitch is also needed, or else the power
pitcher will be consigned to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy throws real hard but doesn't spin the ball well,
whether it's a slider or a curve, he can be successful as a
reliever,'' Dierker says. ``But he can't get through the lineup
three times. After a certain number of pitches he starts losing
velocity, and with no other pitch to go to, he's in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to this decade, if a pitcher threw hard, he would stay in
the minor leagues until he mastered an off-speed pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But now, if a Wagner or a Nen (who throws 99 mph for San
Francisco) shows command of a fastball but not a breaking pitch, he
becomes a closer. All teams want plenty of heat waiting on the back
burner, the theory being that a 98-mph fastball is especially
daunting to weary ninth-inning batters.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros traded Schilling (for Jason Grimsley, in case you've
forgotten) in 1992, mistakenly assuming his preoccupation with
power precluded him from being a successful starter.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't realize Schilling's extraordinary control would
extend his velocity. He needed only 94 pitches for a three-hit
shutout last week in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Schilling throws a sharply diving split-finger pitch, but he
uses it only once or twice an inning _ usually to fetch a third
strike on the unsuspecting batter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I throw it right,'' he says, ``it has the same rotation
as my four-seam fastball. It's very hard for the batter to pick it
up early.'' &QL; 
 &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Ryan may have been the hardest-throwing pitcher ever _ radar
clocked him at 105 in his prime. But he rarely won without command
of his curveball.
</P>
<P>
   Wood throws harder than any other starter in baseball _ 97-100
mph as the ball leaves his hand. But Garner notes that Wood also
``has a very good breaking ball.''
</P>
<P>
   With Wood, as with many young power pitchers, the issue is
control. ``If he has good control,'' Dierker says, ``you're not
gonna hit him. If he doesn't have control, he's gonna struggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys who throw 95-plus are going to have a little trouble
controlling their fastball,'' Dierker says. ``The ball is moving so
fast, spinning so fast, it's hard to keep it on track.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Schilling had control even as a teen-ager, Ryan and
Johnson spent years searching for it. Once they gained command of
the heater, they were able to remain in games long enough to build
their impressive strikeout numbers.
</P>
<P>
   And whether they admit it or not, these power pitchers enjoy
their strikeouts as much as the fans who cheer them on.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson often pumps his fist to register pleasure when he
strikes out a batter. Clemens, who was born in Katy, has won 227
games and claims to value wins above strikeouts, but he gave his
four children names beginning with ``K'' and not ``W.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, 31, is a student of baseball history and a
memorabilia collector, and he doesn't mind saying he'd like to
leave his mark in the strikeout records.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it got close to 300, yeah, I was nervous and it was
something I wanted badly,'' he says. ``After that, I wanted the
record.''
</P>
<P>
   He finished last season with 319 strikeouts. The major-league
record (post-1900) is Ryan's 383, set in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   With teams using five-man rotations instead of four, as they did
in the 1970s, it will be difficult for Schilling or future pitchers
to acquire enough innings to challenge Ryan's record.
</P>
<P>
   But looking at the trends _ more home runs, more swinging from
the heels _ it's not out of the question that strikeout records _
along with home run records _ will be broken. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
