u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-STRIKEOUTS-RELIEV     08-15 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STRIKEOUTS-RELIEVERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Hard-throwing relievers often save the day with a `K'
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARA LaBRIE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Astros closer Billy Wagner is one of the best strikeout artists
among relief pitchers, averaging a major-league record 14.4
strikeouts per nine innings last season, a number he has almost
matched so far this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Wagner doesn't enter the game with K's on the brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just happens,'' Wagner said. ``I never think, `I'm going to
strike this guy out.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You're just thinking, `Three outs before they score.' I don't
go out there with the intention of striking someone out. It just
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Astros catcher Brad Ausmus is more of a pragmatist.
</P>
<P>
   ``A 98-mile-an-hour fastball,'' Ausmus said of Wagner's
proclivity for striking out a lot of batters. ``When you throw that
hard the hitter really has to get his hands moving to hit the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   A fastball in the high-90s followed by a slider in the high 80s
confuses hitters, forces them to commit to a pitch and makes them
swing and miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's (a hitter) moving his hands to hit a 98-mile-an-hour
fastball and then you throw an 88-mph slider, you're way out in
front of it and tend to swing and miss again,'' Ausmus said. ``It's
very difficult to concentrate against guys like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Guys like Randy Johnson, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   At first thought, it would be difficult to equate the Astros'
newest sensation, who stands 6 feet 10, with the 5-11 Wagner. Yet
Brewers manager Phil Garner sees that the two lefthanders have the
same weapon in their arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most hitters fear most is movement on the fastball,''
Garner said. ``The interesting thing about lefthanders is they're
extremely tough because their ball moves more. It's harder to pick
up a lefthanded ball that powers away from you.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson towers more than 7 feet on the mound, so his pitches
arrive on a different plane than do those of other pitchers. Though
almost a foot shorter than Johnson, Wagner has managed to create
the same movement, forcing batters to level the playing field with
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your eyes have to track it rather than using depth
perception,'' Garner said. ``That tells you how good Wagner is. On
a shorter plane, it's easier to pick the ball up. But he's got so
much movement on the ball it's difficult to hit it. That's a
testament to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wagner's reasoning behind his success isn't as technical.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a little lucky,'' Wagner said with a shrug of the
shoulders. ``I'm effectively wild. They swing at a lot of pitches
that they probably shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wagner isn't the only relief pitcher who commands respect
from hitters. The formula for other successful relievers remains
the same: speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all have an explosive fastball,'' Astros infielder Sean
Berry said. ``Everything feeds off the fastball. You've got to have
more than one pitch, of course. Trevor Hoffman has a changeup.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego's Hoffman leads the National League in saves with 39.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a guy who throws 99 miles an hour and has a great
changeup. That's a strikeout pitch,'' Ausmus said.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Myers, who joined the Padres Aug. 7 after recording 28
saves with the Blue Jays, has an out pitch of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most good closers do have a strikeout pitch,'' Garner said.
``Randy Myers has come up with something _ it's not a fastball,
it's not a spitball, but it's something that hitters don't pick
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman and Myers aren't the only strikeout relief pitchers who
come to mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robb Nen (who has 30 saves with the Giants) what about that
guy?'' Berry said. ``He's probably the most prolific strikeout
relief pitcher in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But has he ever sent Berry back to the bench?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's struck out everybody before,'' Berry said,
shaking his head. ``He's fun to hit off of, but it's feast or
famine.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
