<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5688 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-RELIEVERS-WOOD-HN     08-15 1857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RELIEVERS-WOOD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Despite slump, Wood is heir to throne
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Kerry Wood pitched a one-hitter and struck out 20 Astros
on May 6 in what some people feel was the most dominating game in
the history of baseball, he was hailed as the latest in a long line
of Texas flamethrowers.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when the Chicago Cubs rookie takes the mound in the
Astrodome for his first professional start in his home state, he
will be trying to halt a flameout.
</P>
<P>
   Though Wood has an 11-6 record and 193 strikeouts in 138 innings
in his rookie season, he has hit a wall of late. In his last two
starts, Wood has lasted only 10 innings and allowed 14 hits and 12
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Those starts came after Cubs manager Jim Riggleman mentioned he
thought that Wood might be suffering a dead arm, a malady that
young pitchers sometimes face as the season grinds on. Obviously,
there is nothing seriously wrong with Wood _ his fastball was
clocked at 97 mph in his last start against San Francisco _ but the
rookie admits he's in uncharted waters as a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Wood pitched a combined 151 in Class AA and Class
AAA, the most he had worked as a professional. In mid-August,
minor-league pitchers are thinking more about the end of the season
in early September than a race for a division title or wild-card
berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got 10 starts left this year. Last year at this time, I
might have two or three left,'' said Wood. ``So we're cutting back
a little bit (on throwing) in between starts, taking it a little
easy and see how that works. We're seeing how I recover from the
start before and see how my arm reacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're up four, five runs going into the seventh, I might
not go out there this late in the season. In the home stretch, I
want to be able to reach back. I think it's important to do it
(taper off) now rather than not have enough left in the stretch. I
want to be able to turn it up a notch a little later on. Every game
is going to count. I'd rather miss an inning or two now and maybe
even a start rather than not have enough left at the end of the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs clearly understand how valuable a property Wood is. At
21, Wood is on track to become the next dominant strikeout pitcher
from Texas. Nolan Ryan passed the baton to Roger Clemens, and
though Wood is only in his first season in the majors, he already
is drawing comparisons to those two overpowering pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs are caught in a tight situation. They need Wood to
continue his rookie success in order to stay alive in the
postseason chase, but they also want to carefully monitor the
status of his right arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never has pitched more than 150 innings,'' said Chicago
pitching coach Phil Regan. ``We don't know how he's going to react
once he hits that mark. He's going to pitch a month longer than he
ever has, going into September _ and maybe longer.''
</P>
<P>
   After Wood was hit hard for the second straight time last week
at San Francisco, Giants second baseman Jeff Kent explained what he
thought was happening to Wood.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not throwing with Nolan Ryan speed, you'll be able to
hit the fastball,'' said Kent, who hit a home run off Wood. ``I'd
hate to see Kerry Wood on a good day because it'd be a struggle to
hit that slider.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hung a lot of pitches and wasn't throwing them consistently
for strikes, so we were able to sit on fastballs. It showed me he's
tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood acknowledged that he is still learning what he needs to do
to be successful on days when he doesn't have his sharp-breaking
slider or overpowering fastball. All young pitchers _ even those
with wicked stuff like Wood _ must figure out how to get by when
everything isn't clicking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing that I've learned this year, especially in
my last two starts or so, is that when you don't have your great
stuff you still have to go out there and compete,'' said Wood.
``You have to find a way. Every pitcher in the league has days
where they go out without their best stuff. You've got to learn how
to pitch and get through it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days, you're going to be successful, and other times
you're not going to last very long. You realize that's part of
baseball; you're not going to win every game. You're going to get
beat. You're going to have days where you can't throw a strike and
you're going to have days where you throw nothing but strikes.
That's part of it. You just have to grasp that concept.''
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who saw Wood's performance in May against the Astros,
the very idea that he could give up 12 runs to Arizona and San
Francisco in his last two starts is mind-boggling. Wood overpowered
the NL's top-scoring team in a way that may never have been
duplicated.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed only a scratch single to Ricky Gutierrez in the third
inning _ a ball that Cubs third baseman Kevin Orie later said
should have been ruled an error _ and struck out a record-tying 20
batters, including seven straight during a stretch in the final
three innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That particular game might be the most dominant game ever
thrown in the history of major-league baseball,'' said Cubs
president Andy MacPhail. ``It could have been a no-hitter, and he
had 20 strikeouts. There have been one-hitters and no-hitters, and
there have been 20-strikeout games. But never in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, you're talking about one of the premier offensive teams
in the league. In the beginning, you were just kind of enthusiastic
and into it. But by the end of it, with the crowd roaring, you were
fortunate to have been there.''
</P>
<P>
   With that start, Wood went from being a highly touted prospect
scarcely known outside of Chicago _ he was selected fourth overall
out of Grand Prairie High School in the 1995 draft _ to a national
story. Despite having to relive and recount that game in May
against the Astros numerous times, he cannot yet explain why it all
seemed so easy that afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't imagine having better stuff than that,'' said Wood.
``That's the one time where you go out there with the best stuff of
your career. A lot of things have to happen. The umpire (Jerry
Means) was consistent with his calls, and I was able to let it
loose and hit the spots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw the fastball, the breaking balls; I kept with it. It
seemed like every righthanded hitter, I had the same combination _
fastball, fastball, slider. What can I say? It was one of those
days.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, Wood has lived up to the bloated expectations
that were thrust upon him after May 6. MacPhail seems just as
impressed with Wood's ability to handle the pressure of being this
summer's phenom as his talents on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``The expectations right now are very high,'' said MacPhail.
``My feeling is that if anybody can handle it, he can do it. What
impresses me most about Kerry is that down deep, he is really a
fierce competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   Riggleman said: ``He's gotten the respect of his teammates. At
the same time, this is a veteran team that has helped guide him
along and try not to put too much on him. The press and talk radio
are always talking about him. He goes out there now and strikes out
six in six innings or eight in seven innings, and it's like 'Why
didn't you do more?'''
</P>
<P>
   Wood seems to understand the legacy of being a power pitcher. As
a teen-ager in the Dallas area, he watched Ryan close his career
with the Texas Rangers. Wood was at Arlington Stadium when Ryan
pitched his seventh no-hitter in 1990. Wood's father, Garry, told
the Chicago Tribune this summer that, ``I thought Nolan Ryan was
the best pitcher I'd ever seen. So we tried to emulate him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wood said he didn't ask for the No. 34 that Ryan wore during his
career when he reported to the Cubs. Nor did he balk when he was
assigned that number during his first spring training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really a nut for him like everyone's making out,''
Wood said about Ryan. ``I watched him, but I didn't have to watch
every start he made. I watched him if I was flipping through and
the game was on, sure, I didn't change it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a great career, and he'll be remembered in baseball
forever. I don't even have a full season, so it's kind of pointless
to even think about a comparison at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Ryan, Wood is aware that the effectiveness of his breaking
ball will determine whether or not he has a dominant game. Ryan was
only as good as his curve; Wood relies on a hard-breaking slider
and a curve that catcher Scott Servais, the former Astro, says is
as good as ex-teammate Darryl Kile's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The breaking ball determines whether you're going to be out
there for two innings or you're going to be out there for eight,''
said Wood. ``Last year (in the minors), that's why I struggled so
much. I wasn't getting my breaking ball over, and I was getting
knocked out early. Regardless of how hard you throw, even if you're
out there throwing 120 mph, they'll time you.
</P>
<P>
   ``You might be OK the first time through, but after that they'll
time it and you'll get beat. The breaking ball and off-speed stuff
makes your fastball that much more effective. My strikeout pitch
this year has been my slider. You can also use the fastball to set
them up. It can work both ways if you have an effective breaking
ball. You want to keep them off balance and keep them guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   Servais, a seven-year veteran who is not prone to exaggeration,
says that Wood is ``the best pitcher I've ever caught, and I caught
some good ones in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's legit,'' said Servais. ``His curve is probably as good as
Darryl Kile's, just not as consistent yet. But Darryl wasn't
consistent, either, for a long time. His fastball is consistently
95, 96 (mph) and when the big boys come up, the top two or three
hitters on every team, he has a tendency to throw it a couple miles
an hour faster. It's a Nolan-like fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   The key for Wood the rest of this season, says Servais, is to
disregard the high expectations and trust his overpowering stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's struggled a little bit the last two weeks, and it's a
combination of a couple things,'' said Servais. ``Part of it is
that the expectations are so high every time he goes out. That's
tough. He's 21 years old and people expect him to strike out 20
every time and win every time. It's like, `Oh, Wood's pitching
today, the Cubs are going to win.'
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few little mechanical adjustments he needs to make
that he's aware of. And a lot of people are concerned about the
fact that he's never gone through this long of a season before.
You're not going to know how you do until you go through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his recent downturn, Wood says he has been able to enjoy
his rookie season. The pressure of having been so close to pitching
perfection in his fifth start in the majors isn't taking away from
a wondrous summer in which he turned 21 and had the world by the
tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having a blast,'' said Wood. ``This is a childhood dream
that I get to live out every day. I'm having a great time.
Everything that comes along with it is just fine.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
