<HEADER>
A5689 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-STRIKEOUTS-RYAN-H     08-15 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STRIKEOUTS-RYAN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Undisputed `K' king Ryan helped fine-tune Johnson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ALAN TRUEX &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Power pitchers stick together. Even when they're on competing
teams.
</P>
<P>
   When Nolan Ryan, the king of K's, was a Texas Ranger in 1992, he
felt empathy for Randy Johnson, who was with the Seattle Mariners,
rivals in the American League West.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was a taller, lefthanded version of the Ryan Express _
the strikeout machine who lasted 27 years in the major leagues and
produced a record seven no-hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson could throw 98 mph, his performance during the
first four years of his big-league career didn't match his ability.
He had thrown a no-hitter against Detroit in 1990, but by the end
of the '92 season his lifetime won-lost record was a slack 49-48.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew some of the frustration he was experiencing,'' Ryan
says. ``I went through the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Power pitchers often have difficulty developing the fluid
mechanics that allow them to control the fire they throw.
</P>
<P>
   And as Ryan points out, ``When you're real tall like Randy
(6-10), the mechanics are a little more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In the twilight of one of the greatest careers in baseball
history, Ryan felt he might be able to help Johnson, who now
pitches for the Astros. So after the '92 season, Ryan and Tom
House, the Rangers' pitching coach at the time, offered to meet
with Johnson and discuss his delivery.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was looking to fine-tune his mechanics,'' Ryan says. ``I
don't think I helped him much, but at least I was someone he could
talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson insists the advice he accepted from Ryan was a key
to his breakthrough year of 1993, when he went 19-8 with a 3.24 ERA
and 308 strikeouts. Most significantly, he reduced his walks to 99
_ down from 144 the year before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nolan means a great deal to my success,'' Johnson says.
``There were some flaws in my mechanics that he helped me work on.
Being consistent with my mechanics is very important to having
success out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel it's important to try to help other pitchers on other
teams, because Nolan took the time to help me. It was one of the
things that helped get me over the top.''
</P>
<P>
   As brilliantly as Johnson has pitched over the past six years
(87 wins, 30 losses), he knows he's no threat to the legacy of
Ryan, who has retired to Alvin and a life of ranching, banking,
owning a minor-league baseball team (in Austin) and serving on the
state's Parks &AMP; Wildlife Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 34, would need more than 3,000 strikeouts to match
Ryan's career record of 5,714.
</P>
<P>
   On a night when Ryan sat a few feet behind home plate in the
Astrodome, Johnson last Wednesday reached double-digit strikeouts
for the 97th time. He tied Hall of Fame lefthander Sandy Koufax for
second place in that category.
</P>
<P>
   But second place is the best he hopes to attain, because No. 1
is Ryan, with 215 and awaiting his own certain induction into
Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've got a hundred-some-odd to go,'' Johnson said,
grinning. ``I think that's a safe record that Nolan has.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980815.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-08-15 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5690 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-STRIKEOUTS-WOOD-H     08-15 1858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-STRIKEOUTS-WOOD-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Despite slump, Wood is heir to throne
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEIL HOHLFELD &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After Kerry Wood pitched a one-hitter and struck out 20 Astros
