</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ROBERTSON </SLUG>
 COLUMN-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Column: Golf's Golden Boy watches luster fade
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ The signs were all there. This would be Phil
Mickelson's year. Golf's Golden Boy, its would-be lefthanded Golden
Bear, had served a long-enough apprenticeship. He was ready to win.
</P>
<P>
   Not the pedestrian events, nor the automotive ones, either. The
Buick Opens and the Mercedes Championships he long since had
figured out. Heck, he owned the Northern Telecom Open before he
owned a PGA Tour card. But what he hadn't mastered was the Masters
and the other majors, the four tournaments that, we're told, take
the true measure of a man's talents. And heart.
</P>
<P>
   By late Saturday afternoon, though, Mickelson wore a bewildered
look on his made-for-fame face. Self-doubt had crept into his voice
as he stood behind the Sahalee clubhouse, trying to explain what
had happened, why another chance had blown up in his face.
</P>
<P>
   Guys named Stricker and Singh were running away with the 80th
PGA Championship and Mickelson, the can't-miss kid, was having to
answer for a third-round 78, scored in perfect conditions, that
caused him to free-fall from a respectable four shots behind the
leaders to 15.
</P>
<P>
   He must play today, but his tournament is over, as well as his
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be pretty difficult to get motivated,''
Mickelson said, referring to what's left on his '98 schedule.
``I'll keep playing. I mean, it's not the end of the world. But I'm
real disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson's major slumps
</P>
<P>
   He shot himself out of the Masters with a final-round 74. He
never contended at the U.S. Open, posting a 74 in the third round.
His British Open at Royal Birkdale became a royal mess when scores
of 85 and 78 on the weekend left him 28-over par, in 79th place.
</P>
<P>
   And then came Saturday. He needed 41 swings to get around the
front nine. He bogeyed five holes in a row. Golfers of Mickelson's
stature never bogey five holes in a row. But Phil, as in empty,
did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like I was trying to get cute and make a bunch of
birdies, either.'' Mickelson said. ``I just couldn't make any
pars.''
</P>
<P>
   Three-putts. A series of buried bunker lies. Each horror begat
another. Even a modest face-saving on the back nine would include a
double bogey. He went from being nominally in the hunt to having to
punt. Of the 75 players who survived the cut, nobody shot more than
a stroke worse.
</P>
<P>
   So Sahalee becomes Mickelson's 26th major without a win. That's
nowhere near the record for taking a collar _ Tom Kite
hyperventilated through 67 to win his first _ but it's a dreadful
reality for a player with Mickelson's rsum. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   He was a four-time All-American and three-time NCAA champion at
Arizona State. When he won the NCAAs and the U.S. Amateur in the
same year, only Nicklaus had done it before him.
</P>
<P>
   He was just the third golfer, joining Nicklaus and Jerry Pate,
to win five tournaments before his 25th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   He was the fourth-youngest player in history to win a 10th
tournament, trailing only Horton Smith, Gene Sarazen and,
naturally, Nicklaus.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson, 28, has 12 tour victories, the most recent in the
season's leadoff event, the Mercedes Championships, after which he
said: ``This year is going to be a proving ground for me because
I've set a lot of high goals. It's going to be a real challenge to
fulfill those. If I can, I can fulfill a lot of expectations people
have for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Running out of time
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday he was honest about whose expectations mattered the
most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy other people want me to win,'' he said. ``I
appreciate the support. But nobody wants me to win (a major) more
than I do.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he took a major stumble backward. At an age when
Nicklaus was well on his way to collecting 18 Grand Slam titles,
Mickelson hasn't the foggiest idea how to reverse his momentum and
get back on the fast track to immortality. If anything, he fears
he's drifting off the path.
</P>
<P>
   The younger twentysomethings _ Ernie Els, Justin Leonard, Tiger
Woods _ have beaten him to the breakthrough. If he has any
consolation, it's that players such as Tom Lehman, Davis Love III,
Steve Elkington, Fred Couples and, most belatedly, Mark O'Meara
have succeeded with a better-late-than-never approach. The
difference is none of them was supposed to win a bunch of majors.
</P>
<P>
   Negative thoughts creep into his game. He admits he finds
himself waiting for the next mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``As time goes on, the more difficult it becomes to think
positively.'' Mickelson said. ``You assume something bad is going
to happen. And then it does.''
</P>
<P>
   When he arrived here, he was shown a golf magazine cover with
his photograph on it and a large headline that asked: ``Does Phil
Mickelson have what it takes to win a major championship?'' While
he found the article to be ``fair and well-written,'' there was one
large problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked,'' he said, ``to have answered the question
better than I did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
