u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR &LR;      08-15 0597
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News service for Sunday, Aug. 16. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
KIDS (Phoenix) _ He meticulously prepares for an inquiry like none
he's faced, crafting the precise words to be forthcoming, without
saying too much. But still, he fears a single question:Daddy, what
is oral sex? He is Chris Hernandez, a Tempe father of two. And,
like many parents, he faces a dilemma in the wake of a presidential
scandal that has mainstream media tossing out intimate _ and very
adult _ terms. By ALEXA HAUSSLER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POL-DRAMA (Washington) _ The months of singing, clapping and
praying are nearly over, and it's time for Bill Clinton to present
himself for atonement in the Baptist tradition. For those Americans
who have been watching the presidential sex scandal with mounting
incredulity, experts on Southern politics and religion have an
explanation: The legal drama is actually a Southern religious
pageant about redemption. It is less about small perjuries and more
about large sins like adultery. And in this tradition the customary
conclusion is the big, public, tearful confession. Witness
televangelist and Louisiana Pentecostal preacher Jimmy Swaggart. By
ADRIANNE FLYNN. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   IMAC (Phoenix) _ Forget that it has the fastest modem around.
Never mind the oodles of built-in software or the memory that
leaves other computers in the dust. It's just darn cute. At least
that seemed to be the consensus among tech-heads who swarmed Valley
computer stores Saturday to scoop up the hottest commodity: Apple's
iMac. By ALEXA HAUSSLER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOMES (Phoenix) _ Last summer, Nancy Neutz made a surprise
midday visit to the adult care home where her mother was living.
She found her mom slumped in a bedroom, so drugged she couldn't sit
up. ``I think I gave her the sleeping medicine too early,'' the
home's owner said.But Neutz knew instantly that the problem was
more serious than that. Her mother had been given an overdose of
tranquilizers.Neutz soon realized that the reason the house was
always so clean for visitors was that the residents were taken out
of their rooms only for meals. So she moved her mother to another
home. She reports that the last six months of her mother's life
were spent in a caring facility _ a good home. By MAUREEN WEST and
JUDY NICHOLS. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONTINI-COLUMN (Phoenix) _ After months of painstaking effort,
scientists now concede that even their most sophistocated computers
can't calculate the total number of news stories more important
than whether Bill Clinton and Monica Lewinsky. . .you know. They
can say for sure, however, that one of those stories involves a
former Arizona State University offensive lineman named Joe Cajic.
By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BEHAVIORAL INTERVIEWS _ If the interviewer appears more interested
in how you reacted in specific situations than your skills and
qualifications, you could be the subject of a hiring technique
called behavioral interviewing. The relatively new concept is
thought to be a better predictor of job performance than
traditional interviews and is being increasingly utilized by
recruiters and human resource professionals. By MAX JARMAN. Story
will move in the ``F'' category. &QL;
</P>
