<SLUG> BC-RAC-PACIFIC-CLASSIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE HOUSE WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ What Chris McCarron couldn't, or wouldn't, say
in the days leading up to the Pacific Classic, he conveyed as he
rode Free House past the grandstand early in the race Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was a cocky individual, I'd have said, `If he runs the
way he's trained, they (his opponents) have (ITAL)no(END ITAL)
chance,' '' McCarron said later. ``But you couldn't have got me to
say that before the race.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he allowed Free House to run four-wide into the first
turn of the 1\-mile race, losing ground to favorites Gentlemen and
Touch Gold, the Hall of Fame jockey displayed his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   And it was warranted, because Free House made up those lost
lengths and more, going on to win the $1 million race by four
lengths, leaving defending champion Gentlemen second and invader
Touch Gold fifth. Pacificbounty and Lazy Lode finished third and
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It was an especially satisfying victory for owners Trudy
McCaffery and John Toffan, and trainer Paco Gonzalez, coming after
a urine test produced uncorroborated evidence Free House had the
prohibited drug clenbuterol in his system when he won the Bel Air
Handicap in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we vindicated ourselves this afternoon,'' McCaffery
said.
</P>
<P>
   And it was just as satisfying for McCarron, confirming what he
already thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't happy with (racing wide),'' McCarron said. ``But I'm
thinking, `OK, don't panic. I'm on the best horse.' ''
</P>
<P>
   McCarron, who was aboard Free House for the first time when they
dominated the Bel Air in the gray, California-bred colt's
4-year-old debut, rode him in his recent workouts at Santa Anita
and liked what he felt.
</P>
<P>
   But if the 1997 Santa Anita Derby winner was the best horse in
the nine-horse Pacific Classic, it wasn't obvious to the crowd of
27,576, which came to watch the biggest race of the Del Mar season
and to contribute to a pick-six pool of $3,555,771 on a day track
management guaranteed a $2 million pool.
</P>
<P>
   Free House paid $9, going off as the third choice behind the 6-5
entry of Gentlemen and Puerto Madero and 3-2 Touch Gold.
</P>
<P>
   Gentlemen ran well, and trainer Richard Mandella said, ``Maybe
he's just not as good as he was last year.'' Puerto Madero finished
a punchless sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Touch Gold was never better than fourth, joining Cigar, Concern
and Unbridled on the list of big-name, out-of-state horses who
stumbled in the Pacific Classic. ``I'm at a loss to explain his
race,'' jockey Pat Day said.
</P>
<P>
   Free House, always on the outside, moved quickly from fifth to
contention on the backstretch, hooked Gentlemen on the turn for
home and took command entering the stretch. In the box seats,
trainer Paco Gonzalez grabbed McCaffery by the arm and said, ``We
got 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   It's never that easy with Free House, who, even in his 17th race
and seventh victory, shied from McCarron's whip and zigzagged
through the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got kind of scared,'' McCaffery said. But Free House
straightened and won in a solid 2:00 1/5, winning more convincingly
than top-ranked Skip Away beat a similar field in the Hollywood
Gold Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The pick-six pool of more than $3.5 million set a Del Mar
record. But 254 tickets were perfect, so the payoff was small,
$7,821. The 10-race card produced another Del Mar record, total
wagering of $22.9 million. . . . Old Topper, facing elders for the
first time, stayed close to the pace under Eddie Delahoussaye and
won the 7-furlong Pat O'Brien Handicap in a $23 upset over Son of a
Pistol. He and Bold Brawley (1986) are the only 3-year-olds to win
the O'Brien. Alex Solis sent Son of a Pistol to the early lead, not
the gelding's usual style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
