<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-O'MEARA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
O'Meara likes his chances
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
REDMOND, Wash. _ They remind Mark O'Meara on every hole at Sahalee
Country Club, as though wishing it will make it come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey Mark, things always happen in threes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark, the third time is the charm.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans at this PGA Championship have been generous in their
praise for nearly all of the golfers in the field, but they sense
O'Meara has the chance to accomplish something very special. And
after shooting a 1-under-par 69 in Saturday's third round to put
himself five strokes behind the leaders, O'Meara has given himself
a chance to do what no golfer has done since Ben Hogan in 1953 _
win three major championships in one year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I go out there and play the way I played today and hole
some of the putts, I think I have a reasonable shot at it,''
O'Meara said. ``I don't think that I'm out of the tournament by any
means. And I'm going to go out there and play hard and try to play
smart and give myself a chance. That's all you can ask.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans, of course, are asking for a little bit more. They want
to watch O'Meara make history firsthand, and they've left little
doubt about how they feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the people out there are pulling for me,'' O'Meara said
with a smile. ``So I'm using that as a positive. Their feedback
coming toward me is wonderful. Hopefully tomorrow I won't let them
down, and I can get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Meara started the final round of the Masters and the British
Open two shots off the lead. He has more ground to make up this
time but also more experience as well. O'Meara didn't win his first
major championship until he was 41 when he won the Masters, but he
quickly put his new-found knowledge to good use at the British
Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the British Open, I used some of the experience that I
gained at the Masters,'' he said. ``And now I'm using that same
experience to try to play well here and win this championship. So
whether I have a little bit of an edge coming down the stretch if
I'm close to the lead, yes and no. I mean, I've got pressure on me
just like every other player has on him.''
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, however, this new Mark O'Meara doesn't seem to
show the pressure. His playing partners all week have remarked
about how calm and collected he seems. Even after a bad shot,
O'Meara never appears to get rattled and never seems to lose his
control.
</P>
<P>
   He also has handled all of the pressure that comes from winning
not just one but two majors in one season with easy grace. There
have been no temper tantrums, no whining that the demands on his
time are too great. O'Meara, in fact, has flourished with all of
the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite an honor to have your peers come up to you and tell
you how happy they are for you, for the success you've had,''
O'Meara said. ``And the success I've have this year has been
tremendous. If you were going to pick a couple of tournaments that
you'd like to win in one year, most people would put those two
tournaments very high on their list. So with it comes a lot of
respect and a lot of admiration from the fans and your peers, which
is a tremendously nice thing to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts a little more pressure on me, because I think people
expect me to play well. But I expect to play well. So we're trying
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be apparent pretty early in today's final round whether
O'Meara will have a shot at another title. He will have to get off
to a good start, and the co-leaders will have to stumble. But
O'Meara still has a chance, and for him, that is good enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person who is going to hit greens and make some putts is
going to win this championship tomorrow,'' O'Meara said. ``If I can
do that, I might have a chance on the last few holes tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
