<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YANKEES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS ROLL IN NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rangers catcher Ivan Rodriguez demonstrated yesterday
that perhaps one defensive play _ no matter its timeliness _ could
be viewed as the most significant element of an 11-run victory.
</P>
<P>
   It occurred during the second inning of a game that consumed 3
hours, 48 minutes of a beautiful afternoon at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers overcame a four-run, first-inning deficit for a
stirring, 16-5 victory against the New York Yankees, and many would
regard the second-inning grand slam by left fielder Rusty Greer as
the game's critical element.
</P>
<P>
   Greer's home run culminated the visitors' six-run explosion, and
a three-run, eighth-inning home run by right fielder Mike Simms
ensured the Rangers' first victory since Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Rodriguez's catch-and-tag exploit might be the play that
kept the Rangers within a half-game of the first-place Anaheim
Angels in the American League West after their 6-3 in victory in 11
innings against the Blue Jays yesterday in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they score there,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates said, ``I
believe it makes it a different ballgame.''
</P>
<P>
   Greer's opposite-field home run off losing right-hander Hideki
Irabu (11-6) gave the Rangers a 6-4 lead, but Rangers right-hander
Todd Stottlemyre _ who surrendered four runs on five hits and walk
during the first inning _ continued his flirtations with disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees loaded the bases with one out for center fielder
Bernie Williams, and the Yankees cleanup hitter lined a Stottlemyre
pitch into right-center field.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers center fielder Tom Goodwin chased the ball down and made
a running catch in the gap. Yankees second baseman Chuck Knoblauch
tagged and scored easily on the play, and shortstop Derek Jeter
advanced toward third base.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin threw the ball to shortstop Royce Clayton, who served as
the cutoff man on the play. Clayton, though, bobbled and dropped
the throw. Jeter, who witnessed the misplay, rounded third and
continued toward the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton retrieved the loose ball and unleashed a strong throw
that short-hopped Rodriguez at the plate. Rodriguez fielded the
tough bounce in the dirt cleanly, blocked Jeter from the plate and
made the tag to preserve the Rangers' one-run advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way Pudge was going to let him score,'' said
Stottlemyre, who afterward pitched four scoreless innings for his
second victory in three decisions despite an afternoon of
unrelenting ordeals. ``He got the ball and sat down right in front
of the plate. He pumped me up.''
</P>
<P>
   The play ranked more improbable considering Rodriguez's
reputation as a catcher whose strengths do not include blocking the
plate from runners attempting to score.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been told before,'' Oates said, ``that it's better to
live to fight another day than die a hero.''
</P>
<P>
   The unusual, inning-ending double play prevented the Yankees
from tying the game and stranded first baseman Tino Martinez in the
on-deck circle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was huge to get two outs on that particular play,''
Clayton said. ``You really don't want to face Tino in that
situation with runners at first and third and two outs. He's one of
those guys who has the ability to put the ball in the seats. It was
good for us to get out of that inning and immediately put up
another run.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms' third-inning, run-scoring single provided Stottlemyre a
two-run cushion, and his home run off right-hander Ramiro Mendoza
gave the Rangers a 10-5 lead. The Rangers later blasted
right-hander Joe Borowski for another six runs in the ninth inning
as they sent 11 batters to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Even that did nothing to diminish what is arguably Rodriguez's
finest defensive moment this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
