<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-STOTTLEMYRE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR STOTTLEMYRE, EMOTIONS GO THROUGH ROLLER-COASTER RIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nothing prepared right-hander Todd Stottlemyre for
this appearance at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old veteran could not draw upon five World Series
and seven League Championship Series appearances for comfort during
this encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three thousand people attended the Rangers' 16-5 victory
yesterday against the Yankees, and Stottlemyre's emotions allowed
one person in the visitors' dugout affect him.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre's father, Mel, serves as the Yankees' pitching
coach, and it represented the first time the two emerged as
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was probably emotionally tougher to prepare for and pitch
than any game I've ever been in _ and that includes all the World
Series games, playoff games and big games I've pitched in down the
stretch,'' said Stottlemyre, whom the Rangers acquired July 31 from
the Cardinals. ``I'm glad it's over, but I'm glad I got the
opportunity to do it. It will always be a great memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre earned his second victory in three starts with the
Rangers, but the right-hander encountered unrelenting difficulties.
Stottlemyre surrendered five runs on nine hits and six walks during
his six-inning, 116-pitch appearance and wondered if he would
escape the Yankees' four-run first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was such a confusing inning, and there were so many base
runners,'' said Stottlemyre, who did not allow a run during his
final four innings despite the Yankees' unyielding pressure. ``They
don't have any easy outs. I was just trying to do anything to get
out of the first inning because it was ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel's afternoon would be worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a day I should have stayed home,'' said the elder
Stottlemyre, whose pitching staff allowed 19 hits and issued six
walks. ``Watching my son struggle and our guys struggle ... was
really difficult, a tough day on me overall.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd's mother, Jean, sat with her son's wife, Sheri, and her
3-year-old granddaughter, Rachel, in the stands. Jean, even though
Mel's wife, would not be a Yankees fan this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew she was rooting for me,'' Todd said. ``There's no doubt
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean told him as much beforehand, and the five planned to spend
the evening together over dinner afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll have to pick up the tab,'' Todd said.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the afternoon concluded with one Stottlemyre emerging as
the game's winning pitcher and the other a coach on baseball's best
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's anything refreshing about today,'' Mel said, ``it's
that he needed it and their team needed it more than we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-15-98 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
