u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-LEDE-HNS &LR;      08-15 0948
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-LEDE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Stricker, Singh have work cut out
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JAYNE CUSTRED &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
REDMOND, Wash. _ Nine out of the last 10 PGA Championships have
been won by players without a previous major championship victory.
</P>
<P>
   That bodes well for co-leaders Steve Stricker and Vijah Singh,
who are tied at 7-under-par 203 and hold a four-stroke lead on the
field in this 1998 PGA Championship. Both men will be seeking their
first major title today at Sahalee Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   But a quick glance over their shoulders should end any warm,
fuzzy feelings they may be having about their position heading into
the final round. Because the men chasing them are a formidable
group indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker shot a 4-under 66 Saturday that included a great
up-and-down to save par on No. 18 to finish tied with Singh, who
turned in a 67. Stricker and Singh both have shown they can win,
with seven PGA Tour victories between them. But Stricker hasn't won
since 1996, and neither man has ever taken a lead into the final
round of a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there will be a little bit more pressure on myself
and Steve,'' Singh said. ``It really depends on how we start off
and how the rest of the guys are playing. But anybody within five,
six shots has got a chance of winning this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   How's this for a who's who list of pursuers?
</P>
<P>
   At 3-under 207 is defending champion Davis Love III, who won his
first major championship at the 1997 PGA Championship at Winged
Foot. Joining him is last week's winner, Billy Mayfair, along with
former PGA Champion Steve Elkington, who has recorded three
consecutive 69s at Sahalee and is playing his best golf of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   One shot behind them at 208 is Mark O'Meara, who has already won
two majors this season and is making a bid to become the first man
since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three major titles in one year.
Keeping pace with O'Meara is 1997 Masters champion Tiger Woods,
along with Skip Kendall and Frank Lickliter.
</P>
<P>
   Love, for one, had to believe being in this position before, and
succeeding, would serve him well today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll have a little bit of an advantage,'' he said. ``I'll be a
little bit more comfortable than maybe Steve or Vijay. And then you
have others, like Steve Elkington, who's won and been there a lot.
Anything can happen. But I'll feel like I have at least a chance
because I've done it before.''
</P>
<P>
   All of those in the hunt agreed, however, that Stricker and
Singh will have to stumble for any past major success to become any
factor at all. And neither man showed much in the form of weakness
during Saturday's third round.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker had one of the few bogey-free rounds of the tournament,
making three birdies on the front side and then sinking a 10-footer
at No. 16 for his 66. In fact, Stricker has been unflappable all
week, one of the few players under par for every round. Even when
he was in trouble on No. 18, after hitting his second shot into the
trees, Stricker managed to scramble and save par and his share of
the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Stricker also has been playing some incredible golf as of late.
He has finished eighth or better in five of his last seven
tournaments and has made nearly $640,000 in official money. That is
all welcome news to Stricker, who won twice in 1996 and then had a
horrendous 1997 season, finishing 130th on the money list with only
one top-10 finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's round is one of my best rounds that I've ever played,
under the circumstances and under the pressure, which gives me a
whole lot of confidence,'' Stricker said. ``It may be difficult
tomorrow. I haven't been in this situation before. So I'm just
going to have to try to worry about my own game starting off, and
try to get myself going in a nice positive direction and feeling
good about what I'm doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh's round wasn't quite as smooth as Stricker's on the front
side, where he made three bogeys, but he rebounded nicely on the
final nine, making birdie on four of the first six holes on the
back side.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main plan was to go out there and shoot a solid round and
not be out of the tournament,'' Singh said. ``That back nine I
played really good. That got me back in the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Singh also has played solidly in recent weeks, finishing in the
top 12 in three of his last four events. His last chance to win was
at the Motorola Western Open in June, where he took a two-stroke
lead into the final round but ended up in second place, trailing by
two.
</P>
<P>
   After his round Saturday, Singh vowed not to change his routine
at all for today's run at the title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to keep doing what I've been doing all week,'' he
said. ``I felt really comfortable on the back nine, and even on the
front side. But it's a major event. You never know what's going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially if you haven't been there before. So it was O'Meara,
the master of the majors this year, who had the best bit of advice
for the two men he will be chasing today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what they're going to learn is that they've got a nice
opportunity tomorrow to go out and play well and try to win this
championship,'' O'Meara said. ``They'll learn about being patient
and going out there and hitting a couple of bad shots and not
getting too frustrated. It's going to be a long day. So you just
have to hang in there and give yourself a chance coming up the last
few holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the philosophy that I try to use, and I'll think that's
what they'll use, too.''
</P>
<P>
   A valuable lesson. The only problem for Singh and Stricker is
that it is one a number of the men who are behind them already have
learned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
