<SLUG> BC-IMAC-AZR </SLUG>
  
 DEBUT OF iMAC LIVES UP TO HYPE  
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEXA HAUSSLER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget that it has the fastest modem around. Never mind the
oodles of built-in software or the memory that leaves other
computers in the dust.
</P>
<P>
   It's just darn cute.
</P>
<P>
   At least that seemed to be the consensus among tech-heads who
swarmed Arizona computer stores Saturday to scoop up the hottest
commodity: Apple's iMac.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a really cool machine, that's all,'' said Art
Landrey, a high school math teacher who bought the first iMac at
Computer Town in Chandler on Saturday. ``If you're going to have a
computer, this is the one to have.''
</P>
<P>
   The retro-looking machine has been the talk of the computer
world since Apple announced it would unveil its first new model in
years.
</P>
<P>
   And the much-hyped debut didn't disappoint Saturday, as stores
sold out of the funky Mac faster than they could say ``megabyte.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to our zoo,'' said Jerry Koszut, a salesman at
Computer Town in Chandler, where customers bought up 100 iMacs in a
matter of hours.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of customers started peering into the store as early
as 7 a.m. and hovered around waiting for the doors to open.
</P>
<P>
   Landrey and his 14-year-old son showed up precisely when the
store opened at 9 a.m. They smiled proudly for a Polaroid snapshot
and picked out some Star Wars game software, before lugging the
prized possession to their car.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking it home and hooking it up,'' Landrey said.
</P>
<P>
   Other Valley stores, with smaller supplies of the computer, sold
out in less than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opened at 8 and they were gone before 9,'' said Benjamin
Whiting, manager of Re-Mac, a Macintosh retailer in Mesa. ``We've
just got one on display left now.''
</P>
<P>
   The iMac, with its transparent plastic monitor and black
keyboard, is a far cry from Apple's first tubes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original was kind of a joke. I have one that I turned into
an aquarium,'' said Koszut, who has been selling Apple computers
since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The new model is an all-in-one piece, complete with a superfast
modem, a CD-ROM, stereo speakers, an out-of-this-world look and
15-inch screen.
</P>
<P>
   All for $1,299.
</P>
<P>
   ``The newer ones have all the features that they could want at a
price they can afford,'' Koszut said.
</P>
<P>
   And local stores were offering deals on extra memory and
software for the iMacs.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Elsasser, who works at Arizona State University, picked
one up for her home, along with 32 extra megbytes of free memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people are just really excited because it
looks really cool,'' she said. &QL; 
 &UR; Alexa Haussler can be reached at 444-7481 or at
alexa.haussler &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
