<SLUG> BC-WENDT-WEDDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXECUTIVE, ONCE SPOTLIGHTED IN A DIVORCE, TO WED AGAIN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His divorce became a messy public spectacle that
titillated and terrified corporate executives across the country,
but Gary C. Wendt is getting married again anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The 55-year-old chairman of GE Capital Corp., General Electric's
most profitable subsidiary, is scheduled to wed Rosemarie Adams
Sunday night at the First Church of Round Hill in Greenwich, Conn.
Wendt's spokesman, Peter Rosenthal, described the prospective groom
as ``cheerful and optimistic'' but offered few details about the
wedding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they want a private ceremony,'' said Rosenthal, of
Howard J. Rubenstein and Associates. ``Gary generally is a private
person.''
</P>
<P>
   Privacy has been a rarity since Wendt and his first wife, Lorna
J. Wendt, waged a divorce battle that spiraled into the news media
as a test case of the rights _ and value _ of stay-at-home
corporate wives. Rejecting an initial settlement offer of $10
million, Mrs. Wendt and her lawyers contended that she was entitled
to half of her husband's net worth, estimated at $45 million to
$130 million.
</P>
<P>
   In her role as supportive spouse, Mrs. Wendt said, she had
managed their household, entertained her husband's business
associates and even helped put him through Harvard Business School.
The Wendts, who were high school sweethearts, were married for more
than 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt's lawyers argued that his ex-wife had distorted the
equality issue. ``Gary's stand was that he always offered half,''
said Marsha Horowitz, another of Wendt's spokesmen. ``The issue had
to do with future, not-yet-earned options. That was the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The case reverberated in corporate suites across America where a
different set of rules applies in divorce cases. While an even
split is common in divorces for ordinary people, judges
historically have been leery of awarding a wife an equal share when
the net worth is above $10 million. Suddenly, corporate titans
faced the prospect of a judge's ruling that a wife was entitled to
half of everything.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, last December, Judge Kevin Tierney of Connecticut
Superior Court resisted any sweeping historical precedent. He
dissolved the marriage, awarding Mrs. Wendt more than $20 million
in money and property, in addition to future stock and pension
options. Both spouses filed appeals and a final settlement is
pending.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wendt did not return calls to her Stamford, Conn., home
Saturday. She has founded the Foundation for Equality in Marriage
to advocate her belief that society _ and the courts _ should
better recognize the nonmonetary contributions made to a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   The prolonged, bitter divorce apparently has not dimmed Wendt's
opinion of matrimony.
</P>
<P>
   Wendt and Ms. Adams, who are close in age, met in Monte Carlo in
1995, the same year Wendt asked his wife for a divorce. A meetings
planner, Ms. Adams was running a business incentive program for GE
Capital in Europe. She has since retired. Her first marriage, like
Wendt's, ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenthal said he did not know if the couple had signed a
pre-nuptial agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
